WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.200
[Amit Varma]: One of the great temptations of the modern world is to appear certain of everything.

00:00:10.200 --> 00:00:14.080
[Amit Varma]: Another great temptation is to pass judgement on everything.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:19.160
[Amit Varma]: Certainty and moral posturing get us likes and retweets and raise our status on social

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:20.160
[Amit Varma]: media.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:24.920
[Amit Varma]: And yet, those who are sure of themselves and sanctimonious towards others also tend

00:00:24.920 --> 00:00:28.440
[Amit Varma]: to be both ignorant and useless.

00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:35.080
[Amit Varma]: And while we do need to tell simple stories to make sense of it, we also need to be humble.

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:40.120
[Amit Varma]: And in the face of the multitudes around us, we need to nurture the multitudes within us.

00:00:40.120 --> 00:00:44.240
[Amit Varma]: The less dots we join to paint a picture of the world, the less accurate that picture

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:45.240
[Amit Varma]: is.

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:50.040
[Amit Varma]: Also, while it is tempting to pass judgement all the time, as that makes us feel both knowledgeable

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:55.400
[Amit Varma]: and virtuous, it again ignores nuance, context, circumstance.

00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:59.480
[Amit Varma]: And it stands in the way of our actually changing those aspects of the world that we do not

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:00.480
[Amit Varma]: like.

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:04.360
[Amit Varma]: Those who change the world do not stand at a distance and pontificate.

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:10.440
[Amit Varma]: Instead, they plunge right in, get their hands dirty, and try to move that needle one inch

00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:14.800
[Unknown]: at a time.

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:20.240
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:21.240
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:28.200
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:29.440
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:33.520
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is my friend Suyash Rai, who I often describe as the finest thinker no

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:34.680
[Amit Varma]: one has heard of.

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:38.920
[Amit Varma]: Suyash has been on the show a couple of times before, but in older, shorter formats, and

00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:43.080
[Amit Varma]: I think I've described him as someone who always makes my brain expand a little bit

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:44.360
[Amit Varma]: after I meet him.

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:48.900
[Amit Varma]: He always makes me rethink my beliefs and examine my character, though I do have some

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:50.280
[Amit Varma]: disagreements with him.

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:55.080
[Amit Varma]: Suyash used to work at an IPFP, he was a consultant with the finance ministry for a while.

00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:59.840
[Amit Varma]: He has been in the weeds when it comes to actually changing and shaping policy within

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:04.160
[Amit Varma]: the government of India, and he is now a deputy director at Carnegie India.

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:09.040
[Amit Varma]: Suyash has grown up in villages and towns, worked in government, and this conversation,

00:02:09.040 --> 00:02:15.880
[Amit Varma]: in many ways, is a close look first at Indian society, then at the Indian state, and then

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:17.560
[Amit Varma]: at the Indian economy.

00:02:17.560 --> 00:02:23.920
[Amit Varma]: We discuss tradition, modernity, urbanization, family, ethics, and he even mentions, quote,

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:26.960
[Amit Varma]: the limitations of the canine condition, stop quote.

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:30.040
[Amit Varma]: It's a great conversation with one of our finest thinkers.

00:02:30.040 --> 00:02:33.280
[Amit Varma]: And it was recorded, by the way, in Delhi in August this year.

00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:37.320
[Amit Varma]: I've made you wait since then, and I'll make you wait another minute, because hey, it's

00:02:37.320 --> 00:02:41.440
[Amit Varma]: time for a commercial break.

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:44.480
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer, but never quite gotten down to it?

00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:45.920
[Amit Varma]: Well, I'd love to help you.

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:50.800
[Amit Varma]: Since April 2020, I've taught 20 cohorts of my online course, The Art of Clear Writing.

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:53.960
[Amit Varma]: An online community has now sprung up of all my past students.

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:58.280
[Amit Varma]: We have workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community

00:02:58.280 --> 00:02:59.280
[Amit Varma]: interaction.

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:03.400
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through four webinars spread over four weekends, I share all I know

00:03:03.400 --> 00:03:05.600
[Amit Varma]: about the craft and practice of clear writing.

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:09.560
[Amit Varma]: There are many exercises, much interaction, a lovely and lively community at the end of

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:10.560
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:14.640
[Amit Varma]: The course costs rupees 10,000 plus GST, or about $150, and is a monthly thing.

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:19.520
[Amit Varma]: So if you're interested, head on over to register at indiancut.com slash clear writing.

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:22.320
[Amit Varma]: That's indiancut.com slash clear writing.

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:27.120
[Amit Varma]: Being a good writer doesn't require God given talent, just the willingness to work hard

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:30.680
[Amit Varma]: and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:31.680
[Amit Varma]: I can help you.

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:36.400
[Amit Varma]: So Yash, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:38.160
[Guest]: Thank you Amit for having me.

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:41.520
[Amit Varma]: So I just realized this is the third time you're on and the first time you were on we

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:46.160
[Amit Varma]: chatted about demonetization, which was like 20 minutes or something, episode two.

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:50.100
[Amit Varma]: And then episode 120 something, we chatted for two hours.

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:53.720
[Amit Varma]: And then I started that episode by saying that you know what the podcast has changed.

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:58.480
[Amit Varma]: I do deep dives now, which is lol because that was only two hours and I was listening

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:03.720
[Amit Varma]: to it and realizing that I didn't deep dive into some of the things that I like to do.

00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:06.960
[Amit Varma]: So you know, we've known each other for six years.

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:11.200
[Amit Varma]: And as you correctly pointed out, there are very, very few people in India who've known

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:17.240
[Amit Varma]: each other that long, if you look at a total set of possible pairs.

00:04:17.240 --> 00:04:20.760
[Amit Varma]: But I feel like I still don't know enough about you.

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:23.280
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit more about you know, where were you born?

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:24.280
[Amit Varma]: Where did you grow up?

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:27.280
[Amit Varma]: What were your childhood years like?

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:31.240
[Guest]: I'm not very comfortable talking about these kind of things.

00:04:31.240 --> 00:04:37.600
[Guest]: But so I come from Eastern UP, my village is in a district called Mau.

00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:43.800
[Guest]: And my father was the first from his family to come from a village to a city for the first

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:48.480
[Guest]: time and get his college education, get a job and basically live in the city.

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:53.360
[Guest]: So I was the first person from my family, from the father's side to actually be born

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:55.000
[Guest]: in a city.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:01.000
[Guest]: And so my father first made the move basically to come to the city and find a footing in

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:02.000
[Guest]: the city.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.040
[Guest]: And so it's like, basically, he was the first amphibian in that sense in the family.

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:14.760
[Guest]: He's a man of the village, but he also found a place in the city world.

00:05:14.760 --> 00:05:20.280
[Guest]: And that itself is somewhat of an interesting story, I would say that he studied in a local

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:22.080
[Guest]: village school.

00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:27.160
[Guest]: And in that school, there were a couple of good teachers who were interested in teaching

00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:31.880
[Guest]: as an activity which is worth pursuing seriously.

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:35.000
[Guest]: And he was touched by their excellence in some ways.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:41.800
[Guest]: And he worked hard and he got a good schooling education, even though the village is far

00:05:41.800 --> 00:05:46.120
[Guest]: from any nearby city, it's 30 kilometers away from the nearest town.

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:50.160
[Guest]: And the school was right close to that village.

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:56.760
[Guest]: And he did well in school education and basically would have studied in some nearby college

00:05:56.760 --> 00:05:58.180
[Guest]: only.

00:05:58.180 --> 00:06:03.480
[Guest]: But it just so happened that that year when he passed out, there was a census or some

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:08.000
[Guest]: large case survey was being done, perhaps census, that's what I am told.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:14.160
[Guest]: And they came to our family home in village and they were taking basically all the details

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:19.400
[Guest]: of all the members of the family, two persons had come to do this.

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:24.940
[Guest]: And they asked the head of the family, so to speak, who's my uncle, my grandparents

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:29.780
[Guest]: passed away when my father was still a young boy of nine or 10 years of age.

00:06:29.780 --> 00:06:34.720
[Guest]: So my uncle was the senior most person who was also not very old, frankly, just out 15

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:37.360
[Guest]: years older than my father.

00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:43.400
[Guest]: And so he was, he is the one who was basically took charge, I mean, that was his virtue that

00:06:43.400 --> 00:06:48.160
[Guest]: he saw that as his duty to take care of his family after having lost the parents at a

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:49.320
[Guest]: young age.

00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:55.280
[Guest]: So the census was asked him about who all in the family, then my father's name came

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:57.480
[Guest]: up and they asked him what is he doing?

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:02.600
[Guest]: They said that he's just completed schooling and is now going to go to some degree college

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:03.600
[Guest]: nearby.

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:07.240
[Guest]: Then they asked him how much, how many marks have he got, how well has he done?

00:07:07.240 --> 00:07:09.520
[Guest]: And he told how my father had done.

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:12.720
[Guest]: They said this is a very good score that he's got.

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:17.480
[Guest]: He should actually try for a better university, not go to college somewhere nearby, which

00:07:17.480 --> 00:07:18.480
[Guest]: is okay.

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:22.720
[Guest]: I mean, the degree college near village was okay, it wasn't great.

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:27.380
[Guest]: But he said that he has done quite well and he can get admission in Banaras Hindu University

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:31.280
[Guest]: which was the best university in that region, BHU in Varanasi.

00:07:31.280 --> 00:07:32.280
[Guest]: My father was very moody.

00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:33.280
[Guest]: He didn't want to do that.

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:34.280
[Guest]: He didn't want to leave the village.

00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:40.600
[Guest]: He never left his village, you know, since he was born, maybe traveled a little in 20-30

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:43.320
[Guest]: miles in one direction, but not further than that.

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:50.120
[Guest]: But my uncle had the good sense to basically insist that he should go and he should move

00:07:50.120 --> 00:07:56.080
[Guest]: to, I mean, he should try to get an admission in BHU and he listened to him because he was

00:07:56.080 --> 00:07:59.840
[Guest]: his elder and he did listen to only one person and that was his elder brother, otherwise

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:01.440
[Guest]: he didn't listen to anyone.

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:05.760
[Guest]: So he went to BHU trying to get admission in engineering, but by the time he landed

00:08:05.760 --> 00:08:07.980
[Guest]: there, the engineering admissions had closed.

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:12.920
[Guest]: So then he was coming on his way back, he thought I should have some, have a meal sitting

00:08:12.920 --> 00:08:19.440
[Guest]: in BHU itself at a dhaba and there another student he met who suggested that even though

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:24.240
[Guest]: the engineering admissions are closed, you can get admission in BSc physics.

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:29.560
[Guest]: So just chance, right, like the census came and then this person gave him advice and he

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:33.700
[Guest]: said okay, that sounds interesting to me, I mean, physics is interesting.

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:34.700
[Guest]: So he got admission.

00:08:34.700 --> 00:08:39.680
[Guest]: That's how he basically made it into a city, you know, and he got his education at BHU,

00:08:39.680 --> 00:08:43.880
[Guest]: he did his master's also from BHU, then he worked in the private sector for a few years

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:46.360
[Guest]: and then he got a job in the railways.

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:52.160
[Guest]: So I mean, I was born a few years into his first job and then once he got to railways,

00:08:52.160 --> 00:08:54.920
[Guest]: we used to get transferred every few years, three to four years.

00:08:54.920 --> 00:09:00.280
[Guest]: So I lived all over UP, we moved to Gujarat for some time, I lived there.

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:04.600
[Guest]: So my schooling was basically all over three to four years in a city and then we would

00:09:04.600 --> 00:09:06.400
[Guest]: move on to another city.

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:09.600
[Guest]: So that's the way it was.

00:09:09.600 --> 00:09:14.440
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating couple of things I want to double click on and one of them is you spoke about

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:19.200
[Amit Varma]: your uncle that, you know, after your grandparents were no more, he had to take charge, that

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:20.320
[Amit Varma]: is what you do.

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:28.040
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just thinking about the question of how sometimes character can be shaped by necessity

00:09:28.040 --> 00:09:32.960
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that his path also, you know, had his parents not died, might have been

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:33.960
[Amit Varma]: different.

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:37.920
[Amit Varma]: But here he is in this position of being the eldest male in the family and presuming and

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:40.160
[Amit Varma]: therefore he's got to look after everyone.

00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:45.440
[Amit Varma]: He's got to, you know, take almost premature parentship of these younger brothers of his

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:50.600
[Amit Varma]: and all of that and his life, you know, hit as much by circumstance as your father's was

00:09:50.600 --> 00:09:55.040
[Amit Varma]: then just goes off in this direction and I'm thinking of how it can work both ways in the

00:09:55.040 --> 00:10:00.320
[Amit Varma]: sense that on the one hand necessity can shape you and shape your character.

00:10:00.320 --> 00:10:04.720
[Amit Varma]: So like another example could be like any number of single mothers out there, you know,

00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:08.720
[Amit Varma]: who are widowed early or husband leaves them or whatever and then they become completely

00:10:08.720 --> 00:10:13.520
[Amit Varma]: different person, maybe prematurely when they are very young, they get a different kind

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:17.480
[Amit Varma]: of responsibility and they discover a different kind of strength within themselves.

00:10:17.480 --> 00:10:20.680
[Amit Varma]: And that's one way it can work that your character is shaped by situation.

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:26.480
[Amit Varma]: But another way it can work is that circumstance can be oppressive in the sense that your true

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:32.880
[Amit Varma]: nature is something that you then have to suppress because you're going along a particular,

00:10:32.880 --> 00:10:35.880
[Amit Varma]: you're following a particular destiny as it were to use that term loosely and there's

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:37.600
[Amit Varma]: nothing you can do.

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:42.280
[Amit Varma]: And I think many women in India, for example, would say that this is what happens to them

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:46.160
[Amit Varma]: because you know, in a sense, they have no choice but to follow the conventional path.

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:50.400
[Amit Varma]: You get married, you have kids and you know, maybe even if a couple decides not to have

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:55.920
[Amit Varma]: kids but accidentally even that can kind of take you along a certain path which you may

00:10:55.920 --> 00:11:01.640
[Amit Varma]: not otherwise have gone down and that can affect character in a different way and that

00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:03.840
[Amit Varma]: can affect a person in a different way.

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:11.360
[Amit Varma]: So what are your thoughts on this sort of broad question about, you know, how circumstance

00:11:11.360 --> 00:11:16.520
[Amit Varma]: can change character and how the notion of duty falls into all of this?

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:17.520
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:22.760
[Guest]: So if I look at my uncle, when this situation arose, when in his early 20s, he lost both

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:29.520
[Guest]: his parents and with two younger sons, younger brothers and a sister, I mean, he had to decide

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:31.000
[Guest]: what it was to be done.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:32.160
[Guest]: There were different paths to take.

00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:35.760
[Guest]: So he actually had a job offer at that time to become a teacher.

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:40.240
[Guest]: He gave up on that to actually take care of the family, to take care of the family farm.

00:11:40.240 --> 00:11:46.520
[Guest]: We are not a large farm for farmholders, we have medium-sized farm but it was a mainstay

00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:51.800
[Guest]: and if he had taken up the job, it would have probably meant neglect of the farm and also

00:11:51.800 --> 00:11:52.800
[Guest]: the family.

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:57.440
[Guest]: It's not just about earning money, it's also about the day-to-day business of running a

00:11:57.440 --> 00:12:00.920
[Guest]: family with their social obligations to be met and all of that.

00:12:00.920 --> 00:12:05.600
[Guest]: So he made a major sacrifice and I wouldn't ever take it away from him that it was his

00:12:05.600 --> 00:12:06.600
[Guest]: choice.

00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:11.440
[Guest]: It was a decisive choice and he saw that in that situation, what he had to do is to prioritize

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:17.080
[Guest]: the family and he and my aunt both together basically decided that this is something that

00:12:17.080 --> 00:12:21.640
[Guest]: they needed to do and they did their duties fully and completely.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:26.160
[Guest]: And so there was a necessity that arose in some senses but the necessity leads to different

00:12:26.160 --> 00:12:28.800
[Guest]: kinds of choices that people make.

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:33.320
[Guest]: You still have a certain set of choices available to you within that situation that you find

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:39.160
[Guest]: yourself and I would say that he was a very virtuous kind of a person as far as the practice

00:12:39.160 --> 00:12:41.080
[Guest]: of running a family is concerned.

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:46.800
[Guest]: He was very much devoted to the virtuous side of that practice and he was a great role model

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:47.800
[Guest]: for us.

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:52.000
[Guest]: Even though he didn't study much, he was, I mean at that time, if you remember, he didn't

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.640
[Guest]: even have to be a high school pass to get a school teacher job, you know, the education

00:12:56.640 --> 00:12:58.320
[Guest]: standards weren't as high.

00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:02.840
[Guest]: So he didn't even do his high school but he was good in his studies, whatever he studied

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:09.320
[Guest]: and he still gave up on a path of further education and job and all of that to be able

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:11.040
[Guest]: to take care of family.

00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:15.440
[Guest]: So that's on the side of individual choice and virtues and how you define your situation

00:13:15.440 --> 00:13:19.160
[Guest]: in life and what do you do when you face a situation.

00:13:19.160 --> 00:13:22.680
[Guest]: The other side is the larger setting in which you find yourself, right?

00:13:22.680 --> 00:13:27.880
[Guest]: That if you look at a few centuries ago, basically the main predictor of how prosperous you would

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:32.200
[Guest]: be would be where were you born, you know, like which family you were born in, not even

00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:33.200
[Guest]: where were you born.

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:38.160
[Guest]: Basically, it was a Malthusian world, not much productivity growth.

00:13:38.160 --> 00:13:41.600
[Guest]: If you are born in a rich family, that's great and chances are that you are going to die

00:13:41.600 --> 00:13:45.960
[Guest]: in a rich family and if you are born in a poor family, chances were that you are going

00:13:45.960 --> 00:13:50.160
[Guest]: to die in a poor family and there was a little bit of immobility that time.

00:13:50.160 --> 00:13:54.080
[Guest]: But in the last few centuries, especially since the Industrial Revolution and since

00:13:54.080 --> 00:14:00.000
[Guest]: social structures have become more, I mean, liberal and open, there's been much more opening

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:05.160
[Guest]: of opportunities, you know, and there's much more, I mean, there are many more chances

00:14:05.160 --> 00:14:08.400
[Guest]: for a person to find ways to, you know, flourish in different ways.

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:12.800
[Guest]: It need not be just pursuing a particular kind of career, but whatever your interests

00:14:12.800 --> 00:14:17.340
[Guest]: are and it's become possible because the larger society has changed, right?

00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:20.840
[Guest]: Because the economy has changed, the society has changed, the polity has changed.

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:26.080
[Guest]: In many countries now you have a little somewhat more open polity, more open societies and

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:27.960
[Guest]: also economies have changed a lot.

00:14:27.960 --> 00:14:30.240
[Guest]: So resources are much more available now.

00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:34.360
[Guest]: So now, for example, the main predictors of how you're going to do well, you're going

00:14:34.360 --> 00:14:36.840
[Guest]: to do in life is which country you are born in.

00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:42.600
[Guest]: That's the most important because I think the, I mean, if you're born in a rich country,

00:14:42.600 --> 00:14:46.160
[Guest]: there are just so many more opportunities that you have and so much more that you can

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:49.440
[Guest]: do as far as your own kind of past are concerned.

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:54.220
[Guest]: There are less constraints basically imposed upon you and then there are other factors

00:14:54.220 --> 00:14:57.720
[Guest]: that go into play to define how well you do in your life.

00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:01.680
[Guest]: But even if you're born in suppose a country which is a little poor, then quite a few countries

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:06.320
[Guest]: have shown that in a fairly short period of time that can change, you know, and societies

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:11.680
[Guest]: can change, things can become different, families can become more liberal and open.

00:15:11.680 --> 00:15:16.280
[Guest]: My own family I've seen is that there was a certain opposition initially when I was

00:15:16.280 --> 00:15:17.280
[Guest]: very, very young.

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:21.560
[Guest]: I remember when I was a kid, there was some opposition of the idea of women working, you

00:15:21.560 --> 00:15:23.760
[Guest]: know, in a job, like a formal job.

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:27.400
[Guest]: The only job that was acceptable at that time was a teaching job because a half day job,

00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:31.080
[Guest]: you know, in that sense, you go in the morning, you come and then there are things to be done.

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:32.640
[Guest]: But now it's completely changed.

00:15:32.640 --> 00:15:37.800
[Guest]: Like my family still, most of them live in the village, my father, my brother, me, I

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:42.640
[Guest]: mean, we are the only ones who live in the city, our family is still a rural family.

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:46.860
[Guest]: But the opinions have completely changed in terms of education and being open to having

00:15:46.860 --> 00:15:47.860
[Guest]: women work outside.

00:15:47.860 --> 00:15:52.600
[Guest]: You know, it just happened in less than a generation basically because they saw, I mean,

00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:57.400
[Guest]: what works more or less and basically they are following some kind of a herma, what's

00:15:57.400 --> 00:16:01.160
[Guest]: good for the family and what would work and then they are changing the opinion.

00:16:01.160 --> 00:16:06.600
[Guest]: In fact, my uncle who passed away a few years ago, I mean, he was, at a very old age he

00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:11.880
[Guest]: changed his opinions about all of these things, on education, on question of work and all

00:16:11.880 --> 00:16:12.880
[Guest]: of that.

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:15.360
[Guest]: So, I think both things have an interplay.

00:16:15.360 --> 00:16:19.940
[Guest]: So, what is the kind of larger social setting and I think modernity in many ways offers

00:16:19.940 --> 00:16:20.940
[Guest]: many more opportunities.

00:16:20.940 --> 00:16:25.440
[Guest]: There are fewer constraints on, people don't feel so hemmed in by their circumstances as

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:29.840
[Guest]: much, no need to, so more and more societies offer more opportunities, but you still have

00:16:29.840 --> 00:16:34.720
[Guest]: to exercise your virtues, you know, and have a sense of your, what is it that you should

00:16:34.720 --> 00:16:37.700
[Guest]: be doing in a particular situation and what would be the right thing to do for yourself

00:16:37.700 --> 00:16:41.640
[Guest]: and for your family and for your friends or your society, for your nation, for the world,

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:43.200
[Guest]: you know, in that sense.

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:49.080
[Guest]: So, it's both of them have to go hand in hand and to be able to, you know, make most

00:16:49.080 --> 00:16:53.280
[Guest]: of your situation basically.

00:16:53.280 --> 00:16:57.400
[Amit Varma]: So a bunch of broader questions and one of them sort of, there's this beautiful story

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:02.120
[Amit Varma]: I, you know, share with my writing students as an example of really great simple writing

00:17:02.120 --> 00:17:03.120
[Amit Varma]: and what it can achieve.

00:17:03.120 --> 00:17:07.600
[Amit Varma]: It's a story called Paper Menagerie by Ken Liu, I'll link it from the show notes.

00:17:07.600 --> 00:17:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's really about a young man discovering his mother anew after she is no more and discovering

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:20.680
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, he judged her as what we would call unparagovar kind of person, somebody

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:23.760
[Amit Varma]: who was an embarrassment to him, he could never speak to her.

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:28.280
[Amit Varma]: And then when he discovers circumstances of his life, he just sees her in a completely

00:17:28.280 --> 00:17:29.800
[Amit Varma]: new way.

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:34.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's an interesting, so I recorded an episode with Natasha Badwar just before this,

00:17:34.280 --> 00:17:38.480
[Amit Varma]: I don't know whether it will come out before or after this, but she revealed something

00:17:38.480 --> 00:17:39.480
[Amit Varma]: very interesting.

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:42.640
[Amit Varma]: She married someone from a slightly different background, a Muslim man who came from this

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:47.040
[Amit Varma]: village, and she grew very fond of his family and vice versa.

00:17:47.040 --> 00:17:52.320
[Amit Varma]: And she realized that initially, they thought that their respective parents would oppose

00:17:52.320 --> 00:17:55.100
[Amit Varma]: the marriage and not like each other and all of that.

00:17:55.100 --> 00:17:56.520
[Amit Varma]: And they found just the opposite.

00:17:56.520 --> 00:18:01.800
[Amit Varma]: But what she said was that she, that one thing that surprised both of them, both her and

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:07.480
[Amit Varma]: her husband, is how much their respective in-laws turned out to be different from the

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:10.320
[Amit Varma]: portrait painted of them by their child.

00:18:10.320 --> 00:18:14.720
[Amit Varma]: So you know, her husband had portrayed his parents and the village and in a particular

00:18:14.720 --> 00:18:19.120
[Amit Varma]: way, and she meets him and she finds out that no, they are completely different, right?

00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:21.080
[Amit Varma]: And and vice versa.

00:18:21.080 --> 00:18:27.180
[Amit Varma]: And the realization there was that there is this human tendency that we have, that we

00:18:27.180 --> 00:18:31.960
[Amit Varma]: fix, you know, we know a person, they become a fixed point in our head.

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:33.680
[Amit Varma]: And then they are that.

00:18:33.680 --> 00:18:39.080
[Amit Varma]: And that fixed point remains that, you know, they are frozen in our mind as a particular

00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:44.080
[Amit Varma]: kind of person, even when they change and, you know, those changes can sort of be invisible

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:45.080
[Amit Varma]: to us.

00:18:45.080 --> 00:18:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And roles can do that.

00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:49.600
[Amit Varma]: Someone is fixed in a particular role, like she says, she looks at a mother so much more

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:55.240
[Amit Varma]: differently today in her early 50s, as she did when she was 20, you know, but you can

00:18:55.240 --> 00:18:59.520
[Amit Varma]: look back and see that, you know, then you are relating with that person just within

00:18:59.520 --> 00:19:01.720
[Amit Varma]: the bounds of that role and what it means.

00:19:01.720 --> 00:19:05.360
[Amit Varma]: But now you can look at them as a fully fledged human being and all that.

00:19:05.360 --> 00:19:11.240
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just thinking that in this fascinating story of your uncle and your father and the

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:17.120
[Amit Varma]: younger generation, you and your cousins and all of that, you know, I get a sense from

00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:24.680
[Amit Varma]: this of your uncle, in one way, being a profoundly interesting man who is faced with difficult

00:19:24.680 --> 00:19:25.680
[Amit Varma]: choices.

00:19:25.680 --> 00:19:30.160
[Amit Varma]: He thinks about within, you know, the limited bounds of how he can understand it.

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:32.360
[Amit Varma]: He thinks about what is the right thing to do.

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:35.440
[Amit Varma]: He makes a choice, that choice involves sacrifice and courage.

00:19:35.440 --> 00:19:36.760
[Amit Varma]: He does all of that.

00:19:36.760 --> 00:19:40.440
[Amit Varma]: But it is possible that a kid growing up in the family may just see him as an old fogey

00:19:40.440 --> 00:19:44.400
[Amit Varma]: and may not ever see that side of him and may not see him.

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:48.160
[Guest]: Or pay attention to some of his opinions, which may seem a little politically incorrect

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:49.160
[Unknown]: at times.

00:19:49.160 --> 00:19:50.160
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:19:50.160 --> 00:19:54.560
[Guest]: So, you know, today we pay too much attention to just the spoken word and not the whole

00:19:54.560 --> 00:19:58.680
[Guest]: complex set of deeds that people actually live by, choices they actually live.

00:19:58.680 --> 00:20:04.880
[Guest]: I mean, you know, they are not held in a manner which is very deep, you know, so you may have

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:09.120
[Guest]: all kinds of opinions and they can change at times through experience or you may not

00:20:09.120 --> 00:20:11.440
[Guest]: even mean that very seriously.

00:20:11.440 --> 00:20:15.160
[Guest]: But yeah, I mean, there is a, I mean, this is the story of each human being, right?

00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:20.320
[Guest]: In some ways, there's a lot more than meets the eye and it takes a lot of effort and that's

00:20:20.320 --> 00:20:26.440
[Guest]: why literature, I think, plays a very important role that it is able to show us this reality

00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:34.600
[Guest]: of human life and it's very much in our, the nature of human beings to be able to change

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:41.320
[Guest]: in some ways, you know, in terms of human nature as such may be permanent, but our ability

00:20:41.320 --> 00:20:47.040
[Guest]: to change our opinion, adapt to circumstances, do things differently.

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:48.040
[Guest]: So another story.

00:20:48.040 --> 00:20:49.040
[Guest]: Okay.

00:20:49.040 --> 00:20:51.520
[Guest]: So, I was, I think, 10 years old or something.

00:20:51.520 --> 00:20:56.400
[Guest]: I used to spend my summer in my village, usually, it's a month or so doing summer vacations.

00:20:56.400 --> 00:21:02.920
[Guest]: So, I was in my village and I fell ill, very, I mean, I had very high fever and I was just

00:21:02.920 --> 00:21:03.920
[Guest]: basically bedridden.

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:09.240
[Guest]: So, they got me some medicines and I took some, took them, I mean, they were helping

00:21:09.240 --> 00:21:11.560
[Guest]: the symptoms a little, but the fever wasn't going away.

00:21:11.560 --> 00:21:15.480
[Guest]: They took me to a proper doctor and they gave the medicines.

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:20.280
[Guest]: So, I was taking the medicine, but in the meanwhile, they call this old Muslim gentleman,

00:21:20.280 --> 00:21:24.240
[Guest]: you know, he must have been at least around 70 at that time.

00:21:24.240 --> 00:21:28.840
[Guest]: And he said that this guy is unwell and you have to cure him now, you know, like I said,

00:21:28.840 --> 00:21:30.160
[Guest]: what is he going to do?

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:35.800
[Guest]: So he said, he's a, you know, he's a kind of person who does this kind of thing, you

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:39.960
[Guest]: know, like, so it's an alternate way of looking at the situation.

00:21:39.960 --> 00:21:44.640
[Guest]: I was a young kid and I was very much situated in our kind of, you know, what Auden says,

00:21:44.640 --> 00:21:46.040
[Guest]: believing still versus believing again.

00:21:46.040 --> 00:21:50.360
[Guest]: I was still believing still stage that you are very naive about these things and you

00:21:50.360 --> 00:21:56.160
[Guest]: actually accept that, yeah, there is a kind of a magical side of the world and things

00:21:56.160 --> 00:21:57.800
[Guest]: can be cured in this way.

00:21:57.800 --> 00:22:04.520
[Guest]: So he gave me a talisman, you can call me and say, you tie it around your arm and then

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:06.240
[Guest]: this will cure you, you know.

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:10.800
[Guest]: So whatever, it may be placebo or whatever, I think it may have been placebo, but it worked

00:22:10.800 --> 00:22:12.040
[Guest]: and I got better a few days.

00:22:12.040 --> 00:22:15.800
[Guest]: And he used to come and talk to me every day for one or two hours and really comforting

00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:16.800
[Guest]: talk.

00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:22.040
[Guest]: He was a, I would say, gentle kind of a soul, very refined, uneducated, but very refined

00:22:22.040 --> 00:22:23.040
[Guest]: in that sense.

00:22:23.040 --> 00:22:27.240
[Guest]: He was talking in a very, very fine way, you know, his language is very good.

00:22:27.240 --> 00:22:33.160
[Guest]: He spoke very pure Urdu and he used to live basically 20 meters from our house.

00:22:33.160 --> 00:22:36.880
[Guest]: And when I got better, he used to still come and talk to me every day for an hour or two.

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:39.080
[Guest]: It was just a ritual for him.

00:22:39.080 --> 00:22:45.800
[Guest]: And he told me that when his family got into trouble many years ago when he was younger,

00:22:45.800 --> 00:22:49.800
[Guest]: my family basically gave them some land very close to our house for them to settle down.

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:53.600
[Guest]: This is a Muslim family, you know, and very conservative Muslim family.

00:22:53.600 --> 00:22:57.920
[Guest]: And they said that, please, you can, and they had a kacha house at that time and they were

00:22:57.920 --> 00:22:59.480
[Guest]: living in that house.

00:22:59.480 --> 00:23:00.980
[Guest]: Then the family did better.

00:23:00.980 --> 00:23:07.460
[Guest]: So his sons got handloom, got into handloom, learnt a skill which could turn into a kind

00:23:07.460 --> 00:23:09.880
[Guest]: of a livelihood opportunity.

00:23:09.880 --> 00:23:12.920
[Guest]: And then they built a pakka house on the same land and they live basically like 20 meters

00:23:12.920 --> 00:23:13.920
[Guest]: from our house.

00:23:13.920 --> 00:23:19.120
[Guest]: So village is very much, I mean, divided around communities, but there are these interspersed

00:23:19.120 --> 00:23:22.960
[Guest]: interesting spaces where people kind of intertwine with each other.

00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:27.320
[Guest]: And I was just, at that time, it was nothing, you know, it was just something that I had

00:23:27.320 --> 00:23:28.380
[Guest]: an experience.

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:29.380
[Guest]: And that was the last time I met him.

00:23:29.380 --> 00:23:33.760
[Guest]: A few years later, he passed away and I never got a chance to meet him again.

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:39.080
[Guest]: And he gave me a story about how that happened, how that land was given as a, like, this is

00:23:39.080 --> 00:23:42.880
[Guest]: not a very large farmer, so giving a land is not a small thing.

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:47.120
[Guest]: But we had some land and we gave it to a family that was, that needed it.

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:51.640
[Guest]: And I was thinking, I mean, just a few months ago about that episode just came to me.

00:23:51.640 --> 00:23:53.120
[Guest]: My memory had suppressed it.

00:23:53.120 --> 00:23:54.120
[Guest]: Then just think about it.

00:23:54.120 --> 00:23:59.480
[Guest]: I mean, we are a Hindu family living in a basically a Hindu area and some small patch

00:23:59.480 --> 00:24:04.600
[Guest]: of land we gave to a family, a Muslim family to kind of build a small house for some time.

00:24:04.600 --> 00:24:06.800
[Guest]: Then they basically settled down there.

00:24:06.800 --> 00:24:10.200
[Guest]: They did better economically, but they still continued to live there and there was no question

00:24:10.200 --> 00:24:11.200
[Guest]: of taking the land back or anything.

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:12.720
[Guest]: It was their home.

00:24:12.720 --> 00:24:15.920
[Guest]: And it is also that all the neighbors agreed to that, right?

00:24:15.920 --> 00:24:19.600
[Guest]: Because you're basically family settling down right in that area.

00:24:19.600 --> 00:24:24.520
[Guest]: And the way our village works is that basically if you go back hundreds of years, it's the

00:24:24.520 --> 00:24:27.960
[Guest]: same family that basically broke into parts and set up houses nearby.

00:24:27.960 --> 00:24:32.400
[Guest]: So they are our distant cousins all nearby, but they all agreed to that, you know, to

00:24:32.400 --> 00:24:33.400
[Guest]: that process.

00:24:33.400 --> 00:24:37.840
[Guest]: And there was a kind of a very complex intertwining of lives, I would say, which I experienced

00:24:37.840 --> 00:24:38.840
[Guest]: at that time.

00:24:38.840 --> 00:24:43.440
[Guest]: That the eldest son of the only member of the family that has moved out to city is he

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:46.280
[Guest]: has a high human capital potential.

00:24:46.280 --> 00:24:51.080
[Guest]: And still you bet on this one guy, you know, magic to cure him while, of course, also giving

00:24:51.080 --> 00:24:52.080
[Guest]: medicine.

00:24:52.080 --> 00:24:54.000
[Guest]: You know, that's the way belief works.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:25:00.360
[Guest]: Last time also when we spoke on the podcast, this kind of a dynamic came up in the discussion.

00:25:00.360 --> 00:25:05.480
[Guest]: And when you talk to my uncle or someone about their views on Muslims, they were, I mean,

00:25:05.480 --> 00:25:11.160
[Guest]: a little suspicious, you know, that, okay, they are, they have many wounds of the Mughal

00:25:11.160 --> 00:25:12.400
[Guest]: Empire and all of that.

00:25:12.400 --> 00:25:14.400
[Guest]: There are lots of stories that you hear.

00:25:14.400 --> 00:25:19.720
[Guest]: But the fact of the matter is that there is also this side of it, you know, and that in

00:25:19.720 --> 00:25:23.560
[Guest]: actual decision making and actually day to day living together, our village has a large

00:25:23.560 --> 00:25:26.760
[Guest]: number of Hindu and Muslim families both.

00:25:26.760 --> 00:25:29.240
[Guest]: And in many ways, they are very intertwined.

00:25:29.240 --> 00:25:34.040
[Guest]: And in some ways, they are separate, you know, so they live in different areas.

00:25:34.040 --> 00:25:39.160
[Guest]: In some places, as I just gave an example, they also live in the same area as well.

00:25:39.160 --> 00:25:44.840
[Guest]: So, I think what matters more is that when a situation comes to take a decision, what

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:49.240
[Guest]: is to be done, what do you do at that time, what are the, are you following some kind

00:25:49.240 --> 00:25:55.080
[Guest]: of a, some notion of dharma, I would say, you know, or some notion of virtue or righteousness

00:25:55.080 --> 00:25:56.640
[Guest]: at that time or not.

00:25:56.640 --> 00:26:03.280
[Guest]: For the rest, I don't pay too much attention now, at least as I've spent, because my family

00:26:03.280 --> 00:26:06.120
[Guest]: lives in different centuries at the same time, you know.

00:26:06.120 --> 00:26:10.240
[Guest]: So we've seen that, you know, how things can change and what really matters and what doesn't

00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:12.480
[Guest]: matter in some senses.

00:26:12.480 --> 00:26:16.560
[Guest]: So I told you the story mainly to be able to highlight this, the question that you asked

00:26:16.560 --> 00:26:21.040
[Guest]: about people and how complex they can be and how their actions can be very different from

00:26:21.040 --> 00:26:27.360
[Guest]: their stated opinions if you ask them in a survey, whether it's a Pew survey or whatever.

00:26:27.360 --> 00:26:33.400
[Guest]: So give me a sense of the, you know, but before you get in, there's a book recommendation

00:26:33.400 --> 00:26:34.400
[Guest]: I can make.

00:26:34.400 --> 00:26:37.920
[Guest]: So this is a book on Ghazi Mian, which Shahid has written.

00:26:37.920 --> 00:26:44.080
[Guest]: I think it's worth reading carefully in terms of how modernity changes our imagination of

00:26:44.080 --> 00:26:50.480
[Guest]: identity and how in a way it hardens it, while also pretending to give us the opportunity

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:55.000
[Guest]: to make and remake ourselves continuously and also sometimes it also can harden it.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:27:00.120
[Guest]: So this is an interesting book about this conquistador who comes to India and gets intertwined

00:27:00.120 --> 00:27:01.880
[Guest]: in our lives in very, very interesting ways.

00:27:01.880 --> 00:27:06.720
[Amit Varma]: Actually, my question was just going to be about that, about modernity itself, because,

00:27:06.720 --> 00:27:11.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, through our lenses and my lens, a lot of my lens really comes from the West

00:27:11.640 --> 00:27:13.880
[Amit Varma]: in a sense, the Enlightenment and so on.

00:27:13.880 --> 00:27:19.360
[Amit Varma]: We think of modernity in a particular way, but modernity plays out in, you know, different

00:27:19.360 --> 00:27:23.920
[Amit Varma]: kinds of subtle ways when it comes to our towns and our villages and all of that.

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:29.240
[Amit Varma]: And what you sort of describe here, for example, where opinions on women have, you know, subtly

00:27:29.240 --> 00:27:34.320
[Amit Varma]: changed over a generation, where you're moving in so many directions and at the same time,

00:27:34.320 --> 00:27:38.200
[Amit Varma]: it is true, what you said of your family is true of India, that we're living in many different

00:27:38.200 --> 00:27:40.720
[Amit Varma]: centuries at the same time.

00:27:40.720 --> 00:27:45.360
[Amit Varma]: So what is your sense of modernity?

00:27:45.360 --> 00:27:47.280
[Amit Varma]: Like how is that village changing?

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:52.880
[Amit Varma]: I can look around me and in a sense, we have a sense of how a city is changing like Bombay

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:57.800
[Amit Varma]: or Delhi, and of course, it's deeply complex, and there's a lot there, but it is whatever

00:27:57.800 --> 00:28:01.920
[Amit Varma]: of that we don't know, I think would fall in the realm of the known unknown.

00:28:01.920 --> 00:28:07.680
[Amit Varma]: But in villages, which especially for, you know, city slickers like me, is such a dark

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:12.800
[Amit Varma]: space and, you know, and it's been either romanticized by Gandhi, who, you know, which

00:28:12.800 --> 00:28:16.640
[Amit Varma]: he started doing from a time when he hadn't actually been to a village as Ram Guha points

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:23.680
[Amit Varma]: out in the 19th century, or it's been condemned with some justification by Ambedkar as a den

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:26.840
[Amit Varma]: of localism and all of those vices.

00:28:26.840 --> 00:28:33.000
[Amit Varma]: But it's a complicated space, it's a complicated space of real people, you know, who are reacting

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:38.000
[Amit Varma]: in unusual ways, which are hard to pin down, as you just pointed out through the story.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:44.160
[Amit Varma]: So give me a sense, maybe using your village as an example, that how do we look at modernity

00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:49.120
[Amit Varma]: in an Indian context? What does it mean to be modern? What does it mean to progress?

00:28:49.120 --> 00:28:55.240
[Amit Varma]: And is some of this movement in a direction which others may not call modern, which can

00:28:55.240 --> 00:29:00.040
[Amit Varma]: lead to, like you said about Mr. Amin's book, can lead to a hardening of identities rather

00:29:00.040 --> 00:29:01.040
[Amit Varma]: than the suffering?

00:29:01.040 --> 00:29:07.240
[Guest]: Yeah, so I mean, this is something that I've been thinking about, but my thoughts are not

00:29:07.240 --> 00:29:10.160
[Guest]: at the level of, I mean, articulation is not so clear.

00:29:10.160 --> 00:29:13.040
[Amit Varma]: This is the show for thinking about.

00:29:13.040 --> 00:29:14.040
[Amit Varma]: Thinking aloud.

00:29:14.040 --> 00:29:20.480
[Guest]: So I'll give you a few kind of images of and then see how, let's see where it goes.

00:29:20.480 --> 00:29:27.560
[Guest]: So another short story, I went to my village and so to get to my village, you have to take

00:29:27.560 --> 00:29:31.960
[Guest]: a narrow lane away from, I mean, there's a branching off from the road and then that

00:29:31.960 --> 00:29:33.800
[Guest]: lane takes you to my village.

00:29:33.800 --> 00:29:37.080
[Guest]: My cousin had come to pick me up from the bus stand.

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:42.120
[Guest]: So then I was on a bike with him and we were going, this is a few years ago.

00:29:42.120 --> 00:29:46.200
[Guest]: And then as we got into the lane and came near the village, there was a Maruti van,

00:29:46.200 --> 00:29:52.720
[Guest]: a car parked next to the lane and with this very bright light, fluorescent light glowing

00:29:52.720 --> 00:29:55.680
[Guest]: from inside and very loud music being played.

00:29:55.680 --> 00:29:58.600
[Guest]: So I said, this is very odd for us to see that in a village, right?

00:29:58.600 --> 00:30:04.280
[Guest]: And then some guy is sitting there and drinking Limca, Limca, Coke, mostly Limca.

00:30:04.280 --> 00:30:05.920
[Guest]: And I said, what's going on?

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:10.760
[Guest]: So my cousin said something about, you know, basically a caste related thing that these

00:30:10.760 --> 00:30:15.200
[Guest]: guys have gone and earned some money abroad from the city and showing off in the village.

00:30:15.200 --> 00:30:17.560
[Guest]: So I said, yeah, very interesting.

00:30:17.560 --> 00:30:19.960
[Guest]: So that's one image.

00:30:19.960 --> 00:30:22.580
[Guest]: Another image is of locked houses.

00:30:22.580 --> 00:30:26.560
[Guest]: So quite a few people in my village have basically left the village now.

00:30:26.560 --> 00:30:31.480
[Guest]: I mean, the urbanization is happening at a much rapid pace than perhaps even the official

00:30:31.480 --> 00:30:33.020
[Guest]: data actually indicates.

00:30:33.020 --> 00:30:39.040
[Guest]: So lots of people are moving into cities in a manner that the entire family is gone.

00:30:39.040 --> 00:30:43.200
[Guest]: So lots of houses are now basically locked.

00:30:43.200 --> 00:30:48.320
[Guest]: I mean, I wouldn't say at the percentage, it may not be very large, but it's conspicuous.

00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:52.840
[Guest]: So maybe 5% or 10% of the houses are now basically locked.

00:30:52.840 --> 00:30:57.920
[Guest]: And earlier what used to happen is that obviously some member of the family will go to the city

00:30:57.920 --> 00:31:01.880
[Guest]: to earn and maybe even settle down like we did.

00:31:01.880 --> 00:31:05.240
[Guest]: And but there will be people in the village, like in my family, most of the families still

00:31:05.240 --> 00:31:06.400
[Guest]: live in the village.

00:31:06.400 --> 00:31:11.720
[Guest]: But there are now families that are basically just up and left and that will have some impact

00:31:11.720 --> 00:31:18.520
[Guest]: on kind of village life there, you know, if you're part of the village can entirely leave.

00:31:18.520 --> 00:31:22.800
[Guest]: Third is that you see, and market has entered significant ways.

00:31:22.800 --> 00:31:25.840
[Guest]: So my village, slightly larger village than the nearby village.

00:31:25.840 --> 00:31:28.320
[Guest]: So people come there for transactions, economic transactions.

00:31:28.320 --> 00:31:34.160
[Guest]: So 30 years ago, you could only see basically agriculture commodities being exchanged there

00:31:34.160 --> 00:31:36.800
[Guest]: on a Thursday market that used to be held in my village.

00:31:36.800 --> 00:31:41.440
[Guest]: Now you see much more, you know, there are many more products being sold and bought and

00:31:41.440 --> 00:31:43.280
[Guest]: this much larger market.

00:31:43.280 --> 00:31:50.400
[Guest]: And this is, of course, outside of the APMC, you know, the India markets work if the state

00:31:50.400 --> 00:31:55.080
[Guest]: is not looking at it very carefully.

00:31:55.080 --> 00:31:58.400
[Guest]: So the market has expanded very significantly.

00:31:58.400 --> 00:32:03.320
[Guest]: This is something I've got a very clear 30 year, year on year time series on what was

00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:04.320
[Guest]: being sold earlier.

00:32:04.320 --> 00:32:09.240
[Guest]: I used to go there, we would get five rupees to go and go in the market on Thursday evening.

00:32:09.240 --> 00:32:14.760
[Guest]: Now it's much more selling, many more people are participating across different caste groups

00:32:14.760 --> 00:32:16.480
[Guest]: and all of that.

00:32:16.480 --> 00:32:22.240
[Guest]: So there's urbanization, there is some degree of mobility, I think, as far as people going

00:32:22.240 --> 00:32:27.160
[Guest]: to cities especially is concerned, there is some degree of market activity in this in

00:32:27.160 --> 00:32:28.160
[Guest]: the villages.

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:31.160
[Guest]: But overall, I think the village productivity story is not taken off.

00:32:31.160 --> 00:32:36.520
[Guest]: So if you look at my own village land and how much we earn from the land per acre or

00:32:36.520 --> 00:32:40.600
[Guest]: something, it's a very, very small improvement over 30-40 years.

00:32:40.600 --> 00:32:46.080
[Guest]: And that's a big problem because it's basically become that so much of the migration in India

00:32:46.080 --> 00:32:49.880
[Guest]: is now pushed that you don't have anything to do in the village, so you move out and

00:32:49.880 --> 00:32:50.880
[Guest]: do other things.

00:32:50.880 --> 00:32:55.800
[Guest]: So we need to get the agriculture, you know, productivity story right, invest in infrastructure,

00:32:55.800 --> 00:32:58.520
[Guest]: get the markets working, whatever is required.

00:32:58.520 --> 00:33:02.680
[Guest]: I study a little bit of this, I'm not an expert myself, my colleagues have worked on it, that

00:33:02.680 --> 00:33:07.960
[Guest]: per acre productivity in countries like Taiwan and China and all is much higher than us and

00:33:07.960 --> 00:33:09.280
[Guest]: we need to get it right.

00:33:09.280 --> 00:33:14.240
[Guest]: So that's become a problem because especially for people who have land, you know, it's become

00:33:14.240 --> 00:33:19.040
[Guest]: like an albatross around your neck or I don't know what the right metaphor is, it basically

00:33:19.040 --> 00:33:20.960
[Guest]: ties you down in some ways.

00:33:20.960 --> 00:33:23.920
[Guest]: And in fact, people who don't have land are more free, you know, because they don't have

00:33:23.920 --> 00:33:29.440
[Guest]: much anyway, so by the way of property, they freely move and go try to find, it's not easy

00:33:29.440 --> 00:33:33.600
[Guest]: to make it in the city, so I wouldn't underestimate the struggle.

00:33:33.600 --> 00:33:36.280
[Guest]: But there is at least less to be tied down with.

00:33:36.280 --> 00:33:39.320
[Guest]: And that is creating, I think, some degree of bad blood also.

00:33:39.320 --> 00:33:43.200
[Guest]: So I think we are seeing a little bit more of conflict in some ways.

00:33:43.200 --> 00:33:47.160
[Guest]: I'm just talking about my little microcosm, there's a little bit more conflict across

00:33:47.160 --> 00:33:52.400
[Guest]: identity groups, a little more perhaps because there is a little bit more envy that people

00:33:52.400 --> 00:33:58.200
[Guest]: who are supposed to be, you know, in a different class have suddenly, you know, in just a few

00:33:58.200 --> 00:34:02.760
[Guest]: years gone and gotten a little cash rich, you know, and therefore are able to assert

00:34:02.760 --> 00:34:07.680
[Guest]: their identities in a little more assertive, more clear way.

00:34:07.680 --> 00:34:13.240
[Guest]: So it is a time of churning, you know, and it's been a time of churning for because see,

00:34:13.240 --> 00:34:15.040
[Guest]: I am talking about the last 30 years.

00:34:15.040 --> 00:34:20.600
[Guest]: So basically, this is a period of, you know, economic renewal in India, revival, renewal,

00:34:20.600 --> 00:34:21.600
[Guest]: whatever you called it.

00:34:21.600 --> 00:34:25.320
[Guest]: This is a period in which there has been quite a bit of economic activity in India, even

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:31.560
[Guest]: though UP has been not as much touched, but UP has done, I mean, better than it had done

00:34:31.560 --> 00:34:32.560
[Guest]: earlier.

00:34:32.560 --> 00:34:35.000
[Guest]: Plus, also people from UP go and work all over the country.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:39.840
[Guest]: So my village, in fact, the main destination is Bombay, you know, people who go out to

00:34:39.840 --> 00:34:41.680
[Guest]: work, they work in Bombay mostly.

00:34:41.680 --> 00:34:46.520
[Guest]: Lately, many of them have been going to Kerala, Bangalore also, and some come to Delhi.

00:34:46.520 --> 00:34:50.120
[Guest]: But main destination is Bombay and Bombay has always had cash opportunities, you know,

00:34:50.120 --> 00:34:53.760
[Guest]: you land up there and you can make 500 rupees a day, basically at the beginning itself.

00:34:53.760 --> 00:34:57.000
[Guest]: And that's the thing Bombay even today offers.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:03.180
[Guest]: So even though UP itself hasn't got its kind of economic story, right, there is a long

00:35:03.180 --> 00:35:06.680
[Guest]: distance migration that is to be done to be able to make some money.

00:35:06.680 --> 00:35:11.480
[Guest]: My village has always had, at least for last 30 years has that.

00:35:11.480 --> 00:35:16.360
[Guest]: So this churning is economic and social and also to some extent political, you know, like

00:35:16.360 --> 00:35:22.040
[Guest]: I see so much of this coalitions happening across because every year, every election

00:35:22.040 --> 00:35:26.240
[Guest]: there are different party wins in my part of that constituency.

00:35:26.240 --> 00:35:33.560
[Guest]: So and caste alignments are becoming far more, you know, flexible in some senses.

00:35:33.560 --> 00:35:37.960
[Guest]: And I think BJP has a lot to do with because BJP has been making claims for all kinds of,

00:35:37.960 --> 00:35:44.040
[Guest]: you know, because they believe that pretty much anybody who identifies as an Indian can

00:35:44.040 --> 00:35:45.040
[Guest]: vote for them.

00:35:45.040 --> 00:35:47.320
[Guest]: So they make claims for everybody's vote basically.

00:35:47.320 --> 00:35:52.400
[Guest]: So they've been able to make headways into a number of communities and then others have

00:35:52.400 --> 00:35:55.720
[Guest]: to hit back and try to claim what they think is there.

00:35:55.720 --> 00:36:00.960
[Guest]: So political mobilization has also become very, very, very intense, I would say.

00:36:00.960 --> 00:36:04.000
[Guest]: So whenever I go to my village now, there is some kind of, I haven't been in the last

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:07.640
[Guest]: two years, so to be very clear, because of various reasons.

00:36:07.640 --> 00:36:12.400
[Guest]: But until then, whenever you go, basically, there's so much activity happening, you know,

00:36:12.400 --> 00:36:19.440
[Guest]: like something will be happening, either BJP doing some kind of a Ramayana Katha or some

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:25.040
[Guest]: kind of bhajan or some social, we are socially very active and politically also very active.

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:27.040
[Guest]: So these things come together sometimes.

00:36:27.040 --> 00:36:32.120
[Guest]: So one of the things about my village is that it holds the entire Ramayana, this, it stages

00:36:32.120 --> 00:36:35.540
[Guest]: the Ramayana during the Dussehra time.

00:36:35.540 --> 00:36:41.720
[Guest]: So every day, so somebody will play Lord Ram, somebody will play Sitaji, somebody will play

00:36:41.720 --> 00:36:48.240
[Guest]: Lakshman, somebody I used to know, recently used to play Hanuman, he was a local Pehalwan

00:36:48.240 --> 00:36:52.040
[Guest]: and it used to be a very seriously done thing, you know.

00:36:52.040 --> 00:36:55.640
[Guest]: So those traditions have continued, but there is a little more commercialization around

00:36:55.640 --> 00:36:56.640
[Guest]: it.

00:36:56.640 --> 00:37:00.280
[Guest]: So now they get sponsorships, all of that earlier, it used to be just Chanda, go to

00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:03.320
[Guest]: hand, family after family, collect Chanda.

00:37:03.320 --> 00:37:07.160
[Guest]: So I think the association life is still very rich.

00:37:07.160 --> 00:37:14.520
[Guest]: So there is, there are all kinds, so there is, I know there is a Jawahar Yuva Mandli,

00:37:14.520 --> 00:37:22.240
[Guest]: which is basically, it's kept after Nehruji's name, that it's an association of young people.

00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:27.260
[Guest]: Most of them are BJP supporters, but Mandli is still called Jawahar Yuva Mandli.

00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:32.640
[Guest]: But then there is a Gau Raksha Samiti, but not the kind that gets the bad news, but they

00:37:32.640 --> 00:37:37.120
[Guest]: take care of cows that are basically abandoned by others and all of that.

00:37:37.120 --> 00:37:40.880
[Guest]: There is a market and I think because more resources have become available, a little

00:37:40.880 --> 00:37:45.720
[Guest]: more than earlier, people are able to do these things in a slightly grander scale.

00:37:45.720 --> 00:37:49.600
[Guest]: So yeah, so there is churning, there is a little more conflict, there are more opportunities

00:37:49.600 --> 00:37:50.600
[Guest]: overall.

00:37:50.600 --> 00:37:56.120
[Guest]: There is more opening to different people of different identities, men or women of different

00:37:56.120 --> 00:37:57.120
[Guest]: groups.

00:37:57.120 --> 00:38:02.560
[Guest]: And I mean, I would say, I mean, to put a long story short is that we are modernizing,

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:04.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, in our own way.

00:38:04.560 --> 00:38:11.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and those two stories, the first two stories you told have such resonant images.

00:38:11.080 --> 00:38:16.240
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I can totally imagine a book called The Village of Locked Houses, or the image

00:38:16.240 --> 00:38:20.200
[Amit Varma]: of people drinking Limca in a car with fluorescent light from inside.

00:38:20.200 --> 00:38:23.280
[Amit Varma]: And both those stories in one sense are stories of escape.

00:38:23.280 --> 00:38:27.340
[Amit Varma]: Like in the Limca case, it's like you pointed out a bunch of people, they are trapped within

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:29.560
[Amit Varma]: this caste identity and so on.

00:38:29.560 --> 00:38:33.680
[Amit Varma]: But then they go to a city and they feel like with, you know, with what they've earned and

00:38:33.680 --> 00:38:37.680
[Amit Varma]: living a better life, perhaps they can transcend it, perhaps they can escape it.

00:38:37.680 --> 00:38:42.360
[Amit Varma]: And the other story of locked houses is again, very overtly a story of escape, you want to

00:38:42.360 --> 00:38:43.360
[Amit Varma]: get away from the village.

00:38:43.360 --> 00:38:47.900
[Amit Varma]: And you spoke about how, you know, a lot of people leave villages and go to cities because

00:38:47.900 --> 00:38:49.240
[Amit Varma]: of the push factor.

00:38:49.240 --> 00:38:51.160
[Amit Varma]: It is not what is attracting them.

00:38:51.160 --> 00:38:55.560
[Amit Varma]: But it is life is so nasty, brutish and short, as it were.

00:38:55.560 --> 00:38:59.520
[Guest]: Not really nasty, brutish and short, but it's not an easy life.

00:38:59.520 --> 00:39:01.720
[Amit Varma]: And if you have better opportunities, you go out.

00:39:01.720 --> 00:39:07.320
[Amit Varma]: So, my question, therefore, is about how have aspirations changed?

00:39:07.320 --> 00:39:13.680
[Amit Varma]: Because I imagine that in an earlier generation, you know, your typical aspirations would be

00:39:13.680 --> 00:39:17.800
[Amit Varma]: that if life is tough in a village and you can't make it there, that you get some kind

00:39:17.800 --> 00:39:21.400
[Amit Varma]: of government job somewhere, either in the village or the nearby town or the city or

00:39:21.400 --> 00:39:22.400
[Amit Varma]: whatever.

00:39:22.400 --> 00:39:25.440
[Amit Varma]: But you get a government job because the government is everything back in the day before liberalization

00:39:25.440 --> 00:39:30.600
[Amit Varma]: and you become part of the rent seeking apparatus and being part of the government raises your

00:39:30.600 --> 00:39:33.720
[Amit Varma]: social status and all of that comes into play, right?

00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:38.840
[Amit Varma]: But in these times where, number one, markets are much more visible, there are many more

00:39:38.840 --> 00:39:41.100
[Amit Varma]: different kinds of opportunities.

00:39:41.100 --> 00:39:47.520
[Amit Varma]: And number two, technology and the spread of the smartphone, especially post geo, when

00:39:47.520 --> 00:39:52.480
[Amit Varma]: broadband kind of became much more widely available, you know, how does that change

00:39:52.480 --> 00:39:56.160
[Amit Varma]: aspirations and the way that you look at the world and all of that?

00:39:56.160 --> 00:40:01.300
[Amit Varma]: And how does all that also change the politics, because I imagine in the past, from the views

00:40:01.300 --> 00:40:06.720
[Amit Varma]: I have, and you can correct me if they are not nuanced enough, but in the past, I would

00:40:06.720 --> 00:40:10.500
[Amit Varma]: imagine that your village politics would really revolve around two things.

00:40:10.500 --> 00:40:15.000
[Amit Varma]: One is you vote for whatever tribe you have taken, and I don't literally mean tribe, but

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:20.040
[Amit Varma]: whichever side you have taken, so you get some of the spoils of power are shared with

00:40:20.040 --> 00:40:24.400
[Amit Varma]: you or shared by whatever identity grouping you're part of that you voted for.

00:40:24.400 --> 00:40:29.300
[Amit Varma]: And the other is an assertion of that tribal feeling, you know, a lot of voting is actually

00:40:29.300 --> 00:40:32.880
[Amit Varma]: all voting is in a sense irrational at the individual level, because one vote doesn't

00:40:32.880 --> 00:40:33.960
[Amit Varma]: make a difference.

00:40:33.960 --> 00:40:38.380
[Amit Varma]: But people still do it for a variety of complicated reasons, one of which is you're asserting

00:40:38.380 --> 00:40:41.960
[Amit Varma]: your identity, you're saying I'm part of this group, you know, I'll go to watch a, you know,

00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:44.480
[Amit Varma]: Manchester City match, because that's my tribe, right?

00:40:44.480 --> 00:40:47.960
[Amit Varma]: So I'll go vote for Bhajapal or whatever, because that's my tribe.

00:40:47.960 --> 00:40:52.840
[Amit Varma]: And I would imagine these would in the past have been the dominant two reasons for voting.

00:40:52.840 --> 00:40:57.720
[Amit Varma]: And I'm wondering if aspirations regarding to that have also changed since you point

00:40:57.720 --> 00:41:01.360
[Amit Varma]: out that politics has become much more fluid, in a sense.

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:06.920
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, in contrast with what we think about voter apathy, like, again, I have an

00:41:06.920 --> 00:41:10.760
[Amit Varma]: old impression from a long while back, you probably know better, that people in urban

00:41:10.760 --> 00:41:12.800
[Amit Varma]: areas vote less than people in rural areas.

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:13.800
[Amit Varma]: Is that true?

00:41:13.800 --> 00:41:15.440
[Guest]: Or am I getting it the other way around?

00:41:15.440 --> 00:41:16.440
[Guest]: That's true.

00:41:16.440 --> 00:41:17.440
[Guest]: That's true.

00:41:17.440 --> 00:41:18.440
[Amit Varma]: People vote more.

00:41:18.440 --> 00:41:19.440
[Amit Varma]: Vote more.

00:41:19.440 --> 00:41:23.180
[Amit Varma]: And that's because people in cities tend to be sort of more apathetic and whatever.

00:41:23.180 --> 00:41:24.600
[Amit Varma]: So what's your sense of all of this?

00:41:24.600 --> 00:41:26.640
[Amit Varma]: How have aspirations changed?

00:41:26.640 --> 00:41:29.520
[Amit Varma]: What does a young person in a village now want?

00:41:29.520 --> 00:41:33.440
[Amit Varma]: Like what would your nephews and nieces in the village, what would they want as a kind

00:41:33.440 --> 00:41:34.440
[Amit Varma]: of growing up?

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:35.960
[Amit Varma]: What are they thinking of?

00:41:35.960 --> 00:41:38.840
[Amit Varma]: And then as a secondary thing, how does that play into the politics?

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:41.560
[Guest]: Yeah, so you started the question on government jobs.

00:41:41.560 --> 00:41:47.280
[Guest]: So yeah, I think it's even now, because of age compression and similar issues, privileges,

00:41:47.280 --> 00:41:51.320
[Guest]: government job is still a preferred kind of entry point into the urban life, or even if

00:41:51.320 --> 00:41:55.840
[Guest]: you get in the rural area, a government job, I mean, it's pretty good, because the kind

00:41:55.840 --> 00:41:57.800
[Amit Varma]: of wage compression that we have.

00:41:57.800 --> 00:41:59.040
[Amit Varma]: What do you mean wage compression?

00:41:59.040 --> 00:42:04.240
[Guest]: So the entry wage to top wage ratio is quite compressed there.

00:42:04.240 --> 00:42:07.520
[Guest]: So this entry wage is quite good here.

00:42:07.520 --> 00:42:14.240
[Guest]: If you start even at the lowest rank official in government, you get at least twice of what

00:42:14.240 --> 00:42:17.400
[Guest]: you would make in any other comparable kind of position in private sector.

00:42:17.400 --> 00:42:20.400
[Amit Varma]: Though you would rise faster there, but you're getting a guaranteed income and stability.

00:42:20.400 --> 00:42:23.200
[Guest]: But it's also a secure job, other privileges, as I said.

00:42:23.200 --> 00:42:26.920
[Guest]: So it's still there, but it's basically become like a lottery, okay, you'll get it and some

00:42:26.920 --> 00:42:31.680
[Guest]: people who are good in studies, they aspire to good government jobs, like they write UPSC

00:42:31.680 --> 00:42:32.680
[Guest]: exams and all.

00:42:32.680 --> 00:42:36.920
[Guest]: Although once in a generation, once in five, six years, somebody will crack a serious like

00:42:36.920 --> 00:42:40.360
[Guest]: PCA, Professional Civil Services or IAS exam.

00:42:40.360 --> 00:42:46.840
[Guest]: Others will try to get entry into CRPF and police and all and that's a larger number,

00:42:46.840 --> 00:42:47.840
[Guest]: much larger number.

00:42:47.840 --> 00:42:51.480
[Guest]: I know at least quite a few people personally who have become, who at least got into CRPF

00:42:51.480 --> 00:42:58.040
[Guest]: or BSF and all these kind of places where you have a clear entry condition and you pass

00:42:58.040 --> 00:42:59.040
[Guest]: that and you can get in.

00:42:59.040 --> 00:43:06.040
[Guest]: For the rest, as you said, rightly, that the economy has changed significantly and we are

00:43:06.040 --> 00:43:11.160
[Guest]: one country, so whenever, see, it's just a question of longer train rides, right?

00:43:11.160 --> 00:43:15.160
[Guest]: Because you take overnight, you get to Delhi, a little over, more than overnight, get to

00:43:15.160 --> 00:43:16.160
[Guest]: Delhi.

00:43:16.160 --> 00:43:21.000
[Guest]: Travel for 12 more hours, you get to Bombay, you travel for 12 more hours, you get to Bangalore

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:22.080
[Guest]: and travel a little more.

00:43:22.080 --> 00:43:26.880
[Guest]: And then, I mean, if you're going there for a long time and you're trying to, and it's

00:43:26.880 --> 00:43:27.880
[Guest]: not an issue.

00:43:27.880 --> 00:43:31.640
[Guest]: And one of the things that I think about India is that you feel like it's India wherever

00:43:31.640 --> 00:43:32.640
[Guest]: you go.

00:43:32.640 --> 00:43:36.280
[Guest]: Because that's something that I always felt, I've been to most states of India and you

00:43:36.280 --> 00:43:42.560
[Guest]: feel some kind of familiarity, very strangely, but language is very different, cuisine is

00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:43.920
[Guest]: quite different.

00:43:43.920 --> 00:43:49.480
[Guest]: But there is, in the unconscious, there is something about Indian, of course, go to temple,

00:43:49.480 --> 00:43:53.920
[Guest]: you see some other form of the deity, but you see, you can make a connection, you know,

00:43:53.920 --> 00:43:58.560
[Guest]: like I didn't have as much difficulty doing darshan in temples in the south, you know,

00:43:58.560 --> 00:44:01.720
[Guest]: because I could see where the larger mythology is coming from.

00:44:01.720 --> 00:44:06.520
[Guest]: So anyway, so the point of the matter is that the opportunities have really increased in

00:44:06.520 --> 00:44:11.040
[Guest]: terms of, not in my village as such, they have increased a little, but you know how

00:44:11.040 --> 00:44:16.240
[Guest]: UP is and how it's not been as bad as, say, some states like Bihar have done, but it has

00:44:16.240 --> 00:44:20.920
[Guest]: also not done as well as some of the states like Haryana and Tamil Nadu and all of them.

00:44:20.920 --> 00:44:23.840
[Guest]: But so you have the opportunity to move out.

00:44:23.840 --> 00:44:29.000
[Guest]: So there's a lot of seasonal migration, basically, to get a fine and have a footing in the urban

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:30.000
[Guest]: area.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:31.000
[Guest]: So I'm now talking about large numbers.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:35.160
[Guest]: So there are some who get a government job or something, some who get a better higher

00:44:35.160 --> 00:44:38.180
[Guest]: quality private job, like a formal job.

00:44:38.180 --> 00:44:42.280
[Guest]: But most of them, actually, most of the people can't do that, you know, even, even if you

00:44:42.280 --> 00:44:46.360
[Guest]: have a slightly better family, if unless you have very good studies and all, it's very

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:47.360
[Guest]: difficult to do that.

00:44:47.360 --> 00:44:53.880
[Guest]: So there are two paths, either you go and work as a entry level worker in any, you can

00:44:53.880 --> 00:44:58.560
[Guest]: get into a private bank, basically trying to, in the sales side, if you have got a little

00:44:58.560 --> 00:45:01.720
[Guest]: bit of education, or if you are actually you got no education, then you have to basically

00:45:01.720 --> 00:45:06.040
[Guest]: work as a manual labourer and then work and get some skills.

00:45:06.040 --> 00:45:09.920
[Guest]: So within that there are directions, some people have become contractors, or some people

00:45:09.920 --> 00:45:14.280
[Guest]: who went as manual labourers, then in 10 years, they became contractors who then started sourcing

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:17.040
[Guest]: labourers from from our village.

00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:19.980
[Guest]: Then that's so that's one set of paths, there is a trading path.

00:45:19.980 --> 00:45:24.680
[Guest]: So you start trading something, so you start getting stuff from some other part of the

00:45:24.680 --> 00:45:29.240
[Guest]: country and selling here or get take something from here and sell somewhere else.

00:45:29.240 --> 00:45:33.000
[Guest]: Because markets have become a little more, you know, vibrant, there are more opportunities

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:34.000
[Guest]: of that kind.

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:39.120
[Guest]: So for example, in my village, there are a few shops that get the person takes a truck

00:45:39.120 --> 00:45:45.880
[Guest]: travels to Punjab, buys clothes and sells here at 2x basically the price, and including

00:45:45.880 --> 00:45:49.800
[Guest]: the transaction costs of going and coming and and still the reasonable business, somebody

00:45:49.800 --> 00:45:54.320
[Guest]: does the same thing with shoes, they'll go to Agra or somewhere else and get it.

00:45:54.320 --> 00:45:59.040
[Guest]: So the opportunities are now much greater, agriculture has become basically a much smaller

00:45:59.040 --> 00:46:00.600
[Guest]: part of the economy.

00:46:00.600 --> 00:46:02.720
[Guest]: That's the main main thing that has happened.

00:46:02.720 --> 00:46:07.760
[Guest]: So earlier as a share of the activities in village, if you're a landless labourer, something

00:46:07.760 --> 00:46:12.280
[Guest]: and it's not just NREGA, NREGA has had an impact on that as well, because it's pushed

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:13.280
[Guest]: the wages up.

00:46:13.280 --> 00:46:16.640
[Guest]: But there's just so many other opportunities going on at the same time, because the economy

00:46:16.640 --> 00:46:22.040
[Guest]: is growing and not just maybe not in UP, but you just see Haryana is the richest large

00:46:22.040 --> 00:46:26.280
[Guest]: state in the country in per capita income, and it's basically overnight from our from

00:46:26.280 --> 00:46:28.200
[Guest]: our part of the country.

00:46:28.200 --> 00:46:32.080
[Guest]: So you can just go there and if you go to Gurgaon, you will you will end up earning

00:46:32.080 --> 00:46:35.640
[Guest]: at least a decent way so that and what you send back is actually has a much more purchasing

00:46:35.640 --> 00:46:36.640
[Guest]: power, right?

00:46:36.640 --> 00:46:41.280
[Guest]: Even if you send back 200 rupees a day, that 200 rupees a day goes a long way in the village

00:46:41.280 --> 00:46:42.720
[Guest]: as cash goes.

00:46:42.720 --> 00:46:47.440
[Guest]: So the so economic aspirations have really diversified a lot.

00:46:47.440 --> 00:46:51.280
[Guest]: So people are seeking different paths, because they're also good at different things.

00:46:51.280 --> 00:46:55.200
[Guest]: And obviously, you have to keep maintaining the dynamism in the economy to be able to

00:46:55.200 --> 00:46:58.280
[Guest]: do that, you know, to have these opportunities growing.

00:46:58.280 --> 00:47:02.600
[Guest]: So I think these are still I'm talking about mostly about men.

00:47:02.600 --> 00:47:06.160
[Guest]: For women, it's still if you're a woman born in a village, still there are very few

00:47:06.160 --> 00:47:11.440
[Guest]: paths that are available to you directly, unless you get very like, I know, one of my

00:47:11.440 --> 00:47:14.960
[Guest]: neighbor's daughter, she actually got very good, she's very good at studies, she got

00:47:14.960 --> 00:47:20.720
[Guest]: admission in Ames, you know, and did medicine there and basically settled here in national

00:47:20.720 --> 00:47:22.600
[Guest]: capital territory only.

00:47:22.600 --> 00:47:26.600
[Guest]: And but that's very rare, otherwise, basically, the best thing you can aspire to be is a government

00:47:26.600 --> 00:47:31.520
[Guest]: school teacher, still, because one of the main reasons is very poor quality education

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:32.720
[Guest]: in my village.

00:47:32.720 --> 00:47:36.000
[Guest]: So I told you about my father and how he studied in a village school.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:39.920
[Guest]: And there were two good teachers there, who basically, you know, there's, I think Henry

00:47:39.920 --> 00:47:46.760
[Guest]: James, a teacher, she's at Trinity, you know, so it's like that he they basically were so

00:47:46.760 --> 00:47:51.720
[Guest]: virtuous and so devoted to the what you call goods internal to the practice of teaching,

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:56.720
[Guest]: you know, they were just enjoy teaching so much, that they just changed lives, you know,

00:47:56.720 --> 00:47:59.240
[Guest]: and now this just gone.

00:47:59.240 --> 00:48:03.120
[Guest]: And that just shapes the paths of so many kids in my village.

00:48:03.120 --> 00:48:06.440
[Guest]: So the small number that I'm talking about, who are able to get good jobs and all could

00:48:06.440 --> 00:48:12.400
[Guest]: be much larger, if you had just one good teacher, or one good school with two, three good teachers,

00:48:12.400 --> 00:48:17.880
[Guest]: who just did their basic duties, you know, and then there's so much hunger in this in

00:48:17.880 --> 00:48:22.880
[Guest]: my part of the in my village, on young kids, whenever I go and try to talk to them or what

00:48:22.880 --> 00:48:26.760
[Guest]: they plan, they just want to get ahead, you know, they're young, they're full of dreams.

00:48:26.760 --> 00:48:31.600
[Guest]: But I feel that many of them will basically settle down at something which is much below

00:48:31.600 --> 00:48:32.600
[Guest]: their potential.

00:48:32.600 --> 00:48:38.560
[Guest]: So when my father retired, he started this practice of basically going and doing counseling

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:40.500
[Guest]: for kids in village schools.

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:46.360
[Guest]: So he used to just take here a driver in a car, just go and give a talk to all the students

00:48:46.360 --> 00:48:51.160
[Guest]: in a school orientation talk, then give each of them a psychometric test of their aptitude.

00:48:51.160 --> 00:48:53.240
[Guest]: These are the ninth or 10th standard kids.

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:57.200
[Guest]: So they have some, some understanding of, you know, some aptitude has formed in some

00:48:57.200 --> 00:49:01.680
[Guest]: sense is clear, what is a good direction for them to take, and then give them some guidance.

00:49:01.680 --> 00:49:05.560
[Guest]: He developed these tools with some psychology professors in Gorakhpur University only who

00:49:05.560 --> 00:49:09.600
[Guest]: also seemed keen to at least contribute to their community in some ways.

00:49:09.600 --> 00:49:14.200
[Guest]: And he did, there was thousands of kids, you know, to just give them some kind of guidance

00:49:14.200 --> 00:49:18.100
[Guest]: about what would be good for them, what would be a suitable path for them.

00:49:18.100 --> 00:49:22.800
[Guest]: And he used to tell me the hunger with which he was, you know, received, because nobody

00:49:22.800 --> 00:49:26.560
[Guest]: would talk to them, you know, nobody would say, see, internet is full of a lot of information,

00:49:26.560 --> 00:49:30.520
[Guest]: but guidance is not information, guidance is somebody has to take interest in you, you

00:49:30.520 --> 00:49:34.440
[Guest]: know, somebody has to care about you, somebody has to follow you up and somebody has to push

00:49:34.440 --> 00:49:38.880
[Guest]: you when you're feeling down, you know, and that's just missing from our, I mean, at least

00:49:38.880 --> 00:49:43.880
[Guest]: in my village, the private schools that we have and the government school, and I'm sorry

00:49:43.880 --> 00:49:47.320
[Guest]: to say one of the private school is run by my family also, where the teachers simply

00:49:47.320 --> 00:49:52.400
[Guest]: are not, they're just going through the motions, you know, and whenever we try to say, okay,

00:49:52.400 --> 00:49:55.960
[Guest]: can you do it, but the whole economy is set up in such a way that you get teachers who

00:49:55.960 --> 00:50:00.560
[Guest]: pay a little, you can't pay as much, you know, in a private school as the government schools

00:50:00.560 --> 00:50:01.680
[Guest]: get paid.

00:50:01.680 --> 00:50:05.440
[Guest]: And they do it only as a part time thing, and you lucky once in a while, you find a

00:50:05.440 --> 00:50:10.200
[Guest]: good teacher, but then they leave and go elsewhere. In the government school, they get paid a

00:50:10.200 --> 00:50:15.480
[Guest]: very good entry salary for a young teacher in government school is several times of the

00:50:15.480 --> 00:50:21.680
[Guest]: per capita income of that village. But they don't teach and that's a big problem, I think,

00:50:21.680 --> 00:50:27.140
[Guest]: because for the private or government, nobody teaches basically, people send under the illusion

00:50:27.140 --> 00:50:32.440
[Guest]: that private schools are doing better, but they have better, you know, looks, so to speak,

00:50:32.440 --> 00:50:36.440
[Guest]: in terms of, you know, teachers come on time and leave on time. But whether you're learning,

00:50:36.440 --> 00:50:42.240
[Guest]: I really doubt it. So that's become a very big impediment to opportunities are there.

00:50:42.240 --> 00:50:46.480
[Guest]: And if you had a little bit better thing going for you, more guidance, not even so much skill,

00:50:46.480 --> 00:50:52.400
[Guest]: you know, like, if you look at like low end manufacturing, decent salaries, one of my

00:50:52.400 --> 00:50:57.920
[Guest]: neighbors, I mean, a few not neighbor like 50 meters away from us, he got a job in escort

00:50:57.920 --> 00:51:02.880
[Guest]: a young man, and his whole family got lifted out of difficulty because he and then he got

00:51:02.880 --> 00:51:06.680
[Guest]: his brother also there. Then his nephew also got, you know, three people with a formal

00:51:06.680 --> 00:51:10.640
[Guest]: sector job, their entry level only, but they got skilled in the on the job because see,

00:51:10.640 --> 00:51:14.160
[Guest]: at entry level jobs in manufacturing, you don't need to be a very well educated person,

00:51:14.160 --> 00:51:18.360
[Guest]: they'll train you, apprenticeship works very well. Only thing is some basic education and

00:51:18.360 --> 00:51:22.560
[Guest]: some guidance key where to go and where to look that even that is sometimes missing this

00:51:22.560 --> 00:51:27.640
[Guest]: is kind of a big information asymmetry, there are transaction costs that come in the way.

00:51:27.640 --> 00:51:32.760
[Guest]: And there is, I think, if more of that would be there, then these aspirations will be fulfilled

00:51:32.760 --> 00:51:37.800
[Guest]: in a more in a better way, but markets are working. So more or less, we'll have better

00:51:37.800 --> 00:51:42.760
[Guest]: situation than if we had earlier, but public systems and even the private systems on education

00:51:42.760 --> 00:51:49.280
[Guest]: and all are failing. And it's a greatest tragedy, I see, because I've grown up with these guys,

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:53.400
[Guest]: like who are my eyes to play with them. Now, I'm in my late 30s. They're also late 30s.

00:51:53.400 --> 00:51:58.600
[Guest]: They have nothing, you know, like a childhood friend of mine, he drives a taxi in the village

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:02.200
[Guest]: from one place to another and then plies and it's a hard life. It's a very tough life.

00:52:02.200 --> 00:52:07.680
[Guest]: It's also not a life of great dignity, because people don't treat you very well. So it's

00:52:07.680 --> 00:52:12.280
[Guest]: a and I mean, I wouldn't say I don't know what he would have done, who knows. But I

00:52:12.280 --> 00:52:15.440
[Guest]: mean, if just a different setting, he would have done completely different, his life would

00:52:15.440 --> 00:52:20.000
[Guest]: have been very different. So overall Indian economy is a low middle income economy. So

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:25.960
[Guest]: it's not like we're a rich country. And within that, I think these failures of systems in

00:52:25.960 --> 00:52:28.360
[Guest]: our part of the world makes it even harder.

00:52:28.360 --> 00:52:32.700
[Guest]: Now on the politics, I mean, which is all intertwined in this, because it's like democracy

00:52:32.700 --> 00:52:37.760
[Guest]: is working its way through India, and it's been working its way through India 77-75 years.

00:52:37.760 --> 00:52:43.560
[Guest]: There is more or less now a sense of you know, that even in my lifetime, you know, I've born

00:52:43.560 --> 00:52:49.980
[Guest]: about halfway into the democracies life. And I've seen like, there is much more of a sense

00:52:49.980 --> 00:52:53.960
[Guest]: of equality people, the way people assert themselves and talk, you know, there's a much

00:52:53.960 --> 00:52:59.120
[Guest]: more subservient sense, if you're poorer than you would assume that you are inferior, you

00:52:59.120 --> 00:53:03.680
[Guest]: know, in that sense, forget about whether I, a person of upper caste will say that you

00:53:03.680 --> 00:53:09.440
[Guest]: are inferior, there was a subjective sense that your place in society is such and such.

00:53:09.440 --> 00:53:15.180
[Guest]: And that I think is so significantly changed in just last 25 years itself that I've seen.

00:53:15.180 --> 00:53:20.080
[Guest]: Because this whole, that local myth has broken, right, like there's now boundaries are broken,

00:53:20.080 --> 00:53:24.160
[Guest]: urbanization, capitalism, all of that has come in. And there's, it's just much more

00:53:24.160 --> 00:53:29.480
[Guest]: of a, when people talk, they'll say, okay, we're talking with peers, you know, and there

00:53:29.480 --> 00:53:33.400
[Guest]: is some degree of at least democratic equality is there and everybody's people vote very

00:53:33.400 --> 00:53:39.280
[Guest]: enthusiastically in my village, like 70% types, turnouts. And in fact, India generally

00:53:39.280 --> 00:53:43.600
[Guest]: does very well for its level of development in terms of voter turnout. It's a pretty and

00:53:43.600 --> 00:53:48.520
[Guest]: it's improving in the last few years, so much for the death of democracy. But people are

00:53:48.520 --> 00:53:51.760
[Guest]: voting and they're participating. And, and that's the process through which any change

00:53:51.760 --> 00:53:54.960
[Guest]: has to happen. It's not, you may not like what they vote for, but you have to still,

00:53:54.960 --> 00:53:58.600
[Guest]: I mean, engage with that process. That's, that's the right mechanism that we built as

00:53:58.600 --> 00:54:04.800
[Guest]: a people. So, and that is what you see, as I said earlier, there is much more mobilization.

00:54:04.800 --> 00:54:11.120
[Guest]: And when politicians come, there is the rallies are raucous, like, there is so much discussion

00:54:11.120 --> 00:54:16.480
[Guest]: and so much conversation, so much questioning. And, you know, it's a, it's a very interesting

00:54:16.480 --> 00:54:19.920
[Guest]: thing, you know, in fact, India scores very highly, even if you look at the data and all

00:54:19.920 --> 00:54:24.880
[Guest]: of it is very highly on citizen participation in these kind of forums. So, people will go

00:54:24.880 --> 00:54:31.720
[Guest]: like, there is a power station near my village, substation, through which other villages get

00:54:31.720 --> 00:54:35.880
[Guest]: power. Whenever there's a power cut, if it's too long, people will go and do dharma, dharna

00:54:35.880 --> 00:54:40.160
[Guest]: there. Once they tried to actually break it down also, it's a self-defeating kind of,

00:54:40.160 --> 00:54:44.840
[Guest]: that was many years ago. But they will resist, they will try to fight, they will try to,

00:54:44.840 --> 00:54:49.960
[Guest]: you know, voice their opinion. So, it's, I mean, if you're sitting in your room, and

00:54:49.960 --> 00:54:54.320
[Guest]: you're assuming that Indian citizens are apathetic, and they're not worried about the common good

00:54:54.320 --> 00:54:57.960
[Guest]: or association life of democracy, it's not true, simply not true, at least in my part

00:54:57.960 --> 00:55:02.200
[Guest]: of the village, many where I've lived in many cities, I've traveled the length and

00:55:02.200 --> 00:55:06.720
[Guest]: breadth of this country. I think it's a very, you know, we are, we are now understand that

00:55:06.720 --> 00:55:12.240
[Guest]: we are a democracy, and we citizens more or less, to various degree, each individual has

00:55:12.240 --> 00:55:18.040
[Guest]: a different view, think that we have a say, we, our voice is there, and we can exercise

00:55:18.040 --> 00:55:22.480
[Guest]: it may not always work, the state is very impervious and a little opaque and often also

00:55:22.480 --> 00:55:26.680
[Guest]: very quite low capacity. So, many things will not get done. But you go to a government office

00:55:26.680 --> 00:55:30.280
[Guest]: is full of people trying to petition for something or the other, you know, it's full, people

00:55:30.280 --> 00:55:33.960
[Guest]: are approaching, they have trust in institutions, they want to institutions to work better.

00:55:33.960 --> 00:55:39.520
[Guest]: So, participation in electoral democracy is one thing, sense of democracy as a equality

00:55:39.520 --> 00:55:44.440
[Guest]: of people is, is one thing. And then assertion with the state and demanding the state to

00:55:44.440 --> 00:55:49.800
[Guest]: do more is also I mean, one thing. And I think in all these three, there is compared to say

00:55:49.800 --> 00:55:53.600
[Guest]: 30 years ago or 25 years ago, I would say 25 years ago, because that's when I became

00:55:53.600 --> 00:55:58.080
[Guest]: a teenager. So, I have a sense of what was going on a little bit before that I was a

00:55:58.080 --> 00:56:04.600
[Guest]: very young kid. So, it's, there's a directionality is I think, I mean, much more of a spread

00:56:04.600 --> 00:56:07.840
[Guest]: of democracy, I would say at least, and I'm talking about Eastern UP, you know, which

00:56:07.840 --> 00:56:15.800
[Guest]: is actually a pretty underdeveloped part of the country economically, socially very conservative.

00:56:15.800 --> 00:56:19.160
[Guest]: But look at the politics is so much churning, you can't take your seat for granted. You

00:56:19.160 --> 00:56:22.080
[Guest]: know, you can't take, nobody can take your seat for granted, you may whatever caste,

00:56:22.080 --> 00:56:27.120
[Guest]: you have to still come and ask for my vote, and I can vote you out. And every, every election

00:56:27.120 --> 00:56:31.800
[Guest]: some other person wins, some other party wins, you have to still make that make that demand.

00:56:31.800 --> 00:56:37.960
[Guest]: And then hopefully, you will be honoured with my vote or you will not be.

00:56:37.960 --> 00:56:42.480
[Amit Varma]: So before I ask my next big question, a small question, quick question. When you meet your

00:56:42.480 --> 00:56:46.760
[Amit Varma]: old friend who now drives a taxi and your childhood friend, what do you talk about?

00:56:46.760 --> 00:56:53.160
[Guest]: We talk about whatever is, he has a kid. So I talk about his kid, his family or we talk

00:56:53.160 --> 00:56:57.200
[Guest]: as friends. I mean, it has nothing to do with anything else. Like, I mean, he has, I mean,

00:56:57.200 --> 00:57:02.560
[Guest]: we are friends, there's nothing else to, so he lives in the, he's from a poor Brahmin

00:57:02.560 --> 00:57:08.400
[Guest]: family. They don't have any land. So his elder brother did migrate and earned some, but he

00:57:08.400 --> 00:57:12.240
[Guest]: never settled down in the city, because he never made it big. So he remained, he didn't

00:57:12.240 --> 00:57:16.640
[Guest]: get any skills. So he goes and comes back, goes and comes back. So his elder brother's

00:57:16.640 --> 00:57:20.360
[Guest]: family also lives in the village and his family and he live in the village. And they have

00:57:20.360 --> 00:57:25.400
[Guest]: a small house near our, where I used to go and he used to come to our house. It's basically

00:57:25.400 --> 00:57:30.480
[Guest]: like 20 steps or something from my house. And so when we talk, we talk about what's

00:57:30.480 --> 00:57:35.200
[Guest]: going on in the village. He asked me about my life in the city. And, you know, let's

00:57:35.200 --> 00:57:45.000
[Guest]: we go to our, to the farm and we walk around. I mean, there's no grand theme in the conversation,

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:47.200
[Guest]: right? It's just a, you know, like,

00:57:47.200 --> 00:57:51.360
[Amit Varma]: But do you sense a sadness or a bitterness or a regret on his part that

00:57:51.360 --> 00:57:56.800
[Guest]: Yeah, so I think, so he, let me be very clear, he wasn't very good at studies. So his expectations

00:57:56.800 --> 00:58:01.320
[Guest]: were very modest. I mean, he got into bad company at a young age or whatever. But even

00:58:01.320 --> 00:58:05.560
[Guest]: then he would have at least he got a job in a factory, you know, he did high school and

00:58:05.560 --> 00:58:09.320
[Guest]: all of that, that didn't happen, you know, and after you miss the bus, you miss the bus,

00:58:09.320 --> 00:58:13.040
[Guest]: you know, at that time, and I also didn't have the way to, you know, get help him at

00:58:13.040 --> 00:58:17.920
[Guest]: that time, we were roughly the same age, he's slightly older. So then he took this path,

00:58:17.920 --> 00:58:22.200
[Guest]: he started driving, he was driving with the big auto that you have there, you know, like,

00:58:22.200 --> 00:58:26.160
[Guest]: which can have 25 people inside it, then he started driving a taxi, he's trying to drive,

00:58:26.160 --> 00:58:31.360
[Guest]: buy a car and basically drive his own car. There is some sense of what you call, see,

00:58:31.360 --> 00:58:35.320
[Guest]: the good thing about the village life is that your basic consumption is not to be worried

00:58:35.320 --> 00:58:40.120
[Guest]: about. If you're living in the village, and you have a little bit of cash, you'll be okay,

00:58:40.120 --> 00:58:46.040
[Guest]: you don't have to pay rent, you know, you don't have to say, so there is that. So it's

00:58:46.040 --> 00:58:50.160
[Guest]: like the city, city poor can be very, very harsh life, you know, very harsh, like you

00:58:50.160 --> 00:58:55.000
[Guest]: can, why do people just walk back to their villages, you know, because this whole city

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:59.920
[Guest]: ecosystem is very cash intensive. Everything is paid for, you have to pay for the rent,

00:58:59.920 --> 00:59:02.400
[Guest]: you have to pay for the power, you have to pay for water, everything you have to pay

00:59:02.400 --> 00:59:06.400
[Guest]: for. And if your cash flow stops one day, you're done, you can't stay here for one minute

00:59:06.400 --> 00:59:10.920
[Guest]: or two. And anybody who knows India knows this, the reality of India. So people just

00:59:10.920 --> 00:59:15.440
[Guest]: literally walk back, there's no train, there's no bus, I'll just walk back to home because

00:59:15.440 --> 00:59:20.760
[Guest]: there was urban poverty, rural poverty, and he's not, I mean, very poor, right? He has

00:59:20.760 --> 00:59:24.640
[Guest]: some income, his brother also owns a little in the city and sends a little bit of money

00:59:24.640 --> 00:59:29.480
[Guest]: back to his family. So he has got some sense of, I mean, stability in that. But yeah, there

00:59:29.480 --> 00:59:32.680
[Guest]: is always once in a while that conversation about the counterfactual that what if he had

00:59:32.680 --> 00:59:36.880
[Guest]: got a job in a factory. He did try, he went to Kerala once, but he couldn't make it there.

00:59:36.880 --> 00:59:41.160
[Guest]: He tried to go to Gulf once, but that didn't work out. He was almost scammed, he got the

00:59:41.160 --> 00:59:45.440
[Guest]: money back eventually. But so these things they've tried, I mean, everybody tries these

00:59:45.440 --> 00:59:50.320
[Guest]: things in my part of the, sometimes it works, sometimes it don't, it doesn't. But if you

00:59:50.320 --> 00:59:54.640
[Guest]: look at overall the number of people who have been able to be mobile economically compared

00:59:54.640 --> 00:59:59.360
[Guest]: to say 30 years ago, it's not even close, it's not even close. Earlier, it was just

00:59:59.360 --> 01:00:04.760
[Guest]: a few small people who could get good education. Some who could just deal with the hardship

01:00:04.760 --> 01:00:08.280
[Guest]: of I mean, the limited opportunities that are there basically in Bombay and a couple

01:00:08.280 --> 01:00:12.320
[Guest]: of other places. Now it's just spread out. There are some people who go to Gujarat also

01:00:12.320 --> 01:00:17.720
[Guest]: now and earlier that wasn't at all a migration pipe from my part. Like Odisha to Gujarat

01:00:17.720 --> 01:00:22.120
[Guest]: pipe is very well known, South Gujarat, South Ayushan to Gujarat is quite significant. So

01:00:22.120 --> 01:00:26.040
[Guest]: there are these like, but now it's very spread out and people are trying to find opportunities

01:00:26.040 --> 01:00:31.560
[Guest]: and it's a hard life. It's a very hard life, because you have to live away from the family.

01:00:31.560 --> 01:00:34.760
[Guest]: That's a very tough thing because you can't, there's no, when you're seasonal migration,

01:00:34.760 --> 01:00:39.280
[Guest]: you can't really take your family to eat up all your resources. So it's a very tough life.

01:00:39.280 --> 01:00:45.440
[Guest]: But once you make it there, then you settle down and then you are an amphibian.

01:00:45.440 --> 01:00:50.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting how language evolves, like people call people from UP who come to

01:00:50.400 --> 01:00:55.680
[Amit Varma]: Bombay, they're typically called bhaiyas, right? So once we had a domestic help at home,

01:00:55.680 --> 01:01:00.960
[Amit Varma]: and we asked her where she's from, and she said, main to bhaiyan hoon, which was an interesting

01:01:00.960 --> 01:01:05.960
[Amit Varma]: evolution of the language. So the next big question that I want to drill down on is what

01:01:05.960 --> 01:01:10.320
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned earlier, where you spoke about teachers, that your father was lucky that

01:01:10.320 --> 01:01:15.280
[Amit Varma]: he had good teachers, and how most teachers are going through the motions and all of that.

01:01:15.280 --> 01:01:20.400
[Amit Varma]: And what you meant by good teachers, I'm guessing was not someone who is teaching the syllabus

01:01:20.400 --> 01:01:24.880
[Amit Varma]: well, you know, ki geography achche se para diya, ya math achche se para diya. There's

01:01:24.880 --> 01:01:29.080
[Amit Varma]: something else you meant by teacher, that, you know, you spoke about the virtues of it,

01:01:29.080 --> 01:01:33.120
[Amit Varma]: that aspect of it of how a good teacher can lift you. So a good teacher in that sense

01:01:33.120 --> 01:01:38.560
[Amit Varma]: is not just teaching you what's in the syllabus, in a sense, he's within the system, but he's

01:01:38.560 --> 01:01:43.520
[Amit Varma]: also standing outside the system. He's, in a sense, helping shape your character, showing

01:01:43.520 --> 01:01:48.920
[Amit Varma]: you something that you may not otherwise see. So can you elaborate on this for me, both

01:01:48.920 --> 01:01:55.800
[Amit Varma]: in the microcosmic context of that particular village, and you know, what your father may

01:01:55.800 --> 01:01:59.420
[Amit Varma]: have picked up from those teachers or what you may have picked up later from teachers

01:01:59.420 --> 01:02:06.120
[Amit Varma]: who inspired you? And can you and that's a microcosmic context, but also a broader context,

01:02:06.120 --> 01:02:11.720
[Amit Varma]: that everybody needs teachers in their lives, right? And most of us, if we are fortunate,

01:02:11.720 --> 01:02:15.720
[Amit Varma]: we'll probably find we might find teachers who are actually in that official position

01:02:15.720 --> 01:02:20.480
[Amit Varma]: of authority in a school or a college, or we might find teachers elsewhere in life mentors

01:02:20.480 --> 01:02:26.680
[Amit Varma]: or people who teach us things and all of that. So elaborate a little bit on both these microcosmic

01:02:26.680 --> 01:02:32.480
[Amit Varma]: and macrocosmic aspects. And in the macrocosmic aspect, perhaps even, you know, a sense of

01:02:32.480 --> 01:02:38.100
[Amit Varma]: that, do you sometimes feel that you have a responsibility also, to pay it back not

01:02:38.100 --> 01:02:42.160
[Amit Varma]: in a formal sense, but in the sense of if you have something to teach, if you can touch

01:02:42.160 --> 01:02:47.400
[Amit Varma]: somebody's life in some way, that lifts him a little bit that you should do that. So take

01:02:47.400 --> 01:02:49.600
[Amit Varma]: me through all of this, a big question, I know.

01:02:49.600 --> 01:02:55.600
[Guest]: Yeah, it is a big question. It's about life itself. So I think, so there was a teacher

01:02:55.600 --> 01:03:02.320
[Guest]: in my father's school before he went to school, this is a story that he heard, who used to

01:03:02.320 --> 01:03:08.080
[Guest]: insist when it came to the 10th standard that the bottom third of the class in the 9th standard,

01:03:08.080 --> 01:03:14.160
[Guest]: he will teach. And then he would use to produce good results from them in 10th. He said, this

01:03:14.160 --> 01:03:21.080
[Guest]: is my duty that I will take the worst performing third on the 9th standard, or fourth or third,

01:03:21.080 --> 01:03:25.880
[Guest]: whatever, but the basically the people who are doing very badly. And then he will make

01:03:25.880 --> 01:03:30.080
[Guest]: it his life's mission to spend a year with them and basically prove that you know, there's

01:03:30.080 --> 01:03:34.920
[Guest]: nothing wrong with the kids is basically, you know, you as a teacher can do a lot, even

01:03:34.920 --> 01:03:39.320
[Guest]: if there's something wrong, there's a long, big dent that a teacher can make, you know,

01:03:39.320 --> 01:03:44.720
[Guest]: a good teacher. It should be all consuming, right? It's a very intensive process, not

01:03:44.720 --> 01:03:49.280
[Guest]: just going through the class. Lots of kids require special attention, you have to spend

01:03:49.280 --> 01:03:54.240
[Guest]: a lot of time after the class and to keep track of this. So one story that a friend

01:03:54.240 --> 01:03:59.320
[Guest]: of mine who's a very senior civil servant in the government now, he told me that when

01:03:59.320 --> 01:04:06.440
[Guest]: he was in school, he was in 11th standard or entered just 12th standard, his teacher

01:04:06.440 --> 01:04:14.320
[Guest]: called him home. Okay. And she gave him a piece of paper in which the list of top 100

01:04:14.320 --> 01:04:20.000
[Guest]: of CBSE in CBSE exam, the students was given. And he said, this is the list of people who

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:24.760
[Guest]: came in the top 100 this year, you need to be on it next year, what do I need to do to

01:04:24.760 --> 01:04:32.880
[Guest]: make sure that happens? You know, and, and he did, he came in top 20 in the country.

01:04:32.880 --> 01:04:38.640
[Guest]: So I went to St. Stephen's and all of that. And I mean, but he's, yeah, he's a great guy.

01:04:38.640 --> 01:04:44.080
[Guest]: So now do two different categories. One is this guy who says, okay, I'm going to raise

01:04:44.080 --> 01:04:50.080
[Guest]: a large number of kids who are not doing well to a level of standard in which they're able

01:04:50.080 --> 01:04:56.160
[Guest]: to get through the 10th, you know, and then they will find a path, hopefully forward.

01:04:56.160 --> 01:05:01.840
[Guest]: And then there is the other, where you point at a few kids who just need a little bit,

01:05:01.840 --> 01:05:06.840
[Guest]: you know, special attention to go that extra mile and basically get to a completely different

01:05:06.840 --> 01:05:12.120
[Guest]: league, right? So teaching involves both of these things. I've not really done teaching

01:05:12.120 --> 01:05:16.480
[Guest]: in my life, but I have been on the other side of the racing that you need both. I mean,

01:05:16.480 --> 01:05:21.280
[Guest]: you need to be in a larger setting in which education is happening and whatever, or learning

01:05:21.280 --> 01:05:26.040
[Guest]: is considered to be a good, to be an important thing and it's being pursued. And sometimes

01:05:26.040 --> 01:05:29.760
[Guest]: in life, you need somebody to give you that extra push, you know, where you're lost and

01:05:29.760 --> 01:05:32.840
[Guest]: you don't know where you're headed, you need guidance, you need mentorship. And more than

01:05:32.840 --> 01:05:38.520
[Guest]: that, you just need emotional support, you know, that, yes, I have faith in you, you

01:05:38.520 --> 01:05:44.320
[Guest]: don't have faith in me, you know, and that actually, you know, I, it's kind of a preference

01:05:44.320 --> 01:05:49.600
[Guest]: that is there inside the person, you know, who's the teacher. And I'm not one of those

01:05:49.600 --> 01:05:53.680
[Guest]: believers, I have a lot of long standing debates with friends about incentives and all shaping

01:05:53.680 --> 01:05:58.880
[Guest]: it. These are virtues that actually people basically, the combination of factors, perhaps

01:05:58.880 --> 01:06:02.520
[Guest]: something to do with their childhood, how they socialize, how they saw they got into

01:06:02.520 --> 01:06:07.480
[Guest]: this profession, and how they saw it as a meaning of their life, you know, in that sense,

01:06:07.480 --> 01:06:12.440
[Guest]: how they saw. So we can talk about the philosophical framing of it, like the way Alessandra McIntyre

01:06:12.440 --> 01:06:16.280
[Guest]: and all of these guys have done about how to think about virtues. But it's something

01:06:16.280 --> 01:06:20.120
[Guest]: which is which happens, I mean, I would say upstream of the markets, in some senses, you

01:06:20.120 --> 01:06:26.040
[Guest]: know, it happens. And then these are the preferences, which then the market can take and do whatever

01:06:26.040 --> 01:06:30.240
[Guest]: it wants to do with it, it can reward them or punish them as well in certain circumstances.

01:06:30.240 --> 01:06:35.400
[Guest]: Like there are situations in markets punish bad behavior, because a good doctor may take

01:06:35.400 --> 01:06:42.360
[Guest]: a long time to treat a patient. And the markets may, I mean, the way the hospital corporates

01:06:42.360 --> 01:06:46.400
[Guest]: are set up, they may want to do it in a quick way, so that you have a lot of people are

01:06:46.400 --> 01:06:51.600
[Guest]: being churned out quickly. So and then there is a conflict between virtues and the working

01:06:51.600 --> 01:06:55.440
[Guest]: of the market in that particular setting, you know, markets also have work in segmented

01:06:55.440 --> 01:06:59.120
[Guest]: way, you may find a good segment in which you are actually the best place, because that

01:06:59.120 --> 01:07:04.160
[Guest]: segment rewards this kind of a performance with respect to your patients, patient.

01:07:04.160 --> 01:07:09.200
[Guest]: So I think what you need, especially in a country like India, where you have still a

01:07:09.200 --> 01:07:13.800
[Guest]: long way to go, we are quite poor, you know, we are a lower middle income country, is that

01:07:13.800 --> 01:07:19.740
[Guest]: you need to basically have lots of teachers who are, who have at least raised the basic

01:07:19.740 --> 01:07:24.480
[Guest]: standard up, you know, like, do the basic thing that teach the kids on a regular basis,

01:07:24.480 --> 01:07:28.360
[Guest]: get them to a minimum standard, and then they'll find it. And then you will have a few who

01:07:28.360 --> 01:07:36.000
[Guest]: just go above and beyond. And they say that I'm going to give my life to it in some senses.

01:07:36.000 --> 01:07:39.600
[Guest]: And for that, you need, I mean, I don't know how that is done, you know, because I've seen

01:07:39.600 --> 01:07:44.720
[Guest]: I've, I've been lucky to have some mentors in my life, like, maybe it'll make them uncomfortable

01:07:44.720 --> 01:07:48.640
[Guest]: if I name them here. But there are people who have touched my life in very important

01:07:48.640 --> 01:07:53.040
[Guest]: way. My father was one, my mother, my, my, my uncle, I said,

01:07:53.040 --> 01:07:58.080
[Amit Varma]: Can you elaborate a bit on each of those? Actually, I'm very interested in the ways

01:07:58.080 --> 01:07:59.080
[Amit Varma]: that they shaped you.

01:07:59.080 --> 01:08:03.120
[Guest]: So my father was a heroic figure, right? He came from a, he had a hero's journey from

01:08:03.120 --> 01:08:08.560
[Guest]: the village to a city and he settled down here, he, he got an education, he got a decent

01:08:08.560 --> 01:08:15.280
[Guest]: stable job. In his 40s, he did his PhD, again from BHU. And then after the retirement, he

01:08:15.280 --> 01:08:20.840
[Guest]: goes out and helps kids who are really hungry for guidance and support and all of that.

01:08:20.840 --> 01:08:26.320
[Guest]: My some of them may not be very comfortable. I talk about them in public. My uncle, I told

01:08:26.320 --> 01:08:31.600
[Guest]: you how much my uncle and aunt both how they took control of their family took charge and

01:08:31.600 --> 01:08:36.000
[Guest]: how basically they saved the family from utter ruin. Utter ruin, you know, it would have

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:40.800
[Guest]: been a complete ruin if they hadn't performed their duties at that time. And in fact, it

01:08:40.800 --> 01:08:43.920
[Guest]: was a very difficult time generally for the for our village. There was one year in which

01:08:43.920 --> 01:08:47.520
[Guest]: there was a major drought. For two consecutive, there was a major drought. He literally had

01:08:47.520 --> 01:08:51.720
[Guest]: to walk for 50 kilometers to be able to get some help from a distant family, you know,

01:08:51.720 --> 01:08:56.840
[Guest]: walk with up they took a bullock cart and all. It's part of our family lore. And I mean,

01:08:56.840 --> 01:09:01.480
[Guest]: he's the kind of person so I remember I went to village once and I had a Spanish Ark beer

01:09:01.480 --> 01:09:09.560
[Guest]: and he saw it and said, this won't do. I immediately removed it. There was a question that I want

01:09:09.560 --> 01:09:14.040
[Guest]: to debate with him. It's my right or whatever. He didn't like a Spanish Ark beer. He said,

01:09:14.040 --> 01:09:15.440
[Guest]: this one, this is not looking good.

01:09:15.440 --> 01:09:18.120
[Amit Varma]: I know a French beard. What's a Spanish Ark beard?

01:09:18.120 --> 01:09:24.280
[Guest]: There's a basically like a small arc that you make below your chin. So you can look

01:09:24.280 --> 01:09:30.480
[Guest]: it up. So I was a teenager and I said, Okay, let me try a different look. And I landed

01:09:30.480 --> 01:09:33.800
[Guest]: in a village and he said, this is not looking good on you. This is not going to do. I just

01:09:33.800 --> 01:09:38.680
[Guest]: removed it. A lot of fear. I just loved him, you know, that I had a sense that this is

01:09:38.680 --> 01:09:44.640
[Guest]: I come from these people, you know, and whatever I am is because of these people and my father

01:09:44.640 --> 01:09:50.360
[Guest]: and my mother, my uncle and my aunt and I have a written history of eight generations

01:09:50.360 --> 01:09:56.400
[Guest]: back and I know the stories and how much it takes to keep a family together to have to

01:09:56.400 --> 01:10:01.040
[Guest]: stabilize in this world, especially in a poor country, you know, we were poor at that time.

01:10:01.040 --> 01:10:05.600
[Guest]: Now we're low middle income country. It's hard, especially in that Eastern UP and Bihar

01:10:05.600 --> 01:10:11.920
[Guest]: context. So there is a sense of my mother's side, for example, my Nana ji was like that.

01:10:11.920 --> 01:10:18.320
[Guest]: He also came from a village and he became a teacher. He was a college teacher in Agra

01:10:18.320 --> 01:10:24.000
[Guest]: and he came from Eastern UP again from Azamgarh and he was again a very, very amazing person,

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:27.800
[Guest]: you know, he did his PhD and all of that. He became a teacher. He wrote a book, which

01:10:27.800 --> 01:10:32.360
[Guest]: is still going on in Hindi book on research methods, which is still in circulation as

01:10:32.360 --> 01:10:38.120
[Guest]: in taught. I have a copy of that book, very nicely written book. Anusandhan Parichay.

01:10:38.120 --> 01:10:43.520
[Guest]: So it's an introduction to research methods. So, and he came from a, he used to teach in

01:10:43.520 --> 01:10:48.440
[Guest]: a village school and then he got into college and then he did his PhD and became a professor

01:10:48.440 --> 01:10:53.200
[Guest]: and all of that. Very happy man, you know, one of the happiest persons I've ever met.

01:10:53.200 --> 01:10:58.880
[Guest]: Always smiling, always laughing, always joking, always trying to make everybody very happy.

01:10:58.880 --> 01:11:04.120
[Guest]: He passed away many years ago, but I was like, he passed away 15 years ago. Yeah. So I was

01:11:04.120 --> 01:11:10.360
[Guest]: not that young, I was still in 20s. So he, he was also like that. And many of the stories

01:11:10.360 --> 01:11:14.120
[Guest]: of people who actually make these difficult journeys, you know, and are like, and each

01:11:14.120 --> 01:11:18.840
[Guest]: family has this, you know, like, these are the great heroes, you know, and they are,

01:11:18.840 --> 01:11:23.680
[Guest]: they live private lives. And their heroism is basically limited to the, to serving the

01:11:23.680 --> 01:11:28.200
[Guest]: immediate good, which is the good of the family and the friends and the communities, you know.

01:11:28.200 --> 01:11:32.800
[Guest]: He started a school back in his village, which ran for many years. I don't know whether it's

01:11:32.800 --> 01:11:36.680
[Guest]: still running. In fact, that part of my family, my mother's side has left the village. So

01:11:36.680 --> 01:11:41.320
[Guest]: the village home is literally logged now, because everybody moved to the city. So another

01:11:41.320 --> 01:11:47.760
[Guest]: one logged home. So he was there. And when I was in school, I had a few teachers who

01:11:47.760 --> 01:11:54.600
[Guest]: really helped me out. I, when I started working, I mean, I had last 11-12 years, I've had a

01:11:54.600 --> 01:12:00.960
[Guest]: number of mentors, not a number, a few really good mentors, who I look up to, they're very

01:12:00.960 --> 01:12:07.240
[Guest]: virtuous people. Especially one person, I will not name him, you know him. He's an economist.

01:12:07.240 --> 01:12:11.880
[Guest]: I don't want to embarrass him. But I really look up to him as someone, a very decent human

01:12:11.880 --> 01:12:16.760
[Guest]: being, you know, and very good person to learn from, not just economics, but also about life

01:12:16.760 --> 01:12:23.640
[Guest]: and things in general, and consistently good person. I've known him for not 12 years. And

01:12:23.640 --> 01:12:28.520
[Guest]: I've never had a feeling about him that there is something, what you see is what you get

01:12:28.520 --> 01:12:35.280
[Guest]: with him. It's a very, very, very interesting, very good thing to have in a mentor. So, yeah,

01:12:35.280 --> 01:12:40.360
[Guest]: I think it's a very, so this is how societies improve, I think, like one person at another

01:12:40.360 --> 01:12:44.640
[Guest]: time, and you go through an internal process. In some ways, I've improved as a person over

01:12:44.640 --> 01:12:51.440
[Guest]: the last 10 years. And I'm trying to get better, you know, and it's a journey that you go through

01:12:51.440 --> 01:12:56.960
[Guest]: internally and others can help you, you know. And there is a very important role that others

01:12:56.960 --> 01:13:03.000
[Guest]: can play. In that sense, we are not completely isolated human beings, we are very open to

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:11.040
[Guest]: influence, but not lecturing. In subtle ways, you know, like Jung has this insight on how,

01:13:11.040 --> 01:13:15.360
[Guest]: if you want to change somebody, then, you know, Gandhi also had the same insight that

01:13:15.360 --> 01:13:19.200
[Guest]: you want to be the change. I think it's a misquote, he didn't say that, but it's often

01:13:19.200 --> 01:13:22.720
[Guest]: attributed to him, is that, you know, you have to be the change, you have to see the

01:13:22.720 --> 01:13:27.280
[Guest]: world. Similarly, Jung has a very interesting portion in one of his last books, Undiscovered

01:13:27.280 --> 01:13:33.820
[Guest]: Self, where he writes about how in some tribes that he was observing in the Pacific Islands,

01:13:33.820 --> 01:13:39.320
[Guest]: it was this, there was a term, I forget this term, it was called, it'll come to me. It

01:13:39.320 --> 01:13:45.080
[Guest]: was basically a quality of a person that you just watch him and observe him and try to,

01:13:45.080 --> 01:13:51.160
[Guest]: you know, don't copy his bannerisms, just try to, you know, take his character in some

01:13:51.160 --> 01:13:56.840
[Guest]: ways, you know, in some senses, it's almost like a mystical participation in that person's

01:13:56.840 --> 01:14:01.120
[Guest]: personality. And you're trying to, and that's the way to, you know, lecturing and hectoring

01:14:01.120 --> 01:14:05.520
[Guest]: is not the way any human being changes, it puts us in a defensive mode. It's much more

01:14:05.520 --> 01:14:11.280
[Guest]: of a, we learn and get better by observing others who are better than us. One of my favorite

01:14:11.280 --> 01:14:17.360
[Guest]: examples on this is this Nathaniel Hawthorne, who was a great, great author. And I loved

01:14:17.360 --> 01:14:23.560
[Guest]: love his work. And he was one of the great thinkers on human nature and very, very humane

01:14:23.560 --> 01:14:30.880
[Guest]: kind of a writer. And there's a book called The Life of Marianne. Oh, this very young

01:14:30.880 --> 01:14:35.600
[Guest]: girl who was stricken by cancer and she passed away at a very young age. And there was a

01:14:35.600 --> 01:14:40.440
[Guest]: convent in which she was being taken care of. And the convent basically took care of

01:14:40.440 --> 01:14:47.640
[Guest]: only cancer stricken or very badly sick kids. And this young girl was very, very, what you

01:14:47.640 --> 01:14:53.560
[Guest]: call, was considered to be a bundle of joy and very wiser than her age, basically nine

01:14:53.560 --> 01:14:57.880
[Guest]: or eight or nine years of age, very wise, and made everybody very happy. And of course,

01:14:57.880 --> 01:15:04.880
[Guest]: she passed away later. So, then the nuns from that convent came to Flannery O'Connor, who's

01:15:04.880 --> 01:15:09.720
[Guest]: also a great southern writer, America, really great writer. I love her work and said, why

01:15:09.720 --> 01:15:15.440
[Guest]: don't you write her life? So, Flannery said, I am in no position to write any life of a

01:15:15.440 --> 01:15:18.840
[Guest]: person I didn't know, but she sounded like a perfect, great, great person and you should

01:15:18.840 --> 01:15:23.360
[Guest]: write it, the nuns should write it. And I'll happily write a foreword to it. So, in the

01:15:23.360 --> 01:15:27.840
[Guest]: foreword she writes actually very interestingly, it's a very interesting life to read about,

01:15:27.840 --> 01:15:32.000
[Guest]: her foreword is also more interesting, is how Nathaniel Hawthorne, who was a very humane

01:15:32.000 --> 01:15:37.120
[Guest]: person who wrote a number of very interesting stories about human life and dignity of human

01:15:37.120 --> 01:15:44.480
[Guest]: life and the beauty of imperfection and I mean, basically the antithesis to the Aldous

01:15:44.480 --> 01:15:50.520
[Guest]: Huxley's, you know, utopia of trying to make best human being by taking chemicals and by

01:15:50.520 --> 01:15:55.960
[Guest]: doing genetic engineering and all that, taking human life as it is. And his daughter started

01:15:55.960 --> 01:16:02.560
[Guest]: this convent. And in a way, she draws a line between one of his stories, Hawthorne's stories

01:16:02.560 --> 01:16:07.680
[Guest]: and the life path that his daughter took when she started the convent to take care of young

01:16:07.680 --> 01:16:13.360
[Guest]: stricken children who were terminally ill. And then how this little kid who got a good

01:16:13.360 --> 01:16:18.240
[Guest]: life, even though short life, a good life in a convent because of that. So, I think

01:16:18.240 --> 01:16:21.720
[Guest]: that is the main thing that I have learned more recently in life, I wish I had learned

01:16:21.720 --> 01:16:26.000
[Guest]: it earlier is that, you know, the big ideas and the abstract thinking and discussions

01:16:26.000 --> 01:16:31.640
[Guest]: and great grand ideologies are one thing and maybe in some context, they are useful. But

01:16:31.640 --> 01:16:37.400
[Guest]: the most important thing is to, you know, nurture these ways of improving things, whether

01:16:37.400 --> 01:16:43.440
[Guest]: it is in professions, different professions, in which good virtuous professionals can create

01:16:43.440 --> 01:16:48.840
[Guest]: role models for others and help others and aid others, whether it is within families,

01:16:48.840 --> 01:16:52.920
[Guest]: you know, how to be a good father and how to be a good mother. It is not easy, none

01:16:52.920 --> 01:16:56.840
[Guest]: of this is easy, not easy to be a good professional, not easy to be a good parent, not easy to

01:16:56.840 --> 01:17:02.360
[Guest]: be a good professional, good worker, good politician or anything like that. All of that

01:17:02.360 --> 01:17:07.640
[Guest]: is challenging because there are so many necessities, quote unquote, and demands. But I think that

01:17:07.640 --> 01:17:12.800
[Guest]: is the main thing that needs to sustain, there is a hidden thing which we do not see in the,

01:17:12.800 --> 01:17:16.640
[Guest]: because it is kind of a quality which is not easily captured. But that is a hidden thing

01:17:16.640 --> 01:17:21.400
[Guest]: that makes a civilization, country great and other things can flow from there, other utilities

01:17:21.400 --> 01:17:26.680
[Guest]: can flow from there. But this kind of a continuity of good, you know, that and that is it. So

01:17:26.680 --> 01:17:30.440
[Guest]: I think that is the way I draw the arc in teaching and life and all of that.

01:17:30.440 --> 01:17:31.440
[Guest]: How important

01:17:31.440 --> 01:17:34.960
[Amit Varma]: Does that answer your question or I went on and on?

01:17:34.960 --> 01:17:39.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, a lot of my guests say this to me, does that answer your question? Thereby

01:17:39.200 --> 01:17:44.280
[Amit Varma]: kind of missing the point in the sense that the answer to the question is not the point,

01:17:44.280 --> 01:17:48.960
[Amit Varma]: but the thoughts that can spark other points. So, I certainly found it very illuminating

01:17:48.960 --> 01:17:55.360
[Amit Varma]: and it, I think did its job of giving me more questions to ask. The first of which is this,

01:17:55.360 --> 01:17:59.600
[Amit Varma]: how important to you is the rootedness which you feel? Like you mentioned, that you know

01:17:59.600 --> 01:18:05.200
[Amit Varma]: the genealogy of your family going back a long way, that you feel rooted in that village,

01:18:05.200 --> 01:18:08.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, your friends are still there, your family is still there, all of that, and you

01:18:08.640 --> 01:18:13.040
[Amit Varma]: carry that with you. And I'm guessing part of that rootedness is not just a memory of

01:18:13.040 --> 01:18:17.720
[Amit Varma]: people or a sense of place, but also this bedrock of values that, you know, you carry

01:18:17.720 --> 01:18:24.920
[Amit Varma]: with you. And I see myself in a sense in contrast to that, that I don't really feel that rooted.

01:18:24.920 --> 01:18:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And it's a loss, it's something that I bemoan, that I do feel, you know, deracinated. And

01:18:30.880 --> 01:18:36.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I see, I embrace the positive aspects of what comes out of that, the fact that I

01:18:36.520 --> 01:18:41.840
[Amit Varma]: feel like a citizen of the world, I take ideas from everywhere, my influences are from everywhere.

01:18:41.840 --> 01:18:47.160
[Amit Varma]: But I also see the loss that there is. And maybe you and I are sitting here, and you

01:18:47.160 --> 01:18:52.760
[Amit Varma]: are an extremely rooted person, and I'm not. And maybe it's a good time for you to sort

01:18:52.760 --> 01:18:59.440
[Amit Varma]: of talk about what you feel your rootedness brought you in terms of the way you think

01:18:59.440 --> 01:19:04.400
[Amit Varma]: and the way you see the world, and how it would be different from somebody like me,

01:19:04.400 --> 01:19:09.600
[Amit Varma]: like what is perhaps then lacking in my vision, like one of the themes that I've looked at

01:19:09.600 --> 01:19:15.920
[Amit Varma]: in past episodes also, is that many of our English speaking elites, like myself, grew

01:19:15.920 --> 01:19:20.720
[Amit Varma]: up in this small urban bubble, where we looked at the country the wrong way, we didn't really

01:19:20.720 --> 01:19:26.240
[Amit Varma]: know this country, right. And one way of reacting to understanding the country when we do see

01:19:26.240 --> 01:19:30.320
[Amit Varma]: it, see it a little better, is to perhaps swing to a negative extreme, like I might

01:19:30.320 --> 01:19:34.080
[Amit Varma]: sometimes have done and say, Oh, we are so bigoted, we are so illiberal, we are so this,

01:19:34.080 --> 01:19:40.280
[Amit Varma]: we are so that, right, which also might be an overreaction to whatever. But, you know,

01:19:40.280 --> 01:19:47.120
[Amit Varma]: so just going back to that sense of what does rootedness bring you? And what do you think

01:19:47.120 --> 01:19:50.560
[Amit Varma]: the absence of that rootedness does to somebody?

01:19:50.560 --> 01:19:57.960
[Guest]: As I said that, my family lives across many centuries at the same time. So there is, of

01:19:57.960 --> 01:20:04.120
[Guest]: course, some rootedness that I feel and I, it's just a, I know where I come from, more

01:20:04.120 --> 01:20:09.360
[Guest]: or less. My family has been in that one spot for 400 years, same house, same place as house

01:20:09.360 --> 01:20:15.360
[Guest]: has been 400 years, it's been made, built and rebuilt many times. We have a written

01:20:15.360 --> 01:20:22.160
[Guest]: record of eight generations, we have some sense of who we are, but it only goes some

01:20:22.160 --> 01:20:26.720
[Guest]: way, you know, it's, it's just a sense of gratitude that, okay, there are people who

01:20:26.720 --> 01:20:33.080
[Guest]: started the family, who kept it together, who continued the kind of values that went

01:20:33.080 --> 01:20:38.200
[Guest]: into our family, who had different difficult junctures, kept things together when they

01:20:38.200 --> 01:20:45.800
[Guest]: could have fallen apart, they kept the center held, so to speak. And there is that.

01:20:45.800 --> 01:20:51.960
[Guest]: But if you look at me, I actually, a lot of what I have learned is not just, I mean, that's

01:20:51.960 --> 01:20:57.840
[Guest]: the base, like, I would say that's the bedrock. And then you go and it's great, right, to

01:20:57.840 --> 01:21:03.880
[Guest]: be in the modern world, you can read and think and talk about, talk to anyone, you can learn

01:21:03.880 --> 01:21:10.000
[Guest]: from many, many sources. See, one word that I always grew up hearing is dharma, dharma,

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:15.360
[Guest]: dharma. It's like, okay, what's dharma, it's difficult to define, but you know, it's a,

01:21:15.360 --> 01:21:20.200
[Guest]: it's a basically a way of thinking about what is the right thing to do, you know, and what

01:21:20.200 --> 01:21:23.680
[Guest]: would work in some sense. And then you need to learn, you know, it's not, there's no substitute

01:21:23.680 --> 01:21:27.880
[Guest]: for practical judgment. And practical judgment requires learning from many, many sources.

01:21:27.880 --> 01:21:33.000
[Guest]: And for that, you need to be able to open and I mean, you know, it's not like I figured

01:21:33.000 --> 01:21:38.400
[Guest]: things out, I'm still struggling and learning and trying to get better at what I do, whatever

01:21:38.400 --> 01:21:46.280
[Guest]: I do. And that, for that the sources are many, right. But I got basic set of, you know, starting

01:21:46.280 --> 01:21:50.640
[Guest]: because of my, what my father did, my uncle did, and others may have done. And that's

01:21:50.640 --> 01:21:55.280
[Guest]: my past. And that's my history. And I'm very cognizant of that. Not a day goes by before

01:21:55.280 --> 01:22:00.440
[Guest]: I feel gratitude for what they've done for me in some sense. Because, but because of

01:22:00.440 --> 01:22:03.800
[Guest]: the way I am in my family, nobody ever talks about this stuff. I'm sitting here and talking

01:22:03.800 --> 01:22:08.040
[Guest]: about it in a podcast. But I've never ever said this to anyone in my family because that's

01:22:08.040 --> 01:22:11.400
[Guest]: not the way we are, you know, we're not over the top over these things. I never hugged

01:22:11.400 --> 01:22:15.360
[Guest]: my uncle and said, hey, thank you so much for what you did for me. Because

01:22:15.360 --> 01:22:17.680
[Amit Varma]: But he shaved your funky Spanish beard.

01:22:17.680 --> 01:22:23.880
[Guest]: Yeah, those are small ways in which one makes it clear that what matters and what doesn't.

01:22:23.880 --> 01:22:29.720
[Guest]: So it was not my right to keep a beard was certainly not at the top of my mind. It wasn't

01:22:29.720 --> 01:22:34.560
[Guest]: much of a demand, you know, I remember when my I got married, within a year, my wife had

01:22:34.560 --> 01:22:39.440
[Guest]: to, we had to go to higher studies in the US. And my uncle was one of the first ones

01:22:39.440 --> 01:22:44.080
[Guest]: to support it. You know, he's a 75 year old man living in a village. And within a year

01:22:44.080 --> 01:22:49.360
[Guest]: of a village, I mean, so called daughter-in-law of the family is going abroad for a few years

01:22:49.360 --> 01:22:53.960
[Guest]: to study. And he was the first to support it, you know, because and he's the guy who

01:22:53.960 --> 01:22:59.440
[Guest]: for 30 years ago, I remember had very, very conservative views, not just for job or even

01:22:59.440 --> 01:23:04.640
[Guest]: on education, only teaching job is good, all of that is good. And so I mean, there are

01:23:04.640 --> 01:23:08.720
[Guest]: people who earn respect, you know, in some senses, because they act according to situation

01:23:08.720 --> 01:23:13.200
[Guest]: they learn, they change, and they do what's good in many ways. So I'm very grateful for

01:23:13.200 --> 01:23:20.000
[Guest]: all that, that I mean, a certain kind of in fact, I wish I was able to make more of what

01:23:20.000 --> 01:23:25.920
[Guest]: I got from them, you know, it is my own feeling that I'm not a better person or a more virtuous

01:23:25.920 --> 01:23:30.160
[Guest]: person. I'm not done more contribute in many ways, you know, it is my own feeling and I

01:23:30.160 --> 01:23:34.440
[Guest]: could do more. And to be able to do more one has to actually expand, you know, it has to

01:23:34.440 --> 01:23:40.160
[Guest]: venture out and understand how things work, learn and you know, it's a, but it's the love

01:23:40.160 --> 01:23:45.320
[Guest]: that one gets from there. Like one of my favorite quotes is from Chesterton, that he wrote somewhere

01:23:45.320 --> 01:23:50.760
[Guest]: that Romans didn't love Rome because Rome was great. Rome was great because Romans loved

01:23:50.760 --> 01:23:56.240
[Guest]: Rome, you know. So, and that's the foundation. I mean, one loves one family, one village,

01:23:56.240 --> 01:24:01.720
[Guest]: one community, one country, even if they have done you some harm, you know, and they may

01:24:01.720 --> 01:24:06.440
[Guest]: have like, we've been betrayed so many times as a family by others in our village, there

01:24:06.440 --> 01:24:11.120
[Guest]: have been violence, there are a number of court cases going on. I mean, in fact, one

01:24:11.120 --> 01:24:15.240
[Guest]: member of the family is always fighting court cases, designated that this person will go

01:24:15.240 --> 01:24:19.920
[Guest]: and appear in the court. So much conflict, violence, all of that has happened, but we

01:24:19.920 --> 01:24:23.640
[Guest]: still, this is our village, this is our family, we love each other. And there is a tension

01:24:23.640 --> 01:24:28.560
[Guest]: and conflict with that, all that happens. So, then the question comes how to make Rome

01:24:28.560 --> 01:24:33.840
[Guest]: great. And for that you need to be, you know, the past is not a great guide, it's just a

01:24:33.840 --> 01:24:38.560
[Guest]: little bit you get from there, a sense of rootedness. And there actually, in some ways

01:24:38.560 --> 01:24:42.880
[Guest]: people like you have more advantages because you are much more seeing and learning and

01:24:42.880 --> 01:24:48.160
[Guest]: I learn a lot from you and others, like my friend, friends in the economics side. I'm

01:24:48.160 --> 01:24:52.960
[Guest]: not an economist, but I learn a lot from economists, political scientists, I learn a lot from different

01:24:52.960 --> 01:24:57.280
[Guest]: people and say, because my work is in political economy. So, I try to learn as much as I can

01:24:57.280 --> 01:25:02.880
[Guest]: to be able to say how we can, how the Indian economy can grow better, how can we do better.

01:25:02.880 --> 01:25:07.160
[Guest]: Similarly, I work a little bit on professions. So, I learn, in fact, my main thinking on

01:25:07.160 --> 01:25:11.360
[Guest]: professions initiated by Alasdair MacIntyre, who is a, I mean, completely rooted in the

01:25:11.360 --> 01:25:17.600
[Guest]: Western tradition of philosophy, Aristotelian and Thomist and you know that tradition. But

01:25:17.600 --> 01:25:22.240
[Guest]: one can actually learn from many, many places because dharma is universal, you know, and

01:25:22.240 --> 01:25:26.400
[Guest]: there is a, I mean, it is not something which is a monopoly of a particular people. In fact,

01:25:26.400 --> 01:25:29.680
[Guest]: that's, that would be the completely wrong way of thinking about it. It's about what

01:25:29.680 --> 01:25:33.280
[Guest]: you, how you think about the world and what you do. And there, actually, you see a lot

01:25:33.280 --> 01:25:37.640
[Guest]: of dharma all over the world in many ways and one has to be able to learn and see what

01:25:37.640 --> 01:25:42.240
[Guest]: is, what would work, you know, what would be practically the right thing to do and morally

01:25:42.240 --> 01:25:45.400
[Guest]: also the right thing to do at the same time. That's the combination that you need to be

01:25:45.400 --> 01:25:50.760
[Guest]: able to do. And for that, being open, learning from the world, understanding things from

01:25:50.760 --> 01:25:55.000
[Guest]: different perspectives, you know, because you don't see, from your perspective is only

01:25:55.000 --> 01:25:57.560
[Guest]: one side of the mountain and there are other sides of the mountain. So, you need to talk

01:25:57.560 --> 01:26:01.680
[Guest]: to others, learn, you know, you need to wake up with the moderns, spend the day with the

01:26:01.680 --> 01:26:07.960
[Guest]: medievals, retire with the ancients, you know, and have a sense of all encompassing perspective

01:26:07.960 --> 01:26:12.280
[Guest]: to form a world view and then contribute. That's in the world of think tanks and intellectualism

01:26:12.280 --> 01:26:16.680
[Guest]: as in where I am. But suppose you are working in a bank, you can still feel rooted in your

01:26:16.680 --> 01:26:20.440
[Guest]: family, but you still have to be a good banker, right? You need to figure out how to do banking

01:26:20.440 --> 01:26:24.040
[Guest]: well, how to be a good banker. If you are a teacher, you have to do that. Whether you

01:26:24.040 --> 01:26:28.360
[Guest]: are a, if you are a civil servant, you still have to figure it out. But the love for this

01:26:28.360 --> 01:26:34.200
[Guest]: land or this people, we as a people and our whole long history of common suffering and

01:26:34.200 --> 01:26:40.240
[Guest]: struggles and the way we have come is the root on which all of that stands, basically.

01:26:40.240 --> 01:26:45.440
[Guest]: That's the way I look at it. That root is not the future, but that is where we come

01:26:45.440 --> 01:26:46.440
[Guest]: from.

01:26:46.440 --> 01:26:52.440
[Amit Varma]: So, I want to now move to the question of virtue and there are many angles to it, but

01:26:52.440 --> 01:26:58.520
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to start with the personal angle in the sense that, you know, one question

01:26:58.520 --> 01:27:04.960
[Amit Varma]: that I ask myself a lot is how should we live our lives, right? How do we live our lives?

01:27:04.960 --> 01:27:09.680
[Amit Varma]: How do we think about what is the right thing to do and what is the wrong thing to do? And

01:27:09.680 --> 01:27:14.400
[Amit Varma]: I think how we come up upon it early in life is there's a conventional way of thinking

01:27:14.400 --> 01:27:19.040
[Amit Varma]: this is good, that is bad and we kind of go by that. And of course, you know, we are hardwired

01:27:19.040 --> 01:27:24.200
[Amit Varma]: in certain ways with different sort of codes, which often conflict with each other. There's

01:27:24.200 --> 01:27:27.960
[Amit Varma]: a great book by Robert Wright called The Moral Animal, which kind of talks about some of

01:27:27.960 --> 01:27:33.280
[Amit Varma]: this and that's one sort of way of looking at it. But, you know, those are knobs that

01:27:33.280 --> 01:27:37.840
[Amit Varma]: nature gives you and nurture turns them and nurture turns them in different ways where

01:27:37.840 --> 01:27:42.840
[Amit Varma]: you pick up values from your immediate surroundings. You know, religion is one codification of

01:27:42.840 --> 01:27:47.880
[Amit Varma]: it, but that's also diffuse and contextual. But then there comes a time where you actually

01:27:47.880 --> 01:27:55.760
[Amit Varma]: start thinking about it, where you go beyond your broad moral instincts, as it were, and

01:27:55.760 --> 01:28:02.400
[Amit Varma]: you start thinking about, you know, what is a good way to live one's life? And why is

01:28:02.400 --> 01:28:08.080
[Amit Varma]: it a good way to live one's life? And start thinking along those terms. So what's sort

01:28:08.080 --> 01:28:12.600
[Amit Varma]: of your journey been towards? And I asked you this question, I won't ask many others

01:28:12.600 --> 01:28:16.160
[Amit Varma]: this question, but I asked you this question, because I know you've thought about this deeply

01:28:16.160 --> 01:28:20.840
[Amit Varma]: read about it deeply done that self reflection. And it's something I struggle with in the

01:28:20.840 --> 01:28:25.480
[Amit Varma]: sense that struggle with in the sense that it's an ongoing journey, obviously, for everyone.

01:28:25.480 --> 01:28:31.600
[Amit Varma]: But so I'd be very interested in knowing what was your intellectual journey towards, you

01:28:31.600 --> 01:28:36.360
[Amit Varma]: know, figuring out what one should do, like we've been using the term dharma. And, you

01:28:36.360 --> 01:28:41.600
[Amit Varma]: know, we can talk about it in the context of professions after this. But first, I kind

01:28:41.600 --> 01:28:47.760
[Amit Varma]: of want to focus on the personal, that when it comes to your dharma as a person, or perhaps

01:28:47.760 --> 01:28:51.960
[Amit Varma]: broken into roles, your dharma towards your family or dharma towards your wife and kids

01:28:51.960 --> 01:28:56.800
[Amit Varma]: and so on, you know, how have you thought about it? Who are the writers? What are the

01:28:56.800 --> 01:29:01.160
[Amit Varma]: books that have shaped your thinking on this? And what are the lessons that you feel you've

01:29:01.160 --> 01:29:02.160
[Amit Varma]: learned in time?

01:29:02.160 --> 01:29:07.640
[Guest]: Yeah, so I don't think this is an intellectual kind of exercise. I mean, one reads about

01:29:07.640 --> 01:29:12.920
[Guest]: these things, but I think it's much more of an experiential thing. And one has to engage

01:29:12.920 --> 01:29:17.640
[Guest]: with one's situations and try to do the best one can. And sometimes one can get it wrong.

01:29:17.640 --> 01:29:21.440
[Guest]: Sometimes one can get it right. And later you realize whether you got it wrong or right.

01:29:21.440 --> 01:29:25.280
[Guest]: But yeah, I think reading and thinking about these things helps talking about these things

01:29:25.280 --> 01:29:30.160
[Guest]: also helps. So I the way I see human life is basically there are different phases in

01:29:30.160 --> 01:29:34.680
[Guest]: which look backwards and you see what what what is going on. It's not when you're living

01:29:34.680 --> 01:29:39.680
[Guest]: it. So basically, when you get into this world, initially, you're a family person, like in

01:29:39.680 --> 01:29:43.680
[Guest]: many ways, your behavior is shaped by your family in significant ways and your friends

01:29:43.680 --> 01:29:48.360
[Guest]: in a circle in which you find yourself, your teachers and all of that, then you have to

01:29:48.360 --> 01:29:54.120
[Guest]: make a place for yourself in this world. So you enter into the educational and professional

01:29:54.120 --> 01:29:57.960
[Guest]: realm and you start working or start business or whatever it is that you want to do, you

01:29:57.960 --> 01:30:03.160
[Guest]: get into politics. At that time, you're playing a game, right? Because the what is the game

01:30:03.160 --> 01:30:08.200
[Guest]: that there is some situation that you find yourself and you want to get ahead, right?

01:30:08.200 --> 01:30:13.080
[Guest]: And that's the game you played basically, at least in the middle age, you know, and

01:30:13.080 --> 01:30:16.960
[Guest]: within that game, if you're not playing a game, then it's a completely different world.

01:30:16.960 --> 01:30:21.480
[Guest]: If you just kind of like some people do at a young age, they decide that the spiritual

01:30:21.480 --> 01:30:25.760
[Guest]: path is for them and they basically take sannyas. There is a small number who do that in India

01:30:25.760 --> 01:30:31.600
[Guest]: even now. Other traditions also, there is a very small number that that used to do that.

01:30:31.600 --> 01:30:35.880
[Guest]: But otherwise, you're in a game, you are basically, if you're in politics, you want to get ahead

01:30:35.880 --> 01:30:39.560
[Guest]: in politics. If you're in a corporate setting, you want to get ahead in politics. And then

01:30:39.560 --> 01:30:45.400
[Guest]: in certain qualities of your life get accentuated and other qualities get suppressed in the

01:30:45.400 --> 01:30:49.720
[Guest]: process. You know, to some extent, you can have this, you know, both ways a little bit

01:30:49.720 --> 01:30:55.120
[Guest]: five days you work and two days you do whatever, you know, weekends. But more or less, I mean,

01:30:55.120 --> 01:31:00.840
[Guest]: that's talking about our, many people don't have that luxury also, there's hardly a weekend.

01:31:00.840 --> 01:31:04.880
[Guest]: But the structure is the same that there is a period in which you are basically trying

01:31:04.880 --> 01:31:09.600
[Guest]: to find a footing in your life and trying to find a place in this world. And you are

01:31:09.600 --> 01:31:16.840
[Guest]: playing a particular, to repeat myself, game in which you find yourself, right? You entered,

01:31:16.840 --> 01:31:21.680
[Guest]: you did an MBA or whatever, you got into a job, and then you're trying to get ahead.

01:31:21.680 --> 01:31:26.720
[Guest]: In that, I mean, you may have a sense of right and wrong. But in many ways, you find yourself

01:31:26.720 --> 01:31:31.960
[Guest]: in a situation in which it's very expensive, and then you have to take a decision. And

01:31:31.960 --> 01:31:36.200
[Guest]: then those decisions can be hard. If you're lucky, you will not have to take those decisions

01:31:36.200 --> 01:31:43.320
[Guest]: and you will find yourself walking a path of virtue and something which keeps you and

01:31:43.320 --> 01:31:48.400
[Guest]: your moral sense, pride, your conscience is not suppressed too much and you keep walking

01:31:48.400 --> 01:31:52.800
[Guest]: that path and you still do well. But in their situation, which you have to actually pay

01:31:52.800 --> 01:31:56.560
[Guest]: a price for that. So the point I'm trying to make here is that it is not just about

01:31:56.560 --> 01:32:01.520
[Guest]: you sitting in a room and deciding what is virtue and what is not. It is more experiential

01:32:01.520 --> 01:32:05.360
[Guest]: and you are actually interacting with the real world and dealing with situations and

01:32:05.360 --> 01:32:10.120
[Guest]: trying to say what would work and what would. So there is a kind of dialectic between virtue

01:32:10.120 --> 01:32:15.440
[Guest]: and success and there is sometimes they go together very well and more often than not.

01:32:15.440 --> 01:32:20.120
[Guest]: And so the point I'm trying to make is that two journeys happening at the same time. One

01:32:20.120 --> 01:32:24.760
[Guest]: is the journey which is of you being a person in this world trying to find a place for in

01:32:24.760 --> 01:32:30.440
[Guest]: this world. You have a family, you may not have a family, you are trying to make a career

01:32:30.440 --> 01:32:34.280
[Guest]: of whatever kind you want to do and there is a journey. A young person, you don't know

01:32:34.280 --> 01:32:38.760
[Guest]: what the world is like, you are uncertain how much the world will accommodate you. So

01:32:38.760 --> 01:32:43.240
[Guest]: you accommodate a lot of the world, right? You try to adjust yourself to a significant

01:32:43.240 --> 01:32:49.080
[Guest]: extent and if you're lucky, you will continue to be virtuous and get ahead and your sense

01:32:49.080 --> 01:32:55.000
[Guest]: of yourself, your own righteousness and what is required to be done will not be unmatched

01:32:55.000 --> 01:32:56.000
[Guest]: much.

01:32:56.000 --> 01:32:59.800
[Guest]: But often there are compromises. Then you get to something like a middle age, you know

01:32:59.800 --> 01:33:05.320
[Guest]: where at that point you need to actually because you've at least in our setting not universally

01:33:05.320 --> 01:33:09.960
[Guest]: true but in many, we will find some kind of a footing, right? Like after 15, 16, 20 years

01:33:09.960 --> 01:33:13.560
[Guest]: of working, you'll find some kind of footing, you've got some sense of who you are and all

01:33:13.560 --> 01:33:18.880
[Guest]: of that. At that time it's important to say what did you suppress? What all that you actually

01:33:18.880 --> 01:33:24.640
[Guest]: compromised? What got hidden inside you, you know? And then you need to deal with that

01:33:24.640 --> 01:33:29.280
[Guest]: and then there is another rediscovery at that time and that's where I think the most important

01:33:29.280 --> 01:33:34.800
[Guest]: obligation comes in that you actually start living your life at that stage. That is your

01:33:34.800 --> 01:33:39.280
[Guest]: life, that in a way you have a better sense of who you are and you have an obligation

01:33:39.280 --> 01:33:43.640
[Guest]: to have a better sense of who you are because in some ways you've done that bulk of the

01:33:43.640 --> 01:33:48.960
[Guest]: Maya part that you played those games and you've done whatever to the extent keeping

01:33:48.960 --> 01:33:55.880
[Guest]: your conscience alive and then the real moral obligation start that now you need to have

01:33:55.880 --> 01:34:01.440
[Guest]: a very clear sense of who you are and what is the right thing to do and all of that.

01:34:01.440 --> 01:34:05.680
[Guest]: So when you are younger, the obligation is not so much on you. It's about people around

01:34:05.680 --> 01:34:11.920
[Guest]: you much more, you know? So again, I always think in a social sense, it's not myself as

01:34:11.920 --> 01:34:16.520
[Guest]: an individual isolated way. So when I was 22 years old, if I got something wrong, it

01:34:16.520 --> 01:34:20.840
[Guest]: is the elder near me who should have known better to tell me or guide me or whatever

01:34:20.840 --> 01:34:26.120
[Guest]: or I'll just say I was unlucky. I didn't have a good better sense of what is right or wrong.

01:34:26.120 --> 01:34:33.600
[Guest]: As 42, I don't have that luxury. I'm not 42. But when I'm 42 years old, then one has to

01:34:33.600 --> 01:34:38.600
[Guest]: go away, you know, like always said that at 50 everybody deserves a face they have like

01:34:38.600 --> 01:34:43.040
[Guest]: at 50, everybody deserves a character, you know, that's the character they have actually

01:34:43.040 --> 01:34:49.120
[Guest]: in a way chosen to have. So then you actually have to ask this question. And I think more

01:34:49.120 --> 01:34:55.520
[Guest]: and more I'm thinking about it is in terms of trying to find a way in which you you're

01:34:55.520 --> 01:35:02.040
[Guest]: more cautiously driven by some values, you know, and that's those values can be I mean,

01:35:02.040 --> 01:35:05.840
[Guest]: it depends on where you are situated. But broadly speaking, there has to be some sense

01:35:05.840 --> 01:35:10.000
[Guest]: of virtues, you know, that, okay, this, this is what the right thing to do. These are the

01:35:10.000 --> 01:35:15.560
[Guest]: broad kind of markers of what right and wrong are in my setting. And I'll try to follow

01:35:15.560 --> 01:35:19.400
[Guest]: those. So, for example, if you're in the intellectual world, some commitment to truth is very important.

01:35:19.400 --> 01:35:25.360
[Guest]: Some open mindedness is very important. Some sense of rigor, some bit of rigor is important,

01:35:25.360 --> 01:35:28.760
[Guest]: depending on the purpose and the timeliness within which you're working on whatever it

01:35:28.760 --> 01:35:34.460
[Guest]: is trying to find out some kind of a social commitment in terms of that you are not just

01:35:34.460 --> 01:35:37.600
[Guest]: doing this for your own sake. But actually, there are some consequences that are going

01:35:37.600 --> 01:35:42.120
[Guest]: to flow. All those are important, you know, in that sense in the work life. Similarly,

01:35:42.120 --> 01:35:46.640
[Guest]: there are obligations that you feel and the virtues towards your family, towards your

01:35:46.640 --> 01:35:51.080
[Guest]: spouse and your children and your parents and all of that. And as a situation comes,

01:35:51.080 --> 01:35:56.080
[Guest]: it can I mean, you'll have to then make a decision about how to how to approach it in

01:35:56.080 --> 01:36:00.720
[Guest]: a way that is that is the right thing to do. But one thing to always keep in mind is that

01:36:00.720 --> 01:36:07.440
[Guest]: you will always fail. You will always fail. And it is important to try to get up and still

01:36:07.440 --> 01:36:11.920
[Guest]: try to do better the next day, you know. And the only thing is that by the end of your

01:36:11.920 --> 01:36:16.920
[Guest]: life, you should try to be as good as one can be. There's a journey. If you're unlucky,

01:36:16.920 --> 01:36:20.880
[Guest]: you'll die young. Okay, that's one. But towards the end of the life, you should try to be

01:36:20.880 --> 01:36:26.400
[Guest]: you know, there's a great Catholic writer who wrote, I think it was Catholic, who wrote

01:36:26.400 --> 01:36:33.640
[Guest]: that, you know, the only tragedy of life is if you don't die as a saint. You know, so

01:36:33.640 --> 01:36:38.200
[Guest]: something to that effect that at the end you should, you know, all that things about playing

01:36:38.200 --> 01:36:42.120
[Guest]: the games of the world and trying to compromise all of that and not have not knowing what's

01:36:42.120 --> 01:36:47.200
[Guest]: the right thing to do, all those issues should fall apart, fall away. And what should matter

01:36:47.200 --> 01:36:53.440
[Guest]: is what is good. And it's a great tragedy if you see someone who's at an advanced age

01:36:53.440 --> 01:36:58.400
[Guest]: has seen this world, lived through many ups and downs and made a place on the world, but

01:36:58.400 --> 01:37:04.360
[Guest]: still haven't figured out what being a saint is like, you know, and don't have that sense.

01:37:04.360 --> 01:37:09.880
[Guest]: There's a very interesting story by Isaac Singer, Gimple the Fool. You should read it.

01:37:09.880 --> 01:37:13.800
[Guest]: It's a very interesting story about this guy who's fooled by everybody in his village,

01:37:13.800 --> 01:37:19.960
[Guest]: you know, and everybody just takes him for granted. His neighbors take advantage of him.

01:37:19.960 --> 01:37:25.960
[Guest]: He's a baker and his wife is very promiscuous. She also takes advantage of him. So lots of

01:37:25.960 --> 01:37:30.000
[Guest]: people take advantage of him. And, you know, the basic thing is that it's better to be

01:37:30.000 --> 01:37:35.040
[Guest]: fooled than to fool others, you know, and that's the message of the story. It's a very

01:37:35.040 --> 01:37:42.200
[Guest]: nice story. It's worth reading. It's based on some old kind of folktale of Judaism from

01:37:42.200 --> 01:37:47.600
[Guest]: those traditions. And I think, so yeah, I think there's a kind of interplay between

01:37:47.600 --> 01:37:51.480
[Guest]: trying to find a place in this world. And then we also need to create a social order

01:37:51.480 --> 01:37:56.280
[Guest]: or a setting in which virtues are easier to practice in some sense. The right thing is

01:37:56.280 --> 01:38:02.120
[Guest]: easier to do. And I think that's very important because if you put all the onus on the individual,

01:38:02.120 --> 01:38:07.640
[Guest]: it just becomes a very, very difficult situation. So what is good is something that we discover

01:38:07.640 --> 01:38:11.840
[Guest]: over time and in specific situations, but also to be able to do that good and to be

01:38:11.840 --> 01:38:17.880
[Guest]: able to behave well and to be fair to each other, to be just. And it's very important

01:38:17.880 --> 01:38:21.680
[Guest]: to find a setting in which it's something which doesn't destroy your life or take too

01:38:21.680 --> 01:38:25.640
[Guest]: much away from you, you know. And that I think is very important. That's why you should think

01:38:25.640 --> 01:38:29.120
[Guest]: in social settings, virtues. So when you think of profession, you think about professional

01:38:29.120 --> 01:38:33.400
[Guest]: bodies and professions as such, you know, not about the individual heroic professional

01:38:33.400 --> 01:38:37.280
[Guest]: rising up and doing whatever. So when you talk about, for example, you need to, for

01:38:37.280 --> 01:38:41.920
[Guest]: example, these days we talk about institutions and judges and all of that. I think it's completely

01:38:41.920 --> 01:38:45.600
[Guest]: wrong to put things on individual judges and why didn't you stand up and all. What did

01:38:45.600 --> 01:38:49.920
[Guest]: we as a polity do? I mean, why don't we have more balance of power in the polity? Why is

01:38:49.920 --> 01:38:54.960
[Guest]: a heroic judge has to stand up to a dominant power structure and say, oh, I will stand

01:38:54.960 --> 01:39:00.200
[Guest]: up and show it to you. Why? I mean, we as a polity have created a situation in which

01:39:00.200 --> 01:39:05.480
[Guest]: judges have to take very difficult decisions and you say, oh, it's very easy to say, right?

01:39:05.480 --> 01:39:10.120
[Guest]: It could destroy everything and stand up to basically for a meaningless quest, because

01:39:10.120 --> 01:39:13.360
[Guest]: if the government really, a dominant party really wants something, it's very difficult

01:39:13.360 --> 01:39:16.240
[Guest]: for a judge to stand up to it. And you can stand up, but it won't be fructuous because

01:39:16.240 --> 01:39:21.060
[Guest]: they'll find other ways to undermine whatever you did that the judge writes in an order.

01:39:21.060 --> 01:39:25.160
[Guest]: So these are, I think, cost cutting themes across institutions, professions, families,

01:39:25.160 --> 01:39:29.880
[Guest]: all of that, that there's a setting in which it's easier to exercise virtues and be a good

01:39:29.880 --> 01:39:35.460
[Guest]: judge or a good teacher or good doctor and all of that. And then the owner still remains

01:39:35.460 --> 01:39:40.360
[Guest]: on the individual to figure it out and do it, you know, and then you'll always fail

01:39:40.360 --> 01:39:45.200
[Guest]: and you will try to do better. So, I mean, I do have, I mean, situations where I behave

01:39:45.200 --> 01:39:49.760
[Guest]: badly and I still, I'm haunted by them. But that haunting, I try to now process towards

01:39:49.760 --> 01:39:54.760
[Guest]: doing better in the future, you know. I have misspoken with somebody, fought with somebody,

01:39:54.760 --> 01:40:00.280
[Guest]: said something wrong. But it's just a part of human life. If you long, I've now lived

01:40:00.280 --> 01:40:06.640
[Guest]: for almost 39 years in this world. So there is a certain sense of past, you know, and

01:40:06.640 --> 01:40:10.680
[Guest]: then there are wrongs and rights and all of that. But one thing is for sure that one keeps

01:40:10.680 --> 01:40:15.000
[Guest]: getting better is I think what one has to take that the arch should be in that direction

01:40:15.000 --> 01:40:18.320
[Guest]: and hopefully one dies as a saint.

01:40:18.320 --> 01:40:21.640
[Amit Varma]: You mentioned you're almost 39. Listen, my episodes go on for a long time. So by the

01:40:21.640 --> 01:40:26.200
[Amit Varma]: time this recording is over, you might actually get there. You mentioned Orwell, who is of

01:40:26.200 --> 01:40:30.960
[Amit Varma]: course one of, like two of my intellectual heroes Orwell and Bastia and they both died

01:40:30.960 --> 01:40:36.120
[Amit Varma]: at around 50 and they both kind of wrote their greatest works just before they turned 50.

01:40:36.120 --> 01:40:43.640
[Amit Varma]: And I have like a year and a half to go till 50. So, but I, yeah, good luck to me. But

01:40:43.640 --> 01:40:47.680
[Amit Varma]: that's a great quote about, you know, how, which I hadn't heard before, where you quoted

01:40:47.680 --> 01:40:52.160
[Amit Varma]: Orwell as saying that by the time you are 50, you should know your real face or whatever.

01:40:52.160 --> 01:40:56.360
[Amit Varma]: Then you mentioned sainthood and Orwell's thoughts on sainthood are also interesting,

01:40:56.360 --> 01:41:00.400
[Amit Varma]: where in this great essay he wrote called Reflections on Gandhi, this first para is

01:41:00.400 --> 01:41:04.720
[Amit Varma]: just a work of genius. And he wrote, quote, saints should always be judged guilty until

01:41:04.720 --> 01:41:08.760
[Amit Varma]: they are proved innocent. But the tests that have to be applied to them are not, of course,

01:41:08.760 --> 01:41:13.680
[Amit Varma]: the same in all cases. In Gandhi's case, the questions one feel inclined to ask are to

01:41:13.680 --> 01:41:18.880
[Amit Varma]: what extent was Gandhi moved by vanity, by the consciousness of himself as a humble naked

01:41:18.880 --> 01:41:24.160
[Amit Varma]: old man sitting on a prayer mat and shaking empires by sheer spiritual power? And to what

01:41:24.160 --> 01:41:30.000
[Amit Varma]: extent did he compromise his own principles by entering politics, which of their nature

01:41:30.000 --> 01:41:35.400
[Amit Varma]: are inseparable from coercion and fraud? Stop quote. And this leads to a couple of themes,

01:41:35.400 --> 01:41:40.360
[Amit Varma]: which you and I have sort of discussed in the past. And one of them is my sense that

01:41:40.360 --> 01:41:46.880
[Amit Varma]: sometimes the quest for virtue can be driven by the vanity of wanting to see yourself as

01:41:46.880 --> 01:41:53.000
[Amit Varma]: a virtuous person. And this entangling that can be, you know, interesting. Like, for example,

01:41:53.000 --> 01:41:57.360
[Amit Varma]: what I see on social media is that those who project the most virtue are often the least

01:41:57.360 --> 01:42:02.200
[Amit Varma]: virtuous, right? And we can both think of examples of people like this. And that's therefore

01:42:02.200 --> 01:42:05.660
[Amit Varma]: something that makes me question myself. And I think of the right thing to do, like one

01:42:05.660 --> 01:42:10.040
[Amit Varma]: test I have for myself on social media these days, I have failed this test in the past,

01:42:10.040 --> 01:42:14.880
[Amit Varma]: but these days, is that if I'm putting out a tweet, I need to ask myself that am I doing

01:42:14.880 --> 01:42:20.000
[Amit Varma]: it for the validation of other people so that other people think better of me, because that

01:42:20.000 --> 01:42:26.480
[Amit Varma]: is a natural motive, but it is a little suspect. Now, the other aspect that it leads me to

01:42:26.480 --> 01:42:32.200
[Amit Varma]: think about is the way you presented these phases of life, you almost seem to be saying

01:42:32.200 --> 01:42:38.040
[Amit Varma]: that once you reach a certain age, the examined life will lead to the virtuous life that you

01:42:38.040 --> 01:42:43.040
[Amit Varma]: need to sit back and introspect and whatever. And thinking about this, I think about your

01:42:43.040 --> 01:42:48.560
[Amit Varma]: earlier reference to spending your younger years playing a game, which is a great description

01:42:48.560 --> 01:42:54.080
[Amit Varma]: and the term is apt. But I'm just thinking that you can look at it in retrospect and

01:42:54.080 --> 01:43:00.000
[Amit Varma]: know you were playing the game. In the moment, 99.9% of people don't know they are playing

01:43:00.000 --> 01:43:04.460
[Amit Varma]: the game. Yes, they are in the game. And the thing is that the game is shaping who they

01:43:04.460 --> 01:43:09.320
[Amit Varma]: are. So after the game, there is no point in introspecting, they have changed. And the

01:43:09.320 --> 01:43:14.160
[Amit Varma]: morality that they had to or the ways of doing things that they had to adapt while playing

01:43:14.160 --> 01:43:20.240
[Amit Varma]: the game is something that would have sort of changed them so much. Like I think it was

01:43:20.240 --> 01:43:25.180
[Amit Varma]: you who once told me about how politics corrodes character, because the incentives of the political

01:43:25.180 --> 01:43:30.760
[Amit Varma]: game are such that you can enter politics with the finest of intentions. But all the

01:43:30.760 --> 01:43:35.560
[Amit Varma]: necessary compromises that you make will eventually will shape your actions and your actions will

01:43:35.560 --> 01:43:41.040
[Amit Varma]: eventually change who you are. And then you are a different person at the end of the process.

01:43:41.040 --> 01:43:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's exactly what Orwell talks about in this para as well. And so therefore, you

01:43:47.000 --> 01:43:52.720
[Amit Varma]: know, I'll just sort of end this by saying that, therefore, I completely agree with you

01:43:52.720 --> 01:43:59.840
[Amit Varma]: on the centrality of thinking about the systems from which these incentives emerge, the incentives

01:43:59.840 --> 01:44:03.720
[Amit Varma]: which drive us to do the things that we do, like one thing that I've always said of our

01:44:03.720 --> 01:44:08.040
[Amit Varma]: system of government is that we should design our system of government in such a way that

01:44:08.040 --> 01:44:14.360
[Amit Varma]: even the worst, most immoral psychopath is in power, there's limited damage he can do,

01:44:14.360 --> 01:44:18.440
[Amit Varma]: because the system is one that rewards good behavior and punishes bad behavior. And it

01:44:18.440 --> 01:44:24.760
[Amit Varma]: works in that respect. And, you know, so a lot of the responsibility is, therefore, you

01:44:24.760 --> 01:44:29.280
[Amit Varma]: know, comes from the system, you want to design the structures in place in our society. And

01:44:29.280 --> 01:44:34.800
[Amit Varma]: in, and by design, I don't mean in a top down way, obviously, as you know, but, you know,

01:44:34.800 --> 01:44:39.080
[Amit Varma]: we need to think about how to move society in the state in directions where they are

01:44:39.080 --> 01:44:43.840
[Amit Varma]: providing incentives for good behavior, rather than just the other way around, as we see.

01:44:43.840 --> 01:44:51.880
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a lot to chew and talk about. So I think that two questions that you asked,

01:44:51.880 --> 01:44:58.360
[Guest]: one is that, when is virtue, virtue, and one is virtue vanity. And the other question is

01:44:58.360 --> 01:45:03.200
[Guest]: that, what is the point of introspection after a point when you already become something

01:45:03.200 --> 01:45:08.040
[Guest]: by having played a particular game? So I think both of these questions go back to the nature

01:45:08.040 --> 01:45:13.800
[Guest]: of human consciousness. I mean, in some senses, and it's a big term, human consciousness,

01:45:13.800 --> 01:45:21.040
[Guest]: and I'll put a simple kind of a beginning frame to it that if you reflect back on yourself,

01:45:21.040 --> 01:45:26.560
[Guest]: at least when I reflect back on it, I know that my conscious thinking rational mind is

01:45:26.560 --> 01:45:30.960
[Guest]: only the tip of the iceberg. There's a lot of me that I actually don't know, because

01:45:30.960 --> 01:45:35.920
[Guest]: that's the past that is suppressed, and it's unconscious. And I feel it in terms of emotions,

01:45:35.920 --> 01:45:40.600
[Guest]: and sometimes certain longings rise out of it, and certain things come to my mind, conscious

01:45:40.600 --> 01:45:44.880
[Guest]: mind, and I have to pay attention or ignore or whatever, there are complexes hidden. And

01:45:44.880 --> 01:45:49.600
[Guest]: psychoanalysts study this and write about it and all of that. And who we are is often

01:45:49.600 --> 01:45:54.040
[Guest]: not what the stories that we tell ourselves, right? So, but the stories we tell ourselves

01:45:54.040 --> 01:45:58.080
[Guest]: at the readings we do and the conversations we have do have a bearing, you know, it's

01:45:58.080 --> 01:46:02.720
[Guest]: not a, and in fact, the fact that we read something or talk to some people about some

01:46:02.720 --> 01:46:07.800
[Guest]: things itself reflects the kind of a deeper longing, right? And the fact that we're sitting

01:46:07.800 --> 01:46:13.440
[Guest]: here and talking about virtues, maybe partly vanity, and but there's also more to it, perhaps,

01:46:13.440 --> 01:46:16.240
[Guest]: because we're talking about this and not something else, which could also serve vanity at the

01:46:16.240 --> 01:46:20.580
[Guest]: same time. So there are different paths to vanity, which path to vanity do you take?

01:46:20.580 --> 01:46:26.360
[Guest]: But one key point that I've experienced in my own life is that, can you keep a distance

01:46:26.360 --> 01:46:30.480
[Guest]: between what you need to do out of necessity, because it's again going back to the human

01:46:30.480 --> 01:46:35.840
[Guest]: consciousness and then self nature of the self that you have. So, do you have this kind

01:46:35.840 --> 01:46:40.360
[Guest]: of a clear sense that this is a persona that you're wearing, and there is a certain role

01:46:40.360 --> 01:46:45.120
[Guest]: that you need to play. And then there is a self that is within it. And that remains a

01:46:45.120 --> 01:46:49.680
[Guest]: little less uncontaminated, you know, because it's a duty that, for example, if I was a

01:46:49.680 --> 01:46:53.480
[Guest]: prime minister of this country, I would have to do horrible things. I would have to just

01:46:53.480 --> 01:46:59.520
[Guest]: the nature of the responsibility is such that you need to sometimes order violence on your

01:46:59.520 --> 01:47:03.840
[Guest]: enemies. Sometimes you do order violence on your own citizens, because they are doing

01:47:03.840 --> 01:47:08.720
[Guest]: things which are they're trying to break away the republic or something. There are things

01:47:08.720 --> 01:47:12.600
[Guest]: difficult decisions to be taken, which will create harsh hardships, but maybe create good

01:47:12.600 --> 01:47:17.320
[Guest]: things on the on the whole utilitarian kind of logic is particularly sound, but it creates

01:47:17.320 --> 01:47:23.360
[Guest]: some harm. So, if you're sitting in a position like that, and you have to take decisions,

01:47:23.360 --> 01:47:29.040
[Guest]: at that point of time, can you simply get your personal morality into it and make it

01:47:29.040 --> 01:47:34.920
[Guest]: completely transferred into a position that demands by the virtue of you being sitting

01:47:34.920 --> 01:47:38.000
[Guest]: there. I mean, it could be any other human being, the same demands will be made on them.

01:47:38.000 --> 01:47:44.720
[Guest]: It's not about you as such. So, and there is a possibility I think that we need to give

01:47:44.720 --> 01:47:50.640
[Guest]: that there are people who behave badly, but are quite virtuous, actually, because the

01:47:50.640 --> 01:47:54.680
[Guest]: bad behavior was necessary in the context in which they found themselves, because of

01:47:54.680 --> 01:47:59.080
[Guest]: the nature of the world that we live in, that there are power struggles and you have duty

01:47:59.080 --> 01:48:04.120
[Guest]: to play those power struggles and defend your own, you know, especially in the international

01:48:04.120 --> 01:48:08.800
[Guest]: order, right? You're more or less anarchy kind of an order where you're trying to protect

01:48:08.800 --> 01:48:14.280
[Guest]: your country and further its interest in a way others are also fighting the same game

01:48:14.280 --> 01:48:20.320
[Guest]: and many of them don't see it as a, you know, as a win-win situation. Some of them actually

01:48:20.320 --> 01:48:24.400
[Guest]: want to impose a win-lose on you. So, you have to do the things that are necessary.

01:48:24.400 --> 01:48:28.320
[Guest]: You have to hide things, you have to lie a little bit, sometimes you have to cheat, you

01:48:28.320 --> 01:48:33.320
[Guest]: don't do things that you may not do in personal life. So, I think if you want to, if it's

01:48:33.320 --> 01:48:36.280
[Guest]: particularly interesting for anybody to understand someone's character, then you have to watch

01:48:36.280 --> 01:48:41.800
[Guest]: and see how they behave in different situations, you know, and then make a view about, well,

01:48:41.800 --> 01:48:49.680
[Guest]: is it vanity or is it virtue or is it a bit of both, you know. But I see the point that

01:48:49.680 --> 01:48:56.840
[Guest]: Orwell is making that sometimes something like this can also be presented as, and we

01:48:56.840 --> 01:49:00.880
[Guest]: see that in some of the scandals that come out about our Babas and all, sometimes, very

01:49:00.880 --> 01:49:04.880
[Guest]: rare, it's a very small percentage to be very clear. There are many, many spiritual people

01:49:04.880 --> 01:49:09.360
[Guest]: in this country, gurus and all who are not like that. Most are not like that. There are

01:49:09.360 --> 01:49:13.040
[Guest]: a small number who come out and give a bad name to everybody else who play that game

01:49:13.040 --> 01:49:18.080
[Guest]: that this is a path to glory and vanity and all of that. So, I think there's a distinction

01:49:18.080 --> 01:49:22.720
[Guest]: that McIntyre draws, which is very important and it's easy to state it, very difficult

01:49:22.720 --> 01:49:27.160
[Guest]: to actually assess it what's going on. So, he says there are two things. Whenever you

01:49:27.160 --> 01:49:31.760
[Guest]: are doing something, there are two kinds of goods that you can be pursuing. One is the

01:49:31.760 --> 01:49:37.680
[Guest]: goods in external to the practice. So, you're doing podcasting because you want to get money,

01:49:37.680 --> 01:49:43.080
[Guest]: fame, all of that. Or there are goods internal to practice. You're doing podcasting because

01:49:43.080 --> 01:49:48.800
[Guest]: you love the joy of podcasting and you want to be a better podcaster. This activity itself

01:49:48.800 --> 01:49:54.440
[Guest]: makes you feel very, I mean, good and you want to do better at doing that. And it's

01:49:54.440 --> 01:49:59.800
[Guest]: just a great podcast, even if it makes no money for you and basically you die in penury.

01:49:59.800 --> 01:50:09.760
[Guest]: That's not the case with you. Thankfully, in your case, both are more or less aligned.

01:50:09.760 --> 01:50:15.560
[Guest]: But in many cases, there is a conflict between goods internal to practice by trying to be

01:50:15.560 --> 01:50:20.680
[Guest]: a good practitioner of something, being a good professional or whatever it may be and

01:50:20.680 --> 01:50:24.840
[Guest]: goods external to practice, which is the money and the fame and all that comes with it. So,

01:50:24.840 --> 01:50:30.400
[Guest]: virtue is the latter, which is the goods internal to practice. A person who is genuinely virtuous

01:50:30.400 --> 01:50:36.280
[Guest]: is the one who is acting well because he actually wants to act well. Because for the sake of

01:50:36.280 --> 01:50:41.080
[Guest]: acting well, the right behavior is the right behavior for them. And they do it because

01:50:41.080 --> 01:50:44.280
[Guest]: it's the right behavior, not because it will give them something else or something.

01:50:44.280 --> 01:50:49.200
[Guest]: A completely different example. Recently, I read an interview with this Harshal Patel.

01:50:49.200 --> 01:50:54.820
[Guest]: He said that I am not the kind of person who needs 10 crore rupees in his life. He got

01:50:54.820 --> 01:50:59.600
[Guest]: 10 crores in IPL, but it's a signal of the fact that I am a good player, you know, something

01:50:59.600 --> 01:51:03.960
[Guest]: to that effect, he said. It was very interesting to me, because he sees that 10 crore rupees

01:51:03.960 --> 01:51:08.840
[Guest]: is basically a sign of what he's good at. But he actually plays it because he enjoys

01:51:08.840 --> 01:51:15.360
[Guest]: playing cricket. If you go by what he said, and I take it on a space value, why not? So,

01:51:15.360 --> 01:51:18.720
[Guest]: he basically enjoys playing cricket and he wants to be better at playing cricket. It's

01:51:18.720 --> 01:51:22.040
[Guest]: just incidental that he's getting 10 crore rupees. He would still play cricket maybe

01:51:22.040 --> 01:51:26.440
[Guest]: if he's giving him less. So, he said it, I'm not the kind of person who needs 10 crore

01:51:26.440 --> 01:51:32.120
[Guest]: rupees a year in his life. But it just shows that I'm good at this, you know. So, that

01:51:32.120 --> 01:51:37.160
[Guest]: I think distinction is very important. What is it that you're seeking when you're seeking,

01:51:37.160 --> 01:51:40.560
[Guest]: you're working on doing something, whether it's in the personal life or professional

01:51:40.560 --> 01:51:45.480
[Guest]: life, political or whatever. So, there are politicians who do all the bad things, looking

01:51:45.480 --> 01:51:50.200
[Guest]: from a very simplistic perspective of some principles of good or bad. But in their situation,

01:51:50.200 --> 01:51:53.000
[Guest]: bad or the right thing, they may still be very virtuous, actually, as human beings,

01:51:53.000 --> 01:51:58.000
[Guest]: their duty is demanded. And even vanity can sometimes, if you're in a particular position,

01:51:58.000 --> 01:52:02.160
[Guest]: you have to appear a certain kind of a persona, you know. You can't say that I will not give

01:52:02.160 --> 01:52:05.400
[Guest]: public talks, I will not do this and that. Because if you are in public life, you have

01:52:05.400 --> 01:52:09.440
[Guest]: to do all of these things. There's a vanity or is that your duty? You know, giving speeches

01:52:09.440 --> 01:52:14.040
[Guest]: is your duty, right? It's not just vanity, seeking people's attention and all that.

01:52:14.040 --> 01:52:18.560
[Guest]: The other question is a harder one, what you become and what you can become by reflection

01:52:18.560 --> 01:52:22.440
[Guest]: and all of that. It's a much harder question, because I mean, I'm at a stage of life when

01:52:22.440 --> 01:52:26.000
[Guest]: actually I'm going through that kind of a process, right? Because one is looking back

01:52:26.000 --> 01:52:31.640
[Guest]: and saying, okay, I've had this kind of a life and what can I take from there? So, there

01:52:31.640 --> 01:52:35.360
[Guest]: is a becoming, which I'm actually not aware of, because it's just kind of unconscious.

01:52:35.360 --> 01:52:39.440
[Guest]: I've shaped, I've been shaped in certain ways, the directions that took me in. And now I'm

01:52:39.440 --> 01:52:45.680
[Guest]: trying to gradually understand it by trying to imagine myself and trying to, through my

01:52:45.680 --> 01:52:49.640
[Guest]: dreams and all whatever, to understand what is it that I suppress and what is it that

01:52:49.640 --> 01:52:55.920
[Guest]: I elevated to the level of my, this kind of illusory category that I created with my name

01:52:55.920 --> 01:53:01.040
[Guest]: and put a lot of, you know, cool features into it and said, this is what I am, you know,

01:53:01.040 --> 01:53:05.400
[Guest]: which is what actually the persona is. And then the rest of it is basically to be discovered

01:53:05.400 --> 01:53:11.680
[Guest]: and figured out. And to, as I said, you can try to do better and try to be good without

01:53:11.680 --> 01:53:14.680
[Guest]: being too, I mean, you don't have to be very self-conscious about it. No, it's not some

01:53:14.680 --> 01:53:18.960
[Guest]: kind of a project where you start, okay, this is a start date, that's the end date, I need

01:53:18.960 --> 01:53:23.880
[Guest]: to do all this is a critical path I have to follow to get there. That's all. It's just

01:53:23.880 --> 01:53:27.680
[Guest]: a longing and you need to be aware of it and try to do it. It's not something which is

01:53:27.680 --> 01:53:32.200
[Guest]: can be fully planned in advance and there will be surprises in life. And sometimes you'll

01:53:32.200 --> 01:53:34.800
[Guest]: dream something and it will mean something to you and it will change the way you think

01:53:34.800 --> 01:53:39.600
[Guest]: about something. Sometimes you meet somebody who can provide you guidance, you can find

01:53:39.600 --> 01:53:43.960
[Guest]: a guru or something. You sometimes you'll have a conversation with a friend which can

01:53:43.960 --> 01:53:47.160
[Guest]: certainly strike you, okay, yeah, I didn't realize that about myself. Now I'm trying

01:53:47.160 --> 01:53:52.120
[Guest]: to be, I'll try to think more about it and thinking will go some way. I don't think we

01:53:52.120 --> 01:53:56.880
[Guest]: can change completely by just thinking about ourselves. But it's one part of the puzzle

01:53:56.880 --> 01:54:02.440
[Guest]: and self-reflection has in many people's lives made a difference. Not by yourself only, but

01:54:02.440 --> 01:54:08.600
[Guest]: talking to others, reading, thinking, talking, behaving differently, building better habits,

01:54:08.600 --> 01:54:12.400
[Guest]: those kind of things. Having some kind of rules of thumb as well sometimes, although

01:54:12.400 --> 01:54:18.240
[Guest]: they're often kind of meant to be broken. But I don't think that we are completely formed

01:54:18.240 --> 01:54:21.720
[Guest]: by our experiences by the time we are in middle age. At least also, that's not the bet I'm

01:54:21.720 --> 01:54:28.680
[Guest]: taking. I think there is room for a new birth, you know, in some senses, a renewal of sorts

01:54:28.680 --> 01:54:29.680
[Amit Varma]: in life.

01:54:29.680 --> 01:54:33.520
[Amit Varma]: I think in a sense, we are our own projects and the projects are bound to fail because

01:54:33.520 --> 01:54:36.400
[Amit Varma]: you are going to die one day. But you know, just to go back to what you said.

01:54:36.400 --> 01:54:38.400
[Guest]: That's not failure. I mean, life is essential.

01:54:38.400 --> 01:54:39.400
[Amit Varma]: I'm being glib.

01:54:39.400 --> 01:54:41.080
[Amit Varma]: That is an essential part of life.

01:54:41.080 --> 01:54:45.080
[Amit Varma]: I'm being glib though I won't go so far. But I mean, it's the end of life. It's not a part

01:54:45.080 --> 01:54:46.080
[Guest]: of life.

01:54:46.080 --> 01:54:49.200
[Guest]: But life would have no meaning without death.

01:54:49.200 --> 01:54:54.540
[Amit Varma]: Life has no meaning. But just to just to kind of go back to what you said about how even

01:54:54.540 --> 01:55:00.080
[Amit Varma]: someone who does bad things can be virtuous. And I'll say yes and no. And yes, in the sense

01:55:00.080 --> 01:55:05.560
[Amit Varma]: that we are responding to incentives within a particular context. And yeah, so I get where

01:55:05.560 --> 01:55:12.600
[Amit Varma]: that is coming from. And I sort of get where that is coming from. But equally, I think

01:55:12.600 --> 01:55:15.900
[Amit Varma]: that there are places where you have to draw a line. Otherwise, you can do the worst of

01:55:15.900 --> 01:55:20.000
[Amit Varma]: things and you can rationalize them and say that, hey, you know, these were the incentives

01:55:20.000 --> 01:55:23.800
[Amit Varma]: and this is why I did them. And there's a danger in that because you internalize that

01:55:23.800 --> 01:55:28.720
[Amit Varma]: rationalization. And, you know, just when you were thinking of having to do bad things

01:55:28.720 --> 01:55:33.400
[Amit Varma]: and you could still be virtuous and like the two men who came to mind are Vajpayee and

01:55:33.400 --> 01:55:38.840
[Amit Varma]: Modi. And I think Vajpayee, if he was still alive and still active and still in good shape,

01:55:38.840 --> 01:55:43.360
[Amit Varma]: and if he took over in 2014, he would be very different. He was a pretty good prime minister.

01:55:43.360 --> 01:55:46.920
[Amit Varma]: And in my view, the diametrically different from Modi, who is a terrible, terrible prime

01:55:46.920 --> 01:55:51.160
[Amit Varma]: minister and a terrible, terrible man. And the thing is, they would have done different

01:55:51.160 --> 01:55:57.200
[Amit Varma]: things. And you can see this in the sort of not quite the conversation, because they weren't

01:55:57.200 --> 01:56:03.360
[Amit Varma]: talking to each other. But that sort of conversation through intermediaries that they had after

01:56:03.360 --> 01:56:08.960
[Amit Varma]: the Gujarat 2002 riots, which Vajpayee came out against, and he, I think, used the phrase

01:56:08.960 --> 01:56:16.280
[Amit Varma]: Rajdharma. Right. So there was a sense there that there is, you know, a sense of ethics

01:56:16.280 --> 01:56:22.040
[Amit Varma]: that remains overarching. And that pervades what you do within sort of the context of

01:56:22.040 --> 01:56:26.760
[Amit Varma]: within the context of politics and what's within the context of that particular profession.

01:56:26.760 --> 01:56:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And after this, we'll also speak about how virtues relates in a professional context,

01:56:30.880 --> 01:56:37.280
[Amit Varma]: which you have thought about deeply and studied and all of that. So I think, so I agree that,

01:56:37.280 --> 01:56:40.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, the incentives around us shape our behavior and we could, you know, and it is

01:56:40.480 --> 01:56:45.400
[Amit Varma]: what it is. But at the same time, I think there is a danger in letting that excuse and

01:56:45.400 --> 01:56:51.520
[Amit Varma]: justify everything else that letting that excuse and justify crossing certain lines,

01:56:51.520 --> 01:56:53.840
[Amit Varma]: which we should not cross regardless of context.

01:56:53.840 --> 01:56:59.480
[Guest]: Yeah, so I mean, one thing is that I didn't know Mr. Vajpayee, I don't know Mr. Modi.

01:56:59.480 --> 01:57:02.040
[Guest]: Personally, I'm not going to comment on their personal character.

01:57:02.040 --> 01:57:04.440
[Amit Varma]: But you have to judge people by their actions, finally, right?

01:57:04.440 --> 01:57:09.720
[Guest]: Yes, but in politics, things are very different from the way you and I, it's a unit of analysis

01:57:09.720 --> 01:57:15.080
[Guest]: that which our mind kind of, in a way, to be applied very carefully to be able to make

01:57:15.080 --> 01:57:19.240
[Guest]: sense of what's going on. But one thing is for sure, as I said earlier, that virtues

01:57:19.240 --> 01:57:23.600
[Guest]: exist in a particular setting. And I mean, sometimes it's easier to be virtuous, sometimes

01:57:23.600 --> 01:57:27.520
[Guest]: it's easier to be vicious also. So one of the things that is different, like just a

01:57:27.520 --> 01:57:33.400
[Guest]: setting is that Mr. Vajpayee ran a government, which was a coalition government, we never

01:57:33.400 --> 01:57:39.240
[Guest]: really, he never really had the kind of power that is required to actually reveal what he

01:57:39.240 --> 01:57:47.440
[Guest]: would do when he was a kind of a, he had real power in some senses. Mr. Modi has run is

01:57:47.440 --> 01:57:52.080
[Guest]: now the second term of a single party majority, comfortable majority in both times, the second

01:57:52.080 --> 01:57:57.080
[Guest]: largest party has been one sixth or one seventh of the largest party in the House of the People

01:57:57.080 --> 01:58:02.920
[Guest]: Lok Sabha. It's a, so when you have so much power, it's, there's no, there's no check

01:58:02.920 --> 01:58:06.440
[Guest]: on you, right? No real check, especially in a democracy, because power comes from the

01:58:06.440 --> 01:58:10.240
[Guest]: people and the people are with you. And so you, you feel that you can do anything and

01:58:10.240 --> 01:58:14.760
[Guest]: you can experiment, make big experiments, make, try difficult and painful things, and

01:58:14.760 --> 01:58:19.000
[Guest]: hopefully they'll work out and all of that. So one thing that you have to control for

01:58:19.000 --> 01:58:22.760
[Guest]: is the kind of power that when you have, especially when you talk about politics, and when you

01:58:22.760 --> 01:58:26.080
[Guest]: have power, you will behave very differently, the same person will behave very differently

01:58:26.080 --> 01:58:29.720
[Guest]: when you don't have power. So I don't know whether the counterfactual of Mr. Vajpayee

01:58:29.720 --> 01:58:33.160
[Guest]: would have done better than Mr. Modi when he had this much, these many MPs. I think

01:58:33.160 --> 01:58:37.280
[Guest]: we think about this in a very simplistic way. We underestimate the social setting, right?

01:58:37.280 --> 01:58:40.800
[Guest]: What is social setting? If you're a Prime Minister, how important is it to you for you

01:58:40.800 --> 01:58:46.360
[Guest]: to actually consult and take others on board? For the median person, there are lots of exceptions,

01:58:46.360 --> 01:58:50.560
[Guest]: but in the median person, they just want their ideas to be implemented. You know, who wants

01:58:50.560 --> 01:58:56.800
[Guest]: to go and take six months to create consensus and all? You do it because you need to, right?

01:58:56.800 --> 01:59:00.280
[Guest]: Because you need to do consensus, you need to create constituencies, because otherwise

01:59:00.280 --> 01:59:04.160
[Guest]: you can't get anything in. But once you get that kind of power, the chances of making

01:59:04.160 --> 01:59:08.520
[Guest]: a mistake are much greater, even with the best intentions. So you listen to the three

01:59:08.520 --> 01:59:11.480
[Guest]: or four people who are close to you, many of them may not feel like giving you negative

01:59:11.480 --> 01:59:17.520
[Guest]: feedback. And even if they do, I am the one who has a people's, you know, I am this, I

01:59:17.520 --> 01:59:20.920
[Guest]: am that. Imagine the kind of ego inflation you've gone through. Some people have waited

01:59:20.920 --> 01:59:27.400
[Guest]: for you twice that. So then a completely different kind of a situation emerges, social setting

01:59:27.400 --> 01:59:33.240
[Guest]: in which decisions are being made. And I think, I mean, much more, I mean, it's an old Actonian

01:59:33.240 --> 01:59:37.880
[Guest]: kind of wisdom, right? Power corrupts, absolute power corrupts absolutely. And there's a version

01:59:37.880 --> 01:59:43.280
[Guest]: of it, power makes mistakes and absolute power makes more mistakes, you know. And that's

01:59:43.280 --> 01:59:47.960
[Guest]: what I think that's one part of it that you need to consider before making a judgment

01:59:47.960 --> 01:59:53.680
[Guest]: about the person as such, because I don't know, there was certainly a PR image of Mr.

01:59:53.680 --> 01:59:58.120
[Guest]: Vajpayee, which was very good. And I also hold that in my mind, I come from UP and there's

01:59:58.120 --> 02:00:02.800
[Guest]: a nostalgia about his kind of very, in our belt, he was very popular. I even went for

02:00:02.800 --> 02:00:08.640
[Guest]: his rally once and it was amazing. It was a big show, you know, because people just

02:00:08.640 --> 02:00:13.240
[Guest]: thronged from all over the place to actually listen to him. He had that kind of a connect.

02:00:13.240 --> 02:00:19.280
[Guest]: So people just loved him in my part of the world. There was that, but we don't know what

02:00:19.280 --> 02:00:24.360
[Guest]: he was like, right? And more importantly, we would never know what he would have done

02:00:24.360 --> 02:00:27.440
[Guest]: with so much power. Because see, one of the main things about politicians, they always

02:00:27.440 --> 02:00:33.320
[Guest]: tend to hide who they are. You know, they are always trying to play a particular kind

02:00:33.320 --> 02:00:39.160
[Guest]: of game in terms of where projecting a certain kind of image is more important than, I mean,

02:00:39.160 --> 02:00:42.940
[Guest]: being just be yourself, you know, like we saw that with President Obama also, you know,

02:00:42.940 --> 02:00:47.080
[Guest]: he had a very clear, I mean, he projected a certain kind of persona. We'll never know

02:00:47.080 --> 02:00:49.280
[Guest]: what he was like in his personal life or whatever.

02:00:49.280 --> 02:00:52.600
[Amit Varma]: He was bombing the shit out of Afghanistan all that time.

02:00:52.600 --> 02:00:57.200
[Guest]: And also like doing other things which in some other principles that you may apply will

02:00:57.200 --> 02:01:03.120
[Guest]: say are bad things to be done. So it's very, very, all I'm saying is two things. One is

02:01:03.120 --> 02:01:07.840
[Guest]: that in politics, you have to control for the power that person has, judging their actions,

02:01:07.840 --> 02:01:11.720
[Guest]: because that changes the social setting. The other is, it's very difficult to figure out

02:01:11.720 --> 02:01:16.680
[Guest]: what a politician actually is in that they are always, always because they in democracy

02:01:16.680 --> 02:01:21.280
[Guest]: always looking for power, right? And how do they get power by being popular? What does

02:01:21.280 --> 02:01:29.000
[Guest]: it mean to be popular to actually pander to appeal to what would seem acceptable to people?

02:01:29.000 --> 02:01:34.680
[Guest]: So who you are becoming is three layers down, something which you and I will not have access

02:01:34.680 --> 02:01:35.680
[Amit Varma]: to.

02:01:35.680 --> 02:01:40.800
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. I mean, I agree with you power corrupts, but I think that that is a powerful

02:01:40.800 --> 02:01:45.720
[Amit Varma]: explanation and not a justification in any way. So I would still say that if power has

02:01:45.720 --> 02:01:46.720
[Guest]: corrupted you...

02:01:46.720 --> 02:01:52.120
[Guest]: See, you and I are not in the business of justification, we are in the business of explanation.

02:01:52.120 --> 02:01:54.840
[Guest]: Justification requires some kind of a legitimacy and authority to be able to...

02:01:54.840 --> 02:01:58.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but to finish what I'm saying, what I would say is that what I mean by we can

02:01:58.280 --> 02:02:03.720
[Amit Varma]: use it as explanation or justification is that if we say that power has corrupted you,

02:02:03.720 --> 02:02:07.360
[Amit Varma]: you are by definition not virtuous because you are corrupted. Perhaps you had the seeds

02:02:07.360 --> 02:02:13.120
[Amit Varma]: of virtue within you till life took you in another way. But we have we arrive at sort

02:02:13.120 --> 02:02:19.160
[Amit Varma]: of if we speak of someone's virtue by looking at the actions. And I agree that that's nuanced,

02:02:19.160 --> 02:02:22.240
[Amit Varma]: that you know, where do you draw the line and say that this is part of the job, any

02:02:22.240 --> 02:02:23.240
[Guest]: other PM could have done this.

02:02:23.240 --> 02:02:28.040
[Guest]: See, also as in democracy, a citizen is our duty to pass a judgment on our leaders, right

02:02:28.040 --> 02:02:29.520
[Amit Varma]: or wrong, right? It is our duty.

02:02:29.520 --> 02:02:31.520
[Guest]: See, you're contradicting yourself, be content with what you do.

02:02:31.520 --> 02:02:35.360
[Guest]: No, it is our duty, but we have to be also mindful that we often get it wrong and we

02:02:35.360 --> 02:02:39.440
[Guest]: shouldn't assume that we are right about it. So when you made a comparison in two persons,

02:02:39.440 --> 02:02:44.120
[Guest]: I made this answer. But if you ask me, I have been very critical of the decisions that Mr.

02:02:44.120 --> 02:02:49.240
[Guest]: Modi has taken and demonetization was a big mistake that he made. He has made other decisions

02:02:49.240 --> 02:02:53.520
[Guest]: which I don't agree with. So I think he could have done much better with the power that

02:02:53.520 --> 02:02:58.280
[Guest]: he had, he has had now for eight years, we can have those discussions. But I was making

02:02:58.280 --> 02:03:02.600
[Guest]: a limited point about comparing in the because you put a counterfactual in front of me. So

02:03:02.600 --> 02:03:05.800
[Guest]: I had to push back and say, are you really sure about that?

02:03:05.800 --> 02:03:11.040
[Amit Varma]: No, I agree with your answer, you have pushed back successfully, that you know that the

02:03:11.040 --> 02:03:15.160
[Amit Varma]: incentives were different that Modi had much more power and power does corrupt. But at

02:03:15.160 --> 02:03:19.440
[Amit Varma]: the same time, I would say that intellectually, Modi is a far more limited person in the sense

02:03:19.440 --> 02:03:23.640
[Amit Varma]: that Vajpayee was a man of culture, he had a deeper interior life, he read a lot, he

02:03:23.640 --> 02:03:28.120
[Amit Varma]: was into poetry, he was into all of that. And none of that is a guarantee for behaving

02:03:28.120 --> 02:03:33.480
[Amit Varma]: well as we have seen in the past. But you also have to account for human agency and

02:03:33.480 --> 02:03:40.560
[Amit Varma]: the differences between people and but who knows, perhaps everything is just how we are

02:03:40.560 --> 02:03:44.720
[Amit Varma]: shaped by circumstance and everything is rationalization. Let's take a quick commercial break. And on

02:03:44.720 --> 02:03:50.600
[Amit Varma]: the other side of the break, we'll continue our discussion.

02:03:50.600 --> 02:03:55.520
[Amit Varma]: Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer. In fact, chances are that many of you first

02:03:55.520 --> 02:04:01.240
[Amit Varma]: heard of me because of my blog India Uncut, which was active between 2003 and 2009 and

02:04:01.240 --> 02:04:05.880
[Amit Varma]: became somewhat popular at the time. I love the freedom the form gave me. And I feel I

02:04:05.880 --> 02:04:11.520
[Amit Varma]: was shaped by it in many ways. I exercise my writing muscle every day and was forced

02:04:11.520 --> 02:04:16.000
[Amit Varma]: to think about many different things because I wrote about many different things. Well,

02:04:16.000 --> 02:04:21.160
[Amit Varma]: that phase in my life ended for various reasons. And now it is time to revive it. Only now

02:04:21.160 --> 02:04:28.440
[Amit Varma]: I'm doing it through a newsletter. I have started the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com

02:04:28.440 --> 02:04:32.800
[Amit Varma]: where I will write regularly about whatever catches my fancy. I'll write about some of

02:04:32.800 --> 02:04:39.880
[Amit Varma]: the themes I cover in this podcast and about much else. So please do head on over to indiancut.substack.com

02:04:39.880 --> 02:04:44.800
[Amit Varma]: and subscribe. It is free. Once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land

02:04:44.800 --> 02:04:50.400
[Amit Varma]: up in your email inbox. You don't need to go anywhere. So subscribe now for free. The

02:04:50.400 --> 02:04:57.840
[Amit Varma]: India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com. Thank you.

02:04:57.840 --> 02:05:02.480
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with Suyash Rai. And, you know, being

02:05:02.480 --> 02:05:07.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, one of the virtues of a podcast is that once you have embarked upon a particular

02:05:07.360 --> 02:05:11.400
[Amit Varma]: narrative line, you kind of continue as far as you need to go. And we were talking about

02:05:11.400 --> 02:05:19.960
[Amit Varma]: virtue while before the break. So you've also spoken a lot to me in the past about the role

02:05:19.960 --> 02:05:25.360
[Amit Varma]: of virtues in professions, where your point is that in every profession, you know, it's

02:05:25.360 --> 02:05:30.760
[Amit Varma]: not just about following incentives, but professionals need to think about what are the ethics of

02:05:30.760 --> 02:05:35.600
[Amit Varma]: that profession. And there is sort of a deeper meaning that they have to bring to work in

02:05:35.600 --> 02:05:40.360
[Amit Varma]: what they do, you know, almost in contrast, or in addition to playing the game as it were

02:05:40.360 --> 02:05:44.800
[Amit Varma]: the phrase you used earlier. So can you can you elaborate a little bit on this? What sparked

02:05:44.800 --> 02:05:49.160
[Amit Varma]: your interest on this? What is the kind of work you've done? And what are your thoughts

02:05:49.160 --> 02:05:50.160
[Amit Varma]: on the subject?

02:05:50.160 --> 02:05:58.720
[Guest]: Yeah, so the interest got sparked by just observing professionals at work. I worked

02:05:58.720 --> 02:06:07.000
[Guest]: with lawyers, I've gone to doctors, I have dealt with architects, I have worked with

02:06:07.000 --> 02:06:13.560
[Guest]: others who are not professionals, professionals, but work with researchers and civil servants

02:06:13.560 --> 02:06:19.160
[Guest]: and politicians and so on. And basically, it was trying to reflect on experience, you

02:06:19.160 --> 02:06:25.640
[Guest]: know, what, what, who was a good professional and who was not a good professional and trying

02:06:25.640 --> 02:06:30.800
[Guest]: to understand it in a conceptual way, but trying to basically from observation itself.

02:06:30.800 --> 02:06:35.320
[Guest]: And I found help in some philosophers and all of that, but primary focus was on actually

02:06:35.320 --> 02:06:42.480
[Guest]: trying to understand what, what does it mean to be a virtuous person in a work setting

02:06:42.480 --> 02:06:47.720
[Guest]: primarily, that was my kind of thing with work means anything like outside of the home

02:06:47.720 --> 02:06:55.240
[Guest]: sphere in some senses. So, and, and not so much in the social friendship, those domains

02:06:55.240 --> 02:06:59.400
[Guest]: there of course, virtue is very important for that, but my research or thinking on this

02:06:59.400 --> 02:07:03.000
[Guest]: has been primarily about the workspaces.

02:07:03.000 --> 02:07:10.880
[Guest]: So what's going on is that we have two grand kind of types of powers that are playing out

02:07:10.880 --> 02:07:17.320
[Guest]: in this world. One is the state power, you know, which is legitimized by in, in some

02:07:17.320 --> 02:07:24.200
[Guest]: places many countries now legitimized by democratic vote, but still it is a particular kind of

02:07:24.200 --> 02:07:32.080
[Guest]: political power, which is there to command, control, use coercion sometimes, or do some

02:07:32.080 --> 02:07:37.920
[Guest]: nudges or something to get some behavior out of people. It is a, there are different ways

02:07:37.920 --> 02:07:43.360
[Guest]: in which states imagine their role in the society for various reasons, historical reasons,

02:07:43.360 --> 02:07:48.920
[Guest]: but there is some degree of a top-down perspective involved, at least at the apex level.

02:07:48.920 --> 02:07:53.720
[Guest]: In some countries, there is much more decentralization and local liberties are still intact, there

02:07:53.720 --> 02:07:58.960
[Guest]: is local governments and all local, local association life really matters. But in many

02:07:58.960 --> 02:08:04.920
[Guest]: countries, the trend is generally towards more centralization and greater kind of trying

02:08:04.920 --> 02:08:09.480
[Guest]: to find the same principles that apply at the entire country and trying to impose those

02:08:09.480 --> 02:08:11.880
[Guest]: principles in some way or the other.

02:08:11.880 --> 02:08:17.160
[Guest]: And they are all done in the name of certain kind of good, nice, cute, cuddly things like

02:08:17.160 --> 02:08:23.240
[Guest]: rights, certain objectives, which may be utilitarian in nature, trying to maximize good for more

02:08:23.240 --> 02:08:28.200
[Guest]: and more people, maximum good for maximum number of people, happiness for maximum number

02:08:28.200 --> 02:08:29.200
[Guest]: of people.

02:08:29.200 --> 02:08:35.440
[Guest]: Another force that is playing out in this world is the force of markets, which at least

02:08:35.440 --> 02:08:40.800
[Guest]: wherever they work as markets, it is based on voluntary exchange, that you and I enter

02:08:40.800 --> 02:08:45.440
[Guest]: into a contract and there is some kind of an understanding of I will pay you something

02:08:45.440 --> 02:08:50.960
[Guest]: for a service and we will both be happy at the end of the day. But the markets also work

02:08:50.960 --> 02:08:54.920
[Guest]: in a way that is, I mean, there are intermediating structures, there are corporate structures,

02:08:54.920 --> 02:08:58.800
[Guest]: there are competition in market, different corporates are trying to compete to be able

02:08:58.800 --> 02:09:05.400
[Guest]: to get more of the market and those create certain incentives then in which the professionals

02:09:05.400 --> 02:09:07.520
[Guest]: have to operate.

02:09:07.520 --> 02:09:14.720
[Guest]: Now if you look at the global trend, earlier what used to happen is that you saw economies

02:09:14.720 --> 02:09:21.080
[Guest]: of scale in manufacturing. You have a large manufacturing company economy of scale, services

02:09:21.080 --> 02:09:26.960
[Guest]: were not considered to be economies of scale. There is a recent research done in the US

02:09:26.960 --> 02:09:31.960
[Guest]: and also now being replicated elsewhere. We show that even services now use more corporatization

02:09:31.960 --> 02:09:35.640
[Guest]: and more economies of scale are being seen. For various reasons, for example, there are

02:09:35.640 --> 02:09:38.960
[Guest]: some common things that you can provide to all professionals working in a corporate which

02:09:38.960 --> 02:09:43.560
[Guest]: reduces the transaction cost for that. Each professional acting on their own. For example,

02:09:43.560 --> 02:09:48.240
[Guest]: the famous example is dentists. Dentists are getting more corporatized, that now more and

02:09:48.240 --> 02:09:52.800
[Guest]: more dentists are working for larger dentistry practices than they used to earlier. It was

02:09:52.800 --> 02:09:58.920
[Guest]: just always one standalone dentist procuring all the products and using their clinic as

02:09:58.920 --> 02:10:04.240
[Guest]: a provider service. But corporatization is happening to a great extent, at least in large

02:10:04.240 --> 02:10:10.040
[Guest]: part of the economy, professionals operate. So lawyers work in law firms, doctors work

02:10:10.040 --> 02:10:16.280
[Guest]: in highly corporatized hospitals, including dentists, architects, all of those.

02:10:16.280 --> 02:10:22.280
[Guest]: And similarly, many of them work in state and state has its own concerns for working,

02:10:22.280 --> 02:10:28.520
[Guest]: for how they should operate. Now the question comes about, so these processes are playing

02:10:28.520 --> 02:10:32.600
[Guest]: out. The state is trying to do certain things and markets are expanding and corporates are

02:10:32.600 --> 02:10:36.520
[Guest]: growing. Corporatization is happening, there is economy of scale to be had. What is the

02:10:36.520 --> 02:10:42.080
[Guest]: role of professional thinking of the profession by itself? What is the role of a professional's

02:10:42.080 --> 02:10:49.840
[Guest]: own understanding of his or her own responsibility towards their clients, towards their professional,

02:10:49.840 --> 02:10:54.960
[Guest]: towards their professions? It is a question that I basically started by asking that these

02:10:54.960 --> 02:11:01.360
[Guest]: grand processes will play out, but are they just basically to be buffeted by these winds

02:11:01.360 --> 02:11:06.880
[Guest]: and basically land up somewhere or not? Or do they have anything to say about it? And

02:11:06.880 --> 02:11:11.920
[Guest]: is there anything that they can do to shape these things? Because in some ways, the question

02:11:11.920 --> 02:11:16.720
[Guest]: I am asking is upstream some markets or state both. In some ways, it's basically about preferences

02:11:16.720 --> 02:11:20.560
[Guest]: itself. What are the preferences of the professional? And then they will participate in these processes

02:11:20.560 --> 02:11:24.760
[Guest]: and they will probably make some compromises and do whatever is necessary to continue to

02:11:24.760 --> 02:11:29.320
[Guest]: practice their profession. But do they have a sense of what is right, what is the right

02:11:29.320 --> 02:11:33.200
[Guest]: thing to do as a professional? So that was the kind of point of departure.

02:11:33.200 --> 02:11:38.280
[Guest]: So I have been studying and talking to professionals across lawyers and doctors and structural

02:11:38.280 --> 02:11:43.040
[Guest]: engineers and social engineering in India is not a professionalized kind of a practice,

02:11:43.040 --> 02:11:47.680
[Guest]: but in other countries it is. Architects, urban planners and all of those and trying

02:11:47.680 --> 02:11:52.920
[Guest]: to understand what is the setting in which, how do they decide what a good professional

02:11:52.920 --> 02:11:58.560
[Guest]: conduct is? How do they see their ability to practice that conduct in their respective

02:11:58.560 --> 02:12:03.400
[Guest]: setting? What can be done to make it easier for professionals to do better?

02:12:03.400 --> 02:12:08.760
[Guest]: So I was participating in some conference and conversation where this young person,

02:12:08.760 --> 02:12:15.080
[Guest]: this lady spoke about particular profession of doctors where the role is to deliver children.

02:12:15.080 --> 02:12:20.040
[Guest]: And the statistics shows that like in the private hospitals, almost half of the children

02:12:20.040 --> 02:12:24.120
[Guest]: were delivered through an operation which is a C-section operation and the government

02:12:24.120 --> 02:12:28.720
[Guest]: hospital it's a very small percentage, I think like 14-15% or something. It's the same profession

02:12:28.720 --> 02:12:33.520
[Guest]: right and they are responding to different situations, acting very differently as professionals.

02:12:33.520 --> 02:12:37.420
[Guest]: They go through the same training, they are part of the same association, all of that.

02:12:37.420 --> 02:12:41.760
[Guest]: So it was, I was thinking why does this happen? This is the same question I have come across

02:12:41.760 --> 02:12:48.680
[Guest]: in many settings. And what does it take for a professional to navigate the landscape in

02:12:48.680 --> 02:12:52.960
[Guest]: which they are situated and try to do better? And how can this landscape be changed to make

02:12:52.960 --> 02:12:57.920
[Guest]: it easier for them to do better? And there are certainly compulsions, there are constraints,

02:12:57.920 --> 02:13:03.800
[Guest]: there are economic constraints, there are constraints on power. Politicians have to

02:13:03.800 --> 02:13:08.120
[Guest]: respond to certain kind of incentives themselves to deliver certain things which are, which

02:13:08.120 --> 02:13:12.960
[Guest]: have to be delivered with quickly and then there are, that play out, play down through

02:13:12.960 --> 02:13:18.080
[Guest]: the system. So, but you see big differences. If you just look at the same profession in

02:13:18.080 --> 02:13:20.480
[Guest]: different settings, behave differently.

02:13:20.480 --> 02:13:24.640
[Guest]: So then I actually started studying and talking to these people and then, so what I see that

02:13:24.640 --> 02:13:30.640
[Guest]: okay there is one role that is played by education. So what do they, what are they taught when

02:13:30.640 --> 02:13:35.920
[Guest]: they enter into the college to get a professional degree or whatever it may be? Or even if it

02:13:35.920 --> 02:13:40.120
[Guest]: is not a college based thing like a chartered accountancy, but they do get a kind of training

02:13:40.120 --> 02:13:46.160
[Guest]: right and an apprenticeship. So in some senses by working with a chartered accountant, all

02:13:46.160 --> 02:13:52.800
[Guest]: doctors, lawyers, they do at some point in education get apprentice with either they

02:13:52.800 --> 02:13:58.160
[Guest]: do a residency in the hospital doctor or young lawyer, usually starts with basically being

02:13:58.160 --> 02:14:05.080
[Guest]: a rookie for another older lawyer and a lot of their learning happens in that early stage.

02:14:05.080 --> 02:14:09.880
[Guest]: Then they enter into the professional field in a more, slightly more independent way.

02:14:09.880 --> 02:14:13.760
[Guest]: Usually it varies from profession to profession. Sometimes you have to take many years to actually

02:14:13.760 --> 02:14:19.320
[Guest]: then strike it on your own. Otherwise it takes some time and I mean it can be quick also

02:14:19.320 --> 02:14:25.680
[Guest]: and depending on you as a person also, but then the settings do differ. So and that time

02:14:25.680 --> 02:14:29.800
[Guest]: you actually are looking at the market and what's possible and how others are doing and

02:14:29.800 --> 02:14:35.360
[Guest]: what are the standards in which you can operate and in that there are actually many challenges

02:14:35.360 --> 02:14:40.720
[Guest]: in different professions that the standards are so low and so, so much focus on getting

02:14:40.720 --> 02:14:46.920
[Guest]: shortcuts and trying to find the easy least cost path instead of trying to think about

02:14:46.920 --> 02:14:51.200
[Guest]: what would be the right thing to do for the client and all that. And also public goods

02:14:51.200 --> 02:14:55.660
[Guest]: are missing. So one of the things that happens across professions is that if a young professional

02:14:55.660 --> 02:15:00.560
[Guest]: wants to grow as a professional, there's not that much by way of support from the larger

02:15:00.560 --> 02:15:05.120
[Guest]: professional bodies. Professional bodies, not all of them, I will not name any of them

02:15:05.120 --> 02:15:10.800
[Guest]: because it's kind of, it's impolite, but most of them in India are very self-serving bodies.

02:15:10.800 --> 02:15:14.760
[Guest]: They are just there to protect their professionals. They don't hold their professionals to account

02:15:14.760 --> 02:15:19.720
[Guest]: when they behave badly. They don't supply enough public goods to young professionals

02:15:19.720 --> 02:15:24.560
[Guest]: who are coming up. So for example, in some sectors, some areas there's not enough standard

02:15:24.560 --> 02:15:29.640
[Guest]: form contracts, legal advice, different ways in which you can reduce the cost of business

02:15:29.640 --> 02:15:33.600
[Guest]: for the professionals so that they can just focus on the professional practice and then

02:15:33.600 --> 02:15:38.400
[Guest]: transaction costs are related to virtues in some way or the other in this sense.

02:15:38.400 --> 02:15:43.280
[Guest]: So I mean, the method I've used is basically, as I said, observing, reflecting, interviewing

02:15:43.280 --> 02:15:48.680
[Guest]: lots of professionals and doing study groups. So sometimes I've done, I'm not going to details

02:15:48.680 --> 02:15:53.640
[Guest]: because they're all off the record conversations with taking a group of professionals and running

02:15:53.640 --> 02:15:58.920
[Guest]: through them for several weeks about their profession and saying what is it that shapes

02:15:58.920 --> 02:16:03.480
[Guest]: behavior in their profession and how do they, how do we ensure in the language that we spoke

02:16:03.480 --> 02:16:07.600
[Guest]: earlier that more and more professionals pursue goods internal to practice and that becomes

02:16:07.600 --> 02:16:11.400
[Guest]: consistent with goods external to practice, that being a good professional actually pays

02:16:11.400 --> 02:16:16.240
[Guest]: off. I'm not expecting professionals to compromise on everything.

02:16:16.240 --> 02:16:21.240
[Guest]: So the one thing is the market versus virtue thing that can, how do we ensure that markets

02:16:21.240 --> 02:16:26.400
[Guest]: are structured in a manner that virtuous behavior is rewarded more and more. We means, it's

02:16:26.400 --> 02:16:30.640
[Guest]: not for me to design, it's more something that evolves and emerges from interactions

02:16:30.640 --> 02:16:34.740
[Guest]: between the professionals among themselves and professionals with their corporate kind

02:16:34.740 --> 02:16:40.720
[Guest]: of counterparts with whom they work. And the other is on the side of the state, right,

02:16:40.720 --> 02:16:46.520
[Guest]: that how do you as a professional work with the state to do the right thing. So there

02:16:46.520 --> 02:16:47.520
[Guest]: the themes are very different.

02:16:47.520 --> 02:16:52.840
[Guest]: So one thing that I learned from talking to some of the professionals is that in fact

02:16:52.840 --> 02:16:58.600
[Guest]: virtue, the way we think about sometimes in an abstract way is an impediment to improving

02:16:58.600 --> 02:17:03.920
[Guest]: things in the state because you may have a simplistic notion or not simplistic, you may

02:17:03.920 --> 02:17:08.640
[Guest]: have the right notion, perfectly right notion of what good professional ethics are and how

02:17:08.640 --> 02:17:13.080
[Guest]: to implement them in this world. But you work with the state and state is a very messy creature.

02:17:13.080 --> 02:17:18.400
[Guest]: It's a very, it's actually far more informal than we sometimes understand. There are shortcuts

02:17:18.400 --> 02:17:23.480
[Guest]: taken, there are favors to be done, there are compromises to be made, you know, and

02:17:23.480 --> 02:17:28.160
[Guest]: many professionals feel very uncomfortable doing any of that because they feel that it

02:17:28.160 --> 02:17:33.160
[Guest]: would, it compromises the integrity to work with the state. But one thing that I think

02:17:33.160 --> 02:17:38.040
[Guest]: is very important to keep in mind is that when you are moving from one kind of a society

02:17:38.040 --> 02:17:41.800
[Guest]: to another kind of a society, it's a journey. You don't make a leap. You don't go to

02:17:41.800 --> 02:17:46.880
[Guest]: an open access order or a fully well-organized society where complete rule of law, all of

02:17:46.880 --> 02:17:52.920
[Guest]: that in one giant leap. So the way to think about is to make progress. How can we make

02:17:52.920 --> 02:17:57.720
[Guest]: the next step? So more and more professionals should engage with the state while keeping

02:17:57.720 --> 02:18:01.520
[Guest]: as much of their professional ethic intact and how do you make that easy? How do you

02:18:01.520 --> 02:18:04.760
[Guest]: make it easy for professionals to work with the state? Because state is a very important

02:18:04.760 --> 02:18:09.120
[Guest]: entity. If professionals don't join the state or work with the state at least, if

02:18:09.120 --> 02:18:13.000
[Guest]: they feel very suppressed by the state, then it's a big loss for the country. It's

02:18:13.000 --> 02:18:18.040
[Guest]: a big impediment to building genuine state capacity and improving one of the most, probably

02:18:18.040 --> 02:18:21.880
[Guest]: the most important organization in this country, which is the state. Many organizations constituted,

02:18:21.880 --> 02:18:28.120
[Guest]: but there is a state as such, okay. And there are government, there are judiciary, more

02:18:28.120 --> 02:18:31.640
[Guest]: and more professionals should join that and good, excellent professionals should join

02:18:31.640 --> 02:18:36.580
[Guest]: that and they should become judges, they should become civil servants, they should behave

02:18:36.580 --> 02:18:42.080
[Guest]: like professionals while working, they should join government colleges, medical colleges,

02:18:42.080 --> 02:18:46.520
[Guest]: the hospitals, they should be teachers, all of that. So how do you actually work with

02:18:46.520 --> 02:18:52.640
[Guest]: the state while actually being a professional who is virtuous and how do you define virtue

02:18:52.640 --> 02:18:58.000
[Guest]: in that context? So there again, I think the idea of, you know, what is the right dharma

02:18:58.000 --> 02:19:02.880
[Guest]: to follow in a particular context is very important that yes, there are professional

02:19:02.880 --> 02:19:07.200
[Guest]: virtues, but the main thing is that virtues are forged in the practice, right? If you're

02:19:07.200 --> 02:19:10.920
[Guest]: not in the game, if you're not in that field of practice, if you're not actually making

02:19:10.920 --> 02:19:15.400
[Guest]: things, if you're an architect, or if you're not actually serving people as a doctor, if

02:19:15.400 --> 02:19:20.160
[Guest]: you're just in an abstract way in some field, actually, there are NGOs or the academic types

02:19:20.160 --> 02:19:24.480
[Guest]: who just write critiques about their say, they're not in the game, but they are writing

02:19:24.480 --> 02:19:28.200
[Guest]: critiques of the game, so to speak, because they think their abstract notions are far

02:19:28.200 --> 02:19:32.000
[Guest]: superior to the actual practice of that thing, which is always messy, which is easy to critique.

02:19:32.000 --> 02:19:35.480
[Guest]: Critique is always been very easy, right? It's like, it is the easiest thing to do in

02:19:35.480 --> 02:19:39.800
[Guest]: a, especially in a relatively disorganized society like ours, and which is also struggling

02:19:39.800 --> 02:19:45.000
[Guest]: to grow. So how do you actually make that easier, but also more realistic that how do

02:19:45.000 --> 02:19:50.360
[Guest]: you socialize professionals about the realities of the Indian state? And that what will it

02:19:50.360 --> 02:19:55.040
[Guest]: take to work with the state? And what, how do you socialize them into starting working

02:19:55.040 --> 02:19:59.000
[Guest]: with the state and doing more with the state? And I have some friends in different professions

02:19:59.000 --> 02:20:03.240
[Guest]: who have been guiding me, helping me a little bit. I've never written about this at all.

02:20:03.240 --> 02:20:09.120
[Guest]: It's just all, as I said, most change happens one individual at a time. So I work with some

02:20:09.120 --> 02:20:15.200
[Guest]: professionals and individuals and trying to think better about these issues and get something

02:20:15.200 --> 02:20:20.480
[Guest]: started, some, some practices started, some kind of a course is started, which can be

02:20:20.480 --> 02:20:25.800
[Guest]: which can reflect on these issues, some thinking started on, on these issues. But I see both

02:20:25.800 --> 02:20:31.160
[Guest]: these, whether the state's functioning and virtues, how they interact, you know, the,

02:20:31.160 --> 02:20:36.280
[Guest]: the political and governance imperatives and how they can have a very suppressing world

02:20:36.280 --> 02:20:41.160
[Guest]: and bearing on the professionals without actually rewarding the professionals. Markets can reward

02:20:41.160 --> 02:20:45.760
[Guest]: you, but they can also suppress your virtues in certain contexts, especially under certain

02:20:45.760 --> 02:20:50.840
[Guest]: kind of a corporate setting. And because, and so there is an interplay here. So and

02:20:50.840 --> 02:20:54.680
[Guest]: then there's a tripartite thing, there's professional virtues, there's state and then there's market

02:20:54.680 --> 02:20:59.080
[Guest]: because markets and state also interact. And many times the problem in the market is because

02:20:59.080 --> 02:21:04.800
[Guest]: state has shooed some regulation, which actually makes it very difficult to run a good business.

02:21:04.800 --> 02:21:08.480
[Guest]: So those are the interplay that I'm interested in. I'm just taking a few professions and

02:21:08.480 --> 02:21:12.840
[Guest]: studying them. It's been just three years since I started it. So it's not too much work.

02:21:12.840 --> 02:21:17.880
[Guest]: I think this is a 20 year kind of a, I'll understand it maybe in 20 years to have something

02:21:17.880 --> 02:21:21.880
[Guest]: useful to say. But yeah, in the interim, there'll be some things that I'll hopefully write and

02:21:21.880 --> 02:21:26.840
[Guest]: publish. And maybe some things will come out in terms of actual change in behavior and

02:21:26.840 --> 02:21:31.520
[Guest]: all of that. Some new practices will come out. But that's my aspiration that something

02:21:31.520 --> 02:21:37.120
[Guest]: will happen on that. And ultimately, I need co-conspirators, I need virtuous senior doctors

02:21:37.120 --> 02:21:41.880
[Guest]: and lawyers and architects and structural engineers and chartered accountants and company

02:21:41.880 --> 02:21:47.800
[Guest]: secretaries and all those to engage and think about these issues so that we can do better.

02:21:47.800 --> 02:21:52.080
[Guest]: Because professions are sites of virtue. And they are in a way the most important, among

02:21:52.080 --> 02:21:57.000
[Guest]: the most important associations that we have, where not just professional but also democratic

02:21:57.000 --> 02:22:02.960
[Guest]: virtues can thrive. And they are participatory, they are member bodies. In theory, everybody

02:22:02.960 --> 02:22:08.120
[Guest]: is equal because they are all qualified professionals. And you can learn a lot by participating in

02:22:08.120 --> 02:22:13.640
[Guest]: these bodies and helping each other do better. There's a lot of collective common good that

02:22:13.640 --> 02:22:17.920
[Guest]: they can provide to each other. They can reduce transaction costs for specific members, they

02:22:17.920 --> 02:22:22.840
[Guest]: can help them be more virtuous on the market side. They can also try to find ways to work

02:22:22.840 --> 02:22:28.360
[Guest]: with the state and do better in terms of professional input into working with the state bodies.

02:22:28.360 --> 02:22:32.980
[Guest]: If you look at the public infrastructure in India, so much of it is going without proper

02:22:32.980 --> 02:22:38.400
[Guest]: architectural input. It's just ugly buildings, badly designed public spaces, so much, so

02:22:38.400 --> 02:22:44.720
[Guest]: much of it. The cities look so unloved, you know. So I feel that there's a lot to be gained

02:22:44.720 --> 02:22:51.040
[Guest]: by engaging with those professionals. Similarly, whether it's hospitals or schools or build

02:22:51.040 --> 02:22:55.080
[Guest]: bridges and everywhere, professional input is very important. And you need the best of

02:22:55.080 --> 02:22:58.240
[Guest]: the professionals to work with the state.

02:22:58.240 --> 02:23:04.220
[Amit Varma]: So a larger question going a bit deeper into this, but first let me recontextualize, try

02:23:04.220 --> 02:23:09.520
[Amit Varma]: to recontextualize what you said in a context that I understand and that I've sort of spoken

02:23:09.520 --> 02:23:15.080
[Amit Varma]: with past guests about, which is the context of journalism. Now, one question that I've

02:23:15.080 --> 02:23:20.120
[Amit Varma]: often come at journalists on the show with is that, how do you look at journalism in

02:23:20.120 --> 02:23:25.120
[Amit Varma]: the sense that on the one hand, there is an instrumental purpose to journalism, that people

02:23:25.120 --> 02:23:29.960
[Amit Varma]: want information, people want news, you're providing it to them, it is supply and demand.

02:23:29.960 --> 02:23:34.440
[Amit Varma]: Therefore, the bottom line matters, you are after all running an enterprise, you have

02:23:34.440 --> 02:23:38.480
[Amit Varma]: people to employ, mouths to feed, you know, you need to look at ROI for what you do. So

02:23:38.480 --> 02:23:43.040
[Amit Varma]: all those standard business imperatives come into play. And on the other hand, there is

02:23:43.040 --> 02:23:48.300
[Amit Varma]: also a higher notion of journalism, which without quite being able to justify why those

02:23:48.300 --> 02:23:53.040
[Amit Varma]: higher notions exist, I believe they do, at least that's what I have adopted as, you know,

02:23:53.040 --> 02:23:57.800
[Amit Varma]: the way I think about the profession and what I might extend into other things that I do,

02:23:57.800 --> 02:24:03.840
[Amit Varma]: which is that, you know, there is a value to speaking truth to power, there is a value

02:24:03.840 --> 02:24:10.840
[Amit Varma]: in trying to write that first draft to history with as much fidelity to the truth as possible,

02:24:10.840 --> 02:24:18.000
[Amit Varma]: nebulous as the truth is. And so you get it. And in modern times, there are, you know,

02:24:18.000 --> 02:24:22.360
[Amit Varma]: there appears to be a conflict. And this is where the state and the market comes in. Now,

02:24:22.360 --> 02:24:26.200
[Amit Varma]: in an ideal world, the state would protect your rights, and you would just do what you

02:24:26.200 --> 02:24:31.320
[Amit Varma]: have to do, and there would be free speech, so no interference. In an ideal world, the

02:24:31.320 --> 02:24:36.280
[Amit Varma]: market would, you know, reward good behaviour on your part, because you know, you benefit

02:24:36.280 --> 02:24:41.120
[Amit Varma]: in the markets by, you make money in a free market, basically by making someone else better

02:24:41.120 --> 02:24:44.640
[Amit Varma]: off, it is a positive sum game, you provide something that makes them better off, they

02:24:44.640 --> 02:24:49.480
[Amit Varma]: pay you for it, both of you are better off, that's the whole nature of the beast. However,

02:24:49.480 --> 02:24:54.480
[Amit Varma]: what we see in India is issues on both these fronts, in the sense that the state is the

02:24:54.480 --> 02:24:59.120
[Amit Varma]: oppressive predatory state, which I go on about all the time, and it is anything but

02:24:59.120 --> 02:25:04.160
[Amit Varma]: a free environment. And our constitution also does not protect free speech as much as it

02:25:04.160 --> 02:25:09.560
[Amit Varma]: should. So that is one problem at the level of the state. And the state can also use this

02:25:09.560 --> 02:25:14.600
[Amit Varma]: power to clamp down on critics in the sense that, hey, I might own a big newspaper, but

02:25:14.600 --> 02:25:21.380
[Amit Varma]: I'm a business family, I might also have a chemical factory, what am I going to do? So,

02:25:21.380 --> 02:25:26.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, the incentives are messy, everybody who's of a certain size has so much to lose,

02:25:26.960 --> 02:25:31.600
[Amit Varma]: that the incentives are to toe the line. And as far as the market is concerned, one, we

02:25:31.600 --> 02:25:36.200
[Amit Varma]: don't really have a free market free market. But even if we did, you know, the issue that

02:25:36.200 --> 02:25:43.360
[Amit Varma]: would come up there is that, what if people, you know, I might have the highest of values

02:25:43.360 --> 02:25:48.080
[Amit Varma]: ki aisa hona chahiye, but what if the world today is full of narrative battles, and people

02:25:48.080 --> 02:25:53.680
[Amit Varma]: want to engage in those battles, and the the demand from the market is to provide those

02:25:53.680 --> 02:25:58.620
[Amit Varma]: narratives, which they already believe in, or which give them comfort or whatever, and

02:25:58.620 --> 02:26:04.520
[Amit Varma]: not necessarily for a bipartisan pursuit of the truth, then do you play to those forces

02:26:04.520 --> 02:26:09.920
[Amit Varma]: as well. And I would actually not be so negative about it in the sense that I think that one

02:26:09.920 --> 02:26:13.920
[Amit Varma]: of the beautiful things about the market is that it's not just majority wins. And like

02:26:13.920 --> 02:26:19.040
[Amit Varma]: in politics, everybody can express themselves, you know, in that sense, my podcast is not

02:26:19.040 --> 02:26:24.080
[Amit Varma]: a mainstream thing. But it reaches a lot of people who crave depth, who otherwise a market

02:26:24.080 --> 02:26:28.880
[Amit Varma]: does not, you know, otherwise, the mainstream players don't cater to because, you know,

02:26:28.880 --> 02:26:33.640
[Amit Varma]: they want numbers and they are going, you know, a mile wide and an inch deep. And there

02:26:33.640 --> 02:26:38.320
[Amit Varma]: are people who want a lot more depth. So the market has created spaces for all kinds of

02:26:38.320 --> 02:26:43.080
[Amit Varma]: different voices, put the tools of production in our hands, all that is fine. But the but

02:26:43.080 --> 02:26:48.580
[Amit Varma]: the question that this leads me to is that notion of journalism, as high having some

02:26:48.580 --> 02:26:53.880
[Amit Varma]: higher values, where does it come from? Like when you're talking about virtues within professions,

02:26:53.880 --> 02:26:58.080
[Amit Varma]: what you are in a sense implying, when you say that it is upstream of the state and upstream

02:26:58.080 --> 02:27:03.160
[Amit Varma]: of society is you are implying that this is not just something instrumental, right? It

02:27:03.160 --> 02:27:10.480
[Amit Varma]: is not there is each profession has a set of ethics, or maybe that's a question, does

02:27:10.480 --> 02:27:16.480
[Amit Varma]: it have a sense of ethics that exists independent of all these forces, you know, and and to

02:27:16.480 --> 02:27:20.000
[Amit Varma]: turn our attention on medicine, for example, doctors are taught the Hippocratic Oath, for

02:27:20.000 --> 02:27:23.840
[Amit Varma]: example, you know, thou shall do no harm and all of that. And it would appear that there

02:27:23.840 --> 02:27:29.040
[Amit Varma]: is a code of ethics there. But as we have seen, you also have to look at the incentives

02:27:29.040 --> 02:27:33.360
[Amit Varma]: of doctors. And, you know, you could be a doctor who loves to spend 20 minutes with

02:27:33.360 --> 02:27:39.000
[Amit Varma]: each patient, but your incentives are that apply fast and furious heuristics, tell them

02:27:39.000 --> 02:27:43.120
[Amit Varma]: thus test karo for each of which you're getting a commission. And that's how the business

02:27:43.120 --> 02:27:48.400
[Amit Varma]: runs. And you can even rationalize it at a utilitarian level, saying that I'm serving

02:27:48.400 --> 02:27:51.480
[Guest]: many more people and giving less service to many more people.

02:27:51.480 --> 02:27:58.880
[Guest]: That is the main thing about it that it's not good versus evil, right? It's a truly

02:27:58.880 --> 02:28:01.400
[Guest]: tragic situation where different goods have to be balanced against each other.

02:28:01.400 --> 02:28:05.600
[Amit Varma]: So two questions that arise from this and the first of them deals with this directly

02:28:05.600 --> 02:28:13.840
[Amit Varma]: is that have you seen a philosophical justification for these kind of virtues in any profession

02:28:13.840 --> 02:28:19.540
[Amit Varma]: existing independent of the instrumental reason for that profession coming into being an existing

02:28:19.540 --> 02:28:21.760
[Amit Varma]: independent of the state in the markets?

02:28:21.760 --> 02:28:27.920
[Guest]: No, and actually it shouldn't because you are here to serve, right? Like a doctor is

02:28:27.920 --> 02:28:33.840
[Guest]: not someone who is sitting on the top of a mountain and basically being a doctor without

02:28:33.840 --> 02:28:36.840
[Guest]: actually dealing with a patient. And as soon as you deal with a patient, you are actually

02:28:36.840 --> 02:28:37.840
[Amit Varma]: in a social setting.

02:28:37.840 --> 02:28:41.160
[Amit Varma]: The independent ethic could be to serve, but then how do you define that? And where does

02:28:41.160 --> 02:28:42.160
[Amit Varma]: it arise from?

02:28:42.160 --> 02:28:48.240
[Guest]: But when you start serving, then you start dealing with constraints, demands, expectations,

02:28:48.240 --> 02:28:54.440
[Guest]: market forces, state regulation, state's own constraints, political governance constraints.

02:28:54.440 --> 02:29:00.240
[Guest]: And then in that you end up shaping your behavior according to, I mean, what you think is the

02:29:00.240 --> 02:29:03.960
[Guest]: right thing and then what are the, what is the kind of situation that you find yourself

02:29:03.960 --> 02:29:04.960
[Guest]: in.

02:29:04.960 --> 02:29:10.040
[Guest]: So let's talk about journalism. It's not, I don't know whether it can be called a profession,

02:29:10.040 --> 02:29:14.220
[Guest]: I mean, in a philosophical sense, but many journalists think that they are professionals

02:29:14.220 --> 02:29:20.120
[Guest]: and they think about what they do in terms of a profession. But so let's talk about it

02:29:20.120 --> 02:29:25.560
[Guest]: in terms of maybe something akin to a profession where there are certain structured practices

02:29:25.560 --> 02:29:32.280
[Guest]: which are there and finding truth out and reporting it is very important.

02:29:32.280 --> 02:29:37.080
[Guest]: And that's the core of the, I mean, speaking truth to power and all our secondary things,

02:29:37.080 --> 02:29:42.960
[Guest]: those are vanities, you know, truth is what really matters. And finding important truths,

02:29:42.960 --> 02:29:48.560
[Guest]: which are, I think, consequential and having some degree of direction of attention to things

02:29:48.560 --> 02:29:53.600
[Guest]: that really matter is another kind of aspect of a journalistic ethic.

02:29:53.600 --> 02:29:58.520
[Guest]: Having some degree of rigor and some, what you call triangulation of whatever you're

02:29:58.520 --> 02:30:05.960
[Guest]: trying to say is important. Then also stating it in a manner which is non-sensational. It

02:30:05.960 --> 02:30:10.700
[Guest]: should be clear, it should be precise, it should be saying what you know and accepting

02:30:10.700 --> 02:30:17.280
[Guest]: what you don't know. So as a citizen, I have expectations from citizens as well. I have

02:30:17.280 --> 02:30:21.320
[Guest]: expectations from journalists as well that there are some things that I expect from a

02:30:21.320 --> 02:30:26.440
[Guest]: good doctor, some things I expect from a good architect, some things I may expect from a

02:30:26.440 --> 02:30:30.400
[Guest]: good lawyer. I expect certain things from journalists as well.

02:30:30.400 --> 02:30:37.960
[Guest]: Now journalists say that they have a freedom of speech. That's what they want to get. And

02:30:37.960 --> 02:30:44.320
[Guest]: now what is the, so structurally what happens is that whenever you have any right, it each

02:30:44.320 --> 02:30:49.800
[Guest]: right creates some elites. Because people who are good at exercising those rights will

02:30:49.800 --> 02:30:54.440
[Guest]: become elites through those rights. And society confers those rights. I mean you may use the

02:30:54.440 --> 02:30:59.280
[Guest]: language of natural rights and whatever God given, but ultimately society has decided,

02:30:59.280 --> 02:31:04.260
[Guest]: it's a decision that it's taken that those rights have to be conferred on the people.

02:31:04.260 --> 02:31:10.840
[Guest]: And then each right creates some kind of elite. So when you have a right to property, you

02:31:10.840 --> 02:31:15.960
[Guest]: have property, people who either by their sheer ability to run better businesses or

02:31:15.960 --> 02:31:21.760
[Guest]: by their rent seeking behavior are able to get, become rich and they become the property

02:31:21.760 --> 02:31:22.760
[Guest]: elites.

02:31:22.760 --> 02:31:27.320
[Guest]: Similarly, when you freedom of speech, some people are better intellectuals claim, so

02:31:27.320 --> 02:31:33.640
[Guest]: they are better at becoming, at use of speech and they want to influence society. I mean

02:31:33.640 --> 02:31:38.680
[Guest]: perhaps the most important of those are constitutional judges and lawyers, lawyers who say that their

02:31:38.680 --> 02:31:42.560
[Guest]: speech is so powerful that they should transform society in some sense. It's just their views

02:31:42.560 --> 02:31:46.520
[Guest]: right and they think they have the philosophical confidence to say that they should transform

02:31:46.520 --> 02:31:51.400
[Guest]: the society. It takes quite a bit of vanity to say something like that, but they do.

02:31:51.400 --> 02:31:56.520
[Guest]: Journalists are also in that category. They are the elites of the speech right that society

02:31:56.520 --> 02:32:01.760
[Guest]: has confirmed on everybody in some sense, but some are elites in those rights. See most

02:32:01.760 --> 02:32:07.560
[Guest]: of us never, most of us will never use most of the rights in a manner that society would

02:32:07.560 --> 02:32:15.000
[Guest]: want to regulate it, most of us, most of the time. Most of us will sometime use it and

02:32:15.000 --> 02:32:19.320
[Guest]: only some of us use it all the time. Journalists are those who use right to speech, push the

02:32:19.320 --> 02:32:23.440
[Guest]: boundaries all the time because they are in the business of finding things out that are

02:32:23.440 --> 02:32:27.080
[Guest]: not commonly known and reporting those and so on.

02:32:27.080 --> 02:32:31.960
[Guest]: Now why does society confer these rights? Because it thinks it works for them. Everything

02:32:31.960 --> 02:32:34.960
[Guest]: is an instrumentality in that sense. When you think out from a society's point of view

02:32:34.960 --> 02:32:39.480
[Guest]: and why it is conferred those rights, it thinks that it will work for them. So how does a

02:32:39.480 --> 02:32:44.640
[Guest]: property elite which is a big business person or someone say that hey I deserve to be elite.

02:32:44.640 --> 02:32:49.520
[Guest]: So democracies do not like elites right. Everybody is equal and so on. Why they justify is by

02:32:49.520 --> 02:32:55.880
[Guest]: saying that my being rich has helped the society because voluntary exchange in invisible hand

02:32:55.880 --> 02:32:58.520
[Guest]: everybody has been better off and I have been a little better because I have done better

02:32:58.520 --> 02:32:59.840
[Guest]: for you.

02:32:59.840 --> 02:33:05.320
[Guest]: Same thing intellectuals, journalists, everybody also claims that I deserve this disproportionate

02:33:05.320 --> 02:33:11.480
[Guest]: uses of this right because my speech is helping society do better. Intellectuals say that,

02:33:11.480 --> 02:33:16.200
[Guest]: journalists say that. Similarly, other rights you can go to the list. Each right creates

02:33:16.200 --> 02:33:21.880
[Guest]: some kind of elite who are just good, better or more inclined towards using those rights

02:33:21.880 --> 02:33:25.960
[Guest]: in a disproportionate, I mean intensive way.

02:33:25.960 --> 02:33:31.640
[Guest]: Now the tensions come right because you have some right and you are the one small sliver

02:33:31.640 --> 02:33:38.080
[Guest]: of society which uses this rights a lot to speak the truths and so called the truths

02:33:38.080 --> 02:33:42.440
[Guest]: and you say that you should be listened to and you should continue to have that right.

02:33:42.440 --> 02:33:46.480
[Guest]: You say something about a business person. That business person says this is not true.

02:33:46.480 --> 02:33:50.920
[Guest]: Now there are two possibilities. Maybe it is true, maybe it is not true. Maybe it is

02:33:50.920 --> 02:33:56.200
[Guest]: true but you have misstated it. Maybe it is not true and but you are not accepting that

02:33:56.200 --> 02:34:00.680
[Guest]: it is not true and the business person has again a right to fight back against you. I

02:34:00.680 --> 02:34:06.520
[Guest]: mean through legal means or whatever it may be. Defamation and all is there for that.

02:34:06.520 --> 02:34:10.680
[Guest]: You say something about some politician, okay, which may or may not be true and even if it

02:34:10.680 --> 02:34:15.840
[Guest]: is true, the politician does not like it because hey, I mean it basically weakens him in some

02:34:15.840 --> 02:34:20.120
[Guest]: senses because it is maybe something negative. That is why it is being reported and it was

02:34:20.120 --> 02:34:22.480
[Guest]: not anyway in the public domain earlier.

02:34:22.480 --> 02:34:27.160
[Guest]: So at that point all the tensions come and then it is basically a question about this

02:34:27.160 --> 02:34:33.120
[Guest]: profession or this set of people who are exercising these rights versus the people who are trying

02:34:33.120 --> 02:34:36.600
[Guest]: to fight them out, whether it is the property elite or the political elites or the powerful

02:34:36.600 --> 02:34:42.080
[Guest]: and the basically or the administrative elite, the civil servants and all of those who are

02:34:42.080 --> 02:34:48.200
[Guest]: holding the powers so to speak and the journalists pushing back. When that situation comes and

02:34:48.200 --> 02:34:51.320
[Guest]: that is an unavoidable situation. All societies have to deal with it. Even the most developed

02:34:51.320 --> 02:34:56.720
[Guest]: society even today, you have a president who said the media are the enemy of the people

02:34:56.720 --> 02:35:00.900
[Guest]: because he felt aggrieved by the media, so rightly or wrongly but he felt and he is fighting

02:35:00.900 --> 02:35:06.880
[Guest]: the media on a daily basis. He suspended some reporter from coming to his press conferences

02:35:06.880 --> 02:35:10.560
[Guest]: temporarily and then it got reversed in the court or something.

02:35:10.560 --> 02:35:15.940
[Guest]: So there is a constant struggle. The basic point I am trying to make is that if you,

02:35:15.940 --> 02:35:21.240
[Guest]: the first duty of a professional and professionals as a collective in a particular domain is

02:35:21.240 --> 02:35:26.120
[Guest]: to try to do reasonably well as far as their own professional ethic is concerned. In terms

02:35:26.120 --> 02:35:29.760
[Guest]: of within the situation, I am not saying that there is infinite resources and you can do

02:35:29.760 --> 02:35:34.440
[Guest]: whatever, but you do whatever. I just, I mean drop on my head, set four of equality, I as

02:35:34.440 --> 02:35:39.440
[Guest]: a citizen think that as a journalist should at least aspire towards and then what happens

02:35:39.440 --> 02:35:42.160
[Guest]: when a conflict happens is that people should be with you.

02:35:42.160 --> 02:35:46.240
[Guest]: So we should never have an illusion that in democracy there are many sources of, the main

02:35:46.240 --> 02:35:50.560
[Guest]: source of power is the people, are the people. Whether it is a person who is rich or powerful

02:35:50.560 --> 02:35:56.720
[Guest]: in state or journalist getting legitimacy, it has to be earned and it has to be and some

02:35:56.720 --> 02:36:02.320
[Guest]: degree of faith in the democracy and the people is required that if I am doing the right thing,

02:36:02.320 --> 02:36:08.320
[Guest]: maybe sometimes there will be unfair outcomes and I will be very badly hurt. But to at least

02:36:08.320 --> 02:36:12.060
[Guest]: begin with the assumption that if I am doing the right thing, in some way or the other,

02:36:12.060 --> 02:36:16.360
[Guest]: people will say and stand with me and say, hey, you are wrongly implicating this person.

02:36:16.360 --> 02:36:21.960
[Guest]: But for that, it is very important to have collective unit in action within the profession.

02:36:21.960 --> 02:36:27.960
[Guest]: One professional can be destroyed very easily and for the, by the other elites, because

02:36:27.960 --> 02:36:30.800
[Guest]: they have been hurt by it and I am just talking about for journalists right now, but it is

02:36:30.800 --> 02:36:35.320
[Guest]: true of others as well. Because hey, I mean, nobody will pay attention also. What is an

02:36:35.320 --> 02:36:41.080
[Guest]: individual? It is just a, I mean, very easy to forget also. That is the tragedy of human

02:36:41.080 --> 02:36:45.400
[Guest]: behavior. In our minds, we are everything, but in the larger scheme of things, we do

02:36:45.400 --> 02:36:48.800
[Guest]: not mean that much. But when a collective, there is professional

02:36:48.800 --> 02:36:52.800
[Guest]: unity is there and for good reasons, not in the, I mean, self-serving way in which many

02:36:52.800 --> 02:36:56.760
[Guest]: professional bodies in India work. So, we have to be realistic about how professional

02:36:56.760 --> 02:37:00.960
[Guest]: bodies work and when do they actually stand up to bad behavior by their members, when

02:37:00.960 --> 02:37:04.120
[Guest]: do they stand up to defend good behavior by their members, which is under attack from

02:37:04.120 --> 02:37:08.400
[Guest]: others. So, the basic point I am making is that yes, these are situations that arise

02:37:08.400 --> 02:37:12.800
[Guest]: and there are structural good reasons why they arise. Conflict is good in society. When

02:37:12.800 --> 02:37:15.640
[Guest]: it is not a good versus evil thing, journalists get a lot of things wrong.

02:37:15.640 --> 02:37:21.800
[Guest]: I remember how some IAS officers who took decision in good faith, but got badly, I mean,

02:37:21.800 --> 02:37:25.360
[Guest]: implicated in cases later were completely demonized by some of our journalists a few

02:37:25.360 --> 02:37:29.800
[Guest]: years ago under the corruption, I mean, the moment of cacophony around corruption that

02:37:29.800 --> 02:37:35.840
[Guest]: happened in India. And I think many of them went overboard. I mean, whether they should

02:37:35.840 --> 02:37:40.160
[Guest]: have a right to say that or not, it is a different question. It is a legal question one can answer.

02:37:40.160 --> 02:37:44.680
[Guest]: But as a moral question, you know, did you actually exercise the thing before supporting

02:37:44.680 --> 02:37:48.080
[Guest]: somebody's criminalization, putting someone in jail? Literally, there are senior journalists

02:37:48.080 --> 02:37:51.840
[Guest]: who wrote that they should be in jail for not standing up to their political leaders.

02:37:51.840 --> 02:37:55.600
[Guest]: Is that a standard for which someone should go to jail? I mean, that is the kind of language

02:37:55.600 --> 02:38:01.040
[Guest]: that was used against some IAS officers who are in jail right now for basically not having

02:38:01.040 --> 02:38:04.560
[Guest]: taken any money, but they did not stand up to some wrong decision by senior politicians

02:38:04.560 --> 02:38:08.840
[Guest]: who themselves are not in jail, by the way. So, there are many examples of this type.

02:38:08.840 --> 02:38:13.400
[Guest]: And all I am saying is that when the conflicts happen, the most important thing is to appeal

02:38:13.400 --> 02:38:18.320
[Guest]: to the public, you know, in some ways and as a collective stand up for what is good

02:38:18.320 --> 02:38:23.360
[Guest]: and punish what is bad. So, I do not know. I am not an expert on journalism in India.

02:38:23.360 --> 02:38:28.400
[Guest]: One has to think and these are very hard questions. And they require practical judgment, a lot

02:38:28.400 --> 02:38:32.240
[Guest]: of detailed situational awareness of what is the state of journalism in India, what

02:38:32.240 --> 02:38:36.720
[Guest]: are the conditions in this practice. But my big picture is that the question that we should

02:38:36.720 --> 02:38:43.240
[Guest]: ask is, are journalists as a community behaving in a way that a good professional should behave?

02:38:43.240 --> 02:38:48.800
[Guest]: Are they punishing the bad or are they censoring their own bad behavior of the journalists

02:38:48.800 --> 02:38:52.920
[Guest]: at a corporate level, at the level of the professional bodies and all? Are they standing

02:38:52.920 --> 02:38:56.840
[Guest]: up for the good behavior of the journalists? And then the conflicts will happen. Everybody

02:38:56.840 --> 02:39:00.920
[Guest]: has a legitimate right to fight the other person. This abstract invocation of rights

02:39:00.920 --> 02:39:05.600
[Guest]: as something magical, as if it is some kind of fetishized power, which will just suddenly

02:39:05.600 --> 02:39:09.240
[Guest]: have an impact on you while we have abandoned it, is meaningless. It has to be, each right

02:39:09.240 --> 02:39:13.800
[Guest]: has to be sustained through political, I mean, activity, you know, and ultimately it comes

02:39:13.800 --> 02:39:18.680
[Guest]: on to the people. And whether it is journalists or any other professional, it has to earn

02:39:18.680 --> 02:39:25.240
[Guest]: that kind of a legitimacy and hopefully people will have a good sense to side with them and

02:39:25.240 --> 02:39:31.320
[Guest]: support more virtuous journalism than less. And they will also get things wrong sometimes.

02:39:31.320 --> 02:39:36.000
[Guest]: I mean, all of us get things wrong, sometimes injustices happen, but that is the structural

02:39:36.000 --> 02:39:38.360
[Guest]: reality in which this thing has to play out.

02:39:38.360 --> 02:39:44.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think number of points. I mean, firstly, just as an aside, as far as sort of the question

02:39:44.560 --> 02:39:49.200
[Amit Varma]: is concerned of rights producing elites that, you know, you have the right to free speech

02:39:49.200 --> 02:39:53.720
[Amit Varma]: and then, you know, some people use it more than others and equally the right to property,

02:39:53.720 --> 02:39:57.960
[Amit Varma]: some people benefit more than others. But I think they act as incentives for everybody.

02:39:57.960 --> 02:40:02.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, the right to property is important as an incentive for everyone to work hard

02:40:02.920 --> 02:40:06.820
[Amit Varma]: because they can accumulate wealth and they can keep it and that's how you rise in life.

02:40:06.820 --> 02:40:11.160
[Amit Varma]: And it's a positive sum game, it's not a zero sum game. So that's an essential right, which

02:40:11.160 --> 02:40:15.760
[Amit Varma]: actually is no longer a fundamental right. Episode 26 of my show with Shruti Rajgopalan

02:40:15.760 --> 02:40:21.780
[Amit Varma]: deals on that. And also, the right to free speech is essential to democracy. It might

02:40:21.780 --> 02:40:27.360
[Amit Varma]: be the case that, you know, some people exercise it more in an overt way, but that's neither

02:40:27.360 --> 02:40:29.360
[Guest]: here nor there, you know, you kind of...

02:40:29.360 --> 02:40:34.880
[Guest]: So I'm not disagreeing, I'm just stating a particular way in which I see reality. Ultimately,

02:40:34.880 --> 02:40:40.200
[Guest]: you and I can discuss this and agree with it. But society as a whole has to confer it.

02:40:40.200 --> 02:40:43.280
[Guest]: And even if you claim, no, no, it's my natural right, God given right, God is not going to

02:40:43.280 --> 02:40:47.320
[Amit Varma]: come to give it the right. It's politically constructed and sustained.

02:40:47.320 --> 02:40:50.720
[Amit Varma]: I'm not disputing that. But I'm saying that it is something that has to be fought for.

02:40:50.720 --> 02:40:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And even if you look at the US, for example, for all their flaws, they do have the right

02:40:55.000 --> 02:40:59.520
[Amit Varma]: to free speech in as close to a pure form as you can get. And it's worked for them.

02:40:59.520 --> 02:41:00.520
[Guest]: And

02:41:00.520 --> 02:41:03.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it was politically constructed and they have a historical reason why they have

02:41:03.200 --> 02:41:06.680
[Guest]: it. We have a right to privacy, which was sustained over four or five hearings. And

02:41:06.680 --> 02:41:11.240
[Guest]: we I mean, we all celebrated it. But do we really have a right to privacy? Tell me.

02:41:11.240 --> 02:41:14.760
[Amit Varma]: We'll come to that later. But just to finish my thought that, you know, when you speak

02:41:14.760 --> 02:41:19.520
[Amit Varma]: about as a society, we expect truth from journalists. And my thing is, I think there is a danger

02:41:19.520 --> 02:41:25.000
[Amit Varma]: in talking from the point of view of abstract groups like society, like what is society

02:41:25.000 --> 02:41:29.920
[Amit Varma]: even I think some people might want their journalists to be able to pursue the truth.

02:41:29.920 --> 02:41:31.920
[Guest]: Some people want their journalists to pursue, let me finish.

02:41:31.920 --> 02:41:35.520
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I only said as a citizen, I, that's how I framed it.

02:41:35.520 --> 02:41:39.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. But, you know, you you've sort of used that group phrase, you know, what

02:41:39.080 --> 02:41:43.880
[Amit Varma]: society expects, and we should fight for that and all of that. And my sense is that my my

02:41:43.880 --> 02:41:48.200
[Amit Varma]: lament at the start was that I might expect you and I might expect one thing from journalists,

02:41:48.200 --> 02:41:53.880
[Amit Varma]: but, you know, others want sensational news, others want whatever. And that is sort of

02:41:53.880 --> 02:42:00.200
[Amit Varma]: a contestation that is happening. But the deeper question was about is there a philosophical

02:42:00.200 --> 02:42:08.080
[Amit Varma]: way to arrive at the notion that there is a particular sense of ethics that pre exists

02:42:08.080 --> 02:42:12.080
[Amit Varma]: the pressures of society and the pressures of state and land. And like you said, in my

02:42:12.080 --> 02:42:16.280
[Amit Varma]: mind, I don't think there are, but I think we have to construct for ourselves as individuals.

02:42:16.280 --> 02:42:21.280
[Guest]: Yeah, as I said, it's something that is constructed in the practice and experience of practice

02:42:21.280 --> 02:42:27.520
[Guest]: of doing something. And it's the, I find it very harmful, as I said, people who just stay

02:42:27.520 --> 02:42:32.040
[Guest]: away from a practice, but throw stones at that practice and say that, hey, this should

02:42:32.040 --> 02:42:35.800
[Guest]: be the way they should be in the game, at least to know what the constraints are and

02:42:35.800 --> 02:42:39.880
[Guest]: try to understand. I mean, that's why I was not passing a judgment on the way journalists

02:42:39.880 --> 02:42:43.400
[Guest]: in India work. I don't know exactly what's going on there. I'm just putting a frame to

02:42:43.400 --> 02:42:48.520
[Guest]: it. And when I say a society, I'm just, I mean, obviously, it's a collection of individuals,

02:42:48.520 --> 02:42:53.120
[Guest]: and they may have different views and expectations. And if their expectations are to have more

02:42:53.120 --> 02:42:56.600
[Guest]: of yellow journalism and all of that, then there will be consequences for them and their

02:42:56.600 --> 02:43:01.200
[Guest]: society itself. But ultimately, we are a self governing society. And we are, as individuals

02:43:01.200 --> 02:43:07.080
[Guest]: and as a collective, jointly and severally, and individually responsible for our future.

02:43:07.080 --> 02:43:11.240
[Guest]: And that's where there's no shortcut to it. You can't just go to a court and get an injection

02:43:11.240 --> 02:43:16.640
[Guest]: and expect that now you have that right. That kind of thinking, I think, is very anti democratic

02:43:16.640 --> 02:43:20.800
[Guest]: in many ways. And that's what we are seeing that we think there's some shortcut that there's

02:43:20.800 --> 02:43:25.000
[Guest]: some kind of a magical right you can get without convincing a large number of people of this

02:43:25.000 --> 02:43:27.000
[Guest]: this kind of right is instrumentally good for society.

02:43:27.000 --> 02:43:32.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, the messy business of politics is something that we have to keep engaging

02:43:32.240 --> 02:43:36.360
[Amit Varma]: with not in the narrow sense of electoral politics. But I think even what you and I

02:43:36.360 --> 02:43:40.240
[Amit Varma]: are doing by just adding this conversation to the discourse is a form of politics.

02:43:40.240 --> 02:43:44.720
[Guest]: We are all in this game. And in fact, much more than public conversation, private conversations

02:43:44.720 --> 02:43:52.360
[Guest]: are very, I mean, that's where most of the actual meaningful discussions happen. Because

02:43:52.360 --> 02:43:58.160
[Guest]: to be to be able to convince someone, you need to first earn their trust. And that usually

02:43:58.160 --> 02:44:02.000
[Guest]: happens with friends and family and colleagues and all.

02:44:02.000 --> 02:44:06.920
[Amit Varma]: All right. So after floating around in the air of abstract ideas for a while, though,

02:44:06.920 --> 02:44:11.200
[Amit Varma]: with reference to the concrete world, let's kind of get back to your personal story. And

02:44:11.200 --> 02:44:15.640
[Amit Varma]: I know you don't like to talk too much about the personal stuff, because you underplay

02:44:15.640 --> 02:44:20.760
[Amit Varma]: yourself a bit too much. But I'm really curious to know about your early life in the sense

02:44:20.760 --> 02:44:26.080
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, what were your early sort of influences like, like, what were you reading

02:44:26.080 --> 02:44:30.520
[Amit Varma]: when you were a kid? Which language were you reading in? Who are the writers you liked

02:44:30.520 --> 02:44:38.120
[Amit Varma]: and who influenced you? I want to get a sense of how you were formed in a sense.

02:44:38.120 --> 02:44:43.040
[Guest]: I guess the most important thing that comes to mind is that I always escaped to books.

02:44:43.040 --> 02:44:48.920
[Guest]: So, I mean, I was introverted, I still feel that I'm quite generally shy of interaction.

02:44:48.920 --> 02:44:54.000
[Guest]: I used to go out to play with kids every day. That's that was a routine. It was just something

02:44:54.000 --> 02:45:01.000
[Guest]: that was fun also. But whenever I would get time, I was reading something, you know. So,

02:45:01.000 --> 02:45:05.400
[Guest]: the first time I came across like a library was, I think, when I was in sixth standard

02:45:05.400 --> 02:45:10.720
[Guest]: or something. I went with a friend into this, we were living in Gorakhpur and there was

02:45:10.720 --> 02:45:15.560
[Guest]: an office, government office. And we entered and then there was a library inside that office.

02:45:15.560 --> 02:45:21.000
[Guest]: It's an office of basically where engineers in government railway used to work. And you

02:45:21.000 --> 02:45:27.640
[Guest]: go inside and there's a library. And there I found all the children's classics, you know.

02:45:27.640 --> 02:45:34.240
[Guest]: So, till that time, I only had access to mostly, I mean, Hindi literature books, but like children's

02:45:34.240 --> 02:45:38.720
[Guest]: literature. So, at that time, someone like Premchand, you can read as a kid or as a grown

02:45:38.720 --> 02:45:44.440
[Guest]: up, you know, that's the greatness of Premchand. And I was reading Hindi stories and poems

02:45:44.440 --> 02:45:48.600
[Guest]: and all and whatever was available at home, I would read. But that having the access to

02:45:48.600 --> 02:45:54.920
[Guest]: the first library, completely open, so many books can be found at the same place. It was

02:45:54.920 --> 02:45:58.920
[Guest]: a complete sense of wonder because the idea of library wasn't really so much there in

02:45:58.920 --> 02:46:04.680
[Guest]: my mind. And then I started picking up and one by one, I remember I read Adventures of

02:46:04.680 --> 02:46:12.160
[Guest]: Robin Hood, I read Ivanhoe, I read Swiss Family Robinson, Treasure Island, which later also

02:46:12.160 --> 02:46:18.680
[Guest]: I got my school to read Treasure Island as part of my coursework in school. So, and it

02:46:18.680 --> 02:46:25.120
[Guest]: kind of most of my reading when I was in school was basically fiction, more or less. I hardly

02:46:25.120 --> 02:46:30.840
[Guest]: read anything else. And I used to love reading novels as I grew older, I started enjoying

02:46:30.840 --> 02:46:36.560
[Guest]: in my teens, serious, I mean, literature a little bit, and cultivated some taste for

02:46:36.560 --> 02:46:41.840
[Guest]: it automatically. I mean, just snowballing right from one to another, start spending

02:46:41.840 --> 02:46:48.160
[Guest]: a little bit time in bookshops and libraries and pick up. And I actually, the first time

02:46:48.160 --> 02:46:52.800
[Guest]: I actually started reading serious nonfiction was in college only like when I started picking

02:46:52.800 --> 02:46:58.280
[Guest]: up books from different disciplines and reading them. I also got a little bit more money in

02:46:58.280 --> 02:47:02.640
[Guest]: my hand. I was doing internships and making some money and spending all of that on books.

02:47:02.640 --> 02:47:08.240
[Guest]: I remember doing an internship where I got 8000 rupees. I went to this bookshop in Baroda,

02:47:08.240 --> 02:47:12.680
[Guest]: Baroda Book Center, where the owner actually knew the books very well. I said, I've got

02:47:12.680 --> 02:47:16.280
[Guest]: this full money, all of it is to be spent on books, you tell me which ones would be

02:47:16.280 --> 02:47:23.280
[Guest]: good. He gave me a nice set that all discounted, like new books on decent discount, because

02:47:23.280 --> 02:47:27.440
[Guest]: he saw that a student should be given a discount. And he gave me really good books.

02:47:27.440 --> 02:47:28.920
[Guest]: 8000 bucks you spent on books.

02:47:28.920 --> 02:47:35.240
[Guest]: Yes. And that was many, many years ago. So, this was I think about 20 years ago. So, all

02:47:35.240 --> 02:47:40.640
[Guest]: of the money was spent on books he gave me. And he was very gentle and kind enough. It

02:47:40.640 --> 02:47:44.720
[Guest]: took a couple of hours and then he gave me suggestions, which all I accepted. I was in

02:47:44.720 --> 02:47:50.360
[Guest]: no position to. So, it was eclectic, like the book collection was pretty and but it

02:47:50.360 --> 02:47:55.440
[Guest]: basically tripled my book collection one day, because I put all my money into the books.

02:47:55.440 --> 02:48:02.280
[Guest]: Then I so basically, I now read very little literature. I mean, I still read a few books

02:48:02.280 --> 02:48:07.840
[Guest]: every year of literature, but mostly I read, I mean, nonfiction, but at that time, it was

02:48:07.840 --> 02:48:13.000
[Guest]: still substantially reading literature. I really enjoyed that kind of experience of

02:48:13.000 --> 02:48:16.280
[Guest]: literature, you know, I mean, literary critics have a lot of words for it, but I actually

02:48:16.280 --> 02:48:21.160
[Guest]: felt it opened up the whole world for me in some senses, you know, and as a person who

02:48:21.160 --> 02:48:26.400
[Guest]: didn't really enjoy too much social interaction and going out and spending too much time in

02:48:26.400 --> 02:48:30.320
[Guest]: large gatherings and all, it was like I'm sitting in a room and reading a book and this

02:48:30.320 --> 02:48:36.880
[Guest]: is my kind of, you know, I'm participating in something. Initially, it was so I the first

02:48:36.880 --> 02:48:40.840
[Guest]: great book I read was 100 years of solitude. I think I was 19 or something when I read

02:48:40.840 --> 02:48:46.520
[Guest]: it and it just amazing level of, I mean, it was just magical, you know, literally, I mean,

02:48:46.520 --> 02:48:52.000
[Guest]: I think the genre itself is called magical realism. But what you can achieve in a book,

02:48:52.000 --> 02:48:56.600
[Guest]: you know, in terms of the quality of writing the story, the unfettered imagination, put

02:48:56.600 --> 02:49:03.360
[Guest]: everything even something as, you know, bad as I mean, insist and all looks magical in

02:49:03.360 --> 02:49:11.320
[Guest]: that book. It's a stunning achievement. So I started reading a lot of that genre. And

02:49:11.320 --> 02:49:17.640
[Guest]: one key point came when I read my first Saul Bellow, who continues to be my favorite writer

02:49:17.640 --> 02:49:22.920
[Guest]: and his first book I read was this at a very strange time in my life in my early 20s. I

02:49:22.920 --> 02:49:27.960
[Guest]: was going through some difficult time when this book really spoke to me directly, which

02:49:27.960 --> 02:49:36.200
[Guest]: was this basically a thin volume that he read. It was his second book, I think. The dangling

02:49:36.200 --> 02:49:41.760
[Guest]: man I think, yeah, the dangling man it's called. And I was like, wow, I mean, literature can

02:49:41.760 --> 02:49:45.080
[Guest]: be written in this way also, because it is completely different from the magical realism

02:49:45.080 --> 02:49:48.760
[Guest]: and all that I was reading until then and before that children's classic and all of

02:49:48.760 --> 02:49:57.280
[Guest]: that. And it, so I went into this whole, which then I actually branched out to other writers

02:49:57.280 --> 02:50:01.760
[Guest]: of that genre. I was still reading a lot of magical realism, Salman Rushdie, who I mean,

02:50:01.760 --> 02:50:07.120
[Guest]: recently has been in a lot of trouble, great writer. And then I mean, basically branched

02:50:07.120 --> 02:50:14.520
[Guest]: out into different types of literature. So, you know, Philip Roth, I like Isaac Singer,

02:50:14.520 --> 02:50:19.880
[Guest]: Malamud, all of those. And I mean, it was just a part of my, so in a day one or two

02:50:19.880 --> 02:50:27.560
[Guest]: hours you spend reading a nice novel and it's just a very nice part of the day, generally.

02:50:27.560 --> 02:50:32.080
[Guest]: And it's whatever may have happened in the day, that's the couple of hours nobody can

02:50:32.080 --> 02:50:38.680
[Guest]: take away from you. And then I started actually reading more of non-fictions books and I didn't

02:50:38.680 --> 02:50:44.440
[Guest]: have any sense of, so I was, my education was in computer science and I did my MBA later.

02:50:44.440 --> 02:50:49.600
[Guest]: So I didn't have any, I mean, I was studying other things and formally, but because I had

02:50:49.600 --> 02:50:54.520
[Guest]: this kind of a routine of reading regularly, but it was more like chance, you know, what

02:50:54.520 --> 02:51:01.160
[Guest]: I read. If you think back, there was no community of readers with me. There were some elders,

02:51:01.160 --> 02:51:05.600
[Guest]: my father's friends who helped me pick a few books here and there, who were kind enough,

02:51:05.600 --> 02:51:10.280
[Guest]: who had gone through experiences in their life, who had seen some bit of the world.

02:51:10.280 --> 02:51:14.040
[Guest]: So they gave me some hints about what to read and all, but still it was mostly chance what

02:51:14.040 --> 02:51:20.600
[Guest]: I read. Like for example, my first philosophy book I read was actually Aristotle. I literally,

02:51:20.600 --> 02:51:24.520
[Guest]: and Plato. So I actually read the dialogues directly. I didn't know that there were commentaries

02:51:24.520 --> 02:51:29.320
[Guest]: to be read before all of that. I straight away went to the source and started reading

02:51:29.320 --> 02:51:35.520
[Guest]: Plato. I remember specifically Plato's Gorgias was my first serious philosophy book. It's

02:51:35.520 --> 02:51:41.560
[Guest]: a short dialogue, but a very, I mean, it raises permanent questions. So, and I kind of snowballed

02:51:41.560 --> 02:51:46.120
[Guest]: from there and went, first I read the ancient, I had no clue about the modern, but then immediately

02:51:46.120 --> 02:51:50.640
[Guest]: soon I got into some of this modern existential philosophy and all of that and started reading

02:51:50.640 --> 02:51:56.840
[Guest]: that. Our home always had Mahabharata, Ramayana and all those. So those I read when I was

02:51:56.840 --> 02:52:01.640
[Guest]: young. We also used to have these Amar Chitra Kathas, you know, which is, and one of my

02:52:01.640 --> 02:52:08.000
[Guest]: neighbors had these bound volumes, which each volume had five of these comics. And you just

02:52:08.000 --> 02:52:13.400
[Guest]: go through them and it's amazing, each one of the standalone story. And so I was seeped

02:52:13.400 --> 02:52:19.660
[Guest]: in that throughout. But this literature, which is modern and also the, I mean, nonfiction

02:52:19.660 --> 02:52:24.560
[Guest]: writing and philosophy, I read a little bit of psychology, I read a little bit of sociology,

02:52:24.560 --> 02:52:30.280
[Guest]: I read a little bit of economics at that time. It was just, I mean, why was I doing it? I

02:52:30.280 --> 02:52:36.360
[Guest]: couldn't really put a, more like a routine, you know, that almost like that character

02:52:36.360 --> 02:52:42.640
[Guest]: of our autodidact from nausea, who just goes from one, but a little better than that, because

02:52:42.640 --> 02:52:46.520
[Guest]: you're trying to understand some things and you are actually, you have some reasons for

02:52:46.520 --> 02:52:51.480
[Guest]: understanding them. But still, there was a kind of a routine. And then because you read,

02:52:51.480 --> 02:52:55.080
[Guest]: you have more questions, right? And you want to read more. And you want to think more about

02:52:55.080 --> 02:53:00.720
[Guest]: those questions. And then you branch out. It was just, I mean, kind of a serendipity

02:53:00.720 --> 02:53:05.920
[Guest]: that I ended up chancing about some of these great books. And then I developed a taste

02:53:05.920 --> 02:53:10.420
[Guest]: for great books. And what I have a category of great books, I have never defined it formally,

02:53:10.420 --> 02:53:15.880
[Guest]: but I know what a great book is when I see one. So we spent a few months ago, right?

02:53:15.880 --> 02:53:21.000
[Guest]: Looking at 6000 books in a day, you and I. And when I look at a book, I have a sense

02:53:21.000 --> 02:53:27.520
[Guest]: of where it belongs, or how much to read and how much importance to give to it. And that

02:53:27.520 --> 02:53:31.480
[Guest]: cultivation of that habit in the early 20s, I think was a very important, I mean, point

02:53:31.480 --> 02:53:35.400
[Guest]: in my life. And it's been a part of my life. I've really just because we come very late

02:53:35.400 --> 02:53:40.160
[Guest]: in the history, there's so much has happened before us. I have to give dues to those who

02:53:40.160 --> 02:53:44.120
[Guest]: have come before us. And there's really, I mean, the questions that we are wrestling

02:53:44.120 --> 02:53:49.280
[Guest]: with, others have also wrestled with. And I think reading really helps in many ways

02:53:49.280 --> 02:53:54.600
[Guest]: to, you will not get answers by reading, but you will certainly get better at asking the

02:53:54.600 --> 02:53:59.280
[Guest]: right questions. And that's what I think, especially if you read like fundamental works

02:53:59.280 --> 02:54:04.880
[Guest]: on philosophy, psychoanalysis, social systems, sociology, even some of the great works of

02:54:04.880 --> 02:54:11.120
[Guest]: anthropology. So you get politics, of course, political theory. So, and it's a law, it's

02:54:11.120 --> 02:54:16.480
[Guest]: a vast word out there, right. And more recently, like just a few years ago, or five, six years

02:54:16.480 --> 02:54:24.200
[Guest]: ago, I got back to our own kind of reading our own scriptures and trying to see, trying

02:54:24.200 --> 02:54:30.160
[Guest]: to put them in conversation with other traditions and saying, what do we have? Our main concerns

02:54:30.160 --> 02:54:36.200
[Guest]: have always been consciousness. Our main concerns have always been the human consciousness and

02:54:36.200 --> 02:54:42.480
[Guest]: its kind of liberation. And there, I think, our own traditions have a lot to offer. And

02:54:42.480 --> 02:54:47.080
[Guest]: because those questions are now more urgent for me as I'm growing older. So I've gone

02:54:47.080 --> 02:54:51.760
[Guest]: back to more of those and I read, still read the Western philosophy and all, but I read

02:54:51.760 --> 02:54:57.480
[Guest]: more of the ancients there, again, going back then the moderns. And I mean, those that journey

02:54:57.480 --> 02:55:03.040
[Guest]: continues. But yes, this habit of reading regularly, and trying to find great books,

02:55:03.040 --> 02:55:06.800
[Guest]: and trying to have is a background, which is just there every day of my life for the

02:55:06.800 --> 02:55:12.280
[Guest]: last 25 years or so, pretty much. And it's just there. I mean, if there are good days

02:55:12.280 --> 02:55:16.520
[Guest]: and bad days, there are times I'm traveling and all, but I still find at least two hours

02:55:16.520 --> 02:55:18.960
[Amit Varma]: to read every day.

02:55:18.960 --> 02:55:23.440
[Amit Varma]: And I should tell my listeners that when you speak about going through 6000 books, my dad

02:55:23.440 --> 02:55:29.080
[Amit Varma]: had died last year. So in December, I had to go to the house which we were selling off

02:55:29.080 --> 02:55:34.640
[Amit Varma]: and decide what to do with his books. And he had more than 6000 books, 6000-7000 books.

02:55:34.640 --> 02:55:40.120
[Amit Varma]: And I had figured out a community library in Delhi to donate them to. But I thought,

02:55:40.120 --> 02:55:45.000
[Amit Varma]: let's, let me go with three of my friends, Suyash being one of them, and ask them to

02:55:45.000 --> 02:55:49.440
[Amit Varma]: pick out whatever they wanted. And I would pick out whatever I wanted. And then we'd

02:55:49.440 --> 02:55:54.080
[Amit Varma]: give the rest of it away. And as kind of heartbreaking for me in the sense all his collections of

02:55:54.080 --> 02:55:59.960
[Amit Varma]: modern library books, and everyone's classics and all of that and, and, you know, me making

02:55:59.960 --> 02:56:05.080
[Amit Varma]: the choice to kind of give it away and not keep it because I just want to, you know,

02:56:05.080 --> 02:56:08.680
[Amit Varma]: the only physical books I took from there was stuff that I wouldn't actually find anywhere

02:56:08.680 --> 02:56:12.760
[Amit Varma]: otherwise which are out of print or something. I can't even, you know, read it on a Kindle

02:56:12.760 --> 02:56:17.220
[Amit Varma]: or something. So that was kind of I mean, I mean, there was a life of the mind happening

02:56:17.220 --> 02:56:26.000
[Amit Varma]: there as well. Bunch of questions. First of those is that, how did you begin to form frames

02:56:26.000 --> 02:56:30.520
[Amit Varma]: through which you could look at the world and explain the world? Because in my case,

02:56:30.520 --> 02:56:35.280
[Amit Varma]: I read voraciously when it came to fiction, again came to nonfiction a bit more slowly

02:56:35.280 --> 02:56:40.160
[Amit Varma]: and a bit later. But you know, today everyone today young people are so full of certainties

02:56:40.160 --> 02:56:44.840
[Amit Varma]: and the internet is there and there are ideological tribes that are so appealing to join and all

02:56:44.840 --> 02:56:49.960
[Amit Varma]: of that. But in those pre internet days in the 80s, in the early 90s, you know, it took

02:56:49.960 --> 02:56:54.800
[Amit Varma]: a long time for me to be formed. I think I arrived broadly to where I am in terms of

02:56:54.800 --> 02:57:00.600
[Amit Varma]: values and beliefs and all well into my adulthood, really well into my mid 20s, where I could

02:57:00.600 --> 02:57:04.080
[Amit Varma]: even look at the country and say, Oh, these are the things that have gone wrong. This

02:57:04.080 --> 02:57:07.600
[Amit Varma]: is what is wrong with our economics. This is wrong. What is wrong with our politics?

02:57:07.600 --> 02:57:11.480
[Amit Varma]: I suspect if when I was 22, if you asked me what is left, what is right, I would I wouldn't

02:57:11.480 --> 02:57:17.000
[Amit Varma]: know. Right? So tell me a little bit about how, what are the different frames that you

02:57:17.000 --> 02:57:22.200
[Amit Varma]: began to adapt to look at the world and to, you know, begin to understand it? What was

02:57:22.200 --> 02:57:29.280
[Amit Varma]: that process like? I mean, we are always constantly evolving, obviously. But in in the major ways,

02:57:29.280 --> 02:57:33.440
[Amit Varma]: what are the sort of frames that were useful to you? Who were the writers who influenced

02:57:33.440 --> 02:57:38.560
[Amit Varma]: you? Were there any phases where you felt that scales have fallen off your eyes that

02:57:38.560 --> 02:57:42.360
[Amit Varma]: you see something with a clarity with which you hadn't seen it before, whether it is

02:57:42.360 --> 02:57:45.600
[Amit Varma]: in the personal domain or the economic domain or the social domain?

02:57:45.600 --> 02:57:51.080
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a, I wish you had sent me this question a few days in advance and I had thought

02:57:51.080 --> 02:57:56.400
[Guest]: more deeply about it. But I mean, just reflecting on something you said, is that there are many

02:57:56.400 --> 02:58:00.840
[Guest]: disadvantages of being socially shy. But one of the advantages that you don't feel the

02:58:00.840 --> 02:58:06.120
[Guest]: need to belong to a tribe and signal anything to anyone to, to feel that you're part of

02:58:06.120 --> 02:58:11.240
[Guest]: a particular tribe and you're not going out on, I mean, whether it's in physical setting

02:58:11.240 --> 02:58:18.000
[Guest]: or a virtual setting to, to signal things to feel complete person, you feel pretty,

02:58:18.000 --> 02:58:22.800
[Guest]: I mean, comfortable being a little away from any tribe and doing your own thing to the

02:58:22.800 --> 02:58:27.520
[Guest]: extent you're doing those things. And I think that because I've always had that, so I've

02:58:27.520 --> 02:58:32.680
[Guest]: never really needed to belong to any tribe. So I never had to, I mean, it's a good thing

02:58:32.680 --> 02:58:36.040
[Guest]: or a bad thing. Sometimes it's a good thing that you belong to a tribe and you join and

02:58:36.040 --> 02:58:40.040
[Guest]: you take their views. And then hopefully, if you are independent minded enough, then

02:58:40.040 --> 02:58:44.680
[Guest]: you outgrow those, you know, there are many people who get mugged by realities and different

02:58:44.680 --> 02:58:48.880
[Guest]: types of transformations happen. So it's a good thing, but can also be a bad thing because

02:58:48.880 --> 02:58:53.760
[Guest]: it can end, stop thinking because you get comfortable. So I never had that. So I mean,

02:58:53.760 --> 02:58:59.280
[Guest]: one had to find one own way. And so there are two types of beliefs. One is that where

02:58:59.280 --> 02:59:04.120
[Guest]: you actually something very serious for you to act upon, you know, there you have to take

02:59:04.120 --> 02:59:09.520
[Guest]: it very, very, you know, it excites a lot of due diligence because you're acting upon

02:59:09.520 --> 02:59:15.720
[Guest]: something right. But many of the, I mean, so our act, word of action, because we're

02:59:15.720 --> 02:59:19.200
[Guest]: not in, we're not prime ministers and we're not doing those kind of things is a limited

02:59:19.200 --> 02:59:22.000
[Guest]: sphere right. For that you need to have a few things, you have a little bit of excellence

02:59:22.000 --> 02:59:24.640
[Guest]: in some things and that you need to be good at.

02:59:24.640 --> 02:59:29.120
[Guest]: The other types of beliefs are held in a different way, right. We don't act upon them. We just

02:59:29.120 --> 02:59:36.360
[Guest]: we hold them, we revise them. It's just trying to understand, make sense of the word, you

02:59:36.360 --> 02:59:42.160
[Guest]: know, because the old mythological understandings have broken down. The word is not so self-contained

02:59:42.160 --> 02:59:47.720
[Guest]: in our, in a particular cosmology and we need to now remake the meanings in many ways. So

02:59:47.720 --> 02:59:52.000
[Guest]: we need to understand to some extent or we just say it doesn't matter. It's fine. I'm

02:59:52.000 --> 02:59:57.080
[Guest]: just going to do what, take what comes to me and move on. But if you have a longing

02:59:57.080 --> 03:00:02.840
[Guest]: to understand then you need to keep engaging with the word and trying to have some kind

03:00:02.840 --> 03:00:08.080
[Guest]: of working hypothesis about, you know, what's going on, you know.

03:00:08.080 --> 03:00:14.400
[Guest]: And there I think it's a, I don't know, it's just my memories doesn't work in this way.

03:00:14.400 --> 03:00:18.640
[Guest]: How much of it is reading, how much is observation, how much is reflection, how much was it influence

03:00:18.640 --> 03:00:24.620
[Guest]: of others, how much was it reflection, I mean, just habit, you know, it's very hard to say.

03:00:24.620 --> 03:00:29.160
[Guest]: But I think it was a mix of these things. So one thing that you learn from the ancients

03:00:29.160 --> 03:00:33.160
[Guest]: in any tradition is to look at things directly and observe them and comment on them and analyze

03:00:33.160 --> 03:00:37.640
[Guest]: them directly. Some of the moderns also do that, like Tocqueville does that very well

03:00:37.640 --> 03:00:46.480
[Guest]: on democracy. Don't get too impressed by frames and ideologies and clever turn of phrase,

03:00:46.480 --> 03:00:50.320
[Guest]: you know. You're a human being, you're talking about human life and human society, you can

03:00:50.320 --> 03:00:55.220
[Guest]: look at it directly and observe and by the power of your observation and careful thinking

03:00:55.220 --> 03:01:00.760
[Guest]: you can make sense of some of these things. Books, other people's views are useful and

03:01:00.760 --> 03:01:06.720
[Guest]: interesting and important to kind of reflect what you are seeing and sometimes even you

03:01:06.720 --> 03:01:11.880
[Guest]: can adapt some of those. But you need to have your own thinking, there is no substitute

03:01:11.880 --> 03:01:15.880
[Guest]: for that. And I think that one of the things that has always helped me is an intuition

03:01:15.880 --> 03:01:21.720
[Guest]: that I, when I look at something, I have an intuitive sense of what's going on. And then

03:01:21.720 --> 03:01:27.120
[Guest]: I keep revising it over a long period of time. Because whatever I'm studying, I start with

03:01:27.120 --> 03:01:32.280
[Guest]: something with like a, so I'm a rationalist, not empiricist. So I have a kind of a rational

03:01:32.280 --> 03:01:38.720
[Guest]: view of where I'm coming from, you know, and what's going on. And then I look at data,

03:01:38.720 --> 03:01:44.440
[Guest]: look at trying to figure out what's going on. So that's the method that I apply. And

03:01:44.440 --> 03:01:48.440
[Guest]: it sometimes works, sometimes doesn't work, and it keeps evolving, right? It's not a,

03:01:48.440 --> 03:01:53.160
[Guest]: there's never a permanent thing, because descriptions are not reality. Map is not the directory,

03:01:53.160 --> 03:01:58.680
[Guest]: you know, and you're making man remapping the map. But in what I'm working on, I try

03:01:58.680 --> 03:02:03.840
[Guest]: to be as careful as possible so that I get it right and have some, for the rest, it's

03:02:03.840 --> 03:02:09.640
[Guest]: more like a hobby and habit and hopefully someday in some work becomes useful. But otherwise,

03:02:09.640 --> 03:02:16.240
[Guest]: it's just a kind of a need to understand things and have a view on things like human consciousness,

03:02:16.240 --> 03:02:23.500
[Guest]: social processes, workings of democracy, all those things which I don't directly work upon.

03:02:23.500 --> 03:02:27.000
[Guest]: But it's something that you need to have a view on, right? Like you need to have a sense

03:02:27.000 --> 03:02:32.640
[Guest]: of what's going on here, you know, because we are part of that reality. And you can have

03:02:32.640 --> 03:02:38.960
[Guest]: a nuanced and reasonably complex understanding of something or you can have a very simple

03:02:38.960 --> 03:02:44.040
[Guest]: and simplistic understanding also sometimes. And one cannot understand everything, as Saul

03:02:44.040 --> 03:02:49.720
[Guest]: Bellows says, there's simply too much to think about, you know. And, but there are some areas,

03:02:49.720 --> 03:02:55.840
[Guest]: some issues on which I do try to, I have tried long standing themes to understand, for example,

03:02:55.840 --> 03:03:00.960
[Guest]: how literature works on our consciousness, the question of moral philosophy. We've already

03:03:00.960 --> 03:03:07.240
[Guest]: discussed some of that here. Working of democracy in societies, we've touched upon it a little

03:03:07.240 --> 03:03:12.520
[Guest]: bit. And of course, our professional life, working on political economy and all. So we're,

03:03:12.520 --> 03:03:18.360
[Guest]: and I mean, one always lives and learns. I have actually abandoned more of my views than

03:03:18.360 --> 03:03:24.600
[Guest]: I have now. I have been completely wrong on many, many things. In fact, in my even professional

03:03:24.600 --> 03:03:28.080
[Guest]: work, there are so many issues on which my views are completely different from what they

03:03:28.080 --> 03:03:32.040
[Guest]: were eight years ago, seven years ago. And that's a kind of a humbling experience, because

03:03:32.040 --> 03:03:37.680
[Guest]: you know, you're so sure, I haven't figured it out. But then you think about it, or you

03:03:37.680 --> 03:03:43.560
[Guest]: see new data, and you read something, or you go through an experience, and you say, oh,

03:03:43.560 --> 03:03:48.560
[Guest]: I was completely wrong about this. I think that is something which, in fact, I've become

03:03:48.560 --> 03:03:54.120
[Guest]: more open now than I was 15 years ago, or even 10 years ago, about how much I know,

03:03:54.120 --> 03:03:58.880
[Guest]: and how much I know. And one of the things that one actually doesn't know much, you know,

03:03:58.880 --> 03:04:04.000
[Guest]: that is the most fundamental humbling realization that really one doesn't really know much.

03:04:04.000 --> 03:04:09.160
[Guest]: It's really difficult to understand even your own consciousness. Forget about social, political

03:04:09.160 --> 03:04:13.560
[Guest]: systems, the extreme complexity, and we should be humble and modest. That's why I mean, in

03:04:13.560 --> 03:04:20.480
[Guest]: my work, I generally suggest light touch approaches, less coercion, less political economy work

03:04:20.480 --> 03:04:24.760
[Guest]: also, because and that's why I was so upset with decision like demonetization or something

03:04:24.760 --> 03:04:29.520
[Guest]: will be more modest about how much you know about the word and don't do something so drastic

03:04:29.520 --> 03:04:34.760
[Guest]: and so path breaking that you because you think you know, so I and that that is something

03:04:34.760 --> 03:04:39.520
[Guest]: actually, it's more as I said, more recent realization that these frames are very, very

03:04:39.520 --> 03:04:44.880
[Guest]: fragile. And when it comes to them, and when one revises them, and when one gets upset,

03:04:44.880 --> 03:04:50.120
[Guest]: and then one has to move on and try to do better in the future, you know.

03:04:50.120 --> 03:04:57.080
[Amit Varma]: How much of a difference do you think it made that you came from a sort of a different background

03:04:57.080 --> 03:05:02.240
[Amit Varma]: and a different mental space to your profession than many others who are in the profession?

03:05:02.240 --> 03:05:06.280
[Amit Varma]: Like one way in which it is different is of course, that you've gone up reading Hindi

03:05:06.280 --> 03:05:10.000
[Amit Varma]: speaking Hindi, you've come from a different background where you've seen a different view

03:05:10.000 --> 03:05:14.200
[Amit Varma]: of the world. I remember, you know, both Akshay Mukul and Rahul Varma, if I remember correctly,

03:05:14.200 --> 03:05:18.360
[Amit Varma]: in the first episodes with me spoke about how they grew up reading Hindi newspapers,

03:05:18.360 --> 03:05:20.600
[Amit Varma]: and therefore they looked at the world very differently from what

03:05:20.600 --> 03:05:24.920
[Guest]: Yeah, I also mean, we had Dari Jagran and Amrushala coming at us.

03:05:24.920 --> 03:05:29.520
[Amit Varma]: So that's, that's one way in which the background is different. And another way in which the

03:05:29.520 --> 03:05:34.440
[Amit Varma]: mental makeup may be different is that you said you read a lot of fiction. And interestingly,

03:05:34.440 --> 03:05:39.040
[Amit Varma]: English speaking elites often don't read so much, especially in these kind of policy spaces

03:05:39.040 --> 03:05:43.400
[Amit Varma]: and all that. So that rich imaginative interior life that reading a lot of literature and

03:05:43.400 --> 03:05:49.720
[Amit Varma]: fiction gives you is often not there and and you can sometimes be hobbled by it. So do

03:05:49.720 --> 03:05:55.000
[Amit Varma]: you think that this made a difference to how you view the world where you would come at

03:05:55.000 --> 03:05:59.800
[Amit Varma]: things from a different place, you would see things that others sort of may not see?

03:05:59.800 --> 03:06:04.120
[Guest]: Yeah, I think it's different, but I don't know whether it's better, whether it's, it's

03:06:04.120 --> 03:06:10.560
[Guest]: just a path that I happen to take. Literature was available, I read literature. And I just

03:06:10.560 --> 03:06:16.760
[Guest]: liked it. And I really enjoyed it in terms of what it was doing to me into my inner life,

03:06:16.760 --> 03:06:22.960
[Guest]: you know, and it put me in touch with I mean, my own kind of, you know, like you go through

03:06:22.960 --> 03:06:28.200
[Guest]: a, it's, it sounds like a cliche, but you go through some suffering and you read Gutter's

03:06:28.200 --> 03:06:33.200
[Guest]: Sorrow of Young Worth. Actually, it may sound like a cliche, but really it works. You know,

03:06:33.200 --> 03:06:38.600
[Guest]: it's a comforting thing to learn about what do they say, afflict the comforted and comfort

03:06:38.600 --> 03:06:43.320
[Guest]: the afflicted, you know, that kind of a thing. But even I mean, one is not always comforted

03:06:43.320 --> 03:06:48.600
[Guest]: or afflicted. Usually it's somewhere in the middle. And even at that time, it's just something

03:06:48.600 --> 03:06:53.120
[Guest]: that takes you in a different territory as far as a human possibility of thought and

03:06:53.120 --> 03:06:58.040
[Guest]: understanding a concern, right? It's a very empathetic exercise, writing literature, it

03:06:58.040 --> 03:07:03.000
[Guest]: comes from a place, which is not quite available to us, you and me, when we talk about or talk

03:07:03.000 --> 03:07:08.760
[Guest]: to each other. Proust has this kind of, you know, he wrote this essay against leading

03:07:08.760 --> 03:07:13.720
[Guest]: critic, literary critic of his time, about where literature comes from, you know, and

03:07:13.720 --> 03:07:18.200
[Guest]: it's not the kind of self that you and I have direct access to. And it just opens up so

03:07:18.200 --> 03:07:24.040
[Guest]: much possibility and literature, great writers know that it's more like a gift that they

03:07:24.040 --> 03:07:28.240
[Guest]: perfect the form, obviously, they perfect the language and all of that. They work very hard

03:07:28.240 --> 03:07:33.680
[Guest]: on it. But the source of imagination is in the subconscious. And it's kind of comes from

03:07:33.680 --> 03:07:38.080
[Guest]: a place which is not directly accessible to them. It just comes to them, you know, like,

03:07:38.080 --> 03:07:42.920
[Guest]: when you write like Proust, certainly, it sounds like it comes from a different kind

03:07:42.920 --> 03:07:47.080
[Guest]: of place. And it's magic, right? It's magical. It's like some of the religious scriptures

03:07:47.080 --> 03:07:53.000
[Guest]: you read, and they immediately hit you. And, and it just, it has that magical feeling is

03:07:53.000 --> 03:07:59.880
[Guest]: yeah, wow. I mean, it speaks to me as if it's my personal conversation with someone that's

03:07:59.880 --> 03:08:04.280
[Guest]: happening and great philosophers also do that. Like that's the greatness of the dramatic

03:08:04.280 --> 03:08:09.880
[Guest]: way in which Plato writes, right? That it's drama. And of course, you can make the mistake

03:08:09.880 --> 03:08:14.360
[Guest]: of associating with one side or the other without, I mean, understanding that you should

03:08:14.360 --> 03:08:20.280
[Guest]: try to look at both all sides. But, but it just immediately hits you. It's not going

03:08:20.280 --> 03:08:27.280
[Guest]: into a extreme level of qualifications. And, I mean, explaining each term in so much detail

03:08:27.280 --> 03:08:30.680
[Guest]: that it becomes meaningless to read something like that, like some of the, I've tried to

03:08:30.680 --> 03:08:35.520
[Guest]: wrestle with those also, but much more of a direct thing, which immediately hits you.

03:08:35.520 --> 03:08:39.640
[Guest]: And then you have to critically think about what it is doing to you also. And, you know,

03:08:39.640 --> 03:08:48.640
[Guest]: and yeah, so yeah, and I think it is a interesting path that to take to read broadly, widely

03:08:48.640 --> 03:08:56.600
[Guest]: if you're so inclined and read great literature and great philosophers and great thinkers

03:08:56.600 --> 03:09:02.600
[Guest]: in psychology and society and religious scriptures, I think are very, very powerful. I mean, I

03:09:02.600 --> 03:09:09.160
[Guest]: wish more people read them regularly across traditions. You don't have to be narrow-minded

03:09:09.160 --> 03:09:12.760
[Guest]: about it. There's wisdom to be had wherever there is.

03:09:12.760 --> 03:09:18.240
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit more about this because many people who will read your Plato and Aristotle

03:09:18.240 --> 03:09:24.200
[Amit Varma]: and so on and will read sort of Western philosophy and will read these great, great novels will

03:09:24.200 --> 03:09:28.080
[Amit Varma]: also be of a rationalist bent of mind where they will say that, you know, we don't want

03:09:28.080 --> 03:09:31.960
[Amit Varma]: to engage with religious scriptures and at best that they might have an anthropological

03:09:31.960 --> 03:09:38.040
[Amit Varma]: value in explaining why people thought or behaved a particular way. And that's how they

03:09:38.040 --> 03:09:43.200
[Amit Varma]: kind of sort of think about it. But you've been speaking and our previous episode, of

03:09:43.200 --> 03:09:48.560
[Amit Varma]: course, was on the role of religion in Indian society as well and that was very illuminating.

03:09:48.560 --> 03:09:53.120
[Amit Varma]: But what you're sort of saying is that that's a wrong way to think of religion, that religion

03:09:53.120 --> 03:09:58.280
[Amit Varma]: plays a central role in our society and in our existence and that if we are open to it,

03:09:58.280 --> 03:10:03.280
[Amit Varma]: there is a lot of value to be had from religious scriptures. In fact, Pratap Bhanu Mehta once

03:10:03.280 --> 03:10:08.480
[Amit Varma]: while speaking about his own religiosity spoke about the purest form of religion, what he

03:10:08.480 --> 03:10:14.680
[Amit Varma]: got from the elders in his family as being a form of deep skepticism, right? So, I forget

03:10:14.680 --> 03:10:20.640
[Amit Varma]: the exact terms he used, but it was a very sort of, it gave me a different picture into

03:10:20.640 --> 03:10:25.840
[Amit Varma]: what an engagement with religion can be like, which was quite different from the normal,

03:10:25.840 --> 03:10:31.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, one that is full of blind faith and superstition and idolatry and all of that.

03:10:31.360 --> 03:10:35.040
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about the role that religion has played in your life and in your

03:10:35.040 --> 03:10:41.840
[Guest]: thinking. So, I'm not religious in the sense that I don't go to a temple regularly. I don't,

03:10:41.840 --> 03:10:48.200
[Guest]: I mean, I pray sometimes, but it's not something which is a, but I'm more, I mean, philosophically

03:10:48.200 --> 03:10:54.160
[Guest]: religious in that sense. So, it's much more like, so as I said that to understand the

03:10:54.160 --> 03:10:58.960
[Guest]: nature of our consciousness to begin with and we have an unconscious and the language

03:10:58.960 --> 03:11:04.000
[Guest]: of the unconscious is symbolic and it doesn't speak to us in the language that we speak

03:11:04.000 --> 03:11:08.960
[Guest]: of. And I think that's the level at which religious, I mean, whether it's mythology

03:11:08.960 --> 03:11:15.840
[Guest]: or even the more abstract texts speak to that level within us. And therefore, it's a very

03:11:15.840 --> 03:11:20.160
[Guest]: humbling experience because the experience of religion is basically the experience of

03:11:20.160 --> 03:11:25.880
[Guest]: the numinous, right? It's a sense of numinous and it can be represented as some God that

03:11:25.880 --> 03:11:29.080
[Guest]: transcends the world or it's something can be represented more psychologically, some

03:11:29.080 --> 03:11:35.840
[Guest]: people represent it or it can be represented in the sense of the Brahman that exists and

03:11:35.840 --> 03:11:41.520
[Guest]: we are basically, I mean, our Atman is a part, it is the same as that or differently, you

03:11:41.520 --> 03:11:46.420
[Guest]: know, there are different ways in which this has been, I mean, put in different traditions.

03:11:46.420 --> 03:11:53.400
[Guest]: But the core common point, I think, is the experience of this numinosity, which basically

03:11:53.400 --> 03:11:58.240
[Guest]: the religion is supposed to give you and that's a humbling experience. That's a very humbling

03:11:58.240 --> 03:12:02.960
[Guest]: experience because you are, I mean, if you start associating with your gods, I mean,

03:12:02.960 --> 03:12:07.200
[Guest]: psychologically, then you can have a huge ego inflation and you can actually be the

03:12:07.200 --> 03:12:12.240
[Guest]: worst kind of religious person, you know, because while if you actually think about

03:12:12.240 --> 03:12:18.840
[Guest]: it as one consciousness experiencing the presence of numinous, then it's a much more humbling

03:12:18.840 --> 03:12:26.200
[Guest]: experience actually. It's much more about your journey as an individual soul or consciousness

03:12:26.200 --> 03:12:34.520
[Guest]: or whatever you may call it, towards a particular kind of spiritual experience or like, one

03:12:34.520 --> 03:12:39.640
[Guest]: of the things that I've always, I mean, remember whenever I think about religion, I don't think

03:12:39.640 --> 03:12:46.000
[Guest]: about it all the time, but is that when I was like 12 or 13 years old, my family has

03:12:46.000 --> 03:12:52.280
[Guest]: a guru, he passed away a few years ago, he was, he had an ashram in Mathura. And I asked

03:12:52.280 --> 03:13:01.480
[Guest]: my uncle, just like a naive kid, but how do you know somebody is a guru? So, he said something

03:13:01.480 --> 03:13:08.400
[Guest]: very interesting that the way to tell is that the guru will always or the person who's enlightened

03:13:08.400 --> 03:13:14.840
[Guest]: will always treat everybody alike, whether it's a prime minister of the country, or somebody

03:13:14.840 --> 03:13:21.320
[Guest]: who's completely under destitution or powerless, so to speak, he will treat everybody alike.

03:13:21.320 --> 03:13:26.600
[Guest]: That's the one test he gave me, that if you want to know who's a real guru, he's not going

03:13:26.600 --> 03:13:31.400
[Guest]: to treat the prime minister in a special way because of some ceremony or something, we'll

03:13:31.400 --> 03:13:37.120
[Guest]: treat him the same way as anybody else. And that was, as a kid, it didn't mean anything

03:13:37.120 --> 03:13:39.400
[Amit Varma]: to me. But to test this you need an available prime

03:13:39.400 --> 03:13:44.280
[Guest]: minister. No, no, I'm just kidding. I'm just, yeah, I mean, that was a test. Prime minister

03:13:44.280 --> 03:13:49.600
[Guest]: is one, but any level, you know, class differences, anything, skin color, all of that. So, as

03:13:49.600 --> 03:13:53.240
[Guest]: a kid, I said, well, what does it even mean? How can you treat everybody alike? But as

03:13:53.240 --> 03:13:57.120
[Guest]: you grow older, you realize that's the truth of it, right? When you when you're truly religious

03:13:57.120 --> 03:14:02.840
[Guest]: or truly, I mean, spiritual in that sense, then you actually see some very humbling experience.

03:14:02.840 --> 03:14:08.400
[Guest]: It's experience of equality in some ways, you know, that we are all in the most important

03:14:08.400 --> 03:14:14.080
[Guest]: ways equal, you know, all the surface level differences, intelligence, wealth, all that

03:14:14.080 --> 03:14:18.120
[Guest]: alike, in the most important ways, we're equal. And that's represented in different ways.

03:14:18.120 --> 03:14:21.360
[Guest]: For example, in some Western traditions and Abrahamic traditions, there's some God and

03:14:21.360 --> 03:14:26.080
[Guest]: against that you're equal. So, there's one. And in our tradition, it's different, represented

03:14:26.080 --> 03:14:28.600
[Guest]: differently. And the experience and past are different. I'm not saying they're the same

03:14:28.600 --> 03:14:32.080
[Guest]: thing. They're offering different paths, whether they're leading to the same thing or not,

03:14:32.080 --> 03:14:36.560
[Guest]: I don't know. I'll experience that hopefully later in my life. I haven't, I don't have

03:14:36.560 --> 03:14:40.880
[Guest]: the kind of religious experience that is required to comment on that. But these are the things

03:14:40.880 --> 03:14:45.400
[Guest]: that I think are, as you actually practice this thing and think about it and engage with

03:14:45.400 --> 03:14:51.480
[Guest]: it seriously, that this is what it is. And I mean, one doesn't have to, but I link it

03:14:51.480 --> 03:14:56.080
[Guest]: to democracy also in some senses that, you know, these are the kind of values in some

03:14:56.080 --> 03:15:01.200
[Guest]: ways that democracy could use more of, you know, that a guru who teaches, who treats

03:15:01.200 --> 03:15:10.040
[Guest]: everybody alike, a citizen who genuinely and deeply experiences equality, you know, and

03:15:10.040 --> 03:15:18.320
[Guest]: not pays too much attention to the surface level differences that exist between us.

03:15:18.320 --> 03:15:22.800
[Guest]: And that's something actually. So, I've also gone through many phases. I had a very naive

03:15:22.800 --> 03:15:28.200
[Guest]: belief early on, which was as a kid, you know, like literally every day pray, there's Lord

03:15:28.200 --> 03:15:33.360
[Guest]: Shiva, there's this, you know, there was deities to bow in front of and it's a ritual, much

03:15:33.360 --> 03:15:39.160
[Guest]: more of a ritual. It still comforts and calms me very much. But that I kind of outgrew in

03:15:39.160 --> 03:15:44.880
[Guest]: my 20s itself. Like I didn't have that kind of a naive belief anymore. So then I had a

03:15:44.880 --> 03:15:51.360
[Guest]: long march back. That march is too long to talk about here. Hopefully, once the march

03:15:51.360 --> 03:15:56.960
[Guest]: is complete, I'll have something to say about it. But it's been a long, long march.

03:15:56.960 --> 03:16:00.880
[Amit Varma]: Once the march is complete, you will be giving five hour slots to every podcaster because

03:16:00.880 --> 03:16:06.360
[Amit Varma]: you have to treat everyone equally. So, where are we then? So, you know, earlier, I'd asked

03:16:06.360 --> 03:16:10.600
[Amit Varma]: about whether your background set you apart from the other sort of people you worked with

03:16:10.600 --> 03:16:16.880
[Amit Varma]: in the policy space or the quote unquote, intellectual circles of Delhi. Let me come

03:16:16.880 --> 03:16:24.760
[Amit Varma]: at that question from another angle, where one fixes the lens on the intellectual elites

03:16:24.760 --> 03:16:28.560
[Amit Varma]: of Delhi, as it were. You've written this lovely essay on Tocqueville, which of course

03:16:28.560 --> 03:16:34.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll link from the show notes, where you quote Blaise Pascal as saying early on quote, what

03:16:34.000 --> 03:16:39.440
[Amit Varma]: a great advantage to be of noble birth, since it gives a man of 18, the standing recognition

03:16:39.440 --> 03:16:44.880
[Amit Varma]: and respect that another man might not earn before he was 50. That means winning 30 years

03:16:44.880 --> 03:16:50.440
[Amit Varma]: start with no effort, stop quote. And this, of course, is a comment on privilege of sorts

03:16:50.440 --> 03:16:56.120
[Amit Varma]: that we should be aware of. But it's also a comment on how so many of these intellectual

03:16:56.120 --> 03:17:00.840
[Amit Varma]: elites and policy elites and all of that, everything kind of just fell into the lap,

03:17:00.840 --> 03:17:05.120
[Amit Varma]: they were born in a particular place in a particular time, perhaps in a particular family.

03:17:05.120 --> 03:17:10.400
[Amit Varma]: And this was an easy sort of route to take, you do your PhD in a foreign university, perhaps,

03:17:10.400 --> 03:17:14.720
[Amit Varma]: in the course of things, you come back a quote unquote, expert in a particular subject with

03:17:14.720 --> 03:17:20.320
[Amit Varma]: a particular kind of lens, which is the fashionable lens at the time, which might have been acquired

03:17:20.320 --> 03:17:25.520
[Amit Varma]: from wherever you studied and all of that. And you're on a groove, and it's a set groove,

03:17:25.520 --> 03:17:31.440
[Amit Varma]: and it's a set path. And it is natural when one is on that path to not gain epistemic

03:17:31.440 --> 03:17:36.200
[Amit Varma]: humility, or, you know, not to use fancy terms, but to not gain the humility to recognize

03:17:36.200 --> 03:17:40.240
[Amit Varma]: that you're often wrong, that maybe the lens that you were indoctrinated with might be

03:17:40.240 --> 03:17:44.320
[Amit Varma]: the wrong lens might be simplistic, might be looking at the wrong things, that there

03:17:44.320 --> 03:17:49.800
[Amit Varma]: is more to the world that you have to, you know, first engage in good faith, and with

03:17:49.800 --> 03:17:55.280
[Amit Varma]: respect, different points of view, that, you know, you can't just sit back and pass judgment

03:17:55.280 --> 03:18:00.040
[Amit Varma]: on people all the time, you have to make that effort to get down and dirty and really understand

03:18:00.040 --> 03:18:04.280
[Amit Varma]: what's going on. And everything that I'm saying sounds incredibly harsh, but it's certainly

03:18:04.280 --> 03:18:12.240
[Amit Varma]: my view of a lot of the so called Latins elite that I see around me. And that is one thing

03:18:12.240 --> 03:18:16.520
[Amit Varma]: that I think Modi is absolutely right on. I think, you know, as everybody knows, I've

03:18:16.520 --> 03:18:22.920
[Amit Varma]: opposed Modi so strongly that I've been mobbed, I've faced threats, all that shit has happened,

03:18:22.920 --> 03:18:29.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, especially after I opposed him on from day one. So I'm like, at one level, the

03:18:29.560 --> 03:18:34.960
[Amit Varma]: biggest opponent in the policy sphere, but he's right about this. And this is perhaps

03:18:34.960 --> 03:18:40.320
[Amit Varma]: one reason that, you know, there are a lot of people instinctively support him on this

03:18:40.320 --> 03:18:47.280
[Amit Varma]: issue, because there is that sort of understanding that our data clueless elites led us down

03:18:47.280 --> 03:18:54.040
[Amit Varma]: the wrong path, tried to reshape our country in a way that, you know, wasn't in consonance

03:18:54.040 --> 03:18:59.820
[Amit Varma]: with what the country really was. And what is happening today is pushback. So give me

03:18:59.820 --> 03:19:05.720
[Amit Varma]: a sense of these elites because and I don't want to sort of make it sound as if every

03:19:05.720 --> 03:19:10.440
[Amit Varma]: individual who works with you is a scoundrel or something like that. You know, I know many

03:19:10.440 --> 03:19:14.880
[Amit Varma]: of these individuals, I am in a sense one of the privileged elites, many of these people

03:19:14.880 --> 03:19:20.400
[Amit Varma]: are my friends. But there is a systemic problem that we keep going on and on about an idea

03:19:20.400 --> 03:19:24.920
[Amit Varma]: of India that has nothing to do with India. And that we never did the hard work of trying

03:19:24.920 --> 03:19:30.880
[Amit Varma]: to shape this country and shape it from within the culture and from within society instead

03:19:30.880 --> 03:19:37.520
[Amit Varma]: top down bat gay humne socha ki bus, you know, hum apne high ideal se sab kuch badal denge

03:19:37.520 --> 03:19:41.520
[Amit Varma]: like the, you know, like like earlier, you were speaking of hypothetical constitution

03:19:41.520 --> 03:19:46.040
[Amit Varma]: law or lawyers who don't really want to engage in the dirty work of politics, but just change

03:19:46.040 --> 03:19:51.960
[Amit Varma]: it from their pedestals and ivory towers. So tell me a little bit about sort of this

03:19:51.960 --> 03:19:56.120
[Amit Varma]: community and I suspect you're going to be very diplomatic because you are after all,

03:19:56.120 --> 03:19:57.120
[Amit Varma]: in their midst.

03:19:57.120 --> 03:20:05.120
[Guest]: Yeah, who wants to be a class enemy? But yeah, I mean, so you said earlier that politics

03:20:05.120 --> 03:20:10.960
[Guest]: is corrupting, you know, but intellectualism is far more corrupting, you know, because

03:20:10.960 --> 03:20:16.600
[Guest]: if your job is to describe and understand the word and basically make a recommendation

03:20:16.600 --> 03:20:22.080
[Guest]: how to make and remake it, it's impossible to be actually, it's a very unnatural thing,

03:20:22.080 --> 03:20:26.640
[Guest]: right? It's a very unnatural thing to do to be done at scale. You know, when you think

03:20:26.640 --> 03:20:32.920
[Guest]: about large society, complex adaptive systems, which are kind of evolving and emerging, and

03:20:32.920 --> 03:20:38.840
[Guest]: you try to describe them in a way which is not sufficiently complex in representing that

03:20:38.840 --> 03:20:46.520
[Guest]: reality and is much more of a top down perspective of it, then it's impossible to get it right.

03:20:46.520 --> 03:20:51.480
[Guest]: I mean, for the most part, unless you completely reorient yourself and talk in a language which

03:20:51.480 --> 03:20:57.240
[Guest]: is respecting of the complexity of that reality, and whether it's a social reality or economic

03:20:57.240 --> 03:21:03.320
[Guest]: or political, different spheres, and all of them are overlapping, all of that. So it is

03:21:03.320 --> 03:21:08.800
[Guest]: extremely difficult. And one of the most common things that all of us fall to different degrees

03:21:08.800 --> 03:21:15.960
[Guest]: is intellectual pride, you know, that just because we know a little, we have read a little,

03:21:15.960 --> 03:21:25.480
[Guest]: and we have, we can quote a few serious, we can, from Dworkin to Kant, we can quote people

03:21:25.480 --> 03:21:33.080
[Guest]: who sound serious. We think that we have some special knowledge, you know, it's something

03:21:33.080 --> 03:21:42.640
[Guest]: that the best of us have, can fall for. And, I mean, so have I, I mean, it's not like I've

03:21:42.640 --> 03:21:48.080
[Guest]: never said anything about let's do this in this way, you know, which underwent many,

03:21:48.080 --> 03:21:52.880
[Guest]: many assumptions behind it, right. There was not a, it was the recommendations based on

03:21:52.880 --> 03:21:59.000
[Guest]: things that one thought one knew, and then later one thought that maybe one was not right

03:21:59.000 --> 03:22:05.440
[Guest]: about it. So it's, the fundamental thing is that it's very hard to do this, you know,

03:22:05.440 --> 03:22:12.960
[Guest]: that think tanks, and working in bringing intellectualism to this is, is to begin with

03:22:12.960 --> 03:22:18.000
[Guest]: very difficult to get it right. But, I mean, there are obviously, as you said, many shades

03:22:18.000 --> 03:22:23.240
[Guest]: of this, like if you work closely with people who have a sense of constraints, you're working

03:22:23.240 --> 03:22:28.960
[Guest]: on specific problems that you're trying to solve in a democratic way, the role of the

03:22:28.960 --> 03:22:33.080
[Guest]: intellectual or expert in democracy is a very small role, you know, it's a very limited

03:22:33.080 --> 03:22:38.120
[Guest]: role. Democratic processes are basically, there is a system which has been put in place

03:22:38.120 --> 03:22:43.360
[Guest]: constitutionally. And that system has its own internal logic to working. And even if

03:22:43.360 --> 03:22:47.760
[Guest]: you forget about the constitutional system, and the words that are put in the constitution,

03:22:47.760 --> 03:22:52.280
[Guest]: that's not so important. The important thing is the reality of the way societies work.

03:22:52.280 --> 03:22:56.000
[Guest]: And the society will support certain kinds of constitutional practices and oppose certain

03:22:56.000 --> 03:22:59.240
[Guest]: constitutional and nothing you can do about it because the people are sovereign, you know,

03:22:59.240 --> 03:23:04.240
[Guest]: that's the fundamental thing. Everything else is just language games on top of that. So,

03:23:04.240 --> 03:23:09.440
[Guest]: so you have, you have that and so you have to define your role in a manner which is more

03:23:09.440 --> 03:23:13.680
[Guest]: modest and you're trying to frame issues, you're trying to bring out facts for people's

03:23:13.680 --> 03:23:18.360
[Guest]: attention for the experts and for the policy makers' attentions. Policy makers have legitimacy,

03:23:18.360 --> 03:23:23.640
[Guest]: right? Because politicians get elected, they are empowered to take decisions, they don't

03:23:23.640 --> 03:23:29.120
[Guest]: have to go and do a referendum every time. There are some limited amount of power for

03:23:29.120 --> 03:23:32.240
[Guest]: which they have some power, limited amount of time for which they have some power. And

03:23:32.240 --> 03:23:37.040
[Guest]: they can take a decision, you can give them all some alternatives about these are different

03:23:37.040 --> 03:23:41.640
[Guest]: ways, pros and cons. It's they still have to go and figure out what will politically

03:23:41.640 --> 03:23:46.480
[Guest]: be feasible or not. They have to ask their constituents sometimes, at least some stakeholders

03:23:46.480 --> 03:23:51.840
[Guest]: about what would work, what would not. So, there is a role, you know, on shedding lights

03:23:51.840 --> 03:23:59.520
[Guest]: on facts, analyzing facts, but that is, you stop there and then you start, I mean, you

03:23:59.520 --> 03:24:04.120
[Guest]: accept that there is a democratic process through which things will happen. And you

03:24:04.120 --> 03:24:09.760
[Guest]: will often be disappointed. I worked on one particular reform for three years. Three years

03:24:09.760 --> 03:24:14.960
[Guest]: I've devoted to that one issue in my previous job. It was to reform a particular kind of

03:24:14.960 --> 03:24:20.040
[Guest]: do a particular financial sector reform on bankruptcy of financial firms. And after three

03:24:20.040 --> 03:24:26.040
[Guest]: years, it was withdrawn. I mean, in fact, from the parliament, the bill was withdrawn.

03:24:26.040 --> 03:24:29.440
[Guest]: And that's it. I mean, there was a democratic process. There was some opposition. And I

03:24:29.440 --> 03:24:33.280
[Guest]: believe there was some wisdom in the government's decision to withdraw it. It wasn't the right

03:24:33.280 --> 03:24:39.400
[Guest]: time perhaps. My intellectual vanity was certainly hurt that, hey, I have worked on this and

03:24:39.400 --> 03:24:45.040
[Guest]: I was a very small part of it. I'm not elected. I'm not even an IAS officer. I'm working inside

03:24:45.040 --> 03:24:50.560
[Guest]: a system which has its own kind of ways of working. I have some bit of expertise. I've

03:24:50.560 --> 03:24:55.680
[Guest]: done research in that area for many years and I've worked on it for at least six, seven

03:24:55.680 --> 03:25:00.240
[Guest]: years even previously. So I had some ideas, but that's, I mean, a very, I mean, those

03:25:00.240 --> 03:25:04.760
[Guest]: ideas are not there for, nobody's waiting for those ideas to come. Oh, wow, you've now

03:25:04.760 --> 03:25:09.480
[Guest]: saved me, you know. So that I think is, is very important. The most important thing to

03:25:09.480 --> 03:25:15.880
[Guest]: avoid is intellectual pride, which all of us usually fall for. And I think the best

03:25:15.880 --> 03:25:21.800
[Guest]: way to avoid is to accept that you don't know. You don't know anything actually pretty much.

03:25:21.800 --> 03:25:27.640
[Guest]: But there are also other kind of problems that emerge in the way these things are happening

03:25:27.640 --> 03:25:34.520
[Guest]: that there are more localized games, right, that some intellectual and some politicians

03:25:34.520 --> 03:25:41.160
[Guest]: are in a happy relationship like, okay, I'll give you certain ideas that look very good

03:25:41.160 --> 03:25:47.200
[Guest]: on surface, we'll give you some short term wins. And the politicians say, yes, it sounds

03:25:47.200 --> 03:25:51.200
[Guest]: something I can work with. Whether the long term impact will be good or not is something

03:25:51.200 --> 03:25:55.840
[Guest]: which there the intellectual actually has a duty to actually do the right kind of advice

03:25:55.840 --> 03:26:01.720
[Guest]: and not get too political about it that, okay, what will help this person win elections only.

03:26:01.720 --> 03:26:04.440
[Guest]: That's obviously a constraint that the person has to worry about, the politicians to worry

03:26:04.440 --> 03:26:09.800
[Guest]: about. Intellectuals worry about the general equilibrium impact, you know, about what are

03:26:09.800 --> 03:26:16.000
[Guest]: the common good, how and long term how it how it will be served. I think there are quite

03:26:16.000 --> 03:26:21.880
[Guest]: a few compromises often made. I mean, by individuals, it's not a comment on everybody. There are

03:26:21.880 --> 03:26:27.400
[Guest]: lots of people who are who don't do it like that. But I think if some distance is maintained,

03:26:27.400 --> 03:26:31.440
[Guest]: some principle distance is maintained, and you say, okay, I'm here to do research and

03:26:31.440 --> 03:26:38.720
[Guest]: put out analysis and ideas. And it's a privilege, right, to be paid to read and think and write

03:26:38.720 --> 03:26:44.480
[Guest]: and analyze things. And I'm not playing the power game so much, you know, then it's more

03:26:44.480 --> 03:26:49.040
[Guest]: kind of an endishing for both sides, I think, whether intellectual class can serve the political

03:26:49.040 --> 03:26:54.760
[Guest]: class better and political class can benefit from the from the intellectual expertise better.

03:26:54.760 --> 03:26:59.200
[Guest]: And also, I mean, you can be true to your fear. And these are, this is what breaks down

03:26:59.200 --> 03:27:03.760
[Guest]: often because everything is political, you know, there is a person is a political, this

03:27:03.760 --> 03:27:07.440
[Guest]: is political, that is political, everything is political, then I mean, is there anything

03:27:07.440 --> 03:27:13.240
[Guest]: else which is to be considered or is power, the only thing that really matters. And so,

03:27:13.240 --> 03:27:19.160
[Guest]: as I said, intellectual pride is one thing, but also greed, in some ways, you know, hunger

03:27:19.160 --> 03:27:26.320
[Guest]: for power that can can get into this and epistemic humility is then shaped by all these other

03:27:26.320 --> 03:27:32.920
[Guest]: things, right? Like if you are really in it for the reason of Seva, so to speak, service,

03:27:32.920 --> 03:27:38.040
[Guest]: then you will sooner or later figure out that you were wrong and you don't understand much.

03:27:38.040 --> 03:27:41.040
[Guest]: And therefore, you need to be humble and you will you need to know that you are just one

03:27:41.040 --> 03:27:45.800
[Guest]: citizen among 1.4 billion, all of them have the same vote, just because you read a little

03:27:45.800 --> 03:27:49.080
[Guest]: bit, you don't know much. In fact, reading is one way to understand the world. And data

03:27:49.080 --> 03:27:52.200
[Guest]: analysis is one way to understand the world. Experience is another, business people know

03:27:52.200 --> 03:27:56.160
[Guest]: a lot, I talked to a lot of business people, they have a lot more wisdom over in the political

03:27:56.160 --> 03:28:00.360
[Guest]: economy that all the political economy researchers put together, including me, some of them,

03:28:00.360 --> 03:28:04.600
[Guest]: not all, because those who reflect about their world and who have lived through the last

03:28:04.600 --> 03:28:08.920
[Guest]: 30 years of Indian economy and have thought about it deeply. Some of the civil servants

03:28:08.920 --> 03:28:14.000
[Guest]: have deep wisdom about, politicians generally have a lot of wisdom about how the society

03:28:14.000 --> 03:28:17.800
[Guest]: works and what is possible, what is not possible, most of them actually.

03:28:17.800 --> 03:28:25.920
[Guest]: So, I think a much more of a modesty is required from this class, I think, and a little bit

03:28:25.920 --> 03:28:32.720
[Guest]: more honesty about what our role is. And again, being true to the virtues of being an analyst

03:28:32.720 --> 03:28:39.200
[Guest]: and intellectual or a thinker, or a researcher in policy space. I think generally, quite

03:28:39.200 --> 03:28:44.160
[Guest]: a few people do have that. I worked with quite a few of them, I still work with some of them.

03:28:44.160 --> 03:28:51.480
[Guest]: And I admire them, I learn from them, I am trying to do to be like, more like them. And

03:28:51.480 --> 03:28:57.360
[Guest]: I mean, I need to see more role models of that type. And so, otherwise, if you are only

03:28:57.360 --> 03:29:04.240
[Guest]: looking for power, or a lot more attention all the time, the whole thing is going in

03:29:04.240 --> 03:29:10.760
[Guest]: the direction of eyeballs, the game is of eyeballs, getting more and more views, and

03:29:10.760 --> 03:29:13.840
[Guest]: getting access, access comes at a cost, it is not so easy.

03:29:13.840 --> 03:29:19.680
[Guest]: So, but that is the game, everybody, the philanthropists pay for access and impact and all of that.

03:29:19.680 --> 03:29:27.760
[Guest]: So, there is a complex system in which different things have to realign a little to get good

03:29:27.760 --> 03:29:36.760
[Guest]: practices flourishing and bad practices diminishing in this, as it is in other domains. And overall,

03:29:36.760 --> 03:29:43.320
[Guest]: I think the space is expanded, there are now more think tanks and universities, more things

03:29:43.320 --> 03:29:48.120
[Guest]: to be done, more specialized areas of work also, somebody wants to do on tech policy

03:29:48.120 --> 03:29:50.600
[Guest]: can do tech policy, other areas.

03:29:50.600 --> 03:29:56.120
[Guest]: But ultimately, I think, because you are here to serve society, you have to first understand

03:29:56.120 --> 03:30:01.560
[Guest]: the society a little bit, like try to make sense of, I mean, maybe all the major premises,

03:30:01.560 --> 03:30:05.520
[Guest]: you know, like in major premise, minor premise inclusion. So, you all the major premises

03:30:05.520 --> 03:30:09.880
[Guest]: do not come from you only, right? People have their own preferences, like they want to,

03:30:09.880 --> 03:30:14.960
[Guest]: they want certain things, why are you here to impose your values upon them to transform

03:30:14.960 --> 03:30:19.480
[Guest]: their lives, you know, who are you, you are one citizen. And to get that through shortcuts

03:30:19.480 --> 03:30:25.840
[Guest]: that I will get this one, I mean, order passed or something is really, I mean, vitiating

03:30:25.840 --> 03:30:28.040
[Guest]: the democratic atmosphere.

03:30:28.040 --> 03:30:33.240
[Guest]: And in some ways, I mean, I think Mr. Modi goes overboard in his populist rhetoric. But

03:30:33.240 --> 03:30:37.160
[Guest]: it is a symbol, right? Just think about it. He said Khan market, how many people in India

03:30:37.160 --> 03:30:41.920
[Guest]: know Khan market? Only people, it is a Delhi thing, right? But it somehow resonates in

03:30:41.920 --> 03:30:46.120
[Guest]: other parts also, because every place has its Khan market. You know, and there's something

03:30:46.120 --> 03:30:52.560
[Guest]: to be said about that kind of rhetoric working. Why with working? So, it's, and therefore,

03:30:52.560 --> 03:30:56.720
[Guest]: I think there is some need to understand why something like this work. I'm not, I don't

03:30:56.720 --> 03:31:01.960
[Guest]: think populist politics is a good thing. In democracy, it's a perversion of democracy.

03:31:01.960 --> 03:31:07.120
[Guest]: And but democracy is perverted in many ways, not just populism.

03:31:07.120 --> 03:31:12.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I think just speculating aloud, when I look at either some of the Latvians

03:31:12.320 --> 03:31:18.800
[Amit Varma]: elite, or whether I look at many people taking harsh stride in strands on Twitter, for example,

03:31:18.800 --> 03:31:24.160
[Amit Varma]: I see two simultaneous, you know, things driving this. And one is intellectual laziness, that

03:31:24.160 --> 03:31:27.680
[Amit Varma]: you've arrived at a frame through which you look at the world. And now you don't want

03:31:27.680 --> 03:31:33.360
[Amit Varma]: to put in the cognitive energy to modify that frame, or to engage with other ways of looking

03:31:33.360 --> 03:31:37.600
[Amit Varma]: at the world, or to enter a deep, meaningful discourse where you're not lecturing someone,

03:31:37.600 --> 03:31:43.000
[Amit Varma]: but you're actually engaging with them. And the second drive is a drive to sanctimony,

03:31:43.000 --> 03:31:48.080
[Amit Varma]: that you know, it makes all of us feel virtuous if you're giving lectures on morality to others,

03:31:48.080 --> 03:31:54.680
[Amit Varma]: if you're condemning others, if you're passing judgment, and that sort of becomes problematic.

03:31:54.680 --> 03:32:00.360
[Guest]: So like, I mean, see, this is happening because of influence, we want to influence. Influence

03:32:00.360 --> 03:32:04.040
[Guest]: requires certainty, at least appearance of certainty, even if you may be a little bit

03:32:04.040 --> 03:32:07.680
[Guest]: doubt inside, you have to appear that you're certain so that you can make a claim. To make

03:32:07.680 --> 03:32:12.000
[Guest]: a claim, you need to appear at least somewhat sure yourself, right? Otherwise, why would

03:32:12.000 --> 03:32:16.880
[Guest]: other person say that there's something worth listening to? And so one thing is epistemic

03:32:16.880 --> 03:32:21.280
[Guest]: certainty, other is moral superiority. That is also required for influence, because you

03:32:21.280 --> 03:32:25.440
[Guest]: have to not just say that you're sure about this, so this is a morally better thing to

03:32:25.440 --> 03:32:30.800
[Guest]: do. And both are actually, if you think carefully, are important for influence, but also in a

03:32:30.800 --> 03:32:35.320
[Guest]: way intellectually and morally corrupting in some senses that you have to pretend to

03:32:35.320 --> 03:32:41.000
[Guest]: have a particular position, which you may actually inside you have many doubts about.

03:32:41.000 --> 03:32:45.040
[Amit Varma]: Great point. The first time we met, we met in Bombay, our mutual friend Kumar Anand,

03:32:45.040 --> 03:32:50.280
[Amit Varma]: God bless his soul, introduced us. God bless him. He's alive, by the way, we are talking

03:32:50.280 --> 03:32:56.800
[Amit Varma]: like he's very much alive. Shout out to Kumar. And I think we met at Khar Social, was it?

03:32:56.800 --> 03:33:02.140
[Amit Varma]: And some place. And one of the things that immediately you and I were on exactly the

03:33:02.140 --> 03:33:06.200
[Amit Varma]: same page was demonetization, where both of us felt equally strongly. And we both agreed

03:33:06.200 --> 03:33:11.680
[Amit Varma]: that it was a litmus test for us. Key, you know, whether you're really a liberal or you're

03:33:11.680 --> 03:33:17.320
[Amit Varma]: not in terms of, you know, the classical sense of the word liberal. And I later wrote a piece

03:33:17.320 --> 03:33:21.680
[Amit Varma]: called the Beware of the Useful Idiots, which was an editorial for the online magazine I

03:33:21.680 --> 03:33:27.600
[Amit Varma]: edited Pragati, where my argument was that any economist who supported demonetization

03:33:27.600 --> 03:33:34.000
[Amit Varma]: was either a bad economist or a bad human being, because demon was just so evidently

03:33:34.000 --> 03:33:38.920
[Amit Varma]: daft and dangerous. And like I keep saying, the largest attack on property rights in human

03:33:38.920 --> 03:33:46.000
[Amit Varma]: history. And, and that also shows how some of our intellectual elites are not driven

03:33:46.000 --> 03:33:52.960
[Amit Varma]: by what they project as a power of ideas or believing in certain principles, but rather

03:33:52.960 --> 03:33:58.640
[Amit Varma]: other kinds of contingencies, like many of the people who supported demon were people

03:33:58.640 --> 03:34:03.240
[Amit Varma]: who had allied themselves with the government, because they thought key TK, you know, they'll

03:34:03.240 --> 03:34:07.800
[Amit Varma]: bring about the change we want, at least that was their reasoning then. But even when they

03:34:07.800 --> 03:34:12.240
[Amit Varma]: saw that this government was far more status than previous ones, and we're thinking and

03:34:12.240 --> 03:34:16.880
[Amit Varma]: we're doing completely daft and dangerous things like demonetization, they continued

03:34:16.880 --> 03:34:21.320
[Amit Varma]: rationalizing that they continued supporting that, at one hand, of course, the government

03:34:21.320 --> 03:34:27.060
[Amit Varma]: had given out this order to all its house dogs, as it were, that, you know, defend demon.

03:34:27.060 --> 03:34:32.200
[Amit Varma]: But many of them did it. Many of them actually did it. Many of them wrote columns and came

03:34:32.200 --> 03:34:39.840
[Amit Varma]: on TV, supporting demonetization, when you and I know that they knew that it was a disaster.

03:34:39.840 --> 03:34:46.880
[Amit Varma]: And yet they, you know, willfully lied. And that makes me and there are two thoughts connected

03:34:46.880 --> 03:34:54.080
[Amit Varma]: with this. And one is that a lot of what people claim to believe in is a front to themselves

03:34:54.080 --> 03:35:00.880
[Amit Varma]: and to others. And people are more tribal than they are principled, by and large, with

03:35:00.880 --> 03:35:01.880
[Guest]: exceptions.

03:35:01.880 --> 03:35:08.120
[Guest]: Yeah, we are also in, to some extent, I mean, let's not have an assumption in this conversation

03:35:08.120 --> 03:35:13.160
[Amit Varma]: that you and I are morally superior to others, you know, that is one part of the community.

03:35:13.160 --> 03:35:18.100
[Amit Varma]: Let me finish. So no, the thing is, just to address that, and that's, which is why I don't

03:35:18.100 --> 03:35:21.920
[Amit Varma]: like labels being attached to me anymore. And which is why, you know, why does a person

03:35:21.920 --> 03:35:26.680
[Amit Varma]: like me, I mean, in a sense, I have no friends, right, in that, in the ideological space,

03:35:26.680 --> 03:35:31.280
[Amit Varma]: because I'm, I've attacked everyone, because I'm just going by my principles. It doesn't

03:35:31.280 --> 03:35:35.480
[Amit Varma]: mean that there is no circumstance in which I won't compromise, who knows, you know, you

03:35:35.480 --> 03:35:39.440
[Amit Varma]: put me in a dungeon, and you torture me and you make me watch Shahrukh Khan movies all

03:35:39.440 --> 03:35:46.040
[Amit Varma]: day, even I will bend at some point. But, but in general, we've avoided tribalism, which

03:35:46.040 --> 03:35:51.520
[Amit Varma]: is something I can, you know, confidently say, whereas, and this is something I'm lamenting,

03:35:51.520 --> 03:35:57.120
[Amit Varma]: I'm not, you know, I'm just lamenting that, like earlier, you said that we do things for

03:35:57.120 --> 03:36:01.920
[Amit Varma]: reasons that we ourselves may not understand, you know, what is going on in our subconscious,

03:36:01.920 --> 03:36:07.840
[Amit Varma]: we don't know most of it. So that's sort of one thing I saw during that, that kind of

03:36:07.840 --> 03:36:11.320
[Amit Varma]: made me feel that, you know, people are more tribal than their principled, even when they

03:36:11.320 --> 03:36:15.720
[Amit Varma]: appear principled. We saw this in the US with the Republican Party, where so many Republicans

03:36:15.720 --> 03:36:19.760
[Amit Varma]: supported Trump, despite the fact that Trump stood against so many of the principles of

03:36:19.760 --> 03:36:24.080
[Amit Varma]: the Republican Party, like on trade, for example, where his positions are identical to Bernie

03:36:24.080 --> 03:36:29.440
[Amit Varma]: Sanders. So is this something that kind of strikes you that people have chosen sides,

03:36:29.440 --> 03:36:34.480
[Amit Varma]: and they are going with those sides? Is it, is nuance therefore difficult in these times

03:36:34.480 --> 03:36:37.560
[Amit Varma]: for a person like you who works in the sphere of ideas?

03:36:37.560 --> 03:36:43.280
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, as I said, that there's a cost in terms of some influence that you have to

03:36:43.280 --> 03:36:48.640
[Guest]: pay in the, at least for some time, maybe forever, because, I mean, the times are such

03:36:48.640 --> 03:36:54.240
[Guest]: that if you want to be autonomous, you will be isolated. So, and it's just two sides of

03:36:54.240 --> 03:36:59.760
[Guest]: the same coin right now, but the times can change. And when demonetization was a very

03:36:59.760 --> 03:37:04.920
[Guest]: disappointing time, because many people I know who should know better, I mean, still

03:37:04.920 --> 03:37:09.640
[Guest]: said something different from what I, it was apparent to me, I mean, what was going on

03:37:09.640 --> 03:37:14.580
[Guest]: and the harm that it would do not just in terms of direct harm, but also unsettling

03:37:14.580 --> 03:37:19.080
[Guest]: the assumptions about the way policies are made in India and implemented the process

03:37:19.080 --> 03:37:24.400
[Guest]: and kind of diligence that is gone and the direction of India's policymaking in some

03:37:24.400 --> 03:37:28.320
[Guest]: ways was completely, it was a shock event to that, right. There was a general directionality

03:37:28.320 --> 03:37:32.400
[Guest]: of more openness and liberality, a little bit more policy certainty they were trying

03:37:32.400 --> 03:37:36.760
[Guest]: to establish. Even they, between 2014 and 16, the government had stabilized the economy

03:37:36.760 --> 03:37:40.720
[Guest]: in many ways, they had taken quite a few sensible decisions. And suddenly, two and a half years

03:37:40.720 --> 03:37:45.440
[Guest]: into the government, this thing was announced, and I wish there had been more civil society,

03:37:45.440 --> 03:37:50.640
[Guest]: at least among intellectual economies, there had been a little bit more skepticism about

03:37:50.640 --> 03:37:54.680
[Guest]: even trying something like this. And I think more than economics, economics can justify

03:37:54.680 --> 03:37:58.000
[Guest]: many things, because it depends on the assumptions you make about the future, right. So, future

03:37:58.000 --> 03:38:03.160
[Guest]: assumption of analysis of future impact, and which variables you consider. So, some people

03:38:03.160 --> 03:38:07.360
[Guest]: highlight the digitization and all of that. It is more full political philosophy, right.

03:38:07.360 --> 03:38:10.320
[Guest]: What is the political philosophy that you have that you would support a decision like

03:38:10.320 --> 03:38:16.000
[Guest]: this, you know, as a citizen, and that to take in such a way, you know, which was completely

03:38:16.000 --> 03:38:24.600
[Guest]: certain, arbitrary, and in my view, at least harmful and wrong. So, but that is the thing.

03:38:24.600 --> 03:38:29.160
[Guest]: Everybody has their reasons. They have their reasons to do what they do. But I agree that

03:38:29.160 --> 03:38:33.720
[Guest]: wherever tribalism comes in, tribalism becomes a reason. And then it substitutes many other

03:38:33.720 --> 03:38:38.680
[Guest]: reasons, you know, the reasoning and the rationality that should go into at least for people like

03:38:38.680 --> 03:38:44.400
[Guest]: us who are in that luxurious space of thinking carefully, analyzing data and having scenarios

03:38:44.400 --> 03:38:48.480
[Guest]: of the future and seeing what are the plausible scenarios, typical way in which you do policy

03:38:48.480 --> 03:38:52.920
[Guest]: analysis. If you have that, and you don't excise that, it's much more tribalism, it's

03:38:52.920 --> 03:38:57.400
[Guest]: harmful. That's why I think that, yes, politics is very important. It is the main way in which

03:38:57.400 --> 03:39:02.520
[Guest]: you organize society. Politicians are the ones who have greatest legitimacy in a democratic

03:39:02.520 --> 03:39:08.440
[Guest]: setting to take decisions and all of that. And democracy has rewarded that decision in

03:39:08.440 --> 03:39:13.440
[Guest]: some ways. They have won the election and all of that. And it's very important and that

03:39:13.440 --> 03:39:18.040
[Guest]: is the way in which our society settles these questions. I mean, there is nothing else.

03:39:18.040 --> 03:39:22.440
[Guest]: But each one of us has our duty, right, to when we think that something is going to do

03:39:22.440 --> 03:39:27.040
[Guest]: some harm, and we have some basis to say that and we have thought carefully about it, then

03:39:27.040 --> 03:39:31.360
[Guest]: we put it out and hopefully some people will listen to it, some course correction will

03:39:31.360 --> 03:39:37.000
[Guest]: happen and all of that. And that is our role. And whether democracy will listen to us, whether

03:39:37.000 --> 03:39:40.520
[Guest]: people will listen to us, whether the politicians will listen to us, is not something that we

03:39:40.520 --> 03:39:47.120
[Guest]: can really control. We are, I mean, our influence is a matter of more of our time than our own

03:39:47.120 --> 03:39:55.320
[Guest]: self, what happens with the ideas that we have. And so I humbly say that you and I,

03:39:55.320 --> 03:40:01.120
[Guest]: I for sure thought it was a harmful decision, not just in the short term cost, but also

03:40:01.120 --> 03:40:07.600
[Guest]: the long term impact on the political economy of India. It disrupted many things that were

03:40:07.600 --> 03:40:16.440
[Guest]: underpinning our growth, in my view. And, but reasonable people always disagree. I mean,

03:40:16.440 --> 03:40:22.040
[Guest]: some reasonable people can disagree about the economics of it. But the political philosophy,

03:40:22.040 --> 03:40:28.560
[Guest]: the kind of citizens, perspectives that came out, I thought, because the way it was presented,

03:40:28.560 --> 03:40:34.240
[Guest]: it was like a fight against corruption, right. It was a sacrificial kind of a process through

03:40:34.240 --> 03:40:40.400
[Guest]: which you fight and cleanse your body politic of corruption. And that became very difficult

03:40:40.400 --> 03:40:45.160
[Guest]: to oppose for many people. Politically appeared like if you are opposing demonetization, opposing

03:40:45.160 --> 03:40:51.240
[Guest]: corruption. You know, people like us who wrote about it in a critical way, analytically,

03:40:51.240 --> 03:40:55.800
[Guest]: I mean, we had to go to extra lengths to say that we are not supporting corruption, quote

03:40:55.800 --> 03:40:59.360
[Guest]: unquote. Corruption is a complicated business. And we can come to talk about that a little

03:40:59.360 --> 03:41:04.040
[Guest]: later if you want, what is corruption and what is not. But at that time, it was a pretty

03:41:04.040 --> 03:41:09.320
[Guest]: binary situation. And quite a few people, I mean, disappointingly, for tribal reasons

03:41:09.320 --> 03:41:15.080
[Guest]: or for reasons of appearing virtuous at that time, basically said that, hey, this is at

03:41:15.080 --> 03:41:22.280
[Guest]: least it's an experiment worth trying. Or they said that this is, this is going to work,

03:41:22.280 --> 03:41:28.480
[Guest]: you know, all of that, which without offering enough evidence of why it may be. And even

03:41:28.480 --> 03:41:33.560
[Guest]: now, there are lots of people who defend that decision. Even after these many years, they

03:41:33.560 --> 03:41:40.840
[Guest]: still think that it worked. So, I guess, there's a possibility that I may be wrong about it.

03:41:40.840 --> 03:41:45.640
[Guest]: And I have to accept that, because I don't know everything, obviously. But I still hold

03:41:45.640 --> 03:41:47.720
[Guest]: the view that it was the wrong decision.

03:41:47.720 --> 03:41:51.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, absolutely. And like you said, we still have to do what we have to do, even if there's

03:41:51.960 --> 03:41:57.560
[Amit Varma]: a, it seems futile. The dharma of the wolf is to howl at the moon. How's that for a line?

03:41:57.560 --> 03:41:58.560
[Guest]: Dharma?

03:41:58.560 --> 03:42:00.560
[Amit Varma]: Of the wolf is to howl at the moon.

03:42:00.560 --> 03:42:01.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:42:01.560 --> 03:42:04.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Right. So, let's get back to your

03:42:04.600 --> 03:42:11.840
[Guest]: Or in the way Bellow puts it. Bellow writes about that dog who's looking up about what

03:42:11.840 --> 03:42:16.760
[Guest]: is he thinking? And, you know, he's, you know, he's ruminating on the limitations of the

03:42:16.760 --> 03:42:22.000
[Guest]: canine condition and asking the God to open the universe a little more.

03:42:22.000 --> 03:42:27.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, actually, dogs behave with a lot more. I think dogs are perhaps less self delusional

03:42:27.200 --> 03:42:31.560
[Amit Varma]: than humans in the sense that no dog would really do that. Right. So let's get back to

03:42:31.560 --> 03:42:37.320
[Amit Varma]: your sort of personal story. And what I know of your past is really from when you joined

03:42:37.320 --> 03:42:43.040
[Amit Varma]: NIPFP in 2011. And, you know, worked with the finance ministry after that eventually

03:42:43.040 --> 03:42:48.320
[Amit Varma]: joined Carnegie in 2018. But get, bring me to a sense of your journey in the sense that

03:42:48.320 --> 03:42:53.920
[Amit Varma]: what was your early conception of yourself and what brought you to NIPFP to begin with?

03:42:53.920 --> 03:42:58.200
[Amit Varma]: And just give me a sense of, you know, how did you look at yourself and the things you

03:42:58.200 --> 03:43:00.600
[Amit Varma]: wanted to do and so on and so forth?

03:43:00.600 --> 03:43:05.800
[Guest]: Yeah, so I actually didn't have a plan to get into the policy space. I just met this

03:43:05.800 --> 03:43:13.560
[Guest]: person, who was at NIPFP, he was a professor at NIPFP, Ajay, you know, that we were common

03:43:13.560 --> 03:43:18.320
[Guest]: friends. And he had come to a conference that I'd organized in my previous job, I'd helped

03:43:18.320 --> 03:43:25.240
[Guest]: organize and on financial system reforms. And at that time, a commission was being set

03:43:25.240 --> 03:43:29.240
[Guest]: up, Financial Sector Legislative Reforms Commission, and they were looking for researchers to work

03:43:29.240 --> 03:43:35.520
[Guest]: on that. And he made me an offer to come and join and work for the commission. It was two

03:43:35.520 --> 03:43:40.120
[Guest]: year commission, so a good amount of time to work on something. Usually policy work

03:43:40.120 --> 03:43:44.360
[Guest]: often gets done in very short period of time. And it's not very satisfying, because it's

03:43:44.360 --> 03:43:48.800
[Guest]: very short turnaround time, but this was a two year thing. So I thought it'd be interesting

03:43:48.800 --> 03:43:53.080
[Guest]: to do it for two years and then come back and do work, go into private sector or whatever

03:43:53.080 --> 03:43:59.880
[Guest]: it was, microfinance or anything that I mean, whatever the experience at that time working

03:43:59.880 --> 03:44:07.000
[Guest]: on. So I joined in 2011, basically, National Institute of Public Finance and Policy, which

03:44:07.000 --> 03:44:15.760
[Guest]: is a, I mean, basically a policy research shop. But it's an autonomous body promoted

03:44:15.760 --> 03:44:21.480
[Guest]: by the government. So it's, you work mainly with the government, closely with the government,

03:44:21.480 --> 03:44:26.520
[Guest]: and you do some research also, I mean, of your own. And I stayed there for almost eight

03:44:26.520 --> 03:44:33.960
[Guest]: years. And the main work there was to do policy research. I worked on different, I mean, projects,

03:44:33.960 --> 03:44:40.080
[Guest]: I worked with different ministries and departments and government agencies. And I really enjoyed

03:44:40.080 --> 03:44:47.680
[Guest]: that work. So what I had thought I'd do for two years, I ended up doing for eight years.

03:44:47.680 --> 03:44:52.680
[Amit Varma]: And so give me a sense of the insides of the beast. How does government work? Like, you

03:44:52.680 --> 03:44:56.480
[Amit Varma]: know, NIPFP, of course, worked closely with the finance ministry, you were a consultant

03:44:56.480 --> 03:45:01.600
[Guest]: for the finance ministry, for a short period, for a short period later on. So how does government

03:45:01.600 --> 03:45:07.120
[Amit Varma]: work? Because the general sense that you have from the outside is of, you know, very sclerotic,

03:45:07.120 --> 03:45:11.960
[Amit Varma]: very slow, bureaucratic, a lot of discussion, not much gets done, committee by committee,

03:45:11.960 --> 03:45:16.440
[Amit Varma]: all of that. But give me a sense from the inside of how it works. And how was it like,

03:45:16.440 --> 03:45:21.920
[Amit Varma]: what were your expectations of it going in? And what did you discover once you were there,

03:45:21.920 --> 03:45:25.160
[Amit Varma]: which was different from what you had expected?

03:45:25.160 --> 03:45:29.200
[Guest]: So I actually didn't have a very clearly formed view of what the government would be, you

03:45:29.200 --> 03:45:35.480
[Guest]: know, there were some stereotypes, but I mean, not much of a hard view as such. And when

03:45:35.480 --> 03:45:40.160
[Guest]: I had a bit of a soft landing, because I worked for a commission, not directly with a ministry

03:45:40.160 --> 03:45:45.240
[Guest]: or department or agency of government work with a commission, which was an expert body,

03:45:45.240 --> 03:45:52.040
[Guest]: set up under a former Supreme Court judge. And we had a very good leading economist,

03:45:52.040 --> 03:45:58.360
[Guest]: former regulators, experts, and a good bunch of researchers working together, mostly lawyers

03:45:58.360 --> 03:46:03.520
[Guest]: and economists, I was an outsider, I'm neither a lawyer nor an economist, a bit of an odd

03:46:03.520 --> 03:46:07.800
[Guest]: one out there. But I really enjoyed working and learned a lot from these lawyers, and

03:46:07.800 --> 03:46:13.280
[Guest]: economists and the regulators and the civil servants and also the judge who was leading

03:46:13.280 --> 03:46:19.160
[Guest]: it. And it was a soft landing, because although it was work for a government policy research,

03:46:19.160 --> 03:46:24.840
[Guest]: I mean, reform project, it wasn't in the heart of the beast, so to speak, you know, that

03:46:24.840 --> 03:46:29.760
[Guest]: you're not actually changing policy immediately, it's just research and analysis and presenting

03:46:29.760 --> 03:46:33.840
[Guest]: a set of ideas that may work, you know, that was the thing. And it was two years, so two

03:46:33.840 --> 03:46:39.000
[Guest]: years is a good time to do this, you know, it's a right amount of time to think about

03:46:39.000 --> 03:46:45.800
[Guest]: a problem and a set of problems. And I worked on a couple of areas intensively in that collaborated

03:46:45.800 --> 03:46:50.240
[Guest]: with some people and learned a lot from them. And some of those people had been doing policy

03:46:50.240 --> 03:46:57.400
[Guest]: research for years earlier. And then actually, after that, I had a more direct interaction.

03:46:57.400 --> 03:47:01.680
[Guest]: So again, my role was very small, to be very, very clear, it's a research policy researcher,

03:47:01.680 --> 03:47:04.720
[Guest]: right? You're not a decision maker, you're not an IAS officer, you're not a politician,

03:47:04.720 --> 03:47:09.600
[Guest]: you didn't need to get elected, nor did you crack a difficult exam many years ago. So

03:47:09.600 --> 03:47:16.200
[Guest]: you are here to provide analysis. And so when the commission submitted its report, it became

03:47:16.200 --> 03:47:20.520
[Guest]: about implementation. So parts of it was taken and implemented in some ways, inflation targeting

03:47:20.520 --> 03:47:25.440
[Guest]: grew out of it in some ways. There was a reform of capital controls that was done where powers

03:47:25.440 --> 03:47:30.480
[Guest]: are divided between government and RBI. Some reforms have come out of that process. And

03:47:30.480 --> 03:47:36.400
[Guest]: it was basically done by bureaucrats. So joint secretary is a key rank and joint secretaries

03:47:36.400 --> 03:47:40.080
[Guest]: are the ones who drive the world because they had a division and then secretaries have to

03:47:40.080 --> 03:47:45.600
[Guest]: support ministers to support many things go to the cabinet for approval. And one of the

03:47:45.600 --> 03:47:49.760
[Guest]: main things about government is that it's a relatively low capacity organization. It

03:47:49.760 --> 03:47:54.920
[Guest]: really struggles. It's a very difficult thing to do things because you don't have the kind

03:47:54.920 --> 03:48:01.080
[Guest]: of capacity. They are smart officers inside who really know a lot or at least have the

03:48:01.080 --> 03:48:04.680
[Guest]: capacity to quickly pick up because they have moved from one department to another which

03:48:04.680 --> 03:48:10.480
[Guest]: completely unrelated subjectivity, they quickly pick up. But the below director level, I mean,

03:48:10.480 --> 03:48:13.880
[Guest]: bureaucracy is very, very weak. I mean, in terms of just a number of people also the

03:48:13.880 --> 03:48:18.040
[Guest]: kind of quality that you get in terms of training that you provide them the kind of expertise

03:48:18.040 --> 03:48:23.200
[Guest]: that they have. So it's a constant struggle to do anything. So they do value outsiders

03:48:23.200 --> 03:48:28.280
[Guest]: like us who are working in a semi-sarkari government kind of think tank and helping

03:48:28.280 --> 03:48:34.080
[Guest]: them out. So they did value and there was a lot of kind of interest in from secretary,

03:48:34.080 --> 03:48:40.560
[Guest]: joint secretary, minister to kind of get help and get some support, research support and

03:48:40.560 --> 03:48:44.960
[Guest]: analytical support to push things forward a little bit.

03:48:44.960 --> 03:48:52.320
[Guest]: And so one thing that happened when I was working in this area, I will talk more about

03:48:52.320 --> 03:48:57.640
[Guest]: other things that I did, is that I developed a lot of empathy for people who work in government,

03:48:57.640 --> 03:49:04.480
[Guest]: whether it's the ministers or the IAS officers that I really felt that it's a very difficult

03:49:04.480 --> 03:49:08.640
[Guest]: situation and they are taking, partly they are responsible for it because government

03:49:08.640 --> 03:49:13.760
[Guest]: of India has taken on too many responsibilities and for us, for our stage of development,

03:49:13.760 --> 03:49:20.040
[Guest]: it is trying to take on too many things and more things than it should. I mean, we should

03:49:20.040 --> 03:49:25.160
[Guest]: have a much smaller things of set of issues that government is trying to solve and others

03:49:25.160 --> 03:49:30.760
[Guest]: you should just leave to civil society and market organize markets and accept it.

03:49:30.760 --> 03:49:35.720
[Guest]: But some for reasons which I don't fully understand, our democracy makes many, many demands and

03:49:35.720 --> 03:49:40.040
[Guest]: for reasons that again, I don't understand, our political leadership is not able to raise

03:49:40.040 --> 03:49:47.000
[Guest]: those demands. So Ministry of Agriculture is a state subject, it has 30 joint secretaries.

03:49:47.000 --> 03:49:50.960
[Guest]: So why should a government of India have 30 joint secretaries working in a ministry which

03:49:50.960 --> 03:49:55.280
[Guest]: is a state subject because, but still they are not going to raise these demands. So,

03:49:55.280 --> 03:50:00.600
[Guest]: I mean, again, as I said democracy, so there are things that are done which our intellectual

03:50:00.600 --> 03:50:08.280
[Guest]: worldview may find a little odd or inefficient, but allocative efficiency may appear bad,

03:50:08.280 --> 03:50:13.560
[Guest]: but it is done. So it's very difficult because you got a small number of IAS officers and

03:50:13.560 --> 03:50:17.280
[Guest]: a small number of other civil servants, revenue services, audit accounts and all that who

03:50:17.280 --> 03:50:22.320
[Guest]: have to do a lot of these things and the bureaucracy, low bureaucracy is very, very weak. Also,

03:50:22.320 --> 03:50:27.880
[Guest]: I mean, in the 90s, there was a drop in the hiring of IAS officers to the UPSC process.

03:50:27.880 --> 03:50:33.280
[Guest]: So again, that middle bureaucracy is very, very small and same number of same officers

03:50:33.280 --> 03:50:39.280
[Guest]: basically going around and doing things. So that was a one big, I mean, change is becoming

03:50:39.280 --> 03:50:41.120
[Guest]: more empathetic and understanding of the constraints.

03:50:41.120 --> 03:50:45.080
[Guest]: So one of the most important things in government is to understand the constraints within which

03:50:45.080 --> 03:50:49.000
[Guest]: things are done. James Q. Wilson, the great political scientist has a great book on bureaucracy,

03:50:49.000 --> 03:50:53.560
[Guest]: it's worth reading, everybody should read it. So his whole frame is to understand government

03:50:53.560 --> 03:50:57.640
[Guest]: through constraints, you know, that there are things you should never compare a government

03:50:57.640 --> 03:51:01.080
[Guest]: organization with a private organization and don't have a simplistic thing that some private

03:51:01.080 --> 03:51:06.000
[Guest]: CEO will come and transform government, cannot be done because they can add value for sure,

03:51:06.000 --> 03:51:09.720
[Guest]: but for that they have to first be empathetic towards the situation of the government. Government

03:51:09.720 --> 03:51:15.000
[Guest]: cannot hire or fire, government cannot procure freely from wherever, it has to follow due

03:51:15.000 --> 03:51:20.240
[Guest]: process. Government cannot just decide without following a very complex set of laws, there

03:51:20.240 --> 03:51:25.720
[Guest]: is also jurisprudence. And there are many things that the government is held to, and

03:51:25.720 --> 03:51:30.040
[Guest]: the government doesn't really choose its own priorities. There is a complex democratic

03:51:30.040 --> 03:51:33.900
[Guest]: process through which priorities are chosen, they can change. You start working on a policy

03:51:33.900 --> 03:51:38.840
[Guest]: project and then government changes and suddenly the priorities have changed. These are very

03:51:38.840 --> 03:51:42.560
[Guest]: significant constraints and you see that when you actually work in the government, you see

03:51:42.560 --> 03:51:47.880
[Guest]: how things happen. So, in fact, some of the most satisfying work I did was this commission

03:51:47.880 --> 03:51:51.040
[Guest]: called Expenditure Management Commission. I was coordinating research for the whole

03:51:51.040 --> 03:51:55.880
[Guest]: commission which was again two years and we looked at the entire central government expenditure

03:51:55.880 --> 03:51:59.880
[Guest]: and trying to understand how its operational efficiency can be improved, not allocative.

03:51:59.880 --> 03:52:04.120
[Guest]: Allocative is political business, but in a way can we do a little better implementation

03:52:04.120 --> 03:52:09.080
[Guest]: and trying to get more bang for the buck, so to speak. The report is not public, so

03:52:09.080 --> 03:52:14.040
[Guest]: I can't talk anything about it at all. It's still confidential, but I am talking about

03:52:14.040 --> 03:52:18.760
[Guest]: the process. So, there the commission was basically led by a senior economist and also

03:52:18.760 --> 03:52:24.280
[Guest]: a former public servant. It had another economist as a member, it had some couple of bureaucrats,

03:52:24.280 --> 03:52:28.600
[Guest]: one serving, one retired as members and then the team, research team was basically, I mean

03:52:28.600 --> 03:52:34.600
[Guest]: the staff was mostly all civil servants and what I really enjoyed about working in that

03:52:34.600 --> 03:52:41.520
[Guest]: commission was that I could have a sense of where the binding constraints are. See, that's

03:52:41.520 --> 03:52:45.760
[Guest]: one of the most important things in policy is that you may have some abstract notion

03:52:45.760 --> 03:52:50.000
[Guest]: of here is a system and there it should be, but what is the next step?

03:52:50.000 --> 03:52:55.040
[Guest]: See, you can have some UK is doing this, US is doing thing that, but you can't go from

03:52:55.040 --> 03:53:00.920
[Guest]: here to some of that and maybe that is not the right path for you because your path is

03:53:00.920 --> 03:53:05.480
[Guest]: different and therefore you can take a different kind of optimal path, but there is a next

03:53:05.480 --> 03:53:09.600
[Guest]: step and that is about easing the binding constraints that are most important right

03:53:09.600 --> 03:53:14.200
[Guest]: now and people who are in the thick of things, these are civil servants and if they are reflective

03:53:14.200 --> 03:53:19.280
[Guest]: and thoughtful and if you work closely with them, they know that very well. I mean, if

03:53:19.280 --> 03:53:22.720
[Guest]: they get the opportunity to reflect on it and like which we did for two years, we got

03:53:22.720 --> 03:53:27.880
[Guest]: an opportunity to reflect and think about what can be done to improve government procurement,

03:53:27.880 --> 03:53:34.000
[Guest]: expenditure efficiency in health and education, expenditure efficiency, subsidies, all subsidies,

03:53:34.000 --> 03:53:38.840
[Guest]: all of that stuff that we looked at, public enterprise, autonomous body, everything, defence,

03:53:38.840 --> 03:53:44.280
[Guest]: all of that and then you actually have a sense that you are talking to something which matters

03:53:44.280 --> 03:53:48.520
[Guest]: now and not painting some, you know, most of the policy work is basically best practice

03:53:48.520 --> 03:53:53.680
[Guest]: type. Hey, look at this UK, US did it and do five countries study and then why does

03:53:53.680 --> 03:53:57.120
[Guest]: India do this? There are many things that these countries do that we do not do, you

03:53:57.120 --> 03:54:03.240
[Guest]: know, we are in the bottom third in the world in per capita income and in almost all measures

03:54:03.240 --> 03:54:07.560
[Guest]: we are, I mean, in the bottom half in the world. So, why compare only with Frontier?

03:54:07.560 --> 03:54:10.440
[Guest]: And not even compare with others, look at your own path and say, okay, where can we

03:54:10.440 --> 03:54:15.720
[Guest]: go next? And that is where I think this, because these civil servants, the good ones who are

03:54:15.720 --> 03:54:20.560
[Guest]: reflective and have opportunity to think about these things, work with researchers closely,

03:54:20.560 --> 03:54:25.600
[Guest]: they can identify the binding constraints and find an optimal next step, which is what

03:54:25.600 --> 03:54:29.600
[Guest]: matters. Ultimately, you have to evolve to the next step, then the next step after and

03:54:29.600 --> 03:54:34.120
[Guest]: then in a generation or two, many, many problems will get solved. If you try to say that the

03:54:34.120 --> 03:54:38.400
[Guest]: ultimate objective, which anyway you cannot say, right, you do not, you cannot see what

03:54:38.400 --> 03:54:41.680
[Guest]: would be the right institutional design, you know, it is not a, again, you will fall for

03:54:41.680 --> 03:54:47.680
[Guest]: the planning and top down design kind of a trap. So, yeah, the understanding of constraints,

03:54:47.680 --> 03:54:53.960
[Guest]: empathy for difficulty of capacity and political demands and all of that. The most disappointing

03:54:53.960 --> 03:54:59.120
[Guest]: was that work that I did on the reform of financial resolution, where for three years

03:54:59.120 --> 03:55:03.360
[Guest]: I was at it as a researcher only, it was a small role, but I was really at the thick

03:55:03.360 --> 03:55:08.960
[Guest]: of it, in the thick of it, working on it almost continuously. And at the last moment when

03:55:08.960 --> 03:55:13.440
[Guest]: it had to be passed, it got withdrawn from the parliament and it was a disappointing

03:55:13.440 --> 03:55:17.920
[Guest]: moment, but it was a really instructive moment on how political economy works. It was very

03:55:17.920 --> 03:55:23.520
[Guest]: humbling that, okay, maybe it will happen later. It is, I think it is an important reform

03:55:23.520 --> 03:55:28.760
[Guest]: to pursue, but it did not get pursued. I did some work on infrastructure a little bit,

03:55:28.760 --> 03:55:33.640
[Guest]: but most of my work was on financial sector reform and regulation and financial reform

03:55:33.640 --> 03:55:40.080
[Guest]: and on public finance. So, my subject matter expertise, such as it is in these areas, but

03:55:40.080 --> 03:55:44.720
[Guest]: there I have a lot of meta kind of insights on how to work with government and what I

03:55:44.720 --> 03:55:49.720
[Guest]: did, what worked and what didn't work, which I just talked about mostly. I didn't get into

03:55:49.720 --> 03:55:54.080
[Guest]: the subject matter as much. But yeah, I mean, government is a completely different creature

03:55:54.080 --> 03:56:00.520
[Guest]: from companies and it will always be, it is a permanent fact, always very different from,

03:56:00.520 --> 03:56:05.200
[Guest]: you can bring a little bit of so-called private sector experience into it, have a little more

03:56:05.200 --> 03:56:10.720
[Guest]: alignment of incentives and all of that, but not a whole lot can be done on that front.

03:56:10.720 --> 03:56:15.400
[Amit Varma]: So, you mentioned James Q. Wilson and we were talking about virtue earlier and one book

03:56:15.400 --> 03:56:19.880
[Amit Varma]: I remember reading of Wilson was a book called The Moral Sense and I read this around the

03:56:19.880 --> 03:56:24.280
[Amit Varma]: same time as A Moral Animal by Wright though I liked Wright's book more because it seemed

03:56:24.280 --> 03:56:30.440
[Amit Varma]: more right to me. Just kidding. And, you know, again about state capacity, I have an episode

03:56:30.440 --> 03:56:35.240
[Amit Varma]: with Karthik Mulyitharan on this and I've discussed this so many times actually, completely,

03:56:35.240 --> 03:56:38.940
[Amit Varma]: I mean, Fukuyama gave an interesting frame of looking at the state, which is a frame

03:56:38.940 --> 03:56:44.080
[Amit Varma]: of scope and strength. And with the Indian state, it's the scope is too much, the strength

03:56:44.080 --> 03:56:49.200
[Amit Varma]: is too little. We do too many things badly while we should do a few things really well,

03:56:49.200 --> 03:56:54.140
[Amit Varma]: which kind of becomes a problem. So, it is simultaneously the case that the state is,

03:56:54.140 --> 03:56:59.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, in too many places, but it is also incredibly weak as you pointed out. So, here's

03:56:59.880 --> 03:57:06.560
[Amit Varma]: a question. It strikes me that when you are in this policy field, your mindset has to

03:57:06.560 --> 03:57:13.120
[Amit Varma]: be different in two fundamental ways from anything else you did before. One is that

03:57:13.120 --> 03:57:18.960
[Amit Varma]: any change, if it happens, will be incremental, it will be a tiny thing. You know, you can

03:57:18.960 --> 03:57:24.120
[Amit Varma]: aim for the moon, but things move really slowly and you'll just get incremental and you won't

03:57:24.120 --> 03:57:29.000
[Amit Varma]: get big moon shots working out. That's number one. And even those incremental change at

03:57:29.000 --> 03:57:33.720
[Amit Varma]: scale can make a huge difference to people, but in ways that cannot be traced back to

03:57:33.720 --> 03:57:37.720
[Guest]: you or quantified sometimes. Yeah, that's a good part of it, that you never get any

03:57:37.720 --> 03:57:44.000
[Amit Varma]: credit for it. Yeah. And the second, which also ties in with the credit thing, is that

03:57:44.000 --> 03:57:49.480
[Amit Varma]: your rhythm of looking at what you are doing and why you're doing has to slow down a lot

03:57:49.480 --> 03:57:52.960
[Amit Varma]: because you're really playing the long game, that you may work on something for three years

03:57:52.960 --> 03:57:58.080
[Amit Varma]: and nothing may happen. And sometimes you'll work on something for 15-20 years and then

03:57:58.080 --> 03:58:03.440
[Amit Varma]: change will happen. And, you know, and when it does, sometimes, you know, change can happen

03:58:03.440 --> 03:58:07.720
[Amit Varma]: really fast and in dramatic ways. But by and large, you're playing the long game, there's

03:58:07.720 --> 03:58:12.480
[Amit Varma]: no immediate gratification, there's no payoff. If you're working in a company, for example,

03:58:12.480 --> 03:58:16.520
[Amit Varma]: and you implement something, that payoff is visible. In the next quarter, sales will go

03:58:16.520 --> 03:58:21.040
[Amit Varma]: up or sales will go down, shit will happen, new branches will open, you see the payoff.

03:58:21.040 --> 03:58:26.160
[Amit Varma]: Here you don't see a payoff, there is no credit, there is no causality that can be kind of

03:58:26.160 --> 03:58:31.840
[Amit Varma]: given to you. Your validation doesn't come from measurable results, right? So at one

03:58:31.840 --> 03:58:39.120
[Amit Varma]: level, you have to sort of be internally driven. Yet, I would imagine given human nature, that

03:58:39.120 --> 03:58:44.520
[Amit Varma]: most people in any field are not internally driven. They are ticking boxes going through

03:58:44.520 --> 03:58:50.080
[Amit Varma]: the motions within the set group that they are. And some people in every field will be

03:58:50.080 --> 03:58:54.720
[Amit Varma]: internally driven and will be dynamic. Sometimes that is just because of incentives. Like if

03:58:54.720 --> 03:58:58.840
[Amit Varma]: you're the if you're the founder of a startup, you're going to be way more driven than somebody

03:58:58.840 --> 03:59:03.200
[Amit Varma]: three rungs down the ladder. And sometimes that's just the kind of person you are, that

03:59:03.200 --> 03:59:06.720
[Amit Varma]: whatever you do, if you're doing something you love, you're driven by it, even if you're,

03:59:06.720 --> 03:59:12.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, not too high up or there isn't gratification. So you know what this change in mindset, am

03:59:12.080 --> 03:59:16.800
[Amit Varma]: I sort of characterizing it accurately is are there things you'd like to add to it?

03:59:16.800 --> 03:59:23.000
[Amit Varma]: And what was the experience for you coming from, you know, a private world to the world

03:59:23.000 --> 03:59:27.400
[Amit Varma]: of where you're working with government and change happens at a glacial pace, and there

03:59:27.400 --> 03:59:31.680
[Amit Varma]: are all these obstacles, and, and so on and so forth?

03:59:31.680 --> 03:59:37.920
[Guest]: Yeah, so two, three factual things is that one is that when it happens, the impact is

03:59:37.920 --> 03:59:43.240
[Guest]: huge. And I wouldn't say that I'm completely indifferent to the impact that obviously we

03:59:43.240 --> 03:59:47.760
[Guest]: do this because we want things to change and we want things to improve and subject to democratic

03:59:47.760 --> 03:59:53.400
[Guest]: agreement and consensus building, all of that the best possible path that is possible. Sometimes

03:59:53.400 --> 03:59:59.560
[Guest]: the second best, but at least when it happens, it's the impact is very large. And it's it

03:59:59.560 --> 04:00:04.080
[Guest]: can be quite satisfying to see that impact that okay, you had a small contribution to

04:00:04.080 --> 04:00:10.520
[Guest]: your society, even if nobody ever knows about it, you know, and it's, I mean, you're part

04:00:10.520 --> 04:00:11.520
[Amit Varma]: of the society.

04:00:11.520 --> 04:00:13.240
[Amit Varma]: Can you give examples of this from your own work?

04:00:13.240 --> 04:00:17.760
[Guest]: No, I don't want to attribute anything to myself because everything I did was in teams.

04:00:17.760 --> 04:00:21.360
[Amit Varma]: Can you give examples of this from your team's work?

04:00:21.360 --> 04:00:29.640
[Guest]: Yeah, I can. I mean, again, the credit should go to politicians. 100% of it, 0% should come

04:00:29.640 --> 04:00:35.040
[Guest]: to anybody else. But there's been a cleanup of capital controls regulation in India. There

04:00:35.040 --> 04:00:40.800
[Guest]: has been, I mean, introduction of inflation targeting in India. There has been a push

04:00:40.800 --> 04:00:45.600
[Guest]: for consumer protection regulation improvements in finance in India. There's been quite a

04:00:45.600 --> 04:00:50.440
[Guest]: bit of expenditure management reform in the last several years, a few years since we worked.

04:00:50.440 --> 04:00:55.640
[Guest]: I can't say anything specific, but the report is confidential. Raja Chailiah founded NIPFP,

04:00:55.640 --> 04:01:02.200
[Guest]: you know, he was our founder. And he was a great tax economist, public finance specialist

04:01:02.200 --> 04:01:07.920
[Guest]: and special expertise in tax. He worked for many years, you know, on rationalizing our

04:01:07.920 --> 04:01:13.400
[Guest]: tax system. It was only in the late 90s that we actually got to this 30% tax rate that

04:01:13.400 --> 04:01:17.600
[Guest]: we now have, right, under the third front government, the UDF government that we had.

04:01:17.600 --> 04:01:21.920
[Guest]: So that's the other part of it that you have to work for many years. And then there'll

04:01:21.920 --> 04:01:27.680
[Guest]: be a moment suddenly, when things fall in place, human beings have tried everything

04:01:27.680 --> 04:01:33.240
[Guest]: else before doing the right thing, so to speak, you know, or finding a optimal kind of a solution

04:01:33.240 --> 04:01:36.720
[Guest]: that works, at least for a particular kind of social welfare function. Social welfare

04:01:36.720 --> 04:01:40.600
[Guest]: function also changes, right? People have different views about what should be the social

04:01:40.600 --> 04:01:45.440
[Guest]: welfare function. And then you have a particular analysis, making, assuming a certain kind

04:01:45.440 --> 04:01:50.400
[Guest]: of social function, and then suddenly these things align and it works. Hopefully, it's

04:01:50.400 --> 04:01:54.560
[Guest]: a good, it's a good thing it will work because some of the reforms we did in 90s, the thinking

04:01:54.560 --> 04:02:01.240
[Guest]: goes back to 70s also, right? There were committees set up in the late 70s, 80s, people like Mr.

04:02:01.240 --> 04:02:04.400
[Guest]: Ahluwalia and all they were preparing proposals for reform.

04:02:04.400 --> 04:02:09.360
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode with Montague where he talks about how from the late 70s.

04:02:09.360 --> 04:02:15.320
[Guest]: Yeah, late 70s itself, I mean, the work started and then the payoff for the society not for

04:02:15.320 --> 04:02:19.560
[Guest]: the person who worked on it, you're here to serve, happened many, many years later. I

04:02:19.560 --> 04:02:24.520
[Guest]: mean, some of them may have passed away in the process. Raja Chalaiya worked on tax reform

04:02:24.520 --> 04:02:30.280
[Guest]: for many years, you know, and things got better gradually. But the genuine kind of settlement

04:02:30.280 --> 04:02:34.560
[Guest]: of the current relatively better tax regime that we have on the direct tax side came in

04:02:34.560 --> 04:02:40.080
[Guest]: the late 90s. And I think that's the way it is that many of the things that we work on

04:02:40.080 --> 04:02:44.040
[Guest]: will not never get implemented. Some that will get implemented may have a huge impact,

04:02:44.040 --> 04:02:48.480
[Guest]: some will have a smaller impact, but generally you will have a significant kind of impact.

04:02:48.480 --> 04:02:52.440
[Guest]: And then the timing may mismatch that you may have done something and it's there in

04:02:52.440 --> 04:02:57.040
[Guest]: the file system. And then five years later, you are doing something else, but it gets

04:02:57.040 --> 04:03:02.040
[Guest]: drafted. Even now I get calls from people I worked with, okay, why was this drafted?

04:03:02.040 --> 04:03:07.280
[Guest]: We are now pushing it through to the system, putting up a cabinet or whatever. And then

04:03:07.280 --> 04:03:12.200
[Guest]: we need a clarification of this because institutional memory is required to interpret why it was

04:03:12.200 --> 04:03:18.400
[Guest]: done. Even now, like literally last week, so this is a part of that, the way the system

04:03:18.400 --> 04:03:23.320
[Guest]: works. And again, it's a democratic system. And there are many people who can say no to

04:03:23.320 --> 04:03:28.560
[Guest]: something and then can literally stop it from happening. And that's good because many mistakes

04:03:28.560 --> 04:03:32.800
[Guest]: don't get made because people like me may recommend something very bad also and harmful

04:03:32.800 --> 04:03:39.040
[Guest]: and then it doesn't get done. Thank God. If it hadn't been done, we would have been feeling

04:03:39.040 --> 04:03:44.640
[Guest]: much more guilty. So I have faith that, okay, at least now, I mean, if I was living in fifties

04:03:44.640 --> 04:03:49.000
[Guest]: and sixties and seventies, it would be very, very frustrating because hardly any good ideas

04:03:49.000 --> 04:03:55.400
[Guest]: get accepted and bad ideas are taken up very easily. But now we're in a different kind

04:03:55.400 --> 04:04:01.240
[Guest]: of a polity since the nineties at least. And at least the elite consensus was shifting.

04:04:01.240 --> 04:04:07.840
[Guest]: And now I think the shelf life is, I mean, the life from thinking about working on some

04:04:07.840 --> 04:04:12.440
[Guest]: analysis and bringing out something which may work and that being heard is, I mean,

04:04:12.440 --> 04:04:15.760
[Guest]: a shorter period of time. And whether it gets done or not is something which cannot be controlled.

04:04:15.760 --> 04:04:21.120
[Guest]: It's left to the democratic processes. And that's the way to think about it. And in fact,

04:04:21.120 --> 04:04:26.400
[Guest]: I was at eight years, I never got paid for anything. It was the best time of my life

04:04:26.400 --> 04:04:31.440
[Guest]: because a lot of things get got done because we were just enjoying the work, you know,

04:04:31.440 --> 04:04:35.880
[Guest]: it is just so much and it was a good place, a good team, a good set of people to learn

04:04:35.880 --> 04:04:41.160
[Guest]: from work with. Most of them were motivated intrinsically because they were enjoying that

04:04:41.160 --> 04:04:47.120
[Guest]: work. And we had good leaders in the team who were so kind of, who kept us motivated

04:04:47.120 --> 04:04:51.920
[Guest]: because they also were doing it for that reason. And I think that's what it is that, you know,

04:04:51.920 --> 04:04:58.040
[Guest]: it's like, why does a soldier fight? He fights for his buddies in some senses. So similarly,

04:04:58.040 --> 04:05:04.640
[Guest]: I mean, nation is there, but the immediate impulse comes from being a part of a particular

04:05:04.640 --> 04:05:12.440
[Guest]: team. So, and going through that process, we are overestimating like some of the least

04:05:12.440 --> 04:05:18.360
[Guest]: most dangerous professions pay very little, firemen and all, for example. But they are

04:05:18.360 --> 04:05:22.520
[Guest]: very dangerous. You put your life on the line. Soldiers don't get much money, but they go

04:05:22.520 --> 04:05:28.800
[Guest]: and put a line, overestimate the power of material incentives in human nature. I mean,

04:05:28.800 --> 04:05:34.360
[Guest]: people find meaning in a variety of ways. And the question is whether you find meaning

04:05:34.360 --> 04:05:38.880
[Guest]: or not. And it was meaningful. The work is very meaningful. Working with government and

04:05:38.880 --> 04:05:42.960
[Guest]: policy reform in a lower middle income country is a very meaningful thing. And they'll never

04:05:42.960 --> 04:05:46.160
[Guest]: have any shortage of meaning while you're doing that.

04:05:46.160 --> 04:05:51.160
[Amit Varma]: So you know, earlier you had mentioned about how at various points in time, you've changed

04:05:51.160 --> 04:05:58.720
[Amit Varma]: your mind about various things. So take me through some of this because my just as an

04:05:58.720 --> 04:06:04.280
[Amit Varma]: outsider from outside, my thinking about government has also changed from painting broad brush

04:06:04.280 --> 04:06:10.040
[Amit Varma]: strokes like how dysfunctional it is, to still thinking it is dysfunctional, but understanding

04:06:10.040 --> 04:06:13.840
[Amit Varma]: the dysfunction much better understanding the incentives that work understanding the

04:06:13.840 --> 04:06:18.640
[Amit Varma]: pressures that people inside go through and the ways in which they fight them, you know,

04:06:18.640 --> 04:06:22.960
[Amit Varma]: so, you know, as someone who was an insider, you know, you began with a commission, but

04:06:22.960 --> 04:06:27.520
[Amit Varma]: then you work much more closely with them, you even consulted for the Ministry of Finance

04:06:27.520 --> 04:06:31.280
[Amit Varma]: for a while, though, obviously, your work there is confidential, so we won't talk about

04:06:31.280 --> 04:06:35.680
[Amit Varma]: it. But, you know, what was your sense of the innards of government? And what are the

04:06:35.680 --> 04:06:44.440
[Amit Varma]: ways in which you changed your mind, both about the state, and also about broad ideological

04:06:44.440 --> 04:06:48.960
[Amit Varma]: ideas that you might have held, you know, before you actually got into the belly of

04:06:48.960 --> 04:06:49.960
[Amit Varma]: the beast?

04:06:49.960 --> 04:06:55.960
[Guest]: Yeah, so I partly answered this question in terms of what I said earlier about having

04:06:55.960 --> 04:07:01.720
[Guest]: some empathy for people to work in a very difficult situation and with lots of constraints,

04:07:01.720 --> 04:07:06.360
[Guest]: and understanding of those constraints before making any recommendations and, and expecting

04:07:06.360 --> 04:07:12.640
[Guest]: things to change. And, and that's absolutely essential for anybody who's working on policy

04:07:12.640 --> 04:07:18.160
[Guest]: to understand who you're working for or with, and who you're recommending to absolutely

04:07:18.160 --> 04:07:24.280
[Guest]: essential, there is no substitute for that. In fact, if you, you know, there's a famous

04:07:24.280 --> 04:07:29.240
[Guest]: quote that all happy families are alike and all unhappy families are different, unhappy

04:07:29.240 --> 04:07:35.040
[Guest]: for different reasons. And it's quite true that if you're working in developed countries,

04:07:35.040 --> 04:07:39.800
[Guest]: there is a certain commonality in which way the state works there. There are different

04:07:39.800 --> 04:07:45.400
[Guest]: institutional design choices they've made, different varieties of capitalism, different

04:07:45.400 --> 04:07:52.080
[Guest]: varieties of separation of power, or they have, but there is a certain, more or less

04:07:52.080 --> 04:07:57.680
[Guest]: formality to it. And it works in a particular way, there's high capacity in most of those

04:07:57.680 --> 04:08:03.680
[Guest]: states. And, but developing countries are all each one is different. I mean, there's

04:08:03.680 --> 04:08:09.800
[Guest]: a different dynamic in terms of level capacity, how it's utilized, how whether it's democratic

04:08:09.800 --> 04:08:14.960
[Guest]: or not most developing, many countries are not democratic. So that makes a difference.

04:08:14.960 --> 04:08:20.080
[Guest]: Some of them have a permanent civil service, other ones have a much more mix and match

04:08:20.080 --> 04:08:26.200
[Guest]: of permanent civil service with more of when hiring from outside. So there is a, when you

04:08:26.200 --> 04:08:30.400
[Guest]: understand who you're working with, and Indian state is a particular kind of creature and

04:08:30.400 --> 04:08:34.880
[Guest]: each within that each state has its own, there's a national level dynamic and there's a state

04:08:34.880 --> 04:08:40.440
[Guest]: level dynamic, subnational, and different agencies, if you're working with Reserve Bank

04:08:40.440 --> 04:08:43.680
[Guest]: of India, it's a particular kind of agency is very different from SEBI, for example.

04:08:43.680 --> 04:08:50.120
[Guest]: And so you need to understand who you're working for and working with and try to add value

04:08:50.120 --> 04:08:55.440
[Guest]: in that sense. And as I said that, it's very important to try to figure out the next step,

04:08:55.440 --> 04:08:59.520
[Guest]: you know, like, how do you evolve to the next step, how to do little better than you're

04:08:59.520 --> 04:09:05.000
[Guest]: doing earlier, because that, that's what growth is, you know, growth is about improving from

04:09:05.000 --> 04:09:10.640
[Guest]: where you are, you know, and development is something grander, and you want to get there,

04:09:10.640 --> 04:09:14.040
[Guest]: some kind of a state you want to get towards, and you that opinion about what that state

04:09:14.040 --> 04:09:18.040
[Guest]: is may also change over time, but you may have some kind of a lodestar in your mind

04:09:18.040 --> 04:09:22.880
[Guest]: and you work towards it. But growth is about getting from here to there, and then from

04:09:22.880 --> 04:09:29.560
[Guest]: there to there, and you know, a step at a time. And, and that's what I think is a big

04:09:29.560 --> 04:09:34.520
[Guest]: change that earlier I used to think much more in terms of best practices, I think much more

04:09:34.520 --> 04:09:40.040
[Guest]: about abstract notions of what rights should be preserved, you know, what kind of things

04:09:40.040 --> 04:09:44.480
[Guest]: should be pursued, but I now have much more of a sense of what is possible. And also about

04:09:44.480 --> 04:09:49.720
[Guest]: what is possible now, you know, in the next, given the political economy, given the way

04:09:49.720 --> 04:09:55.920
[Guest]: the institutions work, what would be an improvement over from where you are, like, somebody says,

04:09:55.920 --> 04:10:00.760
[Guest]: well, how should we improve tax enforcement, I look at more closely at where can we make

04:10:00.760 --> 04:10:05.960
[Guest]: some of the improvements now to the next step. And then I will not, there's a blueprint that

04:10:05.960 --> 04:10:10.520
[Guest]: you can actually decide, okay, in 20 years where you should be, that next step will then

04:10:10.520 --> 04:10:14.680
[Guest]: in a complex kind of way, I mean, there'll be interactions with other parts of the system

04:10:14.680 --> 04:10:21.280
[Guest]: and stakeholders will then reveal the next binding constraints and you then you go further.

04:10:21.280 --> 04:10:25.960
[Guest]: And I think that's the most important kind of realization I've had. The second is that

04:10:25.960 --> 04:10:32.960
[Guest]: earlier I used to take the de jure as de facto. What I mean by that is, I used to assume that

04:10:32.960 --> 04:10:39.840
[Guest]: whatever is written in the rule book and laws are, is what happens in reality and, but that's

04:10:39.840 --> 04:10:45.000
[Guest]: a very, very wrong assumption. I mean, it's completely wrong, in fact, more wrong than

04:10:45.000 --> 04:10:49.400
[Guest]: even I have fully fathomed till now, you know, I know intellectually, but I haven't fully

04:10:49.400 --> 04:10:57.880
[Guest]: taken grip on this kind of realization that, in fact, in developing countries like India,

04:10:57.880 --> 04:11:03.240
[Guest]: in most circumstances, laws are completely not descriptive of what actually goes on.

04:11:03.240 --> 04:11:09.000
[Guest]: And the way the executive implements the laws is very different from what the laws have

04:11:09.000 --> 04:11:15.120
[Guest]: written or intended. And the reality is shaped much more by decisions by politicians and

04:11:15.120 --> 04:11:19.640
[Guest]: civil servants and the order in which that decisions are taken is much more important

04:11:19.640 --> 04:11:24.520
[Guest]: than what's written in the text of the law. And the correspondence can be very, very weak

04:11:24.520 --> 04:11:29.320
[Guest]: between these two. And sometimes even very counterintuitive in some senses that you've

04:11:29.320 --> 04:11:32.800
[Guest]: written something in the rule book, but the reality is completely different from that.

04:11:32.800 --> 04:11:37.000
[Guest]: You already see that sometimes when you talk about rights, do we have this right? I mean,

04:11:37.000 --> 04:11:41.760
[Guest]: you've read a hundred, dozens of different rights into the constitution through jurisprudence,

04:11:41.760 --> 04:11:45.840
[Guest]: but do you actually have that right when you go and when the reality is very different.

04:11:45.840 --> 04:11:50.320
[Guest]: Similarly on the regulatory side also, similarly on the side of regulation of businesses, side

04:11:50.320 --> 04:11:56.920
[Guest]: of different types of delivery of schemes and welfare programs, implementation of projects,

04:11:56.920 --> 04:12:03.760
[Guest]: procurement, all of that, there is a lot more goes on in terms of informal decision making,

04:12:03.760 --> 04:12:08.840
[Guest]: use of discretion, deal making, which may be actually developmental in its purpose and

04:12:08.840 --> 04:12:16.160
[Guest]: may actually work towards improving things overall. But it's a hidden way in which the

04:12:16.160 --> 04:12:21.760
[Guest]: state works. And unless you understand that, if you just work on policy in terms of just

04:12:21.760 --> 04:12:26.600
[Guest]: saying change this law to that law and things will get better, unless you can first establish

04:12:26.600 --> 04:12:33.440
[Guest]: that law actually is the real framework for governing reality in actuality and not just

04:12:33.440 --> 04:12:39.120
[Guest]: a potentiality, then you are actually sparking up the wrong tree, you know, because what

04:12:39.120 --> 04:12:43.720
[Guest]: matters then is basically how the people who are actually taking the decisions define their

04:12:43.720 --> 04:12:49.360
[Guest]: worldview and what are the incentives that are shaping their behavior, what are the socialization

04:12:49.360 --> 04:12:53.280
[Guest]: that they have gone through, those are things that become much more important.

04:12:53.280 --> 04:12:58.000
[Guest]: And it's not about India only, whatever I have read about this kind of things, there

04:12:58.000 --> 04:13:02.760
[Guest]: are other countries also in developing countries generally have this kind of a reality. And

04:13:02.760 --> 04:13:06.440
[Guest]: there are hard reasons for it. And there are software reasons. The hard reason is the state

04:13:06.440 --> 04:13:12.040
[Guest]: capacity constraint that we make many, many more laws than we can realistically implement.

04:13:12.040 --> 04:13:15.320
[Guest]: Everything will come to a lock jam if we start implementing all the laws, especially on the

04:13:15.320 --> 04:13:21.280
[Guest]: business side in the economy. And sometimes the laws are made at a time when now the current

04:13:21.280 --> 04:13:25.880
[Guest]: executive is not so keen to implement them. And they do have some discretion, you know,

04:13:25.880 --> 04:13:30.640
[Guest]: we may not like it, we want rule of law, this and that, but the political reality is that

04:13:30.640 --> 04:13:36.080
[Guest]: the current executive has a lot of legitimacy to exercise some discretion over how laws

04:13:36.080 --> 04:13:39.680
[Guest]: are to be implemented and all. And that was a big revelation when I started actually studying

04:13:39.680 --> 04:13:43.240
[Guest]: this literature and also talking to lots of people in different sectors like infrastructure

04:13:43.240 --> 04:13:48.160
[Guest]: and all about how they enter into a 30-year contract in a developing country which changes

04:13:48.160 --> 04:13:55.760
[Guest]: so fast and so many realities change and risks they were holding could go bad.

04:13:55.760 --> 04:13:59.000
[Guest]: How what were the assumptions and actually the assumptions were very informal, I mean

04:13:59.000 --> 04:14:04.380
[Guest]: in the sense that they expected that the contract is one thing, but there will be concessions

04:14:04.380 --> 04:14:10.080
[Guest]: made and some reliefs will be given if things go bad, you know. And I think that was realistic

04:14:10.080 --> 04:14:15.360
[Guest]: because the contracts are by definition typically incomplete and much more incomplete in a developing

04:14:15.360 --> 04:14:20.400
[Guest]: country context which is things are very disorganized, they change very rapidly. And it's just a

04:14:20.400 --> 04:14:24.720
[Guest]: completely different world, you know, when you've gone through 10 years of 5% or 6% growth

04:14:24.720 --> 04:14:29.600
[Guest]: or 7% growth, the country completely changed and you entered a contract for 30 years. So

04:14:29.600 --> 04:14:34.880
[Guest]: there are hard realities because of which our discretion, some degree of informality

04:14:34.880 --> 04:14:40.120
[Guest]: and implementation of rules and laws is required and then there are softer. Sometimes you actually

04:14:40.120 --> 04:14:44.280
[Guest]: want to exercise discretion because you have the power and you want to do certain things

04:14:44.280 --> 04:14:47.880
[Guest]: with that power and the law becomes a constraint for you and sometimes for good reasons, sometimes

04:14:47.880 --> 04:14:52.640
[Guest]: bad reasons. So those are things which are on a case-by-case basis to decide. But these

04:14:52.640 --> 04:14:58.480
[Guest]: were I think the main changes in my view. Basically the differences between having an

04:14:58.480 --> 04:15:02.800
[Guest]: idealized conception in my mind, I mean even if it's a negative conception, it's still

04:15:02.800 --> 04:15:07.120
[Guest]: an idealized and a stereotypical conception, from having a little better understanding

04:15:07.120 --> 04:15:13.440
[Guest]: of how the state actually works and like something as simple as transparency and secrecy. Earlier

04:15:13.440 --> 04:15:17.920
[Guest]: I had a very simplistic notion of transparency, more transparency, more transparency, move

04:15:17.920 --> 04:15:24.480
[Guest]: is better for accountability, you know, cliches like sunshine is the best disinfectant, all

04:15:24.480 --> 04:15:30.320
[Guest]: of those. But now I have kind of overcome that. I mean, in fact, a lot of my reading

04:15:30.320 --> 04:15:35.920
[Guest]: these days is to try to philosophically understand it. So I read a lot more on decisionism, lot

04:15:35.920 --> 04:15:41.760
[Guest]: more on utilitarianism, you know, what are the kind of frames in which this behavior

04:15:41.760 --> 04:15:48.480
[Guest]: can be understood, not just justified and rational, but understood so that you can make

04:15:48.480 --> 04:15:53.680
[Guest]: an informed opinion about what's going on, you know, not have some kind of an arbitrary

04:15:53.680 --> 04:15:59.200
[Guest]: normative commitments, which this alienates you from a reality which may actually be what

04:15:59.200 --> 04:16:00.640
[Guest]: it is for good reasons.

04:16:02.240 --> 04:16:05.520
[Amit Varma]: I'll double click on a couple of things. But first, why did your views on transparency

04:16:05.520 --> 04:16:05.840
[Amit Varma]: change?

04:16:07.360 --> 04:16:13.200
[Guest]: Yeah, so if you look at our policies on transparency, they have changed over time, right? And it

04:16:13.200 --> 04:16:18.080
[Guest]: is not like we had complete government transparency to begin with. In fact, the Right to Information

04:16:18.080 --> 04:16:24.640
[Guest]: Act came out only in this century, after almost 55 years of independence or so, more than

04:16:24.640 --> 04:16:31.520
[Guest]: 55 years of independence. And what I think is that transparency is a means to ends, you

04:16:31.520 --> 04:16:35.040
[Guest]: know, it's not an end in itself, like I said, many things like rights and all their means

04:16:35.040 --> 04:16:42.240
[Guest]: to other ends. And in many contexts, transparency works quite well, because it's important for

04:16:42.240 --> 04:16:49.440
[Guest]: accountability, it's important to, for public debate to nudge the politicians and civil

04:16:49.440 --> 04:16:54.960
[Guest]: servants in the right direction. And in some context, some specific context, it can be

04:16:54.960 --> 04:17:00.240
[Guest]: a double edged sword and can even do harm to the ability of the decision maker to actually

04:17:01.440 --> 04:17:07.200
[Guest]: do the right thing. For example, quite a few areas in which even in the developed countries

04:17:07.200 --> 04:17:10.880
[Guest]: in which there's a lot of transparency, otherwise emphasis of transparency, they keep secrecy.

04:17:10.880 --> 04:17:15.360
[Guest]: For example, for quite a few meetings that are held, the minutes are released after decades,

04:17:16.400 --> 04:17:22.000
[Guest]: right? And so, you have to, that what does it show that you will take a decision on a

04:17:22.000 --> 04:17:27.760
[Guest]: case by case basis and when the transparency is beneficial and when it is not. It is not

04:17:27.760 --> 04:17:36.080
[Guest]: something that you can take as a slogan, is all I'm saying, that sunlight is always better than

04:17:36.080 --> 04:17:42.000
[Guest]: darkness and democracy always dies in darkness. It's true, it's by and large true, but there are

04:17:42.000 --> 04:17:47.360
[Guest]: exceptions to that. In the regulation making process, there are exceptions. In the executive

04:17:47.360 --> 04:17:51.440
[Guest]: decision making space, not just in national security, but also in economic governance,

04:17:51.440 --> 04:17:57.040
[Guest]: there are exceptions to that, in which you may need a little bit more discretion to exercise

04:17:57.040 --> 04:18:03.040
[Guest]: and immediate public scrutiny may actually shut out the discussion, may disincentivize genuine

04:18:03.040 --> 04:18:09.520
[Guest]: open discussion, difficult decisions to be taken and much more posturing. So, if you look at, for

04:18:09.520 --> 04:18:16.000
[Guest]: example, some of the high courts in India started streaming their hearings and it's a double-edged

04:18:16.000 --> 04:18:20.000
[Guest]: sword. I mean, there are some advantages to it, but I watched them and some of the judges are

04:18:20.000 --> 04:18:25.280
[Guest]: literally posturing, they are trying to signal their, to quote the title of a book, quoting the

04:18:25.280 --> 04:18:31.600
[Guest]: people in some ways, that they are trying to signal a certain kind of persona to them and

04:18:31.600 --> 04:18:37.520
[Guest]: appear a certain way. So, I think it's a case by case basis, you have to decide in which situation

04:18:37.520 --> 04:18:41.200
[Guest]: it will work and what situation it will not work. You means the people who have the legitimacy to

04:18:41.200 --> 04:18:49.840
[Guest]: decide or I mean, basically in the elected and custodians of a democracy, within judges and the

04:18:49.840 --> 04:18:52.080
[Guest]: elected representatives, they have to decide basically.

04:18:52.640 --> 04:18:57.280
[Amit Varma]: So, let's turn our attention for a moment to, you know, a term that you've used at different parts

04:18:57.280 --> 04:19:03.840
[Amit Varma]: of this conversation, which is utilitarianism. Now, my issue with utilitarianism or consequentialism

04:19:03.840 --> 04:19:10.000
[Amit Varma]: is that there is a knowledge problem that you cannot possibly forecast the future or really

04:19:10.000 --> 04:19:17.120
[Amit Varma]: be able to tell what happens and so on and so forth. And therefore, you can justify any decision

04:19:17.120 --> 04:19:22.240
[Amit Varma]: by saying that these are the ends that we foresee. In fact, in a different context,

04:19:22.240 --> 04:19:26.400
[Amit Varma]: you were talking about the jury de facto, and you pointed out that many people will

04:19:26.400 --> 04:19:30.800
[Amit Varma]: come up with laws and things that solve the problem, and they will be mistaking intention

04:19:30.800 --> 04:19:37.520
[Amit Varma]: for outcome, which is the most popular and lazy policy mistake that people will, you know,

04:19:37.520 --> 04:19:42.240
[Amit Varma]: mistake intention for outcome and not care about the outcomes of something as long as the intentions

04:19:42.240 --> 04:19:48.880
[Amit Varma]: are good. And my issue with utilitarianism is exactly that, that it can be used to justify

04:19:48.880 --> 04:19:52.800
[Amit Varma]: really anything because you can forecast anything about the future, it depends on what your

04:19:52.800 --> 04:19:58.080
[Amit Varma]: assumptions are. And therefore, it becomes a problematic frame. And therefore, I think that

04:19:58.080 --> 04:20:01.760
[Amit Varma]: no matter I mean, obviously, when you're framing policy, you're framing policy, because you want

04:20:01.760 --> 04:20:06.240
[Amit Varma]: it to end up in the right outcomes, and you are thinking of those. But at the same time,

04:20:06.240 --> 04:20:11.920
[Amit Varma]: there should be a few principles, which are just normative, that they are the way they are. And we

04:20:11.920 --> 04:20:16.240
[Amit Varma]: agree on some of those, for example, defending the right to life of citizens, the right to free

04:20:16.240 --> 04:20:21.840
[Amit Varma]: speech, and so on and so forth, that these things should not be contextual, these things should not

04:20:21.840 --> 04:20:26.560
[Amit Varma]: be case by case basis. So I understand the argument for, you know, transparency in certain

04:20:26.560 --> 04:20:32.560
[Amit Varma]: cases being case by case. I'll take some time to kind of process those examples and read your work

04:20:32.560 --> 04:20:39.520
[Amit Varma]: on it. But certain things I think should not be looked at in a utilitarian way, because that can

04:20:39.520 --> 04:20:43.680
[Amit Varma]: lead you to terrible places like the great utilitarian philosopher Peter Singer had once

04:20:43.680 --> 04:20:48.720
[Amit Varma]: argued that in certain situations, it's okay to kill an infant child, not a fetus, mind you,

04:20:48.720 --> 04:20:54.320
[Amit Varma]: but an infant child, if well being of the world goes up under certain conditions, which I think

04:20:54.320 --> 04:20:59.920
[Amit Varma]: is a barbaric way to think that there are certain things that should be considered sacred, we both

04:20:59.920 --> 04:21:04.480
[Amit Varma]: agree the right to life is one of them. And I'd add other things, other negative rights, like

04:21:04.480 --> 04:21:11.680
[Amit Varma]: free speech and property and so on and so forth. So what's your sense of, I mean, you know, using

04:21:11.680 --> 04:21:21.360
[Guest]: utilitarian arguments? Yeah, I think, by default, the state is a utilitarian creature. Okay. So

04:21:22.640 --> 04:21:27.920
[Guest]: for political reasons, more than anything else, that because you're trying to appeal to a large

04:21:27.920 --> 04:21:33.200
[Guest]: number of people and trying to improve, or at least make the claim that you're improving their

04:21:33.200 --> 04:21:40.000
[Guest]: happiness, the general pressure in a democracy, especially, and even in other regimes where

04:21:40.000 --> 04:21:45.280
[Guest]: you need to get some degree of popular legitimacy, you know, like Communist Party in China is seeking

04:21:45.280 --> 04:21:50.480
[Guest]: legitimacy through delivering certain things for the citizens. It's not just pure repression that

04:21:50.480 --> 04:21:54.560
[Guest]: works for them. They're doing other things as well. But in democracy, for sure, there is a

04:21:55.120 --> 04:22:01.840
[Guest]: general kind of pressure towards doing, serving a large number of people and their goals and

04:22:01.840 --> 04:22:08.400
[Guest]: utilitarian frame actually takes you a long way in that direction. And when you think about

04:22:08.400 --> 04:22:15.680
[Guest]: something like pure utilitarianism, it is what direct power fit, there is full of repugnant

04:22:15.680 --> 04:22:19.520
[Guest]: conclusions, you know, especially when you think of population ethics and all, there are lots of

04:22:19.520 --> 04:22:26.240
[Guest]: repugnant conclusions that are there. And you have to, you means, I mean, we as a collective

04:22:26.240 --> 04:22:33.280
[Guest]: have to take a view on what would be the right approach. There is no one rule of thumb or a

04:22:33.280 --> 04:22:38.080
[Guest]: formula, like even something like right to life. Obviously, we all agree right to life. But there

04:22:38.080 --> 04:22:43.360
[Guest]: are situations in which I support the state taking a life, right? Like, there are situations of

04:22:43.360 --> 04:22:49.680
[Guest]: conflict in which the state will rightfully take lives, not just of invaders and people who are

04:22:49.680 --> 04:22:53.840
[Guest]: attacking us, but also when people who are fighting and taking up arms domestically,

04:22:53.840 --> 04:22:58.960
[Guest]: there are criminals who are killed in encounters and that was the only option and that they are

04:22:58.960 --> 04:23:03.920
[Guest]: authorized to kill somebody and the police are authorized to do that. Paramilitary are

04:23:03.920 --> 04:23:08.720
[Guest]: authorized to do that, you know, there are violations of privacy that for utilitarian

04:23:08.720 --> 04:23:13.680
[Guest]: purposes and actually for protecting life itself, because it's not just utilitarian ends,

04:23:13.680 --> 04:23:17.360
[Guest]: but also there is life against life, right? One terrorist can kill another person. So,

04:23:17.360 --> 04:23:22.000
[Guest]: you kill the terrorist before that terrorist comes and the situational awareness is required,

04:23:22.000 --> 04:23:26.640
[Guest]: because obviously, it is better to arrest and bring to justice than all of that. But there

04:23:26.640 --> 04:23:29.360
[Guest]: are situations in which they are authorized to do those things.

04:23:29.360 --> 04:23:32.880
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, those I imagine, like in this case, terrorists are about to shoot someone,

04:23:32.880 --> 04:23:37.600
[Amit Varma]: so you shoot the terrorist is in the case where you are defending someone's right to life

04:23:37.600 --> 04:23:42.240
[Amit Varma]: by doing that. So, you know, that calculation is not utilitarian.

04:23:43.600 --> 04:23:49.600
[Guest]: I mean, the systems calculation for establishing this kind of a system of authorization of violence

04:23:50.240 --> 04:23:55.760
[Guest]: and maintaining a certain kind of order is a utilitarian to basically preserve and enhance

04:23:55.760 --> 04:24:01.040
[Guest]: the happiness for maximum number of people basically is the underlying logic. In a

04:24:01.040 --> 04:24:07.120
[Guest]: particular situation that may actually require basically protecting one life by taking another

04:24:07.120 --> 04:24:12.560
[Guest]: life. But that's not all that happens, right? There is a kind of a systematic repression that

04:24:12.560 --> 04:24:17.680
[Guest]: is done for, for example, if you want to secede, for example. Secession is in that sense,

04:24:17.680 --> 04:24:21.840
[Guest]: if you think about secession, I mean, it's a somebody just wants to leave the republic,

04:24:21.840 --> 04:24:26.880
[Guest]: for example. But even then, if for the larger good of the republic or society,

04:24:26.880 --> 04:24:32.320
[Guest]: citizens do authorize quite a bit of violence all over the world to be able to keep that

04:24:33.680 --> 04:24:39.440
[Guest]: part of the body politic from leaving it. And it cannot be life against life. But there are

04:24:39.440 --> 04:24:45.280
[Guest]: utilitarian gains for of having a republic of a particular kind, which may be lost if one part

04:24:46.000 --> 04:24:52.240
[Guest]: leaves. So, political reasoning, generally, I think, supports a lot of utilitarian thinking.

04:24:52.240 --> 04:24:59.520
[Guest]: And there are obviously, in our moral imaginations, in public imagination, some kind of a

04:24:59.520 --> 04:25:04.320
[Guest]: deontological commitments that we make that thing, okay, there are these things that we think are

04:25:04.320 --> 04:25:08.720
[Guest]: very worthy of preserving at the individual level, that we are not thinking only at the

04:25:08.720 --> 04:25:14.960
[Guest]: collective that we need to preserve life as default and there's some dignity to it.

04:25:14.960 --> 04:25:24.000
[Guest]: We have liberty we need to preserve and there is a degree of sanctity to that. And we have

04:25:24.000 --> 04:25:28.320
[Guest]: put in place some systems to be able to do that and which systems can take a decision,

04:25:29.520 --> 04:25:34.560
[Guest]: what is to be done, and the systems have to be approved over a period of time so that they do

04:25:34.560 --> 04:25:40.400
[Guest]: these things well, you know, all I'm saying is that there is no general formula that can be

04:25:40.400 --> 04:25:46.160
[Guest]: applied which will be universally valid. It depends on the state that the society is in.

04:25:46.160 --> 04:25:51.280
[Guest]: There are situations in which you have to suspend certain rights. There are situations in which

04:25:51.280 --> 04:25:57.200
[Guest]: you have to look the other way from these so called deeply held values, because the larger

04:25:57.200 --> 04:26:02.560
[Guest]: good demands it. And that's where I think this these trade-offs are made and they're done,

04:26:02.560 --> 04:26:08.160
[Guest]: they're made through these systems rather than because it requires certain kind of practical

04:26:08.160 --> 04:26:14.640
[Guest]: judgment and situational awareness which is not available a prior. So, but suppose you say

04:26:14.640 --> 04:26:19.040
[Guest]: there's a particular situation and what should you do? There should be a rule book about it.

04:26:19.600 --> 04:26:24.400
[Guest]: If you were in a situation where every situation can be can be described and you have a rule book

04:26:24.400 --> 04:26:28.560
[Guest]: that says okay this is what is to be done in that situation, then that's preferable because

04:26:28.560 --> 04:26:33.360
[Guest]: every situation has been thought about, every scenario has been thought about and you've put

04:26:33.360 --> 04:26:39.360
[Guest]: rules about it. But that's not possible always. So, discretion comes in. Discretion means some

04:26:39.360 --> 04:26:44.880
[Guest]: somebody has to legitimize the use of that discretion and that's where I think we get

04:26:44.880 --> 04:26:50.480
[Guest]: into the territory where these trade-offs have to be justified ex post rather than ex ante.

04:26:51.760 --> 04:26:56.080
[Amit Varma]: Let's go back to what you said about you know the way government functions and the ways in which

04:26:56.080 --> 04:27:02.560
[Amit Varma]: you changed your mind and one was the de jure de facto thing where you said that we sometimes

04:27:02.560 --> 04:27:08.240
[Amit Varma]: pay too much importance, we sometimes take the existing laws as being reflective of the state

04:27:08.240 --> 04:27:13.440
[Amit Varma]: of the world and they actually aren't and it seems to me to be a very profound point.

04:27:13.440 --> 04:27:19.120
[Amit Varma]: So, can you dive in a little deeper into that with concrete examples so I can understand it a bit

04:27:19.120 --> 04:27:26.480
[Guest]: better? So, one example obviously we've brought it up a couple of times in discussion and I always

04:27:26.480 --> 04:27:31.760
