04:29:29.680 --> 04:29:34.800
[Guest]: because lots of people in the in the ground will say no no no this was excessively used. It's

04:29:34.800 --> 04:29:39.440
[Guest]: really difficult for us to find out as citizens who are living very far from where this kind of

04:29:39.440 --> 04:29:44.320
[Guest]: conflict is going on and that becomes a question of who do you go to benefit of doubt to and then

04:29:44.320 --> 04:29:51.600
[Guest]: of course it usually goes in one direction. So, there is the reality is very different from what

04:29:51.600 --> 04:29:56.400
[Guest]: the rule book says in many parts of the world mostly in developing countries and across the

04:29:56.400 --> 04:30:02.720
[Guest]: world in many many areas whether it's rights, whether it's regulations, whether it's use of

04:30:02.720 --> 04:30:09.760
[Guest]: power by the state for security purposes, intelligence and so on. So, I think there

04:30:09.760 --> 04:30:15.600
[Guest]: is kind of a commonality in literatures across different domains which reveals something very

04:30:15.600 --> 04:30:20.160
[Guest]: deep deep about the nature of developing countries and much more of a kind of a

04:30:20.160 --> 04:30:24.160
[Guest]: decisionist orientation that exists without we actually acknowledging it.

04:30:25.280 --> 04:30:29.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, in fact in our episode together I brought up Hayek and the distinction he makes between

04:30:29.680 --> 04:30:36.240
[Amit Varma]: law and legislation and the way he defines a law over there is just a way of doing things

04:30:36.240 --> 04:30:41.520
[Amit Varma]: a convention that has evolved over time from practice. For example, there may be a particular

04:30:41.520 --> 04:30:46.640
[Amit Varma]: road which is built in a particular way where people just drive at 80 where it's completely

04:30:46.640 --> 04:30:51.360
[Guest]: okay to drive at 80 and that's what people do. The new social economics scholars they define

04:30:51.360 --> 04:30:56.160
