[Amit Varma]: really large questions so i'm really sorry for unleashing them but one uh your potted view

05:15:01.280 --> 05:15:08.560
[Amit Varma]: on where the indian economy is today and how hopeful should we be and to this ecosystem of

05:15:08.560 --> 05:15:15.520
[Amit Varma]: change you know that can we turn it around again that fine you know we had some tough times and we

05:15:15.520 --> 05:15:21.840
[Amit Varma]: were already you know not doing well before covid covid of course exacerbated it to some extent

05:15:21.840 --> 05:15:28.320
[Amit Varma]: but where is the hope for the indian economy and to drill down on that is that hope coming

05:15:28.320 --> 05:15:34.240
[Amit Varma]: from within the ecosystem is there still you know are there young shahs and kilkers in the system

05:15:34.240 --> 05:15:43.520
[Guest]: yeah these are big questions so let me i mean offer like as usual i mean this stream of

05:15:43.520 --> 05:15:51.280
[Guest]: consciousness answer and see if it works so first thing is that in our milieu in the way we and you

05:15:51.280 --> 05:15:56.960
[Guest]: and i move around we overstate the role played by economists and understate the role played by

05:15:56.960 --> 05:16:03.120
[Guest]: politicians and civil servants in in the achievements that we have had as a country

05:16:03.120 --> 05:16:10.480
[Guest]: especially since the 90s and maybe in parts of 80s as well so there is obviously a credit very

05:16:10.480 --> 05:16:15.920
[Guest]: due to give credit wherever who came with a good idea pushed it had the perfect perseverance to

05:16:15.920 --> 05:16:21.840
[Guest]: see it through but there is a as i said there is a system in which we operate and that is a

05:16:21.840 --> 05:16:26.000
[Guest]: democratic system there is a permanent civil service and there is a democratic system of

05:16:26.000 --> 05:16:31.520
[Guest]: elections and give shifting of power based on elections and people who are in power

05:16:31.520 --> 05:16:38.560
[Guest]: do things so a couple of things one is that we are a political economy in which we did

05:16:38.560 --> 05:16:44.880
[Guest]: 91 which was a big bang reform reforms continued through the 90s in that in the 90s we had

05:16:46.240 --> 05:16:52.240
[Guest]: three very different orientation governments there was a Narasimha Rao government then there

05:16:52.240 --> 05:16:59.200
[Guest]: was a third front government under two different prime ministers UDF and then the right of center

05:16:59.200 --> 05:17:05.360
[Guest]: so to speak PGP led NDA government came in but the reforms continued throughout right

05:17:05.360 --> 05:17:10.800
[Guest]: and that was a political decision that there was some kind of a consensus you can say that was

05:17:10.800 --> 05:17:16.720
[Guest]: there within the political and administrative class you know and that this is important and

05:17:16.720 --> 05:17:22.160
[Guest]: we will continue to do this and continue to ease the binding constraints continue to push the

05:17:22.160 --> 05:17:27.520
[Guest]: policy in the right direction and do whatever is necessary not just policy reforms do whatever is

05:17:27.520 --> 05:17:33.680
[Guest]: necessary and I emphasize that because it can mean many things to keep growth going you know

05:17:33.680 --> 05:17:39.600
[Guest]: that's very important and so we had so I did a literature review on when did India's high

05:17:39.600 --> 05:17:43.760
[Guest]: growth episode start and there is a literature on this and reasonable persons have disagreed

05:17:43.760 --> 05:17:50.320
[Guest]: on where and when it start but I had concluded based on a recent paper that it's 93 onwards

05:17:50.320 --> 05:17:58.640
[Guest]: basically and then 2002 onwards we had a really high growth episode and the question is whether

05:17:58.640 --> 05:18:02.320
[Guest]: the high growth episode has ended or not that's the question that we need to ask we don't know

05:18:02.320 --> 05:18:07.680
[Guest]: it's these things are unfortunately understood only retrospectively but decisions have to be

05:18:07.680 --> 05:18:15.600
[Guest]: taken right and you know there's a famous quote by R.L. Stevenson that even the worst of the

05:18:15.600 --> 05:18:20.960
[Guest]: historians know much better about the period they study than the best of us know about the period

05:18:20.960 --> 05:18:26.160
[Guest]: in which we live and unfortunately or fortunately we have to think about what the current period you

05:18:26.160 --> 05:18:32.480
[Guest]: know the past is the past and to the extent possible and it's not easily available to us

05:18:32.480 --> 05:18:35.200
[Guest]: all the facts available to understand what's happening right now we need to understand

05:18:35.200 --> 05:18:40.160
[Guest]: what's happening have situational awareness, awareness of the state of the economy,

05:18:40.160 --> 05:18:44.880
[Guest]: underlying sources of dynamism the economy which are continuing which are not continuing how what

05:18:44.880 --> 05:18:51.200
[Guest]: can we do to you know keep the dynamism going you know there is a very important role to be

05:18:51.200 --> 05:18:55.760
[Guest]: played by this and I am not saying this needs to be done on a local level this is a national

05:18:55.760 --> 05:19:02.080
[Guest]: conversation because nations grow you know I mean obviously growth drivers are local and

05:19:02.080 --> 05:19:08.160
[Guest]: individuals set up businesses, local governments solve problems and all but it is we as a country

05:19:08.160 --> 05:19:15.040
[Guest]: we started growing in the 90s right that was our I mean it wasn't like before 90s said some states

05:19:15.040 --> 05:19:19.280
[Guest]: were rich and other states were poor you know obviously relatively some were better off and

05:19:19.280 --> 05:19:23.520
[Guest]: but it was a very narrow range you know everybody was clustered around that same

05:19:23.520 --> 05:19:28.000
[Guest]: small the richest state was only three times of the poorest state you know at that time.

05:19:28.000 --> 05:19:35.360
[Guest]: As we opened up and we started seeing growth accelerate some states just rushed forward and

05:19:35.360 --> 05:19:40.160
[Guest]: became I mean fairly in fact some of the richest states in India have the per capita income of

05:19:40.160 --> 05:19:48.480
[Guest]: China basically you know so and the poorest states are quite poor and but the most important thing is

05:19:48.480 --> 05:19:56.480
[Guest]: that the rate at which our poorest state Bihar namely has grown since the 90s is higher than

05:19:56.480 --> 05:20:03.040
[Guest]: the rate at which India Indian economy was growing previous to that. So, let's not forget that

05:20:03.040 --> 05:20:06.560
[Guest]: improvement even in the state which is the bottom of the pile which had a decade of

05:20:06.560 --> 05:20:15.280
[Guest]: almost zero real growth in the 90s has benefited from this episode. So, inequality we have

05:20:15.280 --> 05:20:20.000
[Guest]: emphasized too much and we don't pay enough attention to that whole you know cake is

05:20:20.000 --> 05:20:24.160
[Guest]: growing and everybody is getting persuasion and then constitutional mechanisms are there to

05:20:24.160 --> 05:20:27.760
[Guest]: make sure Bihar also gets some part of the benefits from other countries so it's able to

05:20:27.760 --> 05:20:32.080
[Guest]: provide some minimum level of services for its citizens as well through the finance commission

05:20:32.080 --> 05:20:38.000
[Guest]: mechanism and all. So, we have one country and some states marched ahead and Bihar which is

05:20:38.000 --> 05:20:45.040
[Guest]: remain poor UP is also poor they also their entrepreneurs went and set up businesses in

05:20:45.040 --> 05:20:52.000
[Guest]: Bangalore and Bombay their labor went workers went capital also flowed in fact because they

05:20:52.000 --> 05:20:56.160
[Guest]: didn't have enough businesses in those states so capital flowed to the richer states from these

05:20:56.160 --> 05:21:00.240
[Guest]: states and we have one country and being a part of this country is very beneficial for each state

05:21:00.240 --> 05:21:02.880
[Guest]: those states that marched ahead benefited from being a part of this country because

05:21:02.880 --> 05:21:06.400
[Guest]: their products could be sold in these states factors of production other than land everything

05:21:06.400 --> 05:21:12.160
[Guest]: can move across state boundaries easily relatively they could move and set up.

05:21:12.160 --> 05:21:17.920
[Guest]: So, we have benefited a lot from this period and it's been done because there was some kind of a

05:21:17.920 --> 05:21:23.840
[Guest]: political consensus at the national and state levels in many states there's a variation in

05:21:24.720 --> 05:21:28.640
[Guest]: different states how much they could make of this period and some states couldn't make as

05:21:28.640 --> 05:21:33.840
[Guest]: much as they could and others could make a lot more like Punjab for example is an example of

05:21:33.840 --> 05:21:39.200
[Guest]: a state which fell behind it was the richest state in 1990 and now it's basically very close

05:21:39.200 --> 05:21:46.080
[Guest]: to the national average it's a pretty bad story in that sense and it's not doing as badly in

05:21:46.080 --> 05:21:52.720
[Guest]: absolute terms as say Bihar or UP but it's I mean relative position has really fallen

05:21:52.720 --> 05:21:58.640
[Guest]: and there are states like Tamil Nadu and Telangana, Haryana and all which have really marched ahead

05:21:58.640 --> 05:22:05.200
[Guest]: you know since these reforms happened and overall I think lots of ways to problematize what has

05:22:05.200 --> 05:22:11.440
[Guest]: happened but I think it's been a pretty significant success compared to our own past

05:22:11.440 --> 05:22:16.800
[Guest]: and also compared to what is generally seen in comparative sense. So, one of the things is that

05:22:16.800 --> 05:22:22.320
[Guest]: democracies usually don't go very rapidly I mean democracies are rich so obviously you'll say why

05:22:22.320 --> 05:22:26.160
[Guest]: how does not rapid growth is a different form of being rich because you can get rich over 150 years

05:22:26.720 --> 05:22:31.920
[Guest]: which is the story of the most immature democracies in the world developed countries in

05:22:31.920 --> 05:22:38.320
[Guest]: west mostly but democracies usually grow at a moderate rate and generally not just democracies

05:22:38.320 --> 05:22:42.640
[Guest]: for any country to grow for a rapid rate for a very long period of time is very difficult it's

05:22:42.640 --> 05:22:49.120
[Guest]: very rare so regression to mean is the rule and these are exceptions and the longer the growth

05:22:49.120 --> 05:22:54.080
[Guest]: episode is going the more the chances of you regressing back to the mean so the

05:22:54.800 --> 05:22:59.520
[Guest]: adaptive efficiency you need which I mean using Nicholas North's language to continue with the

05:22:59.520 --> 05:23:03.040
[Guest]: growth episode is quite significant you know and you need to have a political economy which is

05:23:03.040 --> 05:23:08.000
[Guest]: very adaptive and which is very mindful of the imbalances that are getting built up across

05:23:08.000 --> 05:23:13.920
[Guest]: different parts of the economy what are the kind of new problems that are emerging and address those

05:23:13.920 --> 05:23:18.400
[Guest]: and it's a political and administrative problem you know economists researchers can play a small

05:23:18.400 --> 05:23:24.400
[Guest]: role in that very small and the main thing is the political settlement and political agreement and

05:23:24.400 --> 05:23:29.280
[Guest]: having the right incentive to solve those problems having a sense of importance of that and and some

05:23:29.280 --> 05:23:33.760
[Guest]: degree of I mean even though people fight elections and they are always trying to destroy each other's

05:23:33.760 --> 05:23:37.440
[Guest]: political legitimacy there is some true underlying agreement and development and growth are very

05:23:37.440 --> 05:23:42.080
[Guest]: important and there's something not to be disrupted I think that is the foundation on which this is

05:23:42.080 --> 05:23:46.560
[Guest]: built and I think we had that we have whether we have it now or not I have a question but we had

05:23:46.560 --> 05:23:53.200
[Guest]: that for a long time and especially in the 90s so one of the things that I always point out is that

05:23:53.200 --> 05:23:57.920
[Guest]: our private investments took off in the 2000s 90s there was no noticeable growth in private

05:23:57.920 --> 05:24:03.840
[Guest]: investments and because I mean we had to the polity has to establish some degree of one way

05:24:03.840 --> 05:24:08.720
[Guest]: to read it many ways to read these facts I'm not saying that my way is only way same facts can be

05:24:08.720 --> 05:24:12.960
[Guest]: reconciled with multiple narratives that's the way history works but one way to read it is that

05:24:12.960 --> 05:24:18.320
[Guest]: we had to establish that credible commitment that we are here to do the reforms and the direction

05:24:18.320 --> 05:24:22.800
[Guest]: will be one way and we will keep liberalizing and opening up and giving you more opportunities

05:24:22.800 --> 05:24:27.520
[Guest]: and please invest and then in the 2000s private investment took off in the early 2010s private

05:24:27.520 --> 05:24:32.160
[Guest]: investments have been very low private investment basically fell and private investment was the

05:24:32.160 --> 05:24:36.880
[Guest]: main driver of growth in the 2000s which are the best years for our economy 2002 onwards

05:24:37.440 --> 05:24:42.160
[Guest]: and then they have been low export was the other major driver continued from 90s to 2000s

05:24:42.160 --> 05:24:49.120
[Guest]: the export of the major driver that has also slowed down significantly since 2011 onwards 12

05:24:49.120 --> 05:24:57.040
[Guest]: 12 onwards so 12 or 13 if I'm not getting the year right so these are drivers of growth you know

05:24:57.760 --> 05:25:03.040
[Guest]: for an economy like India and some people can make an argument that it's the consumption that

05:25:03.040 --> 05:25:07.280
[Guest]: should be driving and we have done enough of the accumulation now we need to do redistribution and

05:25:07.280 --> 05:25:13.280
[Guest]: all I my own judgment is we're not in that stage of growth there will be a situation it could be

05:25:13.280 --> 05:25:17.440
[Guest]: a situation in the future like where Japan reaches the 90s where domestic consumption

05:25:18.000 --> 05:25:24.000
[Guest]: take off and it just stagnated you know that it just kept on the accumulation cycle Hirschman

05:25:24.000 --> 05:25:28.080
[Guest]: has this dynamic between accumulation and redistribution which is the dynamic has to play

05:25:28.080 --> 05:25:34.160
[Guest]: out for the economy to sustain itself its growth so anyway there are matters of judgment but the

05:25:34.160 --> 05:25:39.200
[Guest]: basic thing is that the two drivers of growth export and private investment which were driving

05:25:39.200 --> 05:25:46.000
[Guest]: a growth in that way basically slowed down significantly in the 2010s and they didn't

05:25:46.000 --> 05:25:53.360
[Guest]: really pick up before the pandemic hit at that time and there were some short periods of upswing

05:25:53.360 --> 05:26:00.240
[Guest]: but nothing substantial that was happening and lots of different narratives have been offered

05:26:00.240 --> 05:26:06.400
[Guest]: to why that happened and all of that and I mean we can go into that then the pandemic hit so but

05:26:06.400 --> 05:26:11.680
[Guest]: before the pandemic hit our role our growth in the previous year 2019-20 was 3.7 percent

05:26:12.320 --> 05:26:18.000
[Guest]: if I'm not remembering if I'm doing it right it was 3.7 percent and investment growth was very

05:26:18.000 --> 05:26:23.680
[Guest]: very low and I mean basically all across all the components on the demand side there was a

05:26:23.680 --> 05:26:31.440
[Guest]: low investment, government consumption, private consumption was actually the fastest of the lot

05:26:31.440 --> 05:26:36.800
[Guest]: but it wasn't the economy was not growing much then the pandemic hit and we had a obviously

05:26:36.800 --> 05:26:41.280
[Guest]: lockdown and all and we had a very low very big contraction in the economy and then we had a

05:26:41.280 --> 05:26:47.040
[Guest]: recovery in 2021-22 right and now last couple of years what has happened is our ability to make

05:26:47.040 --> 05:26:51.840
[Guest]: sense of the year-on-year data is you know intuitively it's not the same right because

05:26:51.840 --> 05:26:56.800
[Guest]: we need to track with a pre-pandemic performance so a lot of headlines look very different

05:26:56.800 --> 05:27:01.280
[Guest]: because hey year-on-year look will look like but the main question that I have in my mind

05:27:01.280 --> 05:27:05.840
[Guest]: which I'm trying to understand is that did the issues that were there in the pre-pandemic period

05:27:05.840 --> 05:27:10.240
[Guest]: just go away or are they still there what were those issues why was private investment not

05:27:10.240 --> 05:27:15.120
[Guest]: taking off for 10 years why was exports not picking up you know at that time now we've had

05:27:15.120 --> 05:27:21.200
[Guest]: some short-term periods of good export growth I hope it sustains I pray it sustains because it's

05:27:21.200 --> 05:27:26.000
[Guest]: a major driver of growth in India but that's a question that we need to answer because it's

05:27:26.000 --> 05:27:31.200
[Guest]: very important and very difficult to sustain long periods of rapid growth but that's what

05:27:31.200 --> 05:27:35.600
[Guest]: we need to do that's what China did right China did 40 years plus of rapid growth its economy

05:27:35.600 --> 05:27:42.560
[Guest]: has been slowing recently it's changed its political economy approach but India has had

05:27:42.560 --> 05:27:47.680
[Guest]: rapid growth for at least two decades perhaps longer in between the debate got a little

05:27:47.680 --> 05:27:54.240
[Guest]: vitiated because of the GDP numbers controversy whether the GDP is capturing the actual economic

05:27:54.240 --> 05:27:59.760
[Guest]: activity and growth in it but lately I mean especially just before the pandemic there

05:27:59.760 --> 05:28:03.760
[Guest]: was some correspondence because other indicators are looking bad and GDP indicator itself also

05:28:03.760 --> 05:28:11.760
[Guest]: looking very bad so I mean but apart from these these debates I think there's a substantive

05:28:11.760 --> 05:28:17.360
[Guest]: question about what would it take to continue a rapid growth episode by defying history you know

05:28:17.360 --> 05:28:21.920
[Guest]: because very few countries have been able to sustain growth for more than two decades or

05:28:21.920 --> 05:28:26.640
[Guest]: something they do regress to the mean and then there are periods of relatively moderate or low

05:28:26.640 --> 05:28:33.280
[Guest]: growth and then they go back so but because we gain a lot from this period you know so in fact

05:28:33.280 --> 05:28:39.280
[Guest]: growth one thing I want to just focus on growth is the most important thing to focus on economic

05:28:39.280 --> 05:28:46.080
[Guest]: growth is the thing everything and so if you look at all other you can pick any development indicator

05:28:46.080 --> 05:28:49.280
[Guest]: you care about which is material development I'm not about political and all we've been in

05:28:49.280 --> 05:28:53.840
[Guest]: democracy for a long time it's great all of those things are there but regional development if you

05:28:53.840 --> 05:29:01.360
[Guest]: talk about improvement in health education improvement in availability of material I mean

05:29:01.360 --> 05:29:07.520
[Guest]: things like housing you know those things the nature natural environment and all of that

05:29:07.520 --> 05:29:14.080
[Guest]: very highly correlated with economic I mean GDP per capita all of those not no exceptions

05:29:14.080 --> 05:29:21.920
[Guest]: I mean it is stunning how much growth can do for you you know so for an 11 for love

05:29:21.920 --> 05:29:26.000
[Guest]: some one level of income you can do a little better by spending a little more efficiently

05:29:27.840 --> 05:29:33.360
[Guest]: in some areas but not a whole lot ultimate binding constraint is having more resources

05:29:33.360 --> 05:29:39.200
[Guest]: you know which is what GDP per capita reflects that how much resource is available what is the

05:29:39.200 --> 05:29:46.640
[Guest]: basically the value of the goods and services you produce and that reflected in a per capita basis.

05:29:46.640 --> 05:29:51.680
[Guest]: So in some areas we do a little better some example primary education and all we do

05:29:52.560 --> 05:29:56.880
[Guest]: worse than our even our level of income in terms of the educational quality right the

05:29:56.880 --> 05:30:00.480
[Guest]: learning outcomes are quite poor in India so we could do better on those perhaps even for

05:30:00.480 --> 05:30:05.440
[Guest]: our level of income little better than some area like air quality we do worse than even

05:30:05.440 --> 05:30:10.560
[Guest]: countries at our level of income we could do better on those but in most areas if you want

05:30:10.560 --> 05:30:15.360
[Guest]: any significant improvement you need to get growth going to have more resources to be able to do

05:30:16.000 --> 05:30:20.000
[Guest]: more with with those because this is the main kind of

05:30:22.560 --> 05:30:25.840
[Guest]: underlying driver you know when everything correlates with one thing then you have to

05:30:25.840 --> 05:30:32.480
[Guest]: think about is it just correlation or is there some kind of causality going one way so I see

05:30:32.480 --> 05:30:35.520
[Guest]: that there is a complex relationship with our human capital we talked about health education there is

05:30:35.520 --> 05:30:41.520
[Guest]: obviously some other side I mean the two-way causality growth helps you do more of those

05:30:41.520 --> 05:30:46.320
[Guest]: but the more better human capital gives you growth so there is that of course but focusing on growth

05:30:46.320 --> 05:30:52.080
[Guest]: gets a lot done is is my world view I mean reasonable persons can disagree about how

05:30:52.080 --> 05:30:58.080
[Guest]: much weightage to give to it but I think it is the most important thing to get it right

05:30:58.080 --> 05:31:04.000
[Guest]: and it in our own history right our impact on poverty rate our impact on well-being across

05:31:04.000 --> 05:31:09.760
[Guest]: many many indicators has been much better since we grew it is I agree in some areas

05:31:09.760 --> 05:31:15.200
[Guest]: an uncertain glory we have done worse than we should even have at our level of income in some

05:31:15.200 --> 05:31:21.280
[Guest]: areas but if you want to get much better this is a necessary condition you know and in many cases

05:31:21.280 --> 05:31:26.240
[Guest]: sufficient in some cases not sufficient but it's certainly necessary to get continue to grow

05:31:26.240 --> 05:31:32.320
[Guest]: rapidly and then later we'll get into demographic issues as well and in the essay I think which you

05:31:32.320 --> 05:31:37.520
[Guest]: have cited I had shown how India has been related to the rest of the world you know and in the first

05:31:37.520 --> 05:31:41.520
[Guest]: three decades of our day after independence our relative position in the world may have fallen

05:31:42.080 --> 05:31:46.800
[Guest]: at least on the data that I am referring to may not be fully representative because all countries

05:31:46.800 --> 05:31:52.800
[Guest]: data were not available at that time but it was a pretty bad performance especially in 60s and 70s

05:31:52.800 --> 05:31:58.400
[Guest]: it's only in 80s we started growing at a moderate rate but against a very bad two decades so I mean

05:31:58.400 --> 05:32:04.080
[Guest]: it was more of a recovery happening at that time and in 90s we actually got embarked on a proper

05:32:04.080 --> 05:32:10.800
[Guest]: rapid growth episode and we need to be able to sustain it I mean and that requires I mean

05:32:10.800 --> 05:32:15.760
[Guest]: consensus on growth you know that this is a very important priority this is the top priority this

05:32:15.760 --> 05:32:21.680
[Guest]: is the thing and we are a federal polity we are a polity where power resides at multiple levels

05:32:21.680 --> 05:32:25.600
[Guest]: levels even in dominant party system where there is one party dominant at the national level state

05:32:25.600 --> 05:32:30.000
[Guest]: level there is still quite a bit of competition even at national level even though you are dominant

05:32:30.000 --> 05:32:35.200
[Guest]: party there are other places where power is there sometimes judges can do something others can do

05:32:35.200 --> 05:32:40.080
[Guest]: so you need to create consensus for these things because you can do some try to do something but

05:32:40.080 --> 05:32:44.000
[Guest]: it can be disrupted either way so state government is trying to do something center can disrupt it

05:32:44.000 --> 05:32:47.600
[Guest]: center is trying to do something state governments can disrupt it so some degree of consensus

05:32:47.600 --> 05:32:53.680
[Guest]: building around this these issues is very important so that at least from a developmental perspective

05:32:53.680 --> 05:32:57.440
[Guest]: I mean reasonable policies are made and implemented and reasonable systems are put in

05:32:57.440 --> 05:33:00.960
[Guest]: place to take the right decision at the local level even if the policy is not necessarily

05:33:00.960 --> 05:33:09.040
[Guest]: fully followed in the to the letter and I think those are important questions and I

05:33:09.040 --> 05:33:14.080
[Guest]: thought about in many ways so how anti-corruption strategies in the last 10 years have worked out

05:33:14.080 --> 05:33:20.000
[Guest]: and changed bureaucratic behavior and incentives of bureaucrats to take decisions how state capital

05:33:20.000 --> 05:33:25.520
[Guest]: relations have changed might have changed looking at in rising disputes between the state and

05:33:26.160 --> 05:33:31.600
[Guest]: private capital especially on the tax side but also in enforcement direct rate and all those

05:33:32.160 --> 05:33:36.320
[Guest]: so when one is trying to make sense of things which are not easy to directly study

05:33:36.320 --> 05:33:42.880
[Guest]: because it's a hidden aspect of a political reality what we read is the de jure and the

05:33:42.880 --> 05:33:48.240
[Guest]: headline but what happens on on the ground is not so easily directly so I talk to business people

05:33:48.240 --> 05:33:53.760
[Guest]: I try to get a sense of before after what changed what was happening earlier what has changed now

05:33:53.760 --> 05:33:56.720
[Guest]: I look at whatever data is available try to make sense of these things.

05:33:57.520 --> 05:34:01.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah and I couldn't agree with you more strongly about the importance of growth you know Nitin

05:34:01.200 --> 05:34:06.480
[Amit Varma]: Pai once pointed out that for every one percent rise in GDP two million people came out of poverty

05:34:06.480 --> 05:34:13.040
[Amit Varma]: and I think the estimate has actually gone up since he last mentioned that that has staggering

05:34:13.040 --> 05:34:20.560
[Amit Varma]: humanitarian consequences growth is not just you know statistics or lines on a graph it affects

05:34:20.560 --> 05:34:26.640
[Amit Varma]: the lives of real people and I'm sometimes astonished that there is still an intellectual

05:34:26.640 --> 05:34:33.760
[Amit Varma]: class of people quote-unquote who still question the 91 reforms who still you know question growth

05:34:33.760 --> 05:34:41.200
[Amit Varma]: who are whose brains are still full of the nonsensical dogma that was in vogue 70 years ago

05:34:41.200 --> 05:34:48.720
[Amit Varma]: and it kind of just boggles my mind but luckily like you said that you know maybe intellectuals

05:34:48.720 --> 05:34:52.240
[Amit Varma]: are not that relevant in the real world and that's a good thing you know people can see

05:34:52.240 --> 05:34:59.760
[Guest]: what's good for them one sort of hopes so I think one issue is inequality they focus too much on

05:34:59.760 --> 05:35:06.640
[Guest]: that one metric and some of them have some ideological or psychological reasons to giving

05:35:06.640 --> 05:35:11.600
[Guest]: for giving too much emphasis on that one value if they give too much well emphasis on them by

05:35:11.600 --> 05:35:17.520
[Guest]: them that one value of equality then obviously last 30 years look a little worse than they do

05:35:17.520 --> 05:35:22.960
[Guest]: to you and me who have a different set of values so there is a difference on that so I mean it is

05:35:22.960 --> 05:35:28.480
[Amit Varma]: what it is I mean just to reiterate and regular listeners of the show will know but it's something

05:35:28.480 --> 05:35:33.760
[Amit Varma]: I feel really strongly about that inequality and poverty are different things you know the

05:35:34.640 --> 05:35:39.600
[Amit Varma]: thought experiment question I often ask people is in which of these two countries would be would

05:35:39.600 --> 05:35:45.040
[Amit Varma]: you rather be poor the USA or Bangladesh and obviously everybody would rather be poor in the

05:35:45.040 --> 05:35:51.360
[Guest]: USA yeah but the truth is there is better than being better off in India or Bangladesh so in

05:35:51.360 --> 05:35:56.080
[Amit Varma]: that same essay let me finish the point I was making and the reason for that the reason they

05:35:56.080 --> 05:36:01.600
[Amit Varma]: would choose the USA is because poverty is less even though inequality is far greater in the US

05:36:01.600 --> 05:36:07.680
[Amit Varma]: than Bangladesh you know it's it's a pattern of developing countries that when you're coming out

05:36:07.680 --> 05:36:11.920
[Amit Varma]: of poverty your poverty rates go down as your inequality goes up because we don't live in a

05:36:11.920 --> 05:36:16.000
[Amit Varma]: zero-sum world it is not the case that if the rich are getting richer the poor poor must be

05:36:16.000 --> 05:36:20.000
[Amit Varma]: getting poorer it is the case that they are both getting richer and the rich are of course getting

05:36:20.000 --> 05:36:25.440
[Amit Varma]: richer at a higher rate so inequality increases and the moral imperative for any country which

05:36:25.440 --> 05:36:32.000
[Amit Varma]: has these rates of poverty is reduce the poverty as fast as possible so what we have had since 91

05:36:32.000 --> 05:36:37.200
[Amit Varma]: is poverty has gone down massively inequality has gone up so what it doesn't matter that's

05:36:37.200 --> 05:36:43.200
[Guest]: a wrong metric we are not in a zero-sum world yes absolutely in fact if you look at income

05:36:43.200 --> 05:36:49.760
[Guest]: distributions I've done some quick analysis on this and perform my essays that if the household

05:36:49.760 --> 05:36:54.720
[Guest]: income at the 90th percentile in India is about the same as the household income at the 15th

05:36:54.720 --> 05:37:02.480
[Guest]: percentile in the US so I mean a poor household earns as much as a much better off right their

05:37:02.480 --> 05:37:09.520
[Guest]: 90th percentile is better off than 9 out of 10 households is basically so I mean that's the

05:37:09.520 --> 05:37:14.400
[Guest]: impulse for immigration right that you suddenly go and become a part of a history of another

05:37:14.400 --> 05:37:19.280
[Guest]: place because each square foot in this planet has its own history and suddenly you supplant

05:37:19.280 --> 05:37:25.280
[Guest]: yourself from one history to another history and profit from the years of struggle that went into

05:37:25.280 --> 05:37:31.680
[Guest]: making that history right where you could just land up in a place and suddenly be much much

05:37:31.680 --> 05:37:38.400
[Guest]: better off at least materially and and it's quite a painful thing I was I remember I was on a flight

05:37:38.400 --> 05:37:44.720
[Guest]: from here to Europe and there was going through Abu Dhabi and I was sitting next to this guy who

05:37:44.720 --> 05:37:51.120
[Guest]: was crying and he was like a middle-aged man who was crying and after a while I thought I should

05:37:51.120 --> 05:37:56.000
[Guest]: talk to him at least I don't know whether I can comfort him and all he may have gone through some

05:37:56.000 --> 05:38:03.120
[Guest]: tragedy or something but he was literally like crying you know and he was from Punjab and he

05:38:03.120 --> 05:38:10.720
[Guest]: told me that he's going to work at Abu Dhabi and I said okay I didn't ask him why are you crying I

05:38:10.720 --> 05:38:15.360
[Guest]: just kept talking to him because you know I don't want to approach that directly and also to a

05:38:15.360 --> 05:38:21.280
[Guest]: middle-aged man it's a it's very difficult to talk about this thing but he opened up immediately he

05:38:21.280 --> 05:38:30.000
[Guest]: said I am a plumber from district of Punjab and I'm going to Abu Dhabi for work and I was there

05:38:30.000 --> 05:38:34.800
[Guest]: and I came back for to with my family for a month and a month or two months I don't remember

05:38:34.800 --> 05:38:41.680
[Guest]: and I'm now going back there for work and I my daughter is six years old now and I last I saw

05:38:41.680 --> 05:38:47.840
[Guest]: her when she was four and now I'm seeing her at six and now I'll see her and I can't deal with it

05:38:48.640 --> 05:38:53.600
[Guest]: so I said then I asked how much do you earn you know that and it's a completely different kind

05:38:53.600 --> 05:38:58.560
[Guest]: of level of income that you get there right like even as a plumber you will four or five times or

05:38:58.560 --> 05:39:03.600
[Guest]: something but you run a plumber in your small town in there and simply I mean human beings are the

05:39:03.600 --> 05:39:10.320
[Guest]: same we are not dumber or anything like that it's just institutions basically I mean of course there

05:39:10.320 --> 05:39:14.720
[Guest]: are natural resource rich countries that's a different category but for the rest all kinds

05:39:14.720 --> 05:39:18.880
[Guest]: of countries have become prosperous South Korea didn't get rich by natural resources which China

05:39:18.880 --> 05:39:24.480
[Guest]: didn't get it's just getting the institution and mechanisms right and having the right kind

05:39:24.480 --> 05:39:30.000
[Guest]: of arrangements to just you know do what is necessary to get rich it's a amazing tragedy

05:39:30.000 --> 05:39:34.800
[Guest]: people from my village I mean it's within the country you would go to Bombay to work and then

05:39:34.800 --> 05:39:39.360
[Guest]: come back and see your family after six months or a year and go abroad in fact if they don't come

05:39:39.360 --> 05:39:43.040
[Guest]: back for two years often because it's very expensive to come back and you lose wages

05:39:43.040 --> 05:39:47.040
[Guest]: plus pay for the flight and all of that for two years once in two years go see your children and

05:39:47.040 --> 05:39:54.640
[Guest]: your family and it's a moral failure to not get growth going and it was so this kind of I mean

05:39:55.600 --> 05:39:59.440
[Guest]: I give a lot of benefit of doubt people have their reasons to believe what they believe

05:39:59.440 --> 05:40:04.880
[Guest]: but I can't get this too much now especially now that we have seen all kind of destinations have

05:40:04.880 --> 05:40:09.440
[Guest]: fallen apart and fallen away and we've actually delivered good growth maybe some sources of

05:40:09.440 --> 05:40:15.280
[Guest]: growth had histories going back to the before the 90s but even earlier we could have grown

05:40:15.280 --> 05:40:22.400
[Guest]: more rapidly this argument that oh if we hadn't done the patent act earlier to then we wouldn't

05:40:22.400 --> 05:40:26.800
[Guest]: have been able to benefit from trips and all these are all just excuses broadly speaking

05:40:26.800 --> 05:40:31.680
[Guest]: three or three decades we didn't deliver on the promise and then since then we have done

