05:55:46.880 --> 05:55:52.320
[Guest]: there's a kind of populist strain to our democracy right now and it at times is quite nasty and

05:55:52.320 --> 05:55:58.720
[Guest]: difficult to deal with as a citizen but I'm still very hopeful that democratic sources of resilience

05:55:58.720 --> 05:56:04.160
[Guest]: will come in come into play and there will be some moderation that will happen and I think as a

05:56:04.160 --> 05:56:09.200
[Guest]: democracy that we have sustained as a democracy for such a long time hardly anybody gave us a

05:56:09.200 --> 05:56:14.240
[Guest]: chance when we became democratic and in fact in the colonial era the best liberals in the 19th

05:56:14.240 --> 05:56:18.080
[Guest]: century you mentioned Tocqueville. Tocqueville was a big supporter of colonialism including British

05:56:18.080 --> 05:56:23.760
[Guest]: colonialism in India he said he was a great thinker on democracy he had strong moral commitments to

05:56:23.760 --> 05:56:30.640
[Guest]: democracy but he had a different view of what how colonialism in country like India but we kind of

05:56:30.640 --> 05:56:36.000
[Guest]: you know pushed back against those views and so we made democracy work more or less and now

05:56:36.000 --> 05:56:42.160
[Guest]: I mean compared to that immediate era after independence we've had much more of distribution

05:56:42.160 --> 05:56:46.960
[Guest]: of power in society more and more groups are getting incorporated in different ways finding

05:56:46.960 --> 05:56:53.520
[Guest]: representation in into society into the democratic system into through different political parties

05:56:53.520 --> 05:56:58.640
[Guest]: through state apparatus and all of that so the democracy is working as a social principle you

05:56:58.640 --> 05:57:02.960
[Guest]: should never forget that democracy is finally a fundamentally social principle it's it's some

05:57:02.960 --> 05:57:07.440
[Guest]: it's a quality of societies you know that you're democratic you have a certain commitment to

05:57:07.440 --> 05:57:13.280
[Guest]: fundamental equality of conditions and it's happening I mean we didn't have the American

05:57:13.280 --> 05:57:17.360
[Guest]: kind of beginning right we started with equality of conditions there wasn't any central government

05:57:17.360 --> 05:57:24.080
[Guest]: local liberties all of that we had a colonial state and it was the top heavy state and even

05:57:24.080 --> 05:57:28.800
[Guest]: though villages and communities were pushing back a little bit there was still a quite a bit of

05:57:28.800 --> 05:57:35.680
[Guest]: top heavy interference in life and we democratized and we started we had a it was a matter of faith

05:57:35.680 --> 05:57:40.400
[Guest]: for our founders that we will work as a democracy and we have live up to the expectation more or

05:57:40.400 --> 05:57:46.720
[Guest]: less you know we've continued our democracy there was a brief interlude of of a kind of a

05:57:46.720 --> 05:57:53.520
[Guest]: democratership or dictatorship you can call it and we've continued so on we had a big failing

05:57:53.520 --> 05:57:58.240
[Guest]: on economic side for a few decades we corrected that we corrected that in a very big way I would

05:57:58.240 --> 05:58:03.200
[Guest]: say we should not underestimate what we have achieved in those in these three decades we have

05:58:04.480 --> 05:58:09.920
[Guest]: we can do much better we have a long long way to go but we have a our own one generation of

05:58:09.920 --> 05:58:16.960
[Guest]: record to show that we can do quite quite well on the side of whether I mean there is a side

05:58:16.960 --> 05:58:21.360
[Guest]: of social kind of civic life and social life which needs to have there will be conflicts there will

