[Guest]: own traditions religious traditions so multiculturalism is very hard in India and and and

05:58:55.200 --> 05:59:01.600
[Guest]: therefore controlling for that we've done quite well I would say because democracy itself creates

05:59:01.600 --> 05:59:07.520
[Guest]: you know incentives to mobilize one group against another all of that it happens but given all of

05:59:07.520 --> 05:59:12.880
[Guest]: that we've not done too badly if you took a long view don't get too upset about some particular

05:59:12.880 --> 05:59:18.400
[Guest]: events or something which which which are obviously bad in themselves so and that's a

05:59:18.400 --> 05:59:23.200
[Guest]: surprising thing because democracy creates incentives to do much worse on that and we've

05:59:23.200 --> 05:59:30.640
[Guest]: not done so badly and hopefully we'll not do worse in the near future so across I mean

05:59:30.640 --> 05:59:37.520
[Guest]: phase in which democracy works I think we I'm much more hopeful I mean than I would have been

05:59:37.520 --> 05:59:43.600
[Guest]: say even 30 I mean I I was too young at that time at 30 years ago we are going through on some

05:59:43.600 --> 05:59:48.800
[Guest]: aspects of our especially on the aspects of anti-politics and all some difficult patch right

05:59:48.800 --> 05:59:53.120
[Guest]: now and I think we cannot take it too lightly we should take it seriously and we should try to

05:59:53.840 --> 05:59:59.760
[Guest]: find low-cost ways to get out of this kind of a politics which is pretty I mean harmful for

05:59:59.760 --> 06:00:04.880
[Guest]: democracy because ultimately equality is a foundation of democracy and nobody should feel

06:00:04.880 --> 06:00:10.480
[Guest]: less lesser of a citizen you know than anyone else so that I think is very important but I

06:00:10.480 --> 06:00:16.080
[Guest]: think our democratic resilience is there and we can certainly find ways to you know moderate

06:00:16.080 --> 06:00:22.080
[Guest]: whatever is happening and I'm not I never put democracy up to some abstract standard and say

06:00:22.080 --> 06:00:26.880
[Guest]: if you don't meet my standard then you're not a much of a democracy you have to judge democracy

06:00:26.880 --> 06:00:35.120
[Guest]: on its own terms and given our I mean complexity of our society different identities different

06:00:35.120 --> 06:00:40.720
[Guest]: regional religious identities as a multicultural society given the level of poverty and all we had

06:00:42.400 --> 06:00:47.760
[Guest]: earlier we've come a long way you know and therefore one of the most important things

06:00:47.760 --> 06:00:52.560
[Guest]: I feel at least in private conversation I say is that do not give up on India you know don't give

06:00:52.560 --> 06:00:56.080
[Guest]: up like this is a rotten society and this and that because some events happen and somebody

06:00:56.080 --> 06:01:02.240
[Guest]: reacts in this way that puts the society which is the whole democracy there's one thing right that

06:01:02.240 --> 06:01:08.160
[Guest]: empowers the whole and parts become very weak and you can feel very small because of that sometimes

06:01:08.160 --> 06:01:12.240
[Guest]: if you think about it this way that hey what am I there's this large body politic is there

06:01:12.240 --> 06:01:18.080
[Guest]: and what who am I to I can't change it I should just give up on it and be a part of some other

06:01:18.080 --> 06:01:23.760
[Guest]: country's history just move but I say that I mean let's keep trying you know like to go back to

06:01:23.760 --> 06:01:30.880
[Guest]: Chesterton that Rome Rome would be great because Romans love it so we need to keep that faith and

06:01:30.880 --> 06:01:35.920
[Guest]: keep working whatever we need to do as citizens especially at local I mean everyone friends and

06:01:35.920 --> 06:01:42.720
[Guest]: family level to try to kind of keep doing better because I think it's the most interesting country

06:01:42.720 --> 06:01:48.640
[Guest]: in the world in the sense that what we are trying to do right now the journey that we have made the

06:01:48.640 --> 06:01:55.840
[Guest]: future I mean the stakes are just staggering then to to quote misquote Lucas that you know

06:01:55.840 --> 06:02:00.880
[Guest]: the consequences are simply staggering and we have to invest in this process and ultimately

06:02:00.880 --> 06:02:05.840
[Guest]: democracy is self-governance democracy is ruled by the people every anybody who has power has

06:02:05.840 --> 06:02:10.480
[Guest]: the power from the people and people it's ultimately people who will decide what will

06:02:10.480 --> 06:02:15.280
[Guest]: be rewarded and what will be punished what will work and what will not work and therefore we

06:02:15.280 --> 06:02:20.480
[Guest]: should even though the hole is much larger than us we are part of that hole as well constituent

06:02:20.480 --> 06:02:25.840
[Guest]: of that hole and we need to keep that democratic faith and keep working towards a perfection of

06:02:25.840 --> 06:02:32.720
[Amit Varma]: this democracy you know. Yeah when you say the the hole I mean do you mean WHOLE or HOLE but

06:02:32.720 --> 06:02:38.400
[Amit Varma]: a penultimate question which is that you mentioned that we are in a fix but we have to find a low

06:02:38.400 --> 06:02:42.400
[Amit Varma]: cost way out of it so what do you mean by low cost and what would be high cost?

06:02:42.400 --> 06:02:48.160
[Guest]: I don't know but what would be the low right way out of it but there is a particular dynamic that

06:02:48.160 --> 06:02:55.120
[Guest]: is at play which is an identarian dynamic where basically a community is reduced to its worst

06:02:55.120 --> 06:03:00.080
[Guest]: elements and it happens with different communities at different points of time and it happening with

06:03:00.080 --> 06:03:04.480
[Guest]: some communities at this point of time that you obviously all communities have some fanatics in

06:03:04.480 --> 06:03:11.200
[Guest]: some way but vast majority don't like that don't live like that and although I mean there is a

06:03:11.200 --> 06:03:17.920
[Guest]: they can do something more than they do to moderate the fanatics and maybe they can't

06:03:17.920 --> 06:03:22.960
[Guest]: and we don't know but when you reduce the entire community to the worst of their motivations then

06:03:22.960 --> 06:03:29.520
[Guest]: obviously it becomes a question of can we coexist and all of that. Those kind of questions are

06:03:29.520 --> 06:03:33.920
[Guest]: getting raised more and more now I think in India and democratic politics is working in a way that

06:03:33.920 --> 06:03:38.880
[Guest]: these questions are getting more and more raised on a regular basis and there's much more mobilization

06:03:38.880 --> 06:03:44.880
[Guest]: around those kind of issues. Now I believe at least my understanding of what's possible is that

06:03:45.520 --> 06:03:51.920
[Guest]: if you focus on I mean where the real problem is where there's actual genuine fanaticism and

06:03:51.920 --> 06:03:58.720
[Guest]: there's genuine kind of a threat and not make it something broader and focus on solving that

06:03:58.720 --> 06:04:05.280
[Guest]: problem you can find a way to kind of overcome this sense of anxiety and fear that we have kind

06:04:05.280 --> 06:04:10.720
[Guest]: of there's so much fear in India right now like this strange fear like if you open the television

06:04:10.720 --> 06:04:16.160
[Guest]: just it throws fear at you you know so many news channels just throwing fear and anxiety

06:04:16.160 --> 06:04:22.000
[Guest]: all the time it's really something which has become a part of our air in some ways you know

06:04:22.000 --> 06:04:28.560
[Guest]: Delhi air is very thick anyway and thicker because I don't have a tv at home but whenever I go

06:04:28.560 --> 06:04:34.800
[Guest]: somewhere I watch tv and I'm like oh my god what what is going on the level of you know over the

06:04:34.800 --> 06:04:40.720
[Guest]: top rhetoric and the simple oversimplification of issues like you go anecdotal when you want

06:04:40.720 --> 06:04:45.280
[Guest]: to avoid someone and statistically you want to defend yourself you know so yeah that guy did it

06:04:45.280 --> 06:04:50.880
[Guest]: that identity so it must be the entire community is like that it's it's not good for coexistence

06:04:50.880 --> 06:04:55.920
[Guest]: in a multicultural society you have to be more precise talk about what's going on find facts

06:04:55.920 --> 06:04:59.840
[Guest]: report on the facts there may be problems there may be fanaticism there may be some degree of

06:04:59.840 --> 06:05:07.440
[Guest]: extremism going on but attack that identify that it has to be more precise and fear anxiety that is

06:05:08.080 --> 06:05:12.960
[Guest]: being pervaded social media has done that to some extent mainstream media television media

06:05:12.960 --> 06:05:19.520
[Guest]: is contributing a lot and that fear I really worry that at a subconscious level it it is

06:05:20.240 --> 06:05:24.320
[Guest]: making us into something which we'll see the consequences maybe in a decade or two

06:05:24.880 --> 06:05:29.360
[Guest]: if we can change that if we can get I mean leadership basically it's something that

06:05:29.360 --> 06:05:33.280
[Guest]: we've done that level leaders not just the current leaders people who readers who rise

06:05:33.280 --> 06:05:38.560
[Guest]: who have the wisdom to see the problems of these ways and say okay can we do better can we can we

06:05:38.560 --> 06:05:43.520
[Guest]: be more precise about actual problems and not create demons of our own to destroy you know

06:05:44.080 --> 06:05:48.960
[Guest]: that's one the other is as I said perhaps if we focus on other things which is common good

06:05:48.960 --> 06:05:56.000
[Guest]: collective action cooperation for development and growth hopefully we can have a little less of

06:05:56.000 --> 06:06:01.760
[Guest]: a focus on these things because our psychological wounds are many you know we have been as a

06:06:01.760 --> 06:06:07.200
[Guest]: civilization being ruled for many many centuries and we don't even know the depth of our sufferings

06:06:07.200 --> 06:06:12.560
[Guest]: you know and if we if we bring those out on a regular basis and spread fear and anxiety

06:06:13.280 --> 06:06:18.560
[Guest]: I mean this is a tiger that you will that eat the ones who are riding it also you know so

06:06:18.560 --> 06:06:22.880
[Guest]: it is possible I'm not saying that we are there yet one good hope is that we are not

06:06:22.880 --> 06:06:28.640
[Guest]: completely modern we don't think in those clear-cut category ways many of us some are

06:06:28.640 --> 06:06:34.480
[Guest]: so there is still much more intertwining of lives and much more of a amorphousness to the identity

06:06:34.480 --> 06:06:41.120
[Guest]: in India I think so for example I still go to Dargah sometimes like this that not just me my

06:06:41.120 --> 06:06:47.040
[Guest]: family so there is some of that sources of resilience democracy itself has both sources of

06:06:47.040 --> 06:06:53.520
[Guest]: risk and also sources of resilience and we have a big hope for progress we've got a taste of

06:06:53.520 --> 06:06:58.240
[Guest]: progress right in three years three decades good serious taste of progress economic progress

06:06:58.240 --> 06:07:04.080
[Guest]: we've got some source of social progress let's wet that appetite a little more let's work together

06:07:04.080 --> 06:07:11.440
[Guest]: towards you know progress towards a richer more I mean more robustly multicultural society you

06:07:11.440 --> 06:07:15.680
[Guest]: know because I don't think we're going to secularize anytime soon and I don't know whether

06:07:15.680 --> 06:07:19.920
[Guest]: it's a good thing at all or not we've existed a multicultural society with different religions

06:07:20.480 --> 06:07:25.200
[Guest]: coexisting different regional identities all of that and it's a great advantage to be a part of

06:07:25.200 --> 06:07:31.920
[Guest]: India like sub-regional sub-national sentiments and all should be I mean kept under some kind of a

06:07:31.920 --> 06:07:37.520
[Guest]: limit because it's great to be a part of this country and there are many benefits economic

06:07:37.520 --> 06:07:42.480
[Guest]: and otherwise of being part of this that's another element that we shouldn't stoke too much

06:07:42.480 --> 06:07:52.000
[Guest]: because being a part of a whole like this you know like a country as big as India is culturally

06:07:52.000 --> 06:07:56.720
[Guest]: and economically and politically very beneficial for different parts even the parts that are doing

06:07:56.720 --> 06:08:01.840
[Amit Varma]: the much better than others. I hope your hopes come to fruition though I also worried that the

06:08:01.840 --> 06:08:06.880
[Amit Varma]: fear and the anxiety are real and we might be trapped in a vicious circle where they just

06:08:06.880 --> 06:08:12.160
[Amit Varma]: spiral and take us into a very dark place. Final question which I always sort of end my episodes

06:08:12.160 --> 06:08:19.040
[Amit Varma]: with which is why don't you recommend for me and my listeners books, music, films that mean a lot to you?

06:08:22.800 --> 06:08:29.600
[Guest]: Books, music and films. Oh whatever any art. Yeah so on the book recommendations I link up to

06:08:29.600 --> 06:08:36.240
[Guest]: the themes that we discussed today. So one theme was democracy and I think the best book on

06:08:36.240 --> 06:08:44.160
[Guest]: democracy is Tocqueville's Democracy in America. It's a great book and everyone should try to read

06:08:44.160 --> 06:08:52.160
[Guest]: it and engage with it seriously and if you want to get a book about that book it's basically I think

06:08:52.160 --> 06:09:01.040
[Guest]: the best in that category in my view is Pierre Manon's Tocqueville and the Nature of Democracy.

06:09:01.040 --> 06:09:08.400
[Guest]: It's a short book and it's a really great well-done book. Then a lot of the books by Pierre

06:09:08.400 --> 06:09:15.360
[Guest]: Roseval is also very insightful but especially I really liked his latest book on populism. I think

06:09:15.360 --> 06:09:20.240
[Guest]: it's the best book on populism and it's important to understand our times and how democracy is

06:09:20.240 --> 06:09:24.480
[Guest]: getting transformed in some ways by populism and why that may have happened, how to think about it

06:09:24.480 --> 06:09:30.000
[Guest]: theoretically. We talked about virtues and there are many books on virtues in different traditions

06:09:30.000 --> 06:09:35.680
[Guest]: and I will just recommend one which we mentioned indirectly so that if one wants to go and get

06:09:35.680 --> 06:09:41.360
[Guest]: into it and more deeply is Alasdair MacIntyre's After Virtue. I think it's a great book and

06:09:42.000 --> 06:09:48.720
[Guest]: we mentioned it and others I'm not going to. We talked a little bit about technology also right

06:09:48.720 --> 06:09:56.080
[Guest]: and so I would recommend Don Ide's work on human technology relations philosophy of technology.

06:09:57.280 --> 06:10:01.520
[Guest]: There are a couple of recent books I enjoyed reading one was a book on technology and

06:10:01.520 --> 06:10:07.120
[Guest]: virtues by Shannon Valor and another one on nihilism and technology which takes a Nietzschean

06:10:07.120 --> 06:10:14.800
[Guest]: perspective on technology by this young philosopher Nolan Kurtz. Then we talked about

06:10:14.800 --> 06:10:21.280
[Guest]: political economy also that was the I mean large part of our conversation so I would suggest at

06:10:21.280 --> 06:10:27.120
[Guest]: least from a more comparative and I mean perspective and understanding theory of

06:10:27.120 --> 06:10:33.440
[Guest]: growth and political economy. A lot of new social economics work by people like Douglas North,

06:10:33.440 --> 06:10:37.840
[Guest]: Alina Rostrom and others is quite illuminating and gives you a good way of thinking about this

06:10:37.840 --> 06:10:44.400
[Guest]: thing in my view. Also the work of Albert Hirschman is very powerful even now in thinking

06:10:44.400 --> 06:10:51.200
[Guest]: about growth and development economic progress. Then I've benefited a lot from accessing the

06:10:51.200 --> 06:10:56.160
[Guest]: empirical work by people like Lan Pritchett and all and there are there's a community of people

06:10:56.160 --> 06:11:01.600
[Guest]: who do this kind of work and it's it's worth engaging with it gives you things about thinking

06:11:01.600 --> 06:11:06.720
[Guest]: about it ways to think about these issues and there's a book which is not an economics book

06:11:06.720 --> 06:11:10.560
[Guest]: but I found it very useful to think about political economy then on complex adaptive

06:11:10.560 --> 06:11:15.360
[Guest]: systems. It's a book by Robert Axelrod. It's called Harnessing Complexity. So it's one of

06:11:15.360 --> 06:11:21.360
[Guest]: the best books on complexity and it gives you a language to speak about complexity and move away

06:11:21.360 --> 06:11:28.160
[Guest]: from the language of you know top-down thinking in that sense. I mean religion there I mean

06:11:28.160 --> 06:11:34.560
[Guest]: basically the best way is to read scriptures and try to engage with them whether it's philosophical

06:11:34.560 --> 06:11:43.360
[Guest]: scripts texts or religious books holy books or mythological books but also epics. I really enjoy

06:11:43.360 --> 06:11:50.320
[Guest]: reading epics so Mahabharata, Odyssey also like epic poems like Divine Comedy and Rashmi Rathee

06:11:50.320 --> 06:11:57.280
[Guest]: and all are very interesting to me. So I would say yeah I mean that's where I would I'm linking it to

06:11:57.280 --> 06:12:03.360
[Guest]: themes that we discussed now. I mean music I mean I don't have much of a recommendation with the

06:12:03.360 --> 06:12:10.080
[Guest]: only music I really enjoy is old Hindi film music. I just listen to that only now that's all

